<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPARATING THE SAMMY FROM THE BULL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
If this were one of those Mafia films Americans like so much, we'd
have reached the point where Don Corleone pulls us aside and
whispers in our ear in Italian, ``No fare lo stupido.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be stupid.
</P>
<P>
   The saga of Salvatore ``Sammy the Bull'' Gravano, currently
playing on TV sets throughout Arizona and the United States should
not be confused with The Godfather, Goodfellas or Casino. It's not
an episode of The Sopranos, for which the actual hit man Gravano
was invited to appear on the show as a make-believe hit man.
</P>
<P>
   I understand how some of you may be confused.
</P>
<P>
   Just remember, after filming the scene from The Godfather in
which Luca Brasi is choked to death with piano wire, the actor
being strangled, Lenny ``Bull'' Montana, simply rose from the floor
and went on to play variations of the same character in numerous
movies and television shows.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, not one of the 19 murder victims linked to
Gravano ever made another living appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, after Gravano turned state's evidence and helped
convict John Gotti and 36 other New York mobsters, our federal
government cut him a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Uncle Sam, Sammy the Bull spent less then five years
in prison, after which he was set up with a new identity, a new
house and a new business. And, if local authorities are correct,
this was of enormous assistance to Gravano when he decided to start
selling designer drugs to Arizona kids.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Gravano's criminal syndicate targeted ``normal''
teenagers at local music clubs. They say the operation was financed
by Gravano, who had money in the bank from his deal with the
government and from the book about his life, Underboss, by Peter
Maas.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly, Gravano's people sold more than 30,000 Ecstasy pills
a week, some laced with heroin and methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   To our children.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Gravano told The Republic's Dennis Wagner, ``What
would be so interesting about me? Running a legitimate business.
Being monitored by the government . . . I think it's boring.''
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the FBI tried to protect Gravano, asking The
Republic not to publish an article about him, even after Gravano
told The Republic, ``Have my values changed? No. You can't change
what you are inside. A leopard doesn't change his spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Our government relocated this guy here. Where we live. Without
telling us.
</P>
<P>
   Our government protected him and allowed him to prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Gravano and others remain in jail after their arraignment
Monday. A few weeks ago, at his first court appearance, Gravano
seemed almost confused by the $5 million bond set for him, saying,
``There is no violence in this case that I'm charged with, that I'm
aware of . I'm part of the community. I'm in business. I run a
couple of businesses in Arizona. I never ran from a case in my life
and this is, basically, in my history of crime, this is a minor
thing. Even if it's proven, which I don't think it could be
proven.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Mafia movies probably could picture Ray Liotta making
that speech in Goodfellas. Or maybe Joe Pesci in Casino.
</P>
<P>
   No fare lo stupido.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't them. It wasn't Robert De Niro or Al Pacino or Marlon
Brando.
</P>
<P>
   It was Salvatore ``Sammy the Bull'' Gravano, the real deal, and
the most important thing he said _ for which we can thank our
government _ was this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm part of the community.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 0002EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
