<HEADLINE>
STERN'S `BEACH' NOT EXACTLY A GREAT PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Babes in bikinis, tasteless humor, Howard Stern as executive
producer _ a combo like that should have every 15-year-old boy in
America (and everyone who thinks like one) salivating.
</P>
<P>
   So why won't they be laughing at the new FX series ``Son of the
Beac''h? Simple. It's not very funny.
</P>
<P>
   Please don't mistake this as an anti-Stern rant. I am a somewhat
reluctant fan of his radio show. But with the exception of a couple
of gleefully tasteless scenes, ``Son of the Beach'' falls flat.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Stack, whom you may remember as the star of the funnier
``Night Stand with Dick Dietrick,'' if you remember him at all,
stars as ``Beac''h's pasty-white, dumpy-lifeguard hero. He
supervises other lifeguards with more curves than brains _ the men
and the women. The evil mayor is out to get him, for reasons that
aren't really clear; she enlists a spy to help her in the first
episode, titled ``With Sex You Get Egg Roll.''
</P>
<P>
   The obvious comparisons to ``Baywatch'' are purely coincidental,
Stern said in a conference call recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``This show has as much to do with ``Baywatch'' as ``Get Smart''
had to do with 007,'' he said. ``It's its own program. It's a
ridiculous notion that we're doing ``Baywatch.'' It's a beach full
of lifeguards, which points up the ridiculousness of beach shows
and lifeguards. But other than that, I don't think I can draw a
comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Don't sue.
</P>
<P>
   The first episode has its moments. It's funny when a caption
says, ``Somewhere in the Orient'' and ``Orient'' gets scratched out
and replaced by ``Asia.'' It's funny when Stack's character makes a
joke about his childhood that we can't repeat here. And it's funny
that the evil mayor's evil son is named Cody _ also the name of the
son of Stern's archenemy, a certain soon-to-be-former co-host of
``Live With Regis and Kathie Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, well . . .
</P>
<P>
   Stack, who is also a producer and writer for the show, said he
got the idea for ``Son of the Beach'' while watching ``Police
Squad,'' the series that spawned the ``Naked Gun'' movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gave us the impetus for this show,'' he said, ``which was
`Let's just do something that just is funny.' There's nothing
redeeming. We're not trying to make a message. We just want to make
something funny. It's like a throwback to shows like ``F-Troop''
and ``Hogan's Heroes,'' except with really hot women.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Son of the Beach'' is to make any noise at all _ an
unlikely notion _ it will be for any controversy its
double-entendre-heavy humor is able to stir, especially among
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is fun and light and there is nothing politically
correct about it,'' Stern said. ``We don't even care if women are
not satisfied in this program.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a given they won't be. The trouble this show will have is
when no one else is, either. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 0010EST &QL; 
