<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6105 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-BENCHMARK-2NDTAKE-KAN     03-14 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENCHMARK-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
[START 
</HEADLINE>
  
 OLATHE, Kan. _ carrying it out.'' (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While planning continues for the national expansion, Benchmark also
is spending $16 million to renovate existing stores near 87th
Street in Lenexa and to build a store at 135th Street and Antioch
Road.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the new, 100,000-square-foot Benchmark Town &AMP;
Country store is scheduled to begin late this fall, Davidow said.
The store will be aimed at the high-end furniture market.
</P>
<P>
   In total, the company is spending about $30 million to create 1
million square feet of retail and warehouse space in Johnson
County, Kan. The company's total of 340 employees should top 500 by
the end of the year, Davidow said.
</P>
<P>
   The Davidow name has been around the Kansas City furniture
business for more than 70 years, but brothers Bob and Jerry started
in 1969. Their first business was manufacturing tractor seats,
before they turned to retailing with Foam City, which sold foam and
materials to recover furniture.
</P>
<P>
   They've come a ways since then. Bob Davidow says Benchmark is
projecting revenue of about $100 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Benchmark is ranked No. 94 on the Furniture Today
magazine list of the nation's top 100 furniture stores, with
furniture sales estimated at $39 million and total sales at $57
million.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a bad spot, considering most of the retailers on the
list are national chains with multiple stores.
</P>
<P>
   It's what you don't see at Benchmark that makes the concept
work.
</P>
<P>
   Although the roomlike furniture setups, wide aisles and
restaurants seem to impress customers as they stroll the store,
technology keeps it running.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without technology, we couldn't do it,'' Bob Davidow said.
``We couldn't manage the numbers. Things are happening in real
time, and we have to have the technology to keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the technology is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first things a customer sees when entering the store
are computers with interactive displays with the store layout.
Customers seeking help inside the store can press a button that
pages a salesperson. If no one comes within 45 seconds, other
clerks are automatically beeped. If no one comes at that point, Bob
Davidow is paged.
</P>
<P>
   Salespeople carry laptop computers connected to a company
intranet by wireless modem. Customers can sit on the sofa they've
chosen while a salesperson applies for credit for their purchase
and processes the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We notice these things now because they're new and it's
whiz-bang,'' Davidow said. ``It's not going to be new and different
like that long. It's going to be part of every landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   The heart of Benchmark's business plan is a computer system that
keeps track of furniture inventory, and a warehouse that tracks
where that inventory is located.
</P>
<P>
   Customers interested in an item can pull a tag and take it to a
nearby computer to see if the item is in stock. That tag also is
scanned by a salesperson at purchase. And it's scanned again when
the customer arrives at the kiosk entrance to the warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Once the tag is scanned at the kiosk, the computer assigns the
customer a delivery dock and alerts workers in the warehouse,
telling them where the item is and which dock to deliver it to.
Every purchase is delivered within 15 minutes, Davidow said.
</P>
<P>
   The evening after the sale, the computer links with computers
owned by furniture manufacturers to tell them to send merchandise
to restock the warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   One part of the warehouse is dedicated to packaging Internet
shipments. On a recent day, warehouse workers were opening,
inspecting and repackaging Internet shipments to Boston, Florida
and California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire industry is waiting to see how business-to-consumer
and business-to-business commerce is going to work out,'' said
Epperson, the analyst at Mann Armistead &AMP; Epperson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't deliver furniture in a box the way you do with a CD
or a book. Getting it into the consumer's home, that's the problem.
Consumers won't accept any imperfection.''
</P>
<P>
   And furniture almost always comes with some imperfection, part
of the shipping process.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a huge advantage Benchmark has,'' Epperson said. ``They
know how to handle the furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   The order-by-Internet, same-day-pickup plan makes just as much
financial sense for the company. Online retailer Furniture.com, for
instance, spent $3.6 million on shipping in 1999 while selling only
$10.9 million in furniture. The bottom line: The company lost $43.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   Other furniture retailers say they either welcome or are
unconcerned about the challenge from the Benchmark superstore
concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition is good. It draws more customers to the area,''
said Jim Loftus, general manager of the Olathe Rhodes Furniture
store across the highway from the Benchmark complex. ``Furniture
typically isn't a one-stop shopping event.''
</P>
<P>
   In Omaha, Batt said the new Benchmark complex wouldn't hurt his
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to sit here and say we're going to have
trouble,'' Batt said. ``People like to come up here and stay the
weekend and go shopping with us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about how big you are. It's about customers saying,
`Don't waste my time. Don't have me wait in line.' It's not about
building monuments. It's not a one-up contest. It's a `take care of
the customer' contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Dukelow, manager of Thomasville Home Furnishings By Ed
Marlings in Shawnee, Kan., is seeing competition for the first time
for the Thomasville line of furniture. But it doesn't bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at it as a positive,'' Dukelow said. ``His
influx of advertising dollars will draw more interest to the
market. I've always been jealous of his advertising budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Orman recently opened T. Orman's Furniture and Flooring in
south Overland Park, Kan., at a location where he and his brother
used to run a furniture store together. He said T. Orman's wouldn't
be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``His business is almost the antithesis of ours,'' Orman said of
Benchmark. ``His store will bifurcate the market. He will draw
those people who want instant gratification and aren't worried
about quality. We will continue to draw those people who want to
put some emotional investment into their purchase.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
