<SLUG> BC-BENCHMARK-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENCHMARK OWNERS HOPE TO SPREAD FURNITURE SUPERSTORE CONCEPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
c. 2000 Kansas City Star OLATHE, Kan. _ Bob Davidow has built what
may be the largest furniture store in the country in an old
printing plant and some former farm fields in Olathe.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new Benchmark furniture complex southwest of 119th Street
and Interstate 35 drew between 8,000 and 10,000 customers during
its opening weekend March 4 and 5. Customers apparently liked what
they saw, spending more than $1 million during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Davidow and his brother, Jerry Davidow, want to take on the
rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   As the Davidows and their families opened the final phase of the
725,000-square-foot furniture ``campus'' in Olathe, they already
were meeting with potential partners to build even larger stores in
15 other U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   The Davidows want to use the network of stores, accompanying
warehouses and the Internet to build a $3 billion-a-year ``click
and brick'' business that would capture 5 percent of the $60
billion U.S. retail furniture market within six years.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Davidow says the click-and-mortar approach _ allowing people
to shop on the Internet, drive to the store to check out the
furniture and take it home with them _ is the best way for the
furniture industry to grow in the Internet economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new model for the furniture industry,'' Davidow
said. ``E-commerce sites that don't incorporate a physical location
will never work. We'll win because we offer both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where would you rather shop: a Web site where you order a
product and it might come in six weeks or three months, probably
damaged or the wrong color, or someplace where you can see it
online and pick it up the same day?'' Davidow said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Benchmark stores in Johnson County, the national
stores will carry the name BeHome, the address of the furniture
retailer's Web site. BeHome.com, which went online in 1995, was the
first furniture retailer on the Internet and one of the earliest
e-commerce sites.
</P>
<P>
   Davidow says the company plans to build the BeHome stores on the
outskirts of metropolitan areas with populations of 3 million or
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to drive to get to us. We're a destination
store,'' Davidow said. ``The goal is to be within a three-hour
drive of 80 percent of the U.S. population.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for Benchmark to choose a financial partner and a
location for its first superstore by the end of the year and open
the store in mid- to late 2001. The plan calls for all 15 stores to
open within six years.
</P>
<P>
   Each store//warehouse complex will have 1 million square feet _
600,000 square feet of retail space and a 400,000-square-foot
warehouse. Each would cost about $65 million, Davidow said.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, each store would gross between $180 and $200 million in
sales annually, with a profit of between $22 and $24 million, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   News of Davidow's plan took furniture suppliers by surprise when
he announced it during an industry breakfast meeting a few days
before the Olathe store opened. The expansion plans were featured
on the covers of the retail furniture industry's two leading trade
magazines last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Davidow has always had the industry's attention, said Jerry
Epperson, retail furniture's leading industry analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the industry, if you were to pick up the phone and call
25 people and ask them what's really going on in the furniture
industry, 23 of the 25 would tell you to call Bob Davidow,'' said
Epperson, of Richmond, Va. ``They'd say, `All I know is what Bob
told me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just any old furniture store where you can eat at a
restaurant that serves a pretty mean grilled salmon sandwich with
curried mayonnaise or a portabello mushroom sandwich with grilled
onions.
</P>
<P>
   But Benchmark in Olathe isn't just any old furniture store.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Dexter's Restaurant, which more or less gets lost
inside the Benchmark campus. It offers made-to-order dishes, not
cafeteria food. It is managed by former Hyatt Regency Crown Center
hotel executive Dexter Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   The 230-seat restaurant includes four tables equipped with
computers and Internet access. ``If people want to check our prices
online, they can,'' Davidow said. ``We can take it.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's only one of four food stops in the furniture store, all
operated by Myron Green Food Service Inc. The restaurants alone
employ about 30 persons.
</P>
<P>
   A coffee bar near the restaurant offers scones, bisciotti and
``cascading cappuccino.'' Across the store is Bob and Jerry's _ an
old-fashioned ice cream parlor that won't put Ben &AMP; Jerry's out of
business, but is a bit of a nod to Benchmark's corporate sense of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there's furniture. Lots of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Working with St. Louis-based furniture manufacturer Furniture
Brands International, Benchmark built a 160,000-square-foot store
(about the size of a SuperTarget store) to showcase that company's
product line.
</P>
<P>
   The new store was so large it even surprised Lynn Chipperfield,
senior vice president of Furniture Brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can turn 360 degrees and everywhere you look is our
product,'' Chipperfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Adjoining the new store is Benchmark Express, which carries
lower-priced furniture and also houses Benchmark's home office
center.
</P>
<P>
   Benchmark bought and remodeled the former Ringier America Inc.
printing plant and opened Benchmark Express six years ago. Last
year the company converted warehouse space in the rear of the
building into retail space. The facility now is about 240,000
square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Davidow says it takes 45 minutes _ without stopping to shop _ to
cover the entire Benchmark campus.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of hundred yards behind the store is a
state-of-the-art, computerized, 325,000-square-foot warehouse with
67 cargo doors _ 34 for customers to take merchandise away and 33
for truckers to bring furniture in.
</P>
<P>
   Davidow thinks long delays in furniture delivery hurt the
business in the 1980s and 1990s. ``People just weren't satisfied
waiting weeks and weeks and then having their furniture come in
damaged, or the wrong color,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking that cycle means keeping an inventory of about $20
million worth of furniture. ``It takes a lot of stock to be able to
say you'll have everything available the same day,'' Davidow said.
</P>
<P>
   The Olathe facility probably has the distinction of being the
largest furniture store in the country, overshadowing even the
Nebraska Furniture Mart in Omaha, Neb. The sprawling Omaha store,
owned by Berkshire Hathaway Inc., bills itself as ``the largest
single home-furnishings retailer in North America.''
</P>
<P>
   Note to Berkshire billionaire Warren Buffett: Better rethink
that.
</P>
<P>
   The Olathe Benchmark complex has 400,000 square feet of retail
furniture space. Nebraska Furniture Mart has about 500,000 square
feet of retail space _ but more than 100,000 is used for
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage Benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   Bragging rights are fun, but in the long run ``I'm not sure that
it means anything,'' Davidow said.
</P>
<P>
   His competitors also are downplaying the size issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Davidow has never done anything understated,'' said Robert
Batt, executive vice president of Nebraska Furniture. ``Now it's a
matter of carrying it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
