<HEADLINE>
COUNTRY MUSIC STAR FROM KANSAS GIVES BACK TO HER COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM PERRIN  
c. 2000 Kansas City Star WELLSVILLE, Kan. _ Chely Wright has
performed at venues from coast to coast and even overseas. This
weekend, she's scheduled to sing at the Grand Ole Opry, the country
music mecca in Nashville.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But on Monday she was in Wellsville, performing a free
mini-concert in a gym full of students, school employees and
townspeople at Wellsville School, where she graduated in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the weirdest phenomenon,'' said Wright, whose father,
Stan, still lives nearby in Spring Hill, Kan. ``Looking at all the
people around who taught me algebra or punched my lunch ticket, I
no longer feel like the country music star who has traveled around
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The occasion for Wright's visit was to announce her new
charitable foundation's first donation _ about $6,000 worth of
musical instruments, sheet music and money to Wellsville schools.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, ``Reading, Writing &AMP; Rhythm,'' was formed to
benefit music programs in small-town schools. Wright is hoping to
make two more donations of similar size later this year to schools
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want any kid to miss out on (participating in music
programs) because they don't have money,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, 29, performed three of her singles, ``Shut Up and
Drive,'' ``Single White Female'' and ``It Was,'' which is No. 15 on
the Billboard magazine country chart. ``Single White Female'' was
her first No. 1 single.
</P>
<P>
   Wright had the crowd on its feet and clapping throughout her
acoustic set. She took questions from students and talked about how
she enjoys sharing memories of Wellsville in media interviews.
</P>
<P>
   After the visit to the school, Wright, some associates and
fan-club members made a few stops around town where she talked to
old friends.
</P>
<P>
   Wright was born in Kansas City, Mo., but attended Wellsville
schools from kindergarten through 12th grade. She said she was
involved in band, choir and journalism in high school.
</P>
<P>
   She was a member of the girls basketball team that played in a
state tournament in 1988. Earlier that season, when the 3-point
basket was adopted, she became the first Wellsville athlete to make
one in a game.
</P>
<P>
   But music was always her main interest, and she left for
Nashville, Tenn., to begin her career after graduating. Monday, she
encouraged students to believe in themselves and pursue their
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope what Chely said today, young people will take with
them,'' Stan Wright said. ``It can happen for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   She's keeping pretty good company these days. She is one of five
nominees for the Academy of Country Music's female vocalist of the
year, along with Faith Hill, Martina McBride, Jo Dee Messina and
Shania Twain. The winner will be announced May 3.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Johnson, a sophomore who plays tuba in the school band,
said not all his classmates are country fans, but most everyone has
at least one of Wright's recordings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of shocking to see someone like her come from this
town,'' he said. ``I guess she actually cares. It's nice that she
came back and she's proud of her hometown.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
