<HEADLINE>
FBI'S 10 MOST WANTED LIST CELEBRATES 50 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
c. 2000 Kansas City Star KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ With a nod to its roots
in Kansas City's colorful criminal past, the FBI's 10 Most Wanted
Fugitives list celebrates its golden anniversary Tuesday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas James Holden _ the list's first of 458 members _ had a
long local history that included an escape from the federal
penitentiary in Leavenworth, Kan., in 1930 and his recapture in
1932 on a Kansas City golf course.
</P>
<P>
   After his official release from prison, Holden landed on the
FBI's first top-10 list when he murdered his wife and her two
brothers after a Chicago drinking party. FBI agents arrested him in
1951 near Beaverton, Ore., when a resident recognized him from a
picture in a local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's anniversary observes half a century of media and
public assistance in putting violent criminals in jail,'' said
Larry McCormick, special agent in charge of the Kansas City FBI
office.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's top-10 list got its start in 1949 when a reporter
asked the FBI for a roster of the ``toughest guys'' it wanted to
capture.
</P>
<P>
   Impressed with public reaction to the resulting story in the
Washington Daily News, FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover formally
initiated the program on March 14, 1950.
</P>
<P>
   That bond forged between citizens, the bureau and the press
remains the list's greatest strength, FBI officials said.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of the 429 top-10 arrests have come after
citizens referred information to the bureau, McCormick said. In
recent years, the bureau has attributed 13 arrests to the
television program ``America's Most Wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   As a public relations tool, the program works because it gets to
the point, said Bob Bernstein of Bernstein-Rein Advertising Inc. He
wouldn't change a thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple, clean format,'' Bernstein said. ``It goes right
to the heart of the issue and (FBI officials have) stayed focused
with it. If you keep something that goes to the point and stays
with the issue, it transcends the time barrier.''
</P>
<P>
   The list has changed over the years. Lists in the 1950s were
made up primarily of bank robbers, burglars and car thieves.
</P>
<P>
   Social revolutionaries populated the lists of the turbulent
1960s, which also featured the first appearance of James Earl Ray
for the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr. in 1968. Ray
appeared again on the list nine years later following his escape
from a Tennessee prison.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's emphasis on organized crime and terrorism in the 1970s
continues on the list today, with the addition last summer of
accused terrorist Osama bin Laden and alleged East Coast mobster
James J. Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   Serial murderers such as Ted Bundy or particularly notorious
killers, such as Andrew Cunanan, also have found a place on recent
lists.
</P>
<P>
   During the past 50 years, 23 of the top-10 fugitives committed
their crimes in Missouri and Kansas. Eighteen top-10 criminals were
arrested in Missouri and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Robert J. Mahoney, chairman of Rockhurst University's
sociology department, said the list is a good reflection of the
nation's law enforcement priorities at any particular moment and a
way to bring attention to an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Why else, Mahoney noted, would bin Laden have been included?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not likely he's going to turn up in New Jersey,'' Mahoney
said. ``The point of it is to draw attention to the issue of
terrorism. This does have some consequences. It puts pressure on
somebody like bin Laden and puts attention on him worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Several factors are considered before putting a fugitive on the
list, according to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees from all 56 FBI field offices are reviewed by the
bureau's Criminal Investigative Division and Office of Public and
Congressional Affairs in Washington, D.C. Proposed ``top-tenners''
then are forwarded to the FBI director for final approval.
</P>
<P>
   Potential candidates must be a ``particularly dangerous menace
to society'' or have a long history of serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the FBI must believe that national publicity will help the
bureau arrest the fugitive. That publicity already has gone beyond
print and broadcast media and even international boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   A central attraction at the bureau's Web site, www.fbi.gov, the
list already has notched its first arrest resulting from Internet
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a Web surfer sparked an intense manhunt in Guatemala
for bank robbery suspect Leslie Isben Rogge after his picture
showed up on theInternet. Rogge quickly surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to new technology, the 10 Most Wanted list remains
effective, shedding its G-Man quaintness and is heading into
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
