<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERNANDEZ'S SAVE ON PENALTY SHOT SPARKS STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Don't go down too early. Whatever you do don't go
down too early.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Stars goalie Manny Fernandez said that to himself as New
York Rangers winger Radek Dvorak came swooping in on a penalty shot
with 29.5 seconds remaining in the second period Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had looked like a fool earlier by going down too early on
(Petr) Nedved's goal,'' Fernandez said, explaining his thinking.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't go down. Dvorak, unlike Nedved, didn't score. A half
of a period later, Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner did.
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, what easily could've and probably should've
been a Stars loss instead became a 4-3 Stars victory against a
desperate and hungry Rangers bunch at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought all period to try to get it back to tied and go into
the third 3-3. That would've been a real back breaker,'' Stars
center Mike Modano said of Dvorak's penalty shot. ``Manny made a
big save.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Fernandez's blocker save allowed his teammates to squeak
into the locker room deadlocked instead of down. Langenbrunner's
goal, his second of the night, allowed them to squeak out of New
York with their second victory in as many nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a typical Dallas win right there,'' Stars
captain Derian Hatcher said. ``Lately.''
</P>
<P>
   The typical part is they've been atypical. The usual defensive
wall has shown a few cracks.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars played the first period as if they were ``stuck in the
mud,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. They were outshot 14-8. They
were outscored 2-1. Exactly 2:49 had expired in the second period
when the Rangers took a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Hatcher wasn't kidding when he said these are the kind of
games the Stars win lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another team lets down, gets comfortable, and I think, that's
when we take advantage of that team,'' Hatcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Scott Thornton took advantage of a pretty Joe
Nieuwendyk pass to slice New York's lead to 3-2 at 7:03 of the
second period. The game-tying goal came as a result of the
forechecking by the Stars' fourth line of Kirk Muller, Roman
Lyashenko and Jon Sim with the actual goal coming from Sim at 16:10
of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The game was once again tied. The Stars were on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   But there was Dvorak breaking down the ice all by himself. Well,
until Stars defenseman Sergei Zubov hauled him down. The referee
didn't hesitate, his arm going up immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to take him the first time around, but I guess we
had the rematch going,'' Fernandez joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually was just happy he didn't wind up from the red line.
That probably could've gone in.''
</P>
<P>
   Because while Fernandez stopped Dvorak's shot _ one of his 31
saves _ with his blocker, he wasn't doing so well with the easier
stuff. The reason the Rangers had a 3-1 lead was because Fernandez
struggled near the end of the first and beginning of the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kind of gave them a couple of freebies early and then
stoned them from there,'' Hitchcock said. ``He was good at the end,
eh?''
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy subbing for usual starter Ed Belfour, who
hasn't played since being charged with misdemeanor assault and
resisting arrest on Wednesday. His best save wasn't even on the
penalty shot. He made another two in the final 10 seconds to
preserve the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was created by Langenbrunner, who scored the Stars'
first and last goals. The game winner was a beauty, too, sneaking
between Rangers goalie Mike Richter and the post at 11:43 of the
third period. The play began when Modano chipped the puck away from
two Rangers along the boards, allowing Langenbrunner to skate in
pretty free. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
