<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LeBRETON-MARINO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WASN'T ON HIS OWN TERMS, BUT MARINO AT PEACE WITH DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it's true that you can judge a man by the company he keeps,
what should history make of Dan Marino?
</P>
<P>
   His NFL passing records are so gaudy as to invite chuckles.
Marino threw 48 touchdown passes in the 1984 season. The number is
exactly as many as Troy Aikman has thrown _ total _ in the past
three Cowboys seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was Marino who said goodbye to football Monday on what
was anything but his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Vikings had called, and coach Dennis Green had
tempted the 17-year veteran last week with talk about a
championship waiting to be won. Sure, Marino said Monday, ``you get
excited when a coach calls you.''
</P>
<P>
   But the coach of the Miami Dolphins never called, nor did the
former head coach. The ``Dan thing,'' as new Dolphins coach Dave
Wannstedt called it, lingered in the South Florida air like swamp
gas.
</P>
<P>
   Marino announced the proper decision Monday. At age 38, and with
remnants of a pinched neck nerve and an old Achilles' injury in his
past, Marino didn't need to be wearing a purple Vikings jersey,
running for his life in the shotgun, trying to learn somebody's new
system.
</P>
<P>
   At the tail end of his Broadway marquee career, Joe Namath
ignominiously slipped into a Los Angeles Rams uniform. Johnny
Unitas tried to play out the string as a San Diego Charger. Both
moves produced more winces than memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it comes down to a football decision and a health
decision,'' Marino told a news gathering in Davie, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In the audience beside the media were more than a dozen former
teammates and coaches, including his former coach, Hall of Famer
Don Shula. Marino has such poise and presence that he thanked
nearly every one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say I've been blessed with a career greater than I could
imagine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to miss it. I'm going to miss everything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, despite the footprints that Wannstedt left in running
away from the issue, the Dolphins didn't want Dan Marino anymore.
His health and rumored declining skills had been an issue with
Wannstedt's predecessor, and his 1999 season was a washout. He
arrived in Texas Stadium on Thanksgiving Day, after being out five
games with the neck injury, and the Cowboys intercepted Marino five
times en route to a 20-0 stroll.
</P>
<P>
   Could he have returned? Well, Marino plays golf with the boss,
owner Wayne Huizenga, so anything was possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I could've,'' Marino said, fumbling for the right words.
``But circumstances, last year, things like that ... I felt I
probably wouldn't be a Dolphin after that last game. ''
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuous by his absence from the news conference was the
``circumstances'' himself, Jimmy Johnson. Maybe Johnson felt he was
not invited. Maybe he hadn't been reading the newspapers for the
past 62 days.
</P>
<P>
   To not attend Marino's retirement announcement was tacky, at
best, and mostly inexcusable.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Marino, a class act to the end, took the high road.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Johnson, Marino answered, ``I would just have
to say that our relationship was up and down at times. We had some
great days together, some fun times. Sometimes I wasn't very happy
here, while he was coaching. And that's just being honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson looked upon Marino as an anchor, dragging down his Super
Bowl cruise ship. Dolphins fans, on the other hand, looked at
Marino with nothing but reverence.
</P>
<P>
   Marino's charitable work within the community included helping
to finance a wing of a new children's hospital. He is as revered in
South Florida as Shula.
</P>
<P>
   NFL perfectionists will argue that because he never won a Super
Bowl, Marino's career work was an incomplete canvas, and thus to be
footnoted accordingly. A national publication last November rated
him no higher than sixth on the list of NFL's great quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl victory, Marino sighed Monday, just wasn't meant
to be. He said that he is at peace with his decision to retire.
</P>
<P>
   It was the proper conclusion, but the Dolphins aided and abetted
it poorly.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Dan thing'' will leave a taint on the new Dolphins regime
all the way to the Super Bowl _ should they ever, ever get there.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 0113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
