<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TO-EUROPE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TO VISIT EUROPEAN LEADERS. WILL THERE BE A QUIZ?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors)   (This 925-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Plans are being laid for a visit by George W. Bush,
the Republican presidential candidate, to Europe ahead of this
year's election. The aim would be to help him get to know some of
the leading figures on the world stage, but also to reinforce
Bush's stature.
</P>
<P>
   The challengers in the presidential election, irascible and
independent-minded John McCain and the sleepy if smart Bill
Bradley, have now withdrawn. That leaves Republican George W. Bush,
the governor of Texas and Democrat Al Gore, vice president. Both
are mainstream, slightly dull figures with highly-polished
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   As Molly Ivins, doyenne of the Texas press put it last week:
``Oh, pooh, the fun's over.'' Or as Gail Collins put it in the New
York Times, ``Maybe it will be good for our character. It's really
superficial, you know, this desire for a chief executive with
charisma.''
</P>
<P>
   But the race between the two candidates is very close, and Bush
has lost what was a double-digit margin in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is slightly ahead, according to the latest opinion polls.
At 43 percent to 40 percent, according to NBC and the Wall Street
Journal, the gap is within the polls' margin of error; but the
trend is clear.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has a potentially more serious problem: he is simply not
seen as presidential material by many people. When voters were
asked about ``the right experience and the ability to do the job of
president,'' nearly half preferred Gore; less than a third picked
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel battle-tested and that's what a lot of people wanted to
see,'' said Bush last week. ``I think the people saw I could get
whipped and bounce back.'' But he has a broader problem of stature
which the campaign has not resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are gearing up for the campaign now, with months to
go until the party conventions. Some time before then _ perhaps in
May _ both campaigns are considering international tours, including
visits to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is already well-known on the international stage; for Bush,
a trip abroad is a more important venture.
</P>
<P>
   In part, it is his evident lack of knowledge of international
affairs that has hurt him. Bush is a fine man, but apparently he
thinks that Canada is run by a plate of chips and cottage cheese.
</P>
<P>
   The governor was campaigning in Michigan when a reporter
delivered the news that the Canadian prime minister, Jean Poutine,
had endorsed him. ``I'm honored,'' said Bush. ``I appreciate his
strong statement. He understands our belief in free trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the prime minister of Canada is Jean Chretien. Poutine is
a favorite dish of the Quebecois, an unpalatable mess which few
beyond Canada care to sample.
</P>
<P>
   Ignorance of these matters is hardly crippling in itself _ few
Americans take much notice of politics up north, let alone Canadian
cuisine, and the Canadian prankster who tried it on with Bush has
had plenty of success with many other politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that cheap shots at Bush's knowledge of foreign
affairs are becoming all too common.
</P>
<P>
   His uneasy relationship with spoken English does not help.
``When I was coming up, it was a dangerous world and we knew
exactly who the they were. It was us versus them, and it was clear
who them was. Today, we're not so sure who the they are. But we
know they're there,'' he said on one memorable occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is madmen in the world, and there are terror,'' he said
on another.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, by contrast, has little to worry about in terms of the
legacy of the campaign. One of his weaknesses going into the
election was that (like many vice presidents) he had come to be
seen as ineffectual, but the campaign has started to change that.
</P>
<P>
   His fight against Bradley showed him to be tough and
resourceful, even vicious at times. He will be attacked for being
part of President Bill Clinton's administration, but by contrast he
has few weaknesses when it comes to experience.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has relatively little track record in politics by
comparison. He has been governor of Texas since 1994, but the post
carries fewer responsibilities than in many other states. The
state's legislature meets only every other year; it is not an
especially arduous job.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem for Bush is that he seems lightweight. The
jokes and cartoons of him play on the image; one columnist last
week referred to the contest between the two candidates as the
pinhead versus the sleaze, meaning Gore.
</P>
<P>
   While the latter description will please Bush, the former won't.
The Democrats had hoped since last year to paint Bush as an ``Empty
Suit,'' and that view seems to be gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, by contrast, may be no John Kennedy but he does at least
have a certain solidity.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``whined his way through several states yearning for his
family, his dog and his own no-steam shaving mirror back home,''
says columnist Collins. ``Mr. Gore just seems to be real, real good
at enduring discomfort. In the age of indulgence, we've got a stoic
running for president.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one other question about Bush's stature. In the last
twelve presidential elections, the shorter candidate has won only
twice, in 1972 and 1976. Bush is five feet eleven inches, a little
taller in his cowboy boots. Gore is six feet one inch. Even a visit
to see Tony Blair can't change that. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
