<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARINO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINO RETIRES WITH 25 NFL RECORDS, BUT NO RING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seventeen was enough for Miami Dolphins quarterback Dan Marino.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having never won a Super Bowl, the NFL's all-time
leading passer passed on a chance to return for an 18th season.
Marino made his retirement official Monday, four days after
reaching the decision during a family meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to miss it,'' Marino said, pausing to compose
himself. ``I'm going to miss everything about it. I'm going to miss
the relationships with the players. I'm going to miss the fans. I'm
going to miss the great friends I've made over this time. I'm going
to miss all the good times we've had together. Most of all, I'm
going to miss Sunday afternoons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Vikings had offered Marino a one-year contract and
a starting job. Instead, he opted to retire with the team that
drafted him 27th in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins owner Wayne Huizenga announced that the team will honor
Marino by retiring his No. 13, placing a statue of him outside Pro
Player Stadium and naming a street for him.
</P>
<P>
   Marino said loyalty to the Dolphins, his unwillingness to be
separated from his wife and five children and health concerns were
factors in his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Marino, who turns 39 in September, has endured 291 sacks and
eight operations in his career. Last season he missed five games
with a neck injury, which affected his arm strength when he
returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, I really struggled with this,'' Marino said. ``This has
been the toughest month of my life as far as dealing with playing
football or retiring. After the season, I pretty much thought that
I was not going to play anymore, and I felt that way for a while. I
think it was because of the physical aspects of the game. It kept
coming back to how my legs felt during last season and going
through the neck injury and not knowing whether I was going to be
able to throw the football.''
</P>
<P>
   Throwing the football is what Marino did better than anyone in
history. He leaves with 25 NFL records, including attempts (8,358),
completions (4,967), yards (61,361) and touchdowns (420), and is
tied for five others.
</P>
<P>
   But while Marino was good, he was never lucky enough to win a
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, he threw for 5,084 yards and 48 touchdowns, NFL
regular-season records that still stand, but the Dolphins lost to
the San Francisco 49ers, 38-16, in Super Bowl XIX. Miami has lost
in the AFC Championship Game twice in the 15 seasons since.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (a Super Bowl title) was the only reason really to
continue to play,'' said Marino, who was 155-103, including
playoffs, as a starter. ``That has been a dream of mine my whole
career. I'm not going to have that chance, but it does not take
away from what I've done personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga, who became the team's sole owner in 1994, hugged
Marino and apologized for the Dolphins having never won a
championship for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But just because you didn't win a Super Bowl doesn't mean that
you're not a champion, because we all know otherwise,'' Huizenga
said.
</P>
<P>
   Marino admitted he ``sometimes wasn't happy'' during Jimmy
Johnson's four seasons as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson retired Jan. 16, a day after the Dolphins suffered the
worst loss in team history, a 62-7 playoff defeat to the
Jacksonville Jaguars. It ended a tumultuous season for Marino and
Johnson, who had frequently criticized his quarterback for poor
decisions and costly turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Marino, who had been scheduled to make $7.5 million in 2000,
voided his contract in February and became a free agent. Then, the
Dolphins signed free- agent quarterback Jay Fiedler to a
three-year, $3.8 million contract to compete with Damon Huard for
the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a sense of loss that's huge right now, because I know
I'm not going to be out there playing anymore,'' Marino said.
``...I will not play football again.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
