<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' SHORTFALL WON'T BE IN ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Watching the Texas Rangers take batting
practice Monday morning, Toronto manager Jim Fregosi hinted at some
logical skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, they plan to do it this season with pitching and
defense?'' he asked. The tone of doubt was obvious, particularly
since Fregosi already knew the answer to his question.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing unusual about any of that this spring. Outside of the
Rangers' camp in the Charlotte County swamps, there's not exactly a
roll call needed of baseball types who believe this is a team that
can suddenly wean itself off the long-standing tradition of
bats-outta-hell.
</P>
<P>
   But another voice at Charlotte County Stadium Monday morning
belonged to Rangers pitching coach Dick Bosman, entering his sixth
season on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Normally scrambling for staff answers three weeks into spring
training, Bosman said something totally out of character. ``We've
been good,'' he volunteered, ``and we're going to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Clip and save. Ironically, however, the afternoon exhibition
game with the Blue Jays added a tad of credence to Bosman's show of
optimism. Even for mid-March, the six innings worked by Kenny
Rogers were so crisp, an old-timer like Fregosi offered a verbal
tip of the cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rogers is ready for the season right now,'' Fregosi said. ``He
could have gone nine (innings) easy.
</P>
<P>
   In a 6-1 victory for the Rangers, the only thing that apparently
kept Rogers from a complete game was a 60-pitch limit in his third
Florida outing. The lefty threw 59, which for six innings is a
dominating performance of pitch location and pitching know-how.
Plus, the Toronto lineup was sprinkled with some large bats.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring's big picture, the four definite rotation members
(Rogers, Esteban Loaiza, Darren Oliver and Rick Helling) have now
given up only eight earned runs in 27 innings, and five of those
are from Helling. The leading candidate to fill in for the
rehabilitating Justin Thompson is Mark Clark, who thus far has done
a 180-degree spin from his awful 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us have been around long enough to know what happens
down here has to be tempered with caution,'' Bosman said. ``But
given continued health, what we are seeing thus far will translate
into the regular season. With these guys, it's not a guessing game.
They've all been around for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, the Rangers plan on Thompson being the rotation No. 1.
That's what the Juan Gonzzlez trade was all about. But there will
be no rushing Thompson's recovery from shoulder surgery in August.
Him being ready by the first of May is the ``cautious'' timetable.
</P>
<P>
   But it is interesting that Rogers almost immediately became the
No. 1 while Thompson is out. Manager Johnny Oates hasn't named him
the Opening Day starter, but Oates did set up his Florida rotation
that way. That probably says more about Helling's erratic 1999
season than anything Rogers has accomplished in a long major-league
career that came full circle when free-agent Rogers re-signed with
the Rangers this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Kenny's attitude and approach,'' said Bosman, before
Rogers' performance against the Blue Jays. ``I just think he's
wiser and smarter for the places he's been and what he's had to
endure. I see that, and I've been struck by it.''
</P>
<P>
   When last spotted in October, Rogers was walking home the
winning run in Game 6 of the National League Championship Series.
The Braves went to the World Series. The Mets didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who knew me when I was with the Rangers before probably
thought I'd come in here this spring full of anger,'' said Rogers,
smiling. ``Not that something like that doesn't nick your
confidence a bit, but you learn to deal with stuff. I've never been
afraid of failing, but what I've had to learn is how to become
stronger when I do fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a challenge-em-with-the-fastball kind of pitcher, the
35-year-old Rogers now almost refers to himself as a junk-baller.
``There are going to be people see me pitch and wonder how does he
get anybody out with that stuff,'' he said after Monday's outing.
``But when I had the good fastball, I wish I'd have known then what
I know now. You don't have to overpower hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fregosi was looking at it from the other dugout Monday.
``Kenny has become a pitcher, and it's hard for a guy who used to
throw as hard as he did to make the transition,'' Fregosi said. ``I
give him credit for that. Frank Tanana is one of the few who made
that transition. Kenny will eat up a lot of innings this season.''
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of Bosman, the Rogers fastball has also returned
this spring and was evident Monday with six strikeouts. The
velocity isn't the same, but as a surprise pitch on the inside
corner ... well, that's called pitching.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of people still have to be convinced the Rangers have
enough of it. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
