<HEADLINE>
KINGS TRADE AUDETTE, KABERLE TO ATLANTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Donald Audette, who lost his spot on the second
line because of injuries and inconsistency, wanted a trade and got
one Monday when the Kings sent him and minor leaguer Frantisek
Kaberle to Atlanta for power forward Kelly Buchberger and winger
Nelson Emerson.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had been trying to move Audette since mid-season and
had few takers. He had come from Buffalo last season after missing
half a season in a contract dispute. Audette has scored at least 24
goals five times in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Audette, who scored just one goal in 11 games since returning
from a badly sprained left ankle, had requested the club trade him
after his ice time began to dwindle. In 49 games this season,
Audette had 12 goals and 32 points.
</P>
<P>
   Audette, who scored 19 goals in 51 games last year after being
acquired in midseason from Buffalo for an eighth-round pick, was
scratched from Monday's game against Vancouver. It was his third
healthy scratch in the last five games.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Audette, 30, played right wing on the first line.
But when the club traded for Ziggy Palffy in July, Audette's time
with the Kings appeared in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   New coach Andy Murray moved Audette to left wing on the second
line, pairing him with center Bryan Smolinski and right winger Glen
Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got Ziggy, I knew I wanted him and Glen as the
right-wings on my first two lines,'' Murray said. ``I thought if
Donald worked hard, he might become a solid player on the checking
line. But that can be a difficult transition.
</P>
<P>
   Audette was eligible for unrestricted free agency at the end of
the season and wasn't expected back. He is earning $2.3 million
this year, steep for a third-line player. If the Kings had
attempted to retain his rights, Audette would have earned an
automatic 10-percent raise.
</P>
<P>
   Kaberle, 26, opened the season in a regular rotation on the
Kings power play. But he wore down in January and was sent to
minor-league Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   In 37 games, Kaberle had no goals and nine assists.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK WHISTLES: Emerson is a close friend of Kings captain Rob
Blake from their college days at Bowling Green. Emerson has 14
goals and 33 points but is a minus-24, which is common on an
expansion team....
</P>
<P>
   Enforcer Steve McKenna, a healthy scratch the last nine games,
played Monday night and received a five-minute fighting penalty
midway through the first period for mixing it up with Vancouver's
Brad May.
</P>
<P>
   For McKenna, it was an important game. He has played 38 games
this season and needs 40 for the Kings to protect him in this
summer's expansion draft. The Kings want McKenna to play in Europe
this summer to sharpen his skills beyond fighting. He has no goals
and four assists this season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
