<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEAGUE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS RETAIN TEAGUE WITH FOUR-YEAR DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys took another step in their
deliberate approach to free agency Monday by re-signing free safety
George Teague to a four-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the agreement were not announced. However, a
source said it's a salary-cap friendly contract _ roughly $650,000
against the cap in 2000 _ that is consistent with Cowboys owner
Jerry Jones' new-found philosophy of incentive-laden deals with
modest up-front bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys vice president Stephen Jones said the team made Teague a
priority not just because they like the experienced he brings to
the defense and the leadership he provides in the secondary but
also because they feel the seven-year veteran was the best safety
on market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted Teague back,'' Jones said. ``He made a lot of big
plays for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Teague played with the Cowboys in 1996 before going to Miami as
a free agent. He came back to Dallas in 1998 and has started
alongside strong safety Darren Woodson the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   He has said that he preferred to remain in Dallas and is coming
off a solid 1999 season, when he finished fourth on the team in
tackles with a career-high 102. He also intercepted three passes,
returning two for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Teague back was one of the team's few stated off-season
objectives. The Cowboys achieved two of their goals last month when
they acquired receiver Joey Galloway and signed a veteran
cornerback (Ryan McNeil) to replace the soon-to-be-departed Deion
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   The main objectives left on their free-agent agenda include
re-signing defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman and getting a backup
quarterback to replace Jason Garrett (New York Giants).
</P>
<P>
   They will likely now turn their attention to Spellman, who made
a free-agent visit to Green Bay Packers last week. Spellman has
said he wants to return to the Cowboys, but he is not ruling out
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are also in the market for moderately priced players
at inside linebacker and tight end. They have expressed interest in
Tennessee free-agent tight end Jackie Harris but have yet to extend
an offer. COWBOYS ON TELEVISION IN PRESEASON
</P>
<P>
   The NFL released its 2000 preseason national television
schedule, and the Cowboys will be featured in two of the league's
11 nationally televised games.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 5, ESPN will televise the American Bowl in Tokyo, Japan,
which will match the Cowboys against the Atlanta Falcons. ESPN will
also carry the Cowboys' home game against the Super Bowl champion
St. Louis Rams on Aug. 24. The rest of the preseason schedule will
be announced at a later date. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cowboys signed Brandon Tolbert, an exclusive-rights free
agent, to a one-year deal Monday. Tolbert, a linebacker, spent the
1999 season on injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cowboys are expected to sign free-agent receiver Connie
Moore to a one-year deal Tuesday. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
