<SLUG> BC-LATIMES-DOWNTOWN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. TIMES LATEST HQ TO LEAVE DOWNTOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON TAKENOUCHI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The pending sale of Times Mirror Co. to the
Chicago-based Tribune Co. would strip downtown Los Angeles of one
of its last two major corporate headquarters, underscoring the
Greater San Fernando Valley's emergence as the region's business
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Mirror sale would leave Atlantic Richfield Co. _
itself waiting for approval of a merger with London-based BP Amoco
_ the last Fortune 500 company to call downtown home after the
departure of many corporations and all the banks.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, three corporations on last year's Fortune 500 list
call the Greater San Fernando Valley home _ Foundation Health
Systems and Litton Industries in Woodland Hills and the Walt Disney
Co. in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   A few other Valley-based firms _ including Sylmar's MiniMed and
Chatsworth's MRV Communications _ have market capitalization about
the same as Times Mirror's, emphasizing the growing importance of
the Valley to the city's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Valley is quite well positioned with all these corporate
headquarters, and the challenge is to keep them,'' said Jack Kyser,
chief economist with the nonprofit Los Angeles Economic Development
Corp. ``You have to go out and treasure your corporate
headquarters.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of some of the Valley's largest companies said the key
to keeping them here is their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping workers close to work _ and thus more likely to stay
with the firm _ played a significant role in Unova Inc.'s decision
last year to relocate its headquarters from Beverly Hills to
Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes more sense to stay in the area where the majority of
your good people are,'' said David Brooks, manager of corporate
public relations for the $2.1 billion manufacturer of automatic
identification systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an attractive area to live and work, and we wanted to
keep our team here.''
</P>
<P>
   Unova is far from the only company that has chosen to stay in
the San Fernando Valley to keep its best employees.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Gregg, president of the medical device maker MiniMed Inc.,
said his company turned down offers to move to other cities _ and
even other states _ when it decided to move its headquarters from
Sylmar to Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to stay in the Valley was prompted by a number of
factors, including a first-of-its-kind deal with California State
University, Northridge, which owns the 30-plus-acre site of
MiniMed's future headquarters. But keeping the company's work force
was another major factor, Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a well-trained, educated labor pool that would be
difficult to replace at another locale. We've spent a lot of money
educating the employees.''
</P>
<P>
   San Fernando Valley business leaders say the area's work force
should keep major companies' headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the labor pool is here, this will always be an
attractive place for businesses,'' said Bonny Herman, longtime
president of the Valley Industry and Commerce Association.
</P>
<P>
   Herman said there could be problems on the horizon, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government should but can't figure out how to deal with the
aging industrial stock or build enough affordable housing.''
</P>
<P>
   But those issues might not be enough to discourage the firms
that already call the Valley home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always look for a combination of factors, and the Valley
seems to have it,'' said David Olson, senior vice president of
investor relations for Woodland Hills-based Foundation Health
Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a wonderful experience here. I don't think there's
any sign that we're going to be moving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
