<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVANS SHOWS RANGERS HIS DEFENSIVE SKILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The Rangers' third-base competition
heated up a little more Monday. Tom Evans had another terrific day,
this time on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Evans made three diving backhanded stops to get outs on ground
balls down the line in the Rangers' 6-1 victory against the Toronto
Blue Jays at Charlotte County Stadium. Evans, who is competing with
Mike Lamb, also made a nice barehanded play on a slow chopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Evans said. ``Sometimes you can go three games
and get maybe one ball, or no balls. Then sometimes you get into a
game where you get a chance to make plays like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't lost on Evans that the plays were made in front of the
Blue Jays, the team that put him on waivers last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun,'' Evans said, smiling. ``There are still a few guys
over there who are my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   More important is what manager Johnny Oates thinks, and he was
beaming after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know exactly what I've got at third base, but I like
what I've seen,'' Oates said. ``(Evans) made some very nice plays
over there, very nice.'' DAVIS EMERGING
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Doug Davis, one of the Rangers' top minor-league
starting pitchers, has emerged as a possible replacement for Mike
Venafro in the Rangers' Opening Day bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Davis pitched a scoreless ninth inning Monday and has allowed
only one earned run in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a gut feeling, but I think Doug Davis is ready to
pitch in the big leagues,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Venafro is sidelined with a strained ligament in his left middle
finger, and the Rangers aren't sure if he'll be ready Opening Day.
Oates likes at least two left-handers in the bullpen and the top
three behind Venafro are Mike Mu$oz, Matt Perisho and Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has 69 starts and four relief appearances in the minors
but said, ``Anyway I can get to the major leagues the fastest is
what I want to do.'' PORT CHARLOTTE MEETING
</P>
<P>
   Rangers executive vice president John McMichael is scheduled to
meet with Charlotte County officials Wednesday morning about the
Rangers' spring-training lease, which expires at the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who have formed an unofficial partnership with the
Los Angeles Dodgers, are exploring Las Vegas, Arizona and Vero
Beach, Fla. But general manager Doug Melvin likes Port Charlotte,
and the Rangers aren't ruling out extending the lease.
</P>
<P>
   That could be made possible by a bill pending in the Florida
legislature that would provide state funds to upgrade
spring-training facilities. The Rangers have made it clear their
facility needs improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a plus for Charlotte to have those kind of revenue
streams,'' McMichael said. ``We're interested in hearing more about
it.'' ANOTHER TRY FOR DIAZ
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Diaz, Cuban defector and second-base hopeful for the
Rangers, spent Monday at the American consulate in the Dominican
Republic, resubmitting his visa application.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who signed Diaz on Feb. 28, were hoping to have him
in camp by now, but visa problems have forced him to remain in the
Dominican Republic. Rangers scouting director Chuck McMichael said
if the visa situation isn't cleared up soon, Diaz won't get a
chance to showcase his talent in major-league camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we go to Plan E,'' McMichael said. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Left fielder Rusty Greer underwent tests on his injured right
ankle in Dallas on Monday, but the Rangers aren't expecting the
results until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rangers sent 11 players back to the minor-league camp,
including three first-round draft picks: pitchers Jonathan Johnson
(1995) and R.A. Dickey (1996), and first baseman Carlos Pe$a
(1998). Also sent back were pitchers David Elder, Corey Lee, Juan
Moreno and Matt Miller, catchers Reed Secrist and Luis Taveras,
infielder Jason Grabowski and outfielder Pedro Valdes. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
