<HEADER>
A6135 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-14 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN PLAYERS CAN'T MAKE CUT, THERE'S OFTEN A FINE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ A ritual as familiar here as sunburn was done
Monday at Mariners spring training: roster cuts.
</P>
<P>
   No departures were unexpected. Or explained. Or grieved.
</P>
<P>
   But when elite athletes appear to be hitting and pitching as
well as the established pros, what is the baseball cleaver that can
separate major-leaguer from top minor-leaguer?
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at speed, arm, defensive ability, athleticism,
hustle, attitude, and there's no difference between the
major-leaguers and these guys (just cut),'' said manager Lou
Piniella of the position player trim. ``But you break them down
offensively, they don't hit certain pitches as well as
major-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why they're at Triple-A. They have holes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the baseball lexicon, a hole is a place in the swing where
batters do poorly. Many hitters who put up big numbers in the minor
leagues don't know they have holes until they reach major league
spring training, or get a seasonal callup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up here, you have advance scouts and a great video system,''
Piniella said. ``When a guy hurts you with the bat, you pay
attention to him. You find how he hits against four or five
different pitchers. If the guy has holes, they will be found.''
</P>
<P>
   That's primarily why five solid, young outfielders were sent
down to the minors Monday _ Shane Monahan, Chad Alexander, Rich
Butler, Mike Murphy and Mike Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few of the hitters we sent out, their strengths were hitting
the ball down and in,'' Piniella said. ``For example, if you're a
left-handed hitter in the majors, the first thing the opposing
manager, pitching coach and advance scout will tell the pitcher is,
`Don't throw the ball down and in to a left-handed hitter.'
</P>
<P>
   ``For a good major league hitter, the down-and-in zone might be
a .400 average for them. The down-and-away or up-and-away might be
.250, .260. But in the guys we cut, those zones drop off the
charts.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what separates Dan Rohrmeier from, say, John Olerud _ two
big, strong, veteran first basemen, one a batting champion, one a
career minor-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   For 11 seasons, Rohrmeier tore up the minors. In 1997 in Class
AAA Tacoma, he was the Mariners' minor league player of the year.
He broke long-held team records in doubles, home runs and RBIs.
During his career in the minors, he had 152 home runs and 770 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   His major league career stats? Three hits in nine at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   He's now playing in South Korea's top league, where at 34 last
year he hit 45 home runs, won the triple crown and made more than
$400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rohrmeier is among the vast majority of pro baseball players who
can do well right up to the point where, as Roger Jongewaard, vice
president of scouting, put it, ``they can't adjust their own
weaknesses to major league pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   As a player, Piniella knew the problem, having spent six years
in the minors before getting the hang of hitting at 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to redo myself and learn to cover up my holes,'' he
said. ``I had to learn to hit to all fields and cut down on my
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most hitters, there's a flaw in plate coverage, or in the
stance, and they have to figure those things out. A hitting coach
can't do it for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In pitching, two assets separate the talents into major league
and minor league, according to Mariners pitching coach Bryan Price:
consistent delivery and ownership of an out pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major league pitchers don't pitch out of character and don't
get away from their strengths,'' he said. ``They don't back down,
don't give the hitters too much credit.''
</P>
<P>
   The out pitch is one a pitcher throws when a hitter knows it's
coming, and still flails like a three-armed octopus.
</P>
<P>
   The best pitchers have more than one that can fetch that
precious strike. Freddy Garcia has a fastball, curve and changeup.
Gil Meche has a fastball, slider and change. Newcomer Kevin Hodges
has a power sinker drawing raves, and Kazu Sasaki has a forkball
that hitters haplessly pound into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Moyer? Any pitch, any time, for a strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Price said, ``is special.''
</P>
<P>
   Roster cuts also have much to do with the personnel load at the
major league level. In the outfield, for example, the Mariners,
after cuts, have six with chubby guaranteed contracts, and are
still looking for help.
</P>
<P>
   When the major league chance does come, still more can't handle
the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``A solid prospect can go to Triple-A and put up good numbers
and hit a comfort zone,'' bench coach John McLaren said.
``Sometimes when they get the major league opportunity, they put
extra pressure on themselves, then they have a couple bad at-bats,
and believe they can't handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opportunity doesn't knock often, and some guys just aren't
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   At the elite level, baseball is a game of sufficient difficulty
that it is fairly remarkable anybody can play it well.
</P>
<P>
   Those who do, earn millions. Those who don't, are minor legends
in Tacoma and Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
