<HEADER>
A6163 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LA-SCHOOLS-2Takes-LAD     03-14 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-SCHOOLS-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SCHOOL PLAN TO CREATE MINIDISTRICTS, CUT BUREAUCRACY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID R. BAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Declaring Los Angeles' troubled school system must
change or collapse, interim Superintendent Ramon C. Cortines
unveiled detailed plans Monday to cut 834 administrative jobs and
carve the district into 11 semi- independent pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the minidistricts, three of which would be created in
the San Fernando Valley, would have its own superintendent and
13-member appointed advisory council of parents and community
members. Each local district would make literacy its primary focus
and each would have substantial authority over its own budget.
</P>
<P>
   Cortines said the changes would give parents and individual
schools more power over education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents will have more access to where the action is,'' he
said. ``And also, we as educators will not be able to escape our
clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortines said the changes, expected to save the district about
$46 million a year, were necessary to eliminate the bureaucracy and
political agendas he said have hampered teaching and learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adults in this district have failed the children in this
district,'' Cortines said. ``Our children are not dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortines will formally present the reorganization plan to the
school board today. If board members approve, the changes would
take effect July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Although a vote on the plan isn't scheduled until April 11,
several board members on Monday called it a necessary step to save
the beleaguered school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of comprehensive overhaul the district
needs,'' board member Caprice Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Several district officials also hoped the dramatic changes would
stave off efforts to break up the 711,000-student district
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping the fact that we have a reform-minded school board
and leadership willing to take action will drive people to say,
Let's give this a chance,'' board member Valerie Fields said. ``If
it doesn't, then maybe we'll need more draconian steps.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal did not win over all the district's critics.
</P>
<P>
   San Fernando Valley businessman Bert Boeckmann, who is
spearheading a drive to break up the school district, said the
reorganization plan would not dissuade him. The Los Angeles Unified
School District, he said, is too immense and set in its ways to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling would be they're trying to step in the right
direction,'' he said. ``I just don't think they'll arrive there.''
</P>
<P>
   School board member David Tokofsky warned that unless strictly
monitored, the creation of 11 local districts could produce more
bureaucracy _ not less.
</P>
<P>
   Gerardo Guzman, president of the San Fernando Valley Mexican
American Political Association, said the plan did little to change
basic conditions in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing musical chairs,'' he said. ``They're not
putting more books in the classrooms. They're not opening more
bathrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Guzman also said the minidistrict covering the Northeast Valley
was too large. It would serve 77,000 students _ the most of any
subdistrict. Cortines said the plan allows for reconfiguring the
districts after four or five years.
</P>
<P>
   The new Los Angeles Unified that Cortines envisions would be
leaner and looser than the current organization.
</P>
<P>
   The number of administrators working in the central offices
would be cut nearly in half. Some departments would dissolve _
their responsibilities taken up by the new minidistricts
</P>
<P>
   while others would be reshaped.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the resonsibility for student achievement would rest in
the 11 minidistricts. The 11 local superintendents, however, would
still report to a downtown superintendent and school board with
authority over the entire system.
</P>
<P>
   What remains of the district's downtown headquarters would focus
on providing ``tactical support'' to assist the efforts of
individual schools. The renamed Central Support System also would
handle policy questions as well as retain control over building
schools and policing existing campuses.
</P>
<P>
   The changes outlined Monday also include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cutting 333 jobs from the central administration. Cortines
said he hopes to avoid layoffs, instead eliminating positions
through retirements or perhaps early retirement incentive packages.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moving 501 jobs from the district's downtown headquarters to
the minidistricts. Many of these jobs would cover functions now
handled downtown, such as business and food services.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forming advisory committees to help govern each district. Each
13-member panel would include at least eight parents, one high
school student and local business and community leaders. Each local
superintendent also would be allowed to appoint up to six
ex-officio members, including teachers and administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Should the board approve the plan, administrators would need to
apply for new jobs within the new organizational structure.
</P>
<P>
   Some district officials privately expressed relief Monday that
the district might have an opportunity to purge itself of
unproductive bureaucrats. Some department heads were unable to tell
Cortines precisely how many employees they had.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   But the process will not be easy. Many administrators have
rights to other jobs they can fill if their current positions are
cut _ rights spelled out in their contracts. Some might choose, for
instance, to become school principals.
</P>
<P>
   Cortines said he hopes to work out a way that such
administrators will be able to exercise their ``bumping rights''
without disrupting schools that either are successful or improving.
</P>
<P>
   Such uncertainty made for a nervous atmosphere in the district's
headquarters Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always some level of anxiety. Change isn't easy for a
lot of people,'' said Dan Isaacs, assistant superintendent of
school operations, who expects his office to be split up and its
responsibilities divided among the new, local districts. He said he
hadn't decided which position to apply for if the reorganization is
approved. In the meantime, he and his staff will continue their
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do your job,'' Isaacs said. ``I've been here too long not
to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
