A6165 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-FIRE-ANT-LADN     03-14 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-ANT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED FIRE ANT FOUND IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A red fire ant has been discovered in a San
Fernando Valley garden, marking the first appearance of these
potentially deadly pests in the city, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The lone ant was found Jan. 18 in suburban Van Nuys, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely serious problem,'' Agricultural
Commissioner Cato Fiksdal said. ``The ants swarm in the hundreds,
and each of those stings is reported to be extremely painful and
cause blisters.''
</P>
<P>
   County agricultural officials did not find any more at the home,
but they warned that more could appear later, said Richard Iizuka,
deputy agricultural commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   County officials speculate that common Argentinean ants at
nearby mounds may have killed off a small population of red
imported fire ants, but they won't know for sure until the
temperatures warm up and ants start coming out of their mounds
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the possibility we'll find other fire ants when we go
back,'' said Daniel Papilli, a county agricultural inspector.
</P>
<P>
   The county Board of Supervisors is expected to vote today
whether to approve spending $627,000 to hire six workers to kill
the pests, which sting and can be deadly.
</P>
<P>
   The insect entered the Southern United States in the 1920s and
has since spread to 11 Southeastern states. Its first California
appearance was in 1997 at San Joaquin Valley orchards, making its
way to Orange County in October 1998 and Los Angeles County in
Azusa last March.
</P>
<P>
   County agricultural officials are fighting the fire ants at 172
locations in the county, including in Arcadia, Azusa, Cerritos, La
Mirada, La Verne, Pico Rivera, Rosemead, South El Monte, Torrance,
Walnut, West Covina and Whittier.
</P>
<P>
   Fire ants were blamed for the recent deaths of two elderly
people in a Mississippi nursing home, and they attacked a baby in
Arcadia in September.
</P>
<P>
   The dark red ants build gopher-like mounds 18 inches or higher
and aggressively defend the area.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five years, the county plans to use two types of
insecticides to kill the ants, both considered harmless to people
unless eaten in large quantities.
</P>
<P>
   Agricultural officials encourage those who believe they have red
imported fire ants at their homes to call the pest hotline at (800)
491-1899 or visit the state Web site at www.cdfa.ca.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
