A6167 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      03-14 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYTON'S 40-POINT EFFORT STYMIES GRIZZLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ Fighting for better playoff position, Gary
Payton and the rest of the Sonics are doing their best to
compensate for an injured Vin Baker.
</P>
<P>
   There was an emotional loss at home Sunday to the Toronto
Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   But forgive Payton for interrupting the stretch run of this
regular season with a different motivation.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' high-strung point guard never needs to be aroused on
a basketball court, although a newspaper ad that read: ``Come see
Bibby turn the Glove inside out'' did just that.
</P>
<P>
   Payton scored 40 points and handed out 11 assists Monday night
as the Sonics dispatched Mike Bibby and the Vancouver Grizzlies
113-103 at General Motors Place.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he did was light a fire,'' Payton said, referring to a
local radio personality who showed him the promotion at the team's
practice Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy thought he was having fun by showing it to me. So I
said I'm going to make it funny for everybody in Vancouver. I don't
have anything against (Mike) Bibby. It was just the ad.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement touting the game ran in both local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Payton helped to send Vancouver to its ninth
straight loss. The Sonics, meanwhile, rebounded nicely from a 99-97
loss to Toronto in which Payton was harassed so much by double
teams that he shot a dismal 8-for-23 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   He made 14 of 27 shots and 12 of 15 free throws against the
Grizzlies, finishing just one shy of the career-high 41 points he
set earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the guy who showed him the paper that I want to have a
word with,'' Vancouver coach Lionel Hollins said. ``Gary Payton was
a monster. He was the difference. He accounted for most of their
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton exploded for 15 points in a decisive third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied 60-60 when the Sonics ran away from the
Grizzlies with a 21-4 run. Brent Barry's 3-pointer ignited the
spurt. Payton then scored 11 points, most of which came via layups
off turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's three-point play with 4:07 left in the period put the
Sonics ahead 81-64. They took a 92-80 lead into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver got back within 102-98 with 4:07 left in the game
after forward Shareef Abdur-Rahim got hot.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Sonics scored the next six points. After Payton
made two free throws, he found Horace Grant wide open under the
basket for a layup, and Rashard Lewis hit a short jumper in the
lane.
</P>
<P>
   That mini-barrage put the Sonics ahead by 10 points and sealed
the win with 1:45 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics (39-26) moved back in front of idle Minnesota for
sixth place in the Western Conference playoff standings, with their
next seven games at home in KeyArena. Vancouver is in town on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't wake a sleeping dog,'' Barry said. ``But seriously,
I think (Payton) was more motivated because he didn't play his best
game on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker remained in street clothes for the second consecutive game
because of a strained left hamstring. Jelani McCoy started in his
place.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics coach Paul Westphal favored the same small lineup he used
against the Raptors and it was effective. Lewis and Ruben Patterson
played together with Payton, Barry and Grant down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson had 15 points and eight rebounds, while Grant finished
with 13 points and 11 boards. The Sonics forced 18 turnovers and
shut down Vancouver center Bryant ``Big Country'' Reeves in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves scored 25 of his team-high 31 points in the first two
quarters and tied a club record with eight field goals in the
opening period. He eventually sank 11 consecutive shots, another
club record, before missing an 8-footer over Grant's outstretched
arms just before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Reeves' showing, the Sonics led 60-58 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Big Country was Shaq for awhile,'' Westphal said.
``He came back down to earth in the second half, and our defense
kicked in the third quarter and let us get a little bit of a
margin. Then Gary pretty much took care of the rest. We got good
performances from a lot of people, but Gary was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had fun with it,'' Payton said. ``I don't worry about people
stopping me because they have to come out and stop me.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
