<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6183 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LAD     03-14 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARCH MADNESS WHITTLED DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bob Huggins is whining. Lute Olson is smiling. The
East is a beast. The South is least. Indiana State is going back to
Salt Lake City. Southwest Missouri got shunned _ what a pity.
Michigan State's the team to beat. Louisiana State's the team to
fear. Aside from that, nothing's clear.
</P>
<P>
   Tark must have seen his shadow, because March Madness arrived a
week early.
</P>
<P>
   If the NCAA Tournament is anything like Championship Week, it'll
be quite a ride to Indianapolis. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
EAST
</P>
<P>
   In Winston-Salem: Duke smashes Lamar. Kansas' coaching beats
DePaul's lack of. Florida edges underrated Butler, and Illinois
spanks Penn.
</P>
<P>
   One of the tastiest second-round games of the tournament is
Florida-Illinois, matching Illini coach Lon Kruger against the team
he took to the 1994 Final Four. He stomps on Gators counterpart
Slick Billy Donovan.
</P>
<P>
   Duke sticks it to Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo: Sure, Pepperdine got dinged with an 11th seed, but
look at it this way: The Waves have the guard play and athleticism
to beat Indiana. Problem is, the Hoosiers have A.J. Guyton, who
beats the Waves by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon beats Seton Hall in the game of the day. Oklahoma State
dismantles Hofstra, and Temple does the same to Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, Temple's zone stymies Oregon's attack, and
Oklahoma State coach Eddie Sutton beats Bob Knight.
</P>
<P>
   In Syracuse: Here it is, the upset of the tournament: Kruger
outcoaches Coach K, Duke's freshmen struggle and Illinois stuns the
Blue Devils. Two days later, every Duke player declares for the NBA
Draft. Two weeks later, Coach K signs eight McDonald's
All-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In the other Sweet 16 game, Temple grinds Oklahoma State 38-36.
``We can't allow 38 points and expect to win,'' Sutton says.
</P>
<P>
   Temple beats Illinois and takes lovable coach John Chaney to his
first Final Four. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   In Birmingham: Hours before the game, Missouri coach Quin Snyder
dials his old boss, Coach K, and gets the blueprint for beating
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Utah State (Bernard) Rock and (Troy) Rolle over Connecticut in
the biggest non-upset upset of the first round. The Aggies haven't
lost since January; UConn hasn't lost since Saturday. (Note: No.12
seeds have won a first-round game 11 straight years.)
</P>
<P>
   Stanford celebrates UConn's ouster and names its score against
South Carolina State. Tennessee beats Louisiana-Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, Missouri hangs with Stanford for 35
minutes, then Cardinal guard David Moseley takes control. Tennessee
beats Utah State.
</P>
<P>
   In Nashville: The team to watch is Miami, with its smothering
defense and senior guards Johnny Hemsley and Vernon Jennings. (Yes,
the guys who almost beat UCLA two years ago.) In a tough, sloppy
game, the Hurricanes end Arkansas' season.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State beats Appalachian State and Tulsa beats UNLV.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins is right: The Bearcats shouldn't be
a No.2 seed. They should be a No.4. Without Kenyon Martin, they're
nothing more than a bunch of athletes with no concept of structured
offense. After beating UNC-Wilmington, the Bearcats fall to Tulsa
in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Miami upsets Ohio State and Columbus sighs: Only five months
until football.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin: Stanford beats Tennessee as Moseley continues his Art
Lee impersonation (sans choke gesture). Miami plows past Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the nation's best defenses meet in the regional final.
The difference is Miami's guards, who smother Moseley and Casey
Jacobsen. With no perimeter game, the Cardinal becomes
one-dimensional. Mark Madsen and Jarron Collins can't win playing
two-against-five. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MIDWEST
</P>
<P>
   In Cleveland: Easiest upset pick of the first round is Samford,
which beat St. John's a few months ago, over Syracuse. Samford
considers joining the Big East, then realizes there's more
competition in the TAAC (Trans America Athletic Conference).
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky, without suspended guard Desmond Allison (DUI),
outlasts St. Bonaventure, and Michigan State hammers Valpo. Saint
Louis continues its amazing run as coach Lorenzo Romar beats one of
his coaching idols, Utah's Rick Majerus.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, Michigan State pounds Saint Louis and
Kentucky beats Samford.
</P>
<P>
   In Minneapolis: UCLA's first-round loss to Detroit Mercy last
year was easy to see. Not so this season. The Bruins have more
weapons, and Ball State will let them play.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland pounds Iona. With Chris Porter seated in row 10 (next
to his agent), Auburn beats Creighton. Iowa State crushes Central
Connecticut State.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, Iowa State ends Auburn's tumultuous month
and UCLA upsets Maryland, avenging an embarrassing loss to the
Terps in last seasons' Puerto Rico Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit: Michigan State, experienced, tough and versatile,
sends Kentucky home. UCLA's eight-game winning streak ends as
Cyclones guard Jamaal Tinsley not All-American Marcus Fizer makes
the decisive baskets down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Mo Peterson and Mateen Cleaves, Michigan State beats Iowa
State to become the only repeat Final Four entry. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WEST
</P>
<P>
   In Salt Lake City: Selection committee chairman Craig Thompson
said Arizona's victory over Stanford proved the Wildcats deserved a
No.1 seed without injured center Loren Woods (out for the
tournament).
</P>
<P>
   But didn't Arizona lose at Oregon and !ital!Oregon State!off!
two weeks ago? Lute Olson has done a masterful job this season, but
the Wildcats aren't a No.1, not without Woods. As usual, the
committee sees what it wants to see.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Arizona crushes Jackson State.
</P>
<P>
   The juiciest game of the tournament is the second-round
Arizona-Fresno State matchup, since Olson and Jerry Tarkanian
despise each other. But Wisconsin cancels the lovefest by beating
Tark despite 45 points from Courtney Szczerbiak Alexander. (You can
look it up.)
</P>
<P>
   Indiana State _ playing its first game in Salt Lake City since
Larry Bird's Sycamores lost to Michigan State in the legendary 1979
title game upsets Texas, which hasn't won an important game outside
Austin in 12 years. (You can look that up, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana State swiftly defeats Southeast Missouri State.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, Wisconsin crawls past the frustrated
Wildcats, 17-15. LSU beats ISU to advance to the S16.
</P>
<P>
   In Tucson: Guard Erick Barkley is suspended for the first half,
quits the team at halftime, then returns for the last five minutes
and leads St. John's past Northern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga, seeded 10th in the West (just like last year), loses to
Louisville. (Where have you gone, Quentin Hall?) Oklahoma pounds
Winthrop. Purdue beats Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, St. John's beats Louisville and Purdue
upsets Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   In Albuquerque: Louisiana State rallies in the final minutes to
beat Wisconsin, and St. John's beats Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   In the regional final, LSU freshman guard Torris Bright outplays
Barkley, whose injunction to suspend his suspensions is denied just
before tipoff, and the Tigers reach the Final Four for the first
time in 14 years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 0233EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
