<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CELEBRATING, PEPPERDINE GETS DOWN TO BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif _ There was only token evidence around campus
Monday indicating Pepperdine was playing in the NCAA Tournament.
The first was the bus outside Firestone Fieldhouse with the sign on
the side reading: ``Bound 4 the Big Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   The other was the larger-than-usual media gathering at the
Waves' late-afternoon practice. Otherwise, it was business as usual
as Pepperdine began serious preparation for Indiana, its
first-round opponent in Friday's East Regional in Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Tipoff is set for 7 p.m. PST.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th-seeded Waves (24-8) practiced Sunday night after
learning who their opponent would be, but the air of euphoria
lingered over landing in the tournament. By Monday they were back
in a normal routine, putting in a game plan for the sixth-seeded
Hoosiers (20-8), who finished fifth in the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the regular routine will last much longer. Pepperdine
travels early Wednesday morning to Buffalo, eliminating a normal
practice day. That's the disadvantage teams from the West face when
they play in the East region. Everyone else, including Indiana, can
practice in the morning and travel in the afternoon on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That puts added significance on the Waves' two home practices
this week. After Tuesday, their next workout comes in Buffalo a day
before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get a lot of things accomplished (Monday and
today),'' Waves coach Jan van Breda Kolff said. ``But at this stage
of the season, we've played 32 games, we've played against teams
with similar styles to Indiana. You don't really need six days of
practice to get ready.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!It's good to be the Prince:!off! Perhaps no one was more
relieved when Pepperdine made the tournament than senior Tommie
Prince, whose college career has had many twists, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 forward originally signed with UCLA out of Compton
Dominguez High in 1995 but was not admitted into school when his
SAT test score was invalidated. He enrolled at Arizona State in
August of 1995, and redshirted his first year as a Prop 48. In
March of 1996, Prince was arrested along with teammate Gee Gervin
and Rico Harris for an alleged sexual and physical assault of a
female student. The charges were later dropped, but Prince left
Tempe and transferred to Pepperdine in time for the 1996-97 season.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a strange ride, but here he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had butterflies throughout the whole (selection process)
situation, but I felt pretty good about the season we had as far as
the wins we had,'' Prince said. ``But it's definitely a plus for me
to be here, considering everything I've been through. To make it in
my senior year, I couldn't have hoped for anything better.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 0241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
