<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6187 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-BEACH-REVIEW-SFCHR     03-14 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BEACH-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEACH, BABES AND BRAZEN ASSAULTS ON PC 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone with half a brain and a sliver of sensitivity would be
outraged, offended and otherwise huffy about ``Son of the Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   So I giggled in gales.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty high lasted about 15 minutes, until the new FX cable
series, produced by Howard Stern, began reprocessing the same
jokes.
</P>
<P>
   By my reckoning, that still leaves me with a quarter of a brain,
good enough for TV work. I gave up on sensitivity a long time ago,
as many readers have kindly noted.
</P>
<P>
   The show, premiering Tuesday, is a ``Naked Gun''-style spoof of
``Baywatch,'' starring the decidedly unbuff Tim Stack (remember
``Nightstand With Dick Dietrick''?) as Notch Johnson, the world's
greatest lifeguard.
</P>
<P>
   Notch's dimmer light is fixed on a permanent low setting, but
he's still several watts brighter than his fellow lifeguards.
</P>
<P>
   They're dumb blonde B.J. Cummings (Playboy Playmate Jaime
Bergman), German beef boy Chip Rommel (Roland Kickinger) and
inner-city recruit Jamaica St. Croix (Leila Arcieri). The lone
representative of normal intelligence is junior lifeguard Kimberlee
Clark (Kim Oja).
</P>
<P>
   The all-out assault on political correctness includes broad
swipes at Asians, Germans, blondes, fat people, sick children,
gays, Kathie Lee Gifford and Gifford's darling son, Cody.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Kathie Lee jokes don't fall technically into the
politically incorrect category. Like I said, a quarter of a brain.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, there are dozens of genitalia jokes with a juvenilia
slant. Notch's last name, a slang term for penis, is worn to
flaccidity before the third commercial break.
</P>
<P>
   The show's first gust of vulgarity, though, is funny for anyone
susceptible to tasteless, brazenly stupid humor. That'd be me.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with a couple of Central Casting Asian thugs shipping
a group of young women off to America for servitude as prostitutes.
When one washes ashore, starving, in Southern California, Notch and
his gang _ did I mention Steve, the humping dog? _ try to help.
</P>
<P>
   B.J.: ``I only wish we knew what Cambodians (she pronounces it
Cam-bo-DEE-ans) like to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Cut to Steve, the dog, scurrying for cover.
</P>
<P>
   Notch does some checking and reports to the castaway, ``My
snitch tells me your sisters are working in a massage parlor.''
</P>
<P>
   B.J.: ``Thank God they're not prostitutes.''
</P>
<P>
   And so on. We needn't get into the matter of B.J.'s last name.
Oh, what the heck. ``It's a nickname,'' she chirps. ``I got it from
the men's volleyball team.''
</P>
<P>
   As the lifeguards go about rescuing the newly arrived Asian
women, the villainous Mayor Anita Massengil (Lisa Banes), who hates
Notch for some reason, tries to sabotage his annual Lifeguard Show
for Sick Kids.
</P>
<P>
   Massengil's accomplice is her equally malevolent gay son, Cody
(Jason Hopkins). Apologies to Kathie Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with broad spoofs is that the laughs can turn to
yawns in a hurry. ``S.O.B.'' barely lasts 15 minutes until it
empties the joke bin, begins to repeat itself and finally wilts
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   What does that portend for ``S.O.B.'' in Weeks 3, and 4, and 5?
It could mean viewers flexing their forefingers on their remotes
while the show's writers belabor doggie scatology. Buh-bye.
</P>
<P>
   And anyway, isn't ``Baywatch'' pretty much its own spoof?
</P>
<P>
   Stern isn't the ``S.O.B.'' creator _ Stack claims that honor _
but the radio star has involved himself as executive producer and
avid script reader. One scene, focusing erotically on the slo-mo
application of sunblock, has Stern oiled all over it.
</P>
<P>
   Stern has also been flogging the thing mercilessly on his
syndicated radio program.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, a caller to the radio show told Stern that Los
Angeles traffic had been snarled by a man threatening to jump onto
a freeway from a ramp.
</P>
<P>
   Stern didn't miss a beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not Tim Stack,'' he said. ``I need him for another
seven (episodes).''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
