r s BC-HKN-KINGS-CANUCKS-LAD     03-14 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-CANUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS WIN 3-2 IN OT TO CAP BIG DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ These are heady days for the Kings, who are a good
team that suddenly became better.
</P>
<P>
   On the night they moved ahead of Phoenix in the Western
Conference playoff race with a 3-2 overtime victory against
Vancouver, the Kings improved their postseason possibilities Monday
by acquiring rugged right wing Kelly Buchberger and smooth-skating
Nelson Emerson from the Atlanta Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   It cost them disgruntled Donald Audette, who had fallen out of
the mix through injuries and inconsistency. Audette didn't play
against Vancouver, but before he left for Atlanta, he wrote a big
``Good Luck'' on the blackboard in the Kings dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure is a lot of stuff going on,'' said Jozef Stumpel, who
scored his third game-winning goal on the Kings' seven-game
homestand. ``It's great. Everybody is excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel scored when a shot by Sean O'Donnell glanced off his
skate and past Canucks goaltender Felix Potvin. The play was
reviewed for several minutes, but the Staples Center crowd of
17,309 knew this was too good a day to lose a goal on a
technicality.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Rob Blake even scored a power-play goal, the Kings'
first in four games (1 for 20). And turns out he and Emerson are
old college buddies from their days at Bowling Green.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved them into second place in the Pacific Division
and past Phoenix, which lost. If the Kings, who face the Mighty
Ducks on Wednesday in Anaheim, hold the No.5 spot in the Western
Conference, they could be looking at a first-round playoff date
with the Detroit Red Wings. Sixth probably would mean facing
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, a player of Buchberger's grit and playoff experience
was deemed critical by general manager Dave Taylor, who also sent
minor-league defenseman Frantisek Kaberle to the Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to Kelly and he is very excited about coming,'' Taylor
said. ``He brings great pluses to our team, not just in the
playoffs but down the stretch. He is a tremendous leader and we'll
need that the rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings leading scorer Ziggy Palffy gave them a 2-1 lead with just
74 seconds left in the second period, but Alexander Mogilny scored
midway through the third period to send the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   But in a season where each games seemed so critical, the action
took a back seat to the Kings boardroom.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor had been trying to unload Audette, whose scoring and
attitude had dipped from last season. Emerson is expected to take
his place on the Kings' second line with center Bryan Smolinski and
winger Glen Murray. He also becomes the Kings' second option after
Blake as point man on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   But the key to the deal is Buchberger (pronounced Book-burger),
who will replace winger Marko Tuomainen on the third (checking)
line. Before being selected by Atlanta in last summer's expansion
draft, he played 11 full seasons with the Edmonton Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Seven times, he reached the playoffs and played on three Stanley
Cup championship teams (1987, 1988, 1990). Goaltender Stephane
Fiset (Colorado 1996) is the only other King to play on a Stanley
Cup champion.
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger, 33, isn't much of a scorer. He has just 87 goals in
862 career games, with a career-high 20 during the 1991-92 season.
This year, Buchberger played 67 games for Atlanta, with five goals
and 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were hoping to avoid taking on any multiyear contracts
but inherited two with Buchberger and Emerson.
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger is earning $800,000 this season but has two more
years to run on his contract. Emerson is making $1.7 million this
year and has three left after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Audette is earning $2.2 million this year and is eligible for
unrestricted free agency after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The salaries are pretty much a wash this year,'' Taylor said.
``We take on a little more in the next few years, but we think this
brings us closer to where we want to go.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
