r s BC-BKC-UCLA-OPPONENT-LAD     03-14 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-OPPONENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALL STATE LOOKS MUCH LIKE UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ All the possible opponents, all the disparate
styles and philosophies, all the distinctive problems and
personalties, and for its first-round opponent UCLA draws ... its
fraternal twin.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-season swoons? Ball State knows all about them. Fast
finishes to make the NCAA Tournament? Ball State's was blinding.
Gifted freshman? Ball State's got one. Stellar late-season guard
play? Ball State has it.
</P>
<P>
   Victory over Purdue? Ball State's got one of those, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a great game,'' said Purdue assistant coach Jay
Price, whose team lost to UCLA by two points and to Ball State by
20. ``Ball State is very athletic, and they play with a lot of
emotion. They have scorers. They play decent defense, and they're
hard-nosed. They won't be intimidated by UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams started well. UCLA was 8-2; Ball State was 10-1. Both
lost six of seven games during conference play and seemed destined
for the NIT. Both regrouped, then finished with a rush. The Bruins
won their final six games. Ball State has won 11 of its last 12,
including three in the Mid-American Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals (22-8) haven't won an NCAA game since 1990, but
they're eager to join the MAC's tournament success. Its members
have won first-round games in four of the last five years:
Miami-Ohio beat No.5 seed Arizona in 1995 and No.7 Washington last
year; Eastern Michigan beat No.8 seed Duke in 1996; and Western
Michigan beat No.6 Clemson in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MAC is very underrated as a conference,'' Price said.
``We've played a lot of MAC schools, and they all have good coaches
and good players. Their starting fives are good. Depth is the one
place they tend to struggle. But Ball State is deep.''
</P>
<P>
   As are the Bruins. The similarities don't end there. UCLA
freshman forward Jason Kapono leads the team in scoring and was
named Pac-10 co-freshman of the year. Ball State freshman forward
Theron Smith is the Cardinals' top rebounder (7.7 per game) and
No.2 scorer (12.4 per game), and he was named MAC freshman of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a high-Division I player,'' Price said. ``He could
definitely play in the Big Ten.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as junior guard Earl Watson fueled UCLA's late-season
charge he's averaging six assists and 2.7 turnovers during the
winning streak so did Ball State senior guard Duane Clemens guide
the Cardinals to the MAC title.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, 6-feet, is an athletic left-hander who averaged 21.6
points in the MAC tournament and played the season with his
grandfather's obituary folded in his sock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taken every big shot for us,'' Cardinals point guard
Mickey Hosier said. ``He's a skinny kid, but he finds a way to put
the ball in the basket. He's our leader, and we're going to ride
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as UCLA's February slump strengthened its resolve, so did
Ball State's January spiral create the cohesion needed for its
remarkable finish. The problems began with two consecutive
triple-overtime defeats (to Eastern Michigan and Miami-Ohio).
</P>
<P>
   ``That really affected us, and then we played four games in
(nine) days,'' Hosier said. ``But we had a week off to practice and
get our confidence back, and we started rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Although similar, the teams are not identical.
</P>
<P>
   Ball State is tough and tenacious every game. UCLA is prone to
lethargy.
</P>
<P>
   Ball State is an excellent 3-point shooting team with a passable
inside attack. UCLA is an inconsistent 3-point shooting team that
favors its frontcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Ball State's big men do not have NBA talent. UCLA's do.
</P>
<P>
   Ball State does not have four McDonald's All-Americans. UCLA
does.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA is capable of putting it together and talented enough to
make a Final Four run,'' Ball State coach Ray McCallum said. ``A
lot of times teams go through adversity and come together.''
</P>
<P>
   He should know. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
