<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6282 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEYTALK15-COX     03-14 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cover your disaster
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Getting slammed by a tornado, or any other natural
disaster, is bad luck. But neglecting common-sense precautions is
bad judgment.
</P>
<P>
   You can deal with emotional trauma later on, if big winds or
other disasters come your way. Now is the time to protect all those
financial arrangements that mean so much to your household.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's tornado season began this month, and the peak dangers
will last through May. After that comes hurricane season. Fires and
burglaries are never out of season.
</P>
<P>
   Such disasters, by definition, are unpredictable. Georgia's
first nasty storm of this season came on Valentine's Day, killing
18 people and destroying more than 450 homes in the far south part
of the state.
</P>
<P>
   It's that unpredictability you want to guard against. ``Some
people are very thorough, but for a lot of us, it's something we
always mean to get around to,'' said Marilyn Self, the American Red
Cross' director of disaster education. ``It's something we'll get
to when we're not quite so busy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the realm of personal finance, the steps are easy to list:
Inventory your possessions. Make sure they are adequately insured.
Safeguard your financial records.
</P>
<P>
   An inventory is crucial _ the record that shows what you own
even if most of it gets blown away.
</P>
<P>
   Your property inventory is the best document you will have if
you need to make a big, comprehensive claim with your insurance
company. If all of your property has blown away, your inventory is
the best proof you can offer to an insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   You should make a visual record, photographs or a videotape, of
every room in the house. Don't forget to record the contents of
cabinets and closets. ``Many times, people underestimate their
claims because they just don't remember all the things they have,''
Self said.
</P>
<P>
   The visual record is a supplement to written lists. It may help
if you organize and build your list room-by-room.
</P>
<P>
   If you need a kick-start, check the resource list for Internet
sites that will help get you organized. Another alternative is in
personal finance software, such as Quicken, that includes an
inventory section.
</P>
<P>
   Pay particular attention to expensive items, such as antiques,
collectibles, electronics and appliances. For them, record purchase
dates and prices, plus serial numbers or appraisals where
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be careless about preserving your inventory. ``We suggest
keeping it not in your house but in an extremely safe place,'' said
spokesman Dave Colmans of the Georgia Insurance Information
Service. Safe-deposit boxes are the first choice, though some
people send this record to out-of-town family members.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance _ getting it or upgrading it _ is the second step.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important point is to make sure your coverage has
kept up with the cost of your property,'' Colmans said.
</P>
<P>
   To keep up with inflation in housing prices, many homeowners pay
extra fees to get replacement value coverage on their home.
</P>
<P>
   That goes for contents as well the house. ``Otherwise, your
coverage will be what amounts to depreciated costs,'' said Colmans.
``Your television is worth almost nothing after five years, for
example.''
</P>
<P>
   Note that insurance policies usually set limits on how much they
will pay for losses of jewelry, fine art, camera equipment or
computers. If you have more than the limit, ask about the cost of
extra coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Renters should recognize that the landlord's insurance covers
his building, not your apartment full of property. Only one in four
renters has bothered with insuring his or her goods, which is a
mistake. ``We saw a real increase in interest after that day last
year when there were lightning strikes and apartment buildings were
burning in several places on the same day,'' Colmans observed.
</P>
<P>
   Flood insurance doesn't come with basic homeowners and renters
policies. You'll have to buy that extra, if flooding is a
possibility on your property.
</P>
<P>
   On auto insurance, comprehensive coverage is what pays for
storm, fire or flood damage. You may also want a provision to pay
for a rental car while yours is being repaired.
</P>
<P>
   Preserving your records is relatively simple, though it may
require you to make extra copies of crucial paperwork. Some items
go into an evacuation box; others go to a safe-deposit box.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation box is a sturdy container at home, one you can
snatch up and take with you. Documents should be filed in
waterproof plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   A safe-deposit box is for papers and computer backups that you
can't afford to lose but don't expect to need immediately. Your
household inventory records go there, along with stock
certificates, perhaps some keepsakes and all the items on the
checklist.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few more items to consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ An emergency fund. The traveler's checks in your evacuation
box will get you into a motel. Thoughtful people often stash away a
larger amount of savings, often enough to cover three months of
living expenses, in case of job losses or other disasters. A
tornado might well qualify.
</P>
<P>
   _ A where-everything-is list. This would tell your family the
locations of bank accounts and other assets, wills, documents
stating your last wishes, insurance policies and persons to
contact. Your list typically should be left with an attorney or
trusted family member.
</P>
<P>
   _ Medications. If there are some you truly can't live without,
it's best to keep a small supply away from your home.
</P>
<P>
   _ A good book on the basics is Janet Bamford's ``Smarter
Insurance Solutions.'' It costs $19.95. You can order it by calling
(800) 233-4830.
</P>
<P>
   _ For a useful pamphlet with detailed advice, go to www.nefe.org
and search for ``Before Disaster Strikes.'' Or call the American
Red Cross at (404) 876-3302.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other useful pamphlets are available at www.lifeadvice.com
(search for ``tornado'') or by calling (800) 638-5433.
</P>
<P>
   _ To download a worksheet for your property inventory, go to
www.metlife.com and search for ``inventory.'' You can find a
similar worksheet at www.iii.org/individuals/home
</P>
<P>
   /inventory.html.
</P>
<P>
   _ For a mother lode of consumer information, including
storm-related issues, go to www.insure.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ For much more information on storm preparations, particularly
for hurricanes, check out www.storm2000.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ A useful discussion of renters insurance is at www.giis.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
