<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6283 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN15-COX     03-14 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old hotel wears history well
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR KEY, Fla. _ I swallowed the last bite of tiramisu and
scraped back my chair along the bare boards of the hotel dining
room floor. ``I'm going to check out the bar,'' I said. If my
dinner companions, both of whom have known me since high school,
were a bit surprised at my abrupt leave-taking, they didn't let on.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, wandering into bars is not a habit of mine, but this
one I had to see. The Neptune Bar in the 140-year-old Island Hotel,
boasts that it's the only one in all of Levy County without a
television. Throughout dinner I'd been trying to picture a place
where folks go to practice the almost extinct art of conversation
rather than to stare bug-eyed at a speeding spheroid and indulge in
little more chat than to intermittently yell, ``GO, YOU HAIRY
DAWGS!''
</P>
<P>
   On my way through the lobby, I stopped to help Hannah and Annie,
the resident German shepherds, search for the red rubber ball
they'd lost under a low table. During dinner, we had commented on
how well behaved the girls were _ occasionally peeking around the
corner into the dining room but never setting foot inside.
</P>
<P>
   I fished out the ball and Hannah thanked me with a nuzzle.
Annie, the pup, grabbed it and ran.
</P>
<P>
   Just around the corner, the Neptune Bar was even better than I'd
hoped _ the kind of a place we'd all like to have in our
neighborhoods, where folks stop in for a drink, a chat, and maybe
even a hand or two of friendly bridge _ kibitzers encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   And no television.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, behind the bar is an elaborate mural of its namesake,
the ancient Roman god of the sea. Painted in 1948 by Helen Tooker,
it shows the royal denizen of the briny with a trident in his left
hand and a bare-breasted mermaid on his lap.
</P>
<P>
   When new owners took over the hotel in 1992, the Neptune had to
be rebuilt because a previous proprietor, a New England school
marm, had closed the bar to the public and (to the disgust of the
natives) turned it into a coffee and juice bar. Some regulars were
so incensed that they buried the owner in effigy in front of the
Post Office. ``A dubious honor,'' according to one historian,
``that had been previously awarded only to politicians who lost in
the local city commission elections.''
</P>
<P>
   A longtime patron of the pub volunteered his carpentry skills to
help restore it. His romance with the Neptune goes all the way back
to his boyhood when he had sneaked a peek around the door for a
glimpse of the mermaid _ the first naked lady he'd ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1950, the mural was stained by water leaking from
upstairs guest rooms when the roof was blown off in a hurricane.
And in 1993, when the painting was removed for restoration, bullet
slugs were found embedded in the wall behind it, grim evidence of
its lively past.
</P>
<P>
   Florida songwriter and balladeer Jimmy Buffet, a frequent
visitor to the Island Hotel, used to give impromptu concerts in the
Neptune. Once, he sat outside on the balcony singing to folks
passing by on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Famous names live on in the hotel's register: writer Pearl Buck,
singers Vaughn Monroe and Tennessee Ernie Ford, actresses Frances
Langford and Myrna Loy.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Boone, best known for his small-screen Paladin role,
spent time here, too, writing each morning and holding court in the
Neptune Bar come evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Island Hotel, built of massive 12-inch oak supports and
seashell tabby walls 10 inches thick, has withstood hurricanes,
tidal waves, and even the Civil War. Historians suggest it survived
the see-saw occupation, first by Union and then by Confederate
troops (the owner at that time was a Confederate
</P>
<P>
   major) because of its usefulness as a barracks and warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Personifying the 140-year-old structure, one historian describes
it as a building with uneven floors, expanding and contracting with
the seasons, and having all the aches and pains of an elderly lady.
</P>
<P>
   And a grand lady she is, too. She wears her history well.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett (AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
