<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meat becoming misty memory at our dinner table
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Tony Roma's, long did I lust for you.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what made me so covetous. Maybe it was the animal
in me as inheritor of the cave and the club. You specialize in
Flintstones food _ ribs _ meat off the bone. Such a primal feast.
Is this not why we have canine teeth?
</P>
<P>
   And now that you're in Waco, Tony, our love affair will never
be. Given a choice of meat or my family, I chose the latter, and
we're getting along just fine.
</P>
<P>
   My oldest son gave up meat almost three years ago. About a year
ago, after researching her son's vegetarian inclination, my wife
gave up meat, too. Her motivation was part nutrition, part animal
cruelty. Whatever, it stuck.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves two omnivores in the family, little brother and big
Daddy. But we rarely eat meat in any context because we've become
accustomed to doing without it. I will not swear off flesh, for no
other reason than I will not alter my chili, and I reserve for my
future an occasional burger or bratwurst with kraut. But by and
large I can get by without meat, and will.
</P>
<P>
   More and more families we know are just like us, with one or
more no-meat eaters. Commonly it is the young people swearing it
off and parents figuring out they don't need it either. Often,
adults who get accustomed to a low-fat diet come to realize they
have gone neo-vegetarian.
</P>
<P>
   How to account for Monday's Associated Press report that for the
first time since the 1980s meat consumption is going up, rather
than down? I don't know. I just know a whole bunch of families that
haven't been contributing to that trend.
</P>
<P>
   Navigating the meatless lifestyle has been an adventure, such as
finding substitutes that simulate some of life's staples.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one of the things our son missed when he swore off
meat was chicken noodle soup. His mother went looking for a
meatless substitute broth and found it. Now his occasional craving
is for fake chicken _ or ficken _ soup.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar Farms has found itself a niche in producing meatlike
entrees out of vegetable matter. It does burgers and sausages and
fake hot wings.
</P>
<P>
   This Thanksgiving, though, when she graciously committed herself
to preparing turkey for the flesh eaters in the family, my wife
looked high and low for something she'd read about in the paper _
tofu turkey _ for the others. Her search for tofurkey was in vain.
</P>
<P>
   I was waiting for this product, and wondering if someone had
figured out how to fake giblets.
</P>
<P>
   I have spent a lot of time in the last two years poring over can
labels looking for traces of meat in food. It's amazing how often
something that needn't have it _ vegetable soup, for instance _ has
beef or chicken by-products smuggled into it.
</P>
<P>
   The food industry seems to be largely oblivious to the fact that
more and more people just won't eat meat.
</P>
<P>
   As frustrating as shopping is, even more frustrating are
restaurants that give nary a thought to the fact that many
customers don't want meat. Too often, for many non-meat eaters, the
choice comes down to baked potatoes and salads.
</P>
<P>
   And fast-food? Get real. One of the savviest moves in the
industry was Wendy's introduction of pitas a couple of years ago.
Not only did Wendy's tap the quest of many to eat less fat, but for
those who don't eat meat the product was a godsend.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants seem to be missing a lick when they fail to adjust
to the numbers who eat no meat. Here's one family that goes only
where it has options.
</P>
<P>
   As for Tony Roma's, it still sounds appetizing. But it will have
to be ``Fony Romas _ A place for fibs'' to get my whole crew
through the door.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
