<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-SUNFIRE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pontiac Sunfire GT not lacking in spirit
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The ``pocket rocket'' segment of the auto market is
supposed to be history because of changing tastes, safety concerns
and fuel costs, but Pontiac blithely soldiers on with its Sunfire
GT, a spirited sprinter with attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The latter comes from an aggressive front end with low-slung fog
lamps, aero body-side trim and a teensy rear spoiler. Lively
performance comes from a 2.4-liter four-cylinder engine worth 150
horsepower and 155 pounds-feet of torque mated to a smooth
German-built, five-speed Getrag shifter.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunfire, with a base price of $14,420, is Pontiac's
entry-level offering, but the numbers move on up to $16,210 for the
GT and $21,610 for the GT convertible. The EPA labels the coupe and
droptop a subcompact but gives the $14,010 four-door a compact tag.
Either way, it's a small car.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunfire GT is fun, though, as long as you stay away from
speed limits _ the GT's not a stealth machine _ and heavy traffic.
It gives good road feel with enough steering-wheel feedback to
satisfy drivers who decry numbed-down steering. The
performance/economy compromise is a good one with the GT pegged at
23 mpg regular unleaded in the city and 33 on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Pontiac's efforts to upscale the Sunfire, it is
essentially a pumped-up Chevrolet Cavalier _ so, in coupe guise,
that means it's your basic two-adult car. Sitting in the rear is no
fun, but, hey, the entire rear seat back does fold down to provide
good cargo room. (It doesn't lock, not even on convertibles, which
can be an irritant).
</P>
<P>
   Few cars come with more options than the Sunfire, which does
make it possible to cater to individual tastes. The youth market,
which the Sunfire targets, is certain to appreciate the 200-watt,
eight-speaker Monsoon stereo system that tops the list of audio
offerings. A point Pontiac pushed is the RDS, or Radio Data
Systems, receiver that displays secondary signals on the FM band.
It'll identify stations and the format and pick up other text
messages such as weather forecasts, sports scores and even name
that tune.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the GT does lack the refinement of some of its
competitors. It's a bit of a throwback, sure, but give Pontiac
credit for making an honest effort to give entry-level buyers more
than basic transportation.
</P>
<P>
   2000 PONTIAC SUNFIRE GT
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 2000 Pontiac Sunfire GT front-drive coupe
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $18,600 (base: $16,210, plus $510 delivery)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 2.4-liter four-cylinder engine with 16 valves (150
horsepower), five-speed manual overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front air bags, side-impact beams, power
anti-lock brakes
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: package with 200-watt, eight-speaker
stereo, power mirrors and windows, keyless entry, cruise control,
$1,325; power sunroof, $555
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 23 mpg regular unleaded city, 33 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
