<P>
   DEATH-ROW (San Francisco) _ Death row inmate Darrell Rich will
not be allowed to participate in a Native American sweat lodge
ceremony to purify his soul before his scheduled execution early
Wednesday. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-HOUSING (San Francisco) _ Citing California's tightening
housing market, a coalition of state business, labor, housing
advocates and legislators are pushing legislation that would
increase affordable housing in the state's high job growth areas.
By RICHARD PAOLI.
</P>
<P>
   LEAP-CHAIR (San Francisco) _ Basketball coach Bobby Knight likes
to throw them, executives like to spin in them as they count their
money, and TV stars like to have sex in them _ at least during
``sweeps'' months. But chairs are rarely a hot topic for
watercooler chats. Mostly they just sort of sit in the background.
A $35 million chair may change all that. That's how much it cost
Steelcase to design its Leap chair, a four-year project aimed at
changing the basic foundation of the office chair. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CALIF (San Francisco) _ That California voters so strongly
embraced several Republican-backed ballot initiatives is a reminder
of just how conservative voters in the Golden State can be. This is
the state, after all, of Ronald Reagan and Richard Nixon, the state
that overwhelmingly rejected affirmative action, shut off services
to illegal immigrants, and snubbed gay and lesbian marriages. This
may be good news for Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive
Republican presidential nominee. By ZACHARY COILE and ROBERT
SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HERBAL-REMEDIES (San Francisco) _ The California Department of
Health is warning that herbal remedies may be toxic. The agency has
found dozens of imported herbal products contaminated with lead,
mercury, arsenic or dangerous chemicals. And it has identified
cases in which mishandled or mislabeled ingredients led to
life-threatening injuries and deaths. By ERIN McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-WINE-WEEK (Undated) _ This week's featured wine, the 1997
Ravenswood ``Napa Valley'' Zinfandel, costs about $15.99, and the
price tag is quite reasonable for a wine of this quality. By
MICHAEL LONSFORD. (For release Friday, March 17.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ Every day has cause for jubilation in
Louisiana. And this year is no different. The emphasis in 2000 is
on the rich musical heritage of a state that has produced Louis
``Satchmo'' Armstrong and Britney Spears, Mahalia Jackson and Tim
McGraw, Fats Domino and Harry Connick Jr. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ If you've been hearing the latest
stuff about computers taking over the world, and you're worried
your iMac might conspire with your Palm Pilot and murder you in the
night, I suggest you take a vacation and do some reading. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I figure a lot of you might have
heard about the anti-gay marriage ballot measure, known as the
Knight Initiative, which voters just enacted, overwhelmingly, out
here in California. I figure this because my mother (who lives in
Indiana) told me that Don Imus (who lives in New York) talked about
the proposition (22) on his daily radio-TV show. Mom said Imus
thought Californians were pretty mean-spirited to make such a big
deal out of denying lesbians and gays the right to
officially-recognized coupledom, or marriage. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   GUERRILLA-SCIENCE (Medford, N.J.) _ Actor Christopher Reeve is a
proponent of it. Michael J. Fox recently announced his retirement
from a hit TV series to become a full-time activist for it. A
number of individuals and families affected by amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis (ALS), or Lou Gehrig's Disease, have started their own
initiatives on its various fronts. ``It'' has been called
``guerrilla science''_ a war on incurable, often deadly, diseases.
Though the terms are ilitaristic, the goals are to save, not take,
lives. By DALE O'REILLEY.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6320 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BOTBALL-$ADV19-COX     03-14 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTBALL-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRMS TRY TECHNO-SPORTS TO BOLSTER SCIENCE AND MATH
 &HT;    1130&AMP;add. With BOTBALL-WEB. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, March 19.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SILVER SPRING, Md. _ Hundreds of Botball fans roared in the
bleachers as foot-high robots created by teens and pre-teens
scattered pingpong balls across a white tabletop.
</P>
<P>
   ``If every science classroom had this level of enthusiasm, we'd
be turning out world-class scientists by the dozens,'' said Lou
Mayo, a planetary scientist who works for Raytheon Corp. at the
Goddard Space Flight Center.
</P>
<P>
   His firm and Goddard are among the many employers testing the
notion that techno-sports can lure the next generation of workers
into studying more science and math.
</P>
<P>
   On each Botball table, kid-built robots that looked like
souped-up Mars rovers crashed into each other, retreated, twisted
and surged forward. The machines scored points by clambering onto a
slab of plastic foam or reaching up to sweep the correct color of
pingpong balls from an array on an overhead shelf.
</P>
<P>
   The robots started, operated and stopped themselves without
remote controls. They were designed, built and programmed by teams
from middle schools and high schools in the Baltimore-Washington
area.
</P>
<P>
   After each 90-second match, winners and losers in last weekend's
regional tournament scurried back to the kids-only pit area at the
other end of the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Parents, teachers and coaches hovered nervously behind the
velvet-covered ropes around the pit area. They watched some
students settle down at laptop computers to tweak programs in the
robots' computers and recalculate friction formulas. Others changed
gear ratios, recharged batteries and replaced parts that had broken
off.
</P>
<P>
   After six hours, The Claw, a robot created at North Bethesda
Middle School in Montgomery County, Md., ended up in second place
behind LegoMyRobot(cq), a pair of robots from Thomas Jefferson, a
science high school in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   At a post-victory news conference, David Sibert, 18, of
Alexandria, said, ``I think we won because we didn't build one big
robot. We used our parts to make a pair of simple, sturdy robots,
each with one simplified task.''
</P>
<P>
   His team won a trip to Austin, Texas, in August for the national
finals at the convention of the American Association for Artificial
Intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Seven weeks before the regional showdown, sponsors bought each
team a Tupperware tub full of loose plastic and metal parts, wire,
batteries, motors and light-reading sensors. Each tub also held two
unprogrammed computers _ a tiny RCX embedded in a Lego brick and a
mousetrap-sized Handy Board, which can control more motors and
sensors than the RCX.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors said they chipped in roughly $2,000 per team in order
to create good will, support education and enlarge their pool of
potential employees.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Nurvala of the Northern Virginia Technology Council said
that on occasion, a sponsor will offer a summer internship to one
of its players.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we don't want the kids to drop out of school and go to
work for our members right away,'' he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do want them to think about taking the right kind of
courses,'' he said, such as advanced algebra, trigonometry,
calculus and physics.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will prepare them for all sorts of careers with a
technology component, even if they don't go into programming or
building space vehicles,'' Nurvala said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Education Department, senior researcher Clifford Adelman
said, ``Algebra 2 will get you into college, and research shows
that going one step beyond algebra 2 will double the odds that you
will earn a bachelor's degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet pollsters confirm the paradox that while most youngsters
want to go to college, a high percentage of the students with those
dreams want to stop taking math and science as soon as they can.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some schools, particularly in poor areas, don't even
offer the most challenging courses.
</P>
<P>
   And with the advent of state-mandated tests, principals often
want their teachers to concentrate on preparing students for those
basic exams.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the nation's biggest and best-known high tech firms _
IBM, GTE, Intel, Cisco, BellSouth and others _ have been working
directly on those problems for years. The firms and related
foundations subsidize educational experiments and try to influence
state and federal policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in re-inventing education,'' said Robin
Willner, director of corporate social policy at IBM Corp. ``We want
every student to learn enough math and science to cope with the
modern world, whether they work for us, are our customers or are
citizens contributing to strong, stable communities.''
</P>
<P>
   However, reformers haven't detected much change. For example,
only about 16 percent of high school students take four years of
science and math.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel and Cisco and Microsoft: We're all dabbling in this, but
we don't know what to do,'' complained Craig Barrett, president and
chief executive officer of Intel. He estimated that his firm alone
spends more than $100 million on education efforts each year.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Gordon, author of ``Skill Wars: Winning the Battle for
Productivity and Profit,'' said, ``If we did have enough young
people interested in becoming chip makers, aerospace designers,
photocopy machine repair workers and electricians, we'd still lack
the schools to train them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidestepping the hassle over curricular content, many
technology-oriented businesses and trade associations are offering
more support to after-school activities like Botball.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-growing techno-sport began in Florida in 1997. It is
governed by the KISS Institute for Practical Robotics, a national
professional group that recently moved its headquarters to the
University of Oklahoma. KISS is derived from the slogan ``Keep it
simple, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years earlier, a nonprofit group in Manchester, N.H.,
called FIRST started another national robotics competition, in
which high school students pair up with engineers from corporations
or universities to build heavy-duty robots weighing up to 400
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST means ``for inspiration and recognition of science and
technology.'' Its cable-televised finals will be conducted at
Disney World in Orlando, Fla., in June.
</P>
<P>
   For youngsters 12 through 19 who prefer virtual reality, the
worldwide ThinkQuest (cq) competition provides an opportunity to
join international teams that use the Internet to build Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   With finals to be held this November in Cairo, Egypt, ThinkQuest
offers more than $1 million in scholarships and prizes for creators
of educational Web sites in five categories: arts and literature,
science and mathematics, sports and health, social sciences and
interdisciplinary.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good way for employers to target students,'' said
Maudie Hampden, 16, a freshman at Simon's Rock College in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   She was still studying at Orlando's Edgewater High School last
year when she, a girl from India and a boy from the Netherlands won
$25,000 apiece for their Web site on electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Hampden doubts that ThinkQuest could be integrated into the high
school curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes too intense an effort to expect it of anyone in
school, even in a design curriculum,'' Hampden said. ``We three
each had to work literally hundreds of hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Working on the Web site taught her ``networking skills and team
dynamics, and leadership in allotting work loads in different time
zones,'' Hampden said. She and one teammate, Alok Ladsaria (cq) of
Bombay, ``are working on a business plan for a start-up to create
multimedia educational tools for the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
