<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6324 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-14 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE MOUSE PAD THAT ROARED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you have been hearing the latest stuff about
computers taking over the world, and you are worried your iMac
might conspire with your Palm Pilot and murder you in the night, I
suggest you take a vacation and do some reading.
</P>
<P>
   You could buy the latest issue of Wired and read ``Why the
Future Doesn't Need Us,'' by Sun Microsystems co-founder Bill Joy,
who contends that the human race is threatened by advances in
robotics, nanotechnology and genetic engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Or you could read something much better written and more
prescient. Go on line or, better, go to a real bookstore and find a
short story by E.M. Forster called ``The Machine Stops.''
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``A Passage to India'' and ``A Room With a View''
wrote this science fiction story in 1909, and it presents a much
more interesting technological dystopia (a utopia you don't want)
than the one nearly a hundred years later in Wired.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, you don't have to put up with Joy's
self-absorption (he's lived in Aspen for the last decade, after
all) and his name-dropping. One day there may be computers as
intelligent as humans, but I doubt there ever will be computers as
egocentric.
</P>
<P>
   Joy is selling us the idea that computers could self-replicate
and take control of the world, or genetically engineered diseases
could kill us. He begins his argument by dropping the most
attention-getting name of all.
</P>
<P>
   He quotes mad bomber Theodore Kaczynski, who wrote in his
manifesto that computer systems could become so powerful that human
beings will be incapable of making the decisions to keep them
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that stage the machines will be in effective control,''
wrote Kaczynski. ``People won't be able to just turn the machines
off, because they will be so dependent on them that turning them
off would amount to suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost a century ago the gentle Forster was far ahead of both
Kaczynski and Joy.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Machine Stops,'' which understandably has a modern cult
following, Forster created a future world in which human beings
live underground in small rooms, hardly moving from their chairs,
their comfort perfectly maintained by the Machine man has invented.
</P>
<P>
   People are isolated, but communicate instantaneously with each
other all over the world, as they do on the Internet now. They can
adjust the light or climate in their rooms simply by speaking, just
as Bill Gates does in his dumb ``smart'' mansion. They've come to
hate nature. They worship the Machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created the Machine, but we cannot make it do our will
now,'' says one of Forster's characters, a rebellious one.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the Machine stops, dooming those who have become
dependent upon it.
</P>
<P>
   As Forster wrote, ``beautiful naked man was dying, strangled in
the garments he had woven.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's too 1909 poetic for you, think of those garments as a
2000 web of electrons.
</P>
<P>
   Some people survive Forster's dystopia, though _ those who
rejected the Machine and were sentenced to live above ground.
Intriguingly enough, those inheritors of the Earth are called the
Homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Joy recognizes that technological dystopias are hardly new, and
cites science fiction by Ray Bradbury and Kurt Vonnegut (but not
Forster's technological dystopia, one of the earliest). Joy
realizes that utopian techies will accuse him of being a Luddite,
despite his credentials as an ``architect of computer systems.''
</P>
<P>
   A builder of the Machine, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   His argument is that the human race can make itself obsolete
through the combination of genetic engineering, robotics and the
ability to engineer at the molecular level. To the threat of
nuclear weapons, we can add the threat of self-replicating plagues
or machines.
</P>
<P>
   Joy calls these instruments of ``knowledge-based mass
destruction,'' or KMD. He advocates the voluntary
``relinquishment'' by scientists of dangerous genetic,
nanotechnological and robotic (GNR) research, much as the United
States unilaterally renounced the development of biological
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   This may be hard, as Joy recognizes, because most GNR research
is done by highly competitive private companies. This is 2000, and
let's be realistic. The value of those companies' stock is more
important than the theoretical survival of our species.
</P>
<P>
   Is the human race threatened by what goes on in the flat
buildings of the Silicon Valley? The human race is always thinking
of some way to kill itself, so it's not a bad worry.
</P>
<P>
   So far, computer technology has mainly endangered our wrists,
our eyesight and, in the Silicon Valley, the ability to buy a home
at a reasonable price. Those who reject the Machine are threatened
with homelessness, as Forster foresaw.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe that devices that crash all the time can
get organized enough to make us obsolete. The fears raised by Joy
may be the ultimate arrogance of the computer technician _ that
he's helped create what could be Doomsday Machine 5.0.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, we don't know where technology is going. All we
know is that new technology is coming, and humans are pre-wired to
first fear it, then accept it, no matter how awful it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Machine develops _ but not on our lies,'' as Forster
wrote. ``The Machine proceeds _ but not to our good.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, I'm not shooting my balky iMac quite yet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
