<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH DAKOTA, OTHER STATES BRUTALIZE PROBLEM CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the 
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   Being
tough on crime has become an excuse to brutalize children.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rehabilitation of juvenile offenders is no longer the goal,
punishment is. Teen-agers have been beaten, abused, raped,
impregnated and sometimes even killed by guards in state detention
centers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Currently there are investigations of such abuses in Maryland,
Georgia, Delaware, Texas, Illinois, California, Louisiana,
Virginia, Florida, Arizona and South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Virginia's Juvenile Justice Director Gerald Glenn
instituted training in new kicking and striking techniques for
officers in the state's eight juvenile detention centers. The
officers were trained to use the ``whip kick,'' ``elbow strike,''
``shin rake,'' ``instep stomp'' and ``forearm body blow'' against
juveniles they think pose a threat. The new philosophy sanctions
the striking of children in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia's Department of Juvenile Justice came under scrutiny
last year for the death of a 16-year-old retarded boy who died
while in restraints in a youth detention center in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is closing its paramilitary boot camps after the U.S.
Department of Justice rebuked the state, calling the camps ``not
only ineffective but harmful'' to the juveniles in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's boot camps aren't the only ones investigated for
brutalizing children. South Dakota's juvenile corrections system
and its boot camps are currently under scrutiny by the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   In South Dakota, even ``children in need of supervision''
(CHINS) have been placed under the control of the Department of
Corrections for such ``offenses'' as truancy, running away from
home and poor grades. These children _ some as young as 13 _ have
been placed in boot camps and mistreated.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1999, Gina Score, a 226-pound, 14-year-old girl was
forced to run 2.7 miles at the boot camp Plankinton on her first
day at the corrections facility. She collapsed and died of
hyperthermia. She had been left lying in the sun for more than
three hours before an ambulance was called to take her to a
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations into this incident uncovered other abuses at the
Plankinton boot camp. Several girls were forced to run in shackles
until their ankles bled.
</P>
<P>
   A guard put a handcuff over his fist and punched a teen-age boy
in the face, breaking the child's tooth. The boy was in restraints
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Argus Leader, the Sioux Falls newspaper, in November
reported on a number of incidents at the State Training School at
Plankinton, which includes the boot camp: ``Teen-age girl inmates
strip-searched by male guards. Others sprayed with pepper spray
while naked. Still others handcuffed spread-eagled to beds.''
</P>
<P>
   The story failed to report that other teen-age girls had their
clothes cut off by male guards while they were spread-eagled in
handcuffs. According to one parent, her daughter was blindfolded so
she couldn't recognize the guards involved.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. William Janklow, who created the boot camps in South Dakota
after he took office in 1995, calls these incidents a problem with
``rogue guards.'' In an interview with the Argus Leader, Janklow
claimed he ``never ever had an inkling'' about the problems at
Plankinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the boot camp in Plankinton isn't the only problem in the
juvenile justice system in South Dakota. The boot camp in Custer
also has a record of abusing its teen-age wards. A counselor there
has been accused of molesting six young boys.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the governor nor his spokesman, Bob Mercer, returned
numerous telephone calls requesting an interview last week,
although both were present in the office, according to the
governor's secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Gramkow, a resident of Sioux Falls, frustrated at the
way her 14-year-old daughter had been treated in the Plankinton
facility, began the Parents Who Care Coalition for parents of
children caught up by the state's Department of Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 130 parents are now active members who are
attempting to educate state legislators about the abuses occurring
in the juvenile justice system in South Dakota. So far, their three
main proposals for legislation have been killed: a children's
rights bill, a parent's rights bill, and a bill that would separate
CHINS from juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
   When Gramkow visited her daughter at the Plankinton facility,
she found her daughter had multiple bruises on both arms. One, she
said, looked as if it had been the result of being struck with a
club.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, a group of teen girls in a suicidal rage broke
light bulbs and cut up their arms. The guards merely watched, said
Gramkow. She said one girl attacked her daughter and cut up her
arms and wrists. The girls didn't get medical treatment for their
lacerations for more than four hours.
</P>
<P>
   How did Gramkow's daughter enter the nightmare world of South
Dakota juvenile corrections? She was a runaway. Now she's scarred
for life _ emotionally and physically.
</P>
<P>
   Edith Barden of Spearfish has a 14-year-old granddaughter in the
juvenile corrections system. The granddaughter's crime was truancy
and poor grades in school. The granddaughter's mother, according to
Barden, is an alcoholic and the child would sometimes stay home to
care for her.
</P>
<P>
   From the child's own compassion and love for her mother, she
became a truant and subsequently her grades suffered.
</P>
<P>
   And now she is in a hospital in Yankton because she attempted
suicide after being told she wouldn't be allowed to go home until
she was 21 years old. They can do that in South Dakota _ hold a
child for an indeterminate period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Deb Phillips of Rapid City is the western coordinator for the
Parents Who Care Coalition. Her 13-year-old daughter entered the
juvenile corrections system when she became truant and a runaway.
She was sent to the boot camp in Custer.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Guettler lives in Spearfish. Her daughter was put in the
Juvenile Services Center in Rapid City because she skipped school
and missed 20 days. The Guettlers were forced to sign a paper,
which turned their daughter over to the state, under the threat of
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Guettler's daughter has a drug and alcohol problem. State
corrections officials wanted her in a boot camp, not a treatment
center. The daughter also has a severe ear infection, but the
officials at the Custer boot camp would not allow her to see a
doctor for the problem.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 24, the Youth Law Center filed a class action lawsuit in
a federal district court against the South Dakota Department of
Corrections and the superintendent of the State Training School at
Plankinton. The lawsuit alleges numerous abuses and inhumane
treatment of children while they were in state custody.
</P>
<P>
   On March 6, the international watchdog group Human Rights Watch
sent a letter to Gov. Janklow urging him to take steps to ensure
that state policy respects children's fundamental rights and end
their inhumane treatment.
</P>
<P>
   These stories illustrate the depth and breadth of the problem in
one state. This is how South Dakota treats its problem children.
The governor has been quoted as calling them ``scum.'' And, as the
governor sets the tone of his administration, the children are
treated accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem of the mistreatment of our children is much
deeper and broader than any one state. This nightmare has swept
across our nation.
</P>
<P>
   The brutalization of children in state custody is the product of
a corrupt philosophy _ a philosophy without compassion, without an
understanding of the troubles faced by children, without trust or
respect and without a faith in their potential for rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-13-00 1116EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
