<P>
   &UR; NEW AMERICA, SAME OLD POLITICS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And then there were two. ``Super Tuesday'' has left America,
predictably, with a choice between Al Gore and George W. Bush. They
won by showing that they are regular party animals. And that, for
the United States, is where the problem lies. The country is
undergoing its greatest social and demographic changes in a
century. Neither political party has come to terms with these
changes. Curiously, the oldest man running for president, John
McCain, was the one who most clearly understood the future. But now
he is gone, and it's back to ``politics as usual.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
