<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOOD NEWS: MEXICAN MEDIA ARE GETTING BOLDER, BETTER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The methods of control were more subtle, but Mexico's media long
bore more than a passing resemblance to those of Soviet Russia. No
wonder, then, that for the past seven decades the Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI) rarely had trouble winning elections or,
when it did, in getting away with fraud. Things are changing
though, and Mexico's media are well on the road to freedom; the
road to quality may prove to be much longer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-PRESS-MEXICO-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILL VENEZUELA'S DISGRUNTLED TROOPS TURN ON CHAVEZ? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hugo Chavez, Venezuela's elected president, first grabbed the
attention of his countrymen in 1992, when as a paratroop
lieutenant-colonel he tried to stage a coup against a democratic
government. Could Chavez himself be ousted by a coup? Such talk
seems premature, but that has not stopped several Venezuelans from
musing aloud about the ironic possibility. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-COUP-CARACAS?-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10-GALLON CLOUT: TEXAS ART LOSES ITS DRAWL, STANDS TALL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Art boosters in Texas have long boasted that their state was a
``third coast'' of contemporary art in America. Yet they were never
really able to convince New York or California to take them
seriously _ until now. On March 23, the 2000 Biennial Exhibition
opens at the Whitney Museum of American Art in New York. The show
will feature nine artists from the Lone Star State, the largest
number of Texas artists ever in a Biennial, and the largest from
any one state outside of New York and California. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Texas Editors...NOTE March 23, N.Y. Biennial) &QL;
</P>
