   &UR; Moved as BC-HOT-TEXAS-ART-ECONOMIST-725&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IF YOU THINK THIS CAMPAIGN IS SLEAZY, CHECK OUT 1948'S &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks this year's American election campaign is
particularly dirty should read a new book, ``American Dreamer: A
Life of Henry A. Wallace,'' and think again. When Henry Wallace,
Franklin D. Roosevelt's third-term vice president, had the temerity
to break away from the Democratic Party and run on the Progressive
ticket in 1948, he was ruthlessly demonized as a wild-eyed fanatic
bent on destroying the American way of life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary, Book Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-DIRTY-POLITICS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOBILE INTERNET: A MATCH MADE IN HEAVEN _ AND JAPAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nobody doubts it anymore. The marriage of the mobile telephone
and the Internet is a match made in heaven. Hardly a day passes in
America and Europe without an announcement of a new alliance
between dot.coms, telecoms firms and computer companies, all
jostling for advantage in the brave new world around the corner.
Yet, despite the buzz, the embarrassing truth is that while the
Americans and Europeans have been talking, NTT DoCoMo, Japan's
dominant mobile operator, has been doing: turning the wireless
Internet into reality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 600 words; 1,350 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WIRELESS-WEB-400&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GERMAN GENDER-BENDERS: BREAKING THE POLITICAL GLASS CEILING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For now, there is only one serious candidate left in the running
for the leadership of Germany's Christian Democratic Union (CDU).
After the withdrawal on March 5 of Volker Ruhe, Angela Merkel, the
party's general secretary, has become the hot favorite among the
rank and file. But in the eyes of the CDU leadership and of its
conservative Bavarian sister party, Mrs. Merkel suffers from two
grave drawbacks: she comes from the former communist east, and _
god forbid _ she is a woman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-`FRAU'-POLITICS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE INTERNET AND FRENCH CULTURE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than any other medium in recent years, the Internet is
challenging France's vigilant attempts to control and protect its
culture. This is, after all, a cyberworld dominated by the English
language, in which French is used by only 1.2 percent of the
world's Web sites and even fewer of all international online
forums. ``Mon Dieu! To the barricades!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-CYBER-CULTUREKILLER-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MARTIANS: COMING SOON TO A SCREEN NEAR YOU &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is going out of this world. On March 10, ``Mission to
Mars,'' the first of several forthcoming Martian movies, opened in
cinemas across America. For the growing ``Mars advocacy'' movement,
these movies are more than mere entertainment. They are also a
valuable opportunity to capitalize on public interest in all things
Martian to raise support _ and cash _ for exploration of the red
planet itself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 325 words; 1,200 uncut) &QL;
