   In Podgorica the real fear is that an economic noose is being
tightened around them.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Villa Gorica, Montenegro's official government
house, Vujanovic said that Belgrade's ``brutal'' strategy is to use
economic hardship to prompt civil unrest which will provide a fig
leaf for military intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``His intention,'' said Vujanovic ``is to destabilize Montenegro
in two stages: first economically and socially and then he will use
economic and social dissatisfaction, provoking people to go out
into the streets and make demonstrations in which conflicts will
arise.
</P>
<P>
   ``These conflicts could,'' he added, ``be used by Milosevic to
interfere with his army.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro remains part of the Yugoslav federation but has
regularly defied Belgrade and even adopted the deutschmark as its
official currency.
</P>
<P>
   In return Milosevic started to choke the economy of the small
republic of around 650,000 people which is reliant on Serbia for 60
percent of its food supplies and 70 percent of its medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Although the standard of living is higher in Montenegro than in
Serbia, attempts to bolster the economy have so far failed.
</P>
<P>
   When Montenegro agreed to open its borders to Albania, Belgrade
responded by setting up regular police blockades of the routes from
Serbia into Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   In another apparent move to intimidate Montenegro, Belgrade has
announced several weeks of military maneuvers and, according to
sources in Podgorica, begun a new round of recruitment into his
paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Political instability has again dented Montenegro's hopes of
attracting foreign visitors to its spectacular coastline which once
supported a thriving tourist trade.
</P>
<P>
   In another blow to local hoteliers, Montenegro's adoption of the
deutschmark has made Montenegro too expensive for most Yugoslav
visitors this summer.
</P>
<P>
   With mounting concern about security of the region, Europe gave
its most public demonstration of support for Montenegro on Friday
when Chris Patten, European Commissioner for Foreign Affairs,
became the first western politician to cross the border into
Montenegro since the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing 5 million euros of new financial support for the
country, Patten said that some of Milosevic's decisions ``suggest
that he is up to his old malign tricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Madeleine Albright, the U.S. secretary of state, who met
Djukanovic in Sarajevo last week, Patten is anxious to dissuade
Montenegro from attempting full independence fearing that this
would provoke violent opposition from sections of the population in
the north which is loyal to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Vujanovic said he was satisfied with assurances, given to the
Montenegran president by Albright, that any Yugoslav invasion would
be resisted by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``These messages should be reiterated all the time
because they are hard for Milosevic is understand. Even when he
hears them, he forgets.'' &QL; 
