<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEFT COAST ISN'T AS BAD AS YOU THINK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I figure a lot of Americans might have heard
about the anti-gay marriage ballot measure, known as the Knight
Initiative, that voters just enacted, overwhelmingly, in
California.
</P>
<P>
   I figure this because my mother (who lives in Indiana) told me
that Don Imus (who lives in New York) talked about California's
Proposition 22 on his daily radio/TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Mom said Imus thought Californians were pretty mean-spirited to
make such a big deal out of denying lesbians and gays the right to
officially recognized coupledom, or marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said love is love and if people want to get married, we
should let 'em,'' she said. ``It was kind of surprising because the
I-man tends to make fun of just about everybody but the little kids
with cancer who come to his ranch.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I couldn't agree more with Don Imus. Proposition 22, the
so-called ``definition of marriage'' measure, was a sad, nasty and
totally avoidable exercise in divisiveness.
</P>
<P>
   What I'd ask you folks outside of California to remember,
though, is something most Americans forget when we hear about a
voter referendum passing or failing in somebody else's state:
</P>
<P>
   ``California'' did not vote for Proposition 22.
</P>
<P>
   What happened was that 4,162,017 Californians voted for it.
That's a majority, for sure, and laws are made by majority rule.
But a not-inconsequential number of people punched ``No'' on the
measure _ 2,618,337, to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   As one of those 2.6 million-plus people, I'll be damned if I'll
be lumped in with Californians who feel compelled to tell the world
that, ``Only marriage between a man and a woman is valid or
recognized in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Paint all of California with the broad brush of intolerance and
exclusivity, and you paint me and 2,618,336 other like-minded
souls.
</P>
<P>
   You paint a Daly City man named Livius Guiao, who wrote a letter
to the editor: ``I cringe when I think of what the (pro-Proposition
22) message might be.''
</P>
<P>
   You paint a San Francisco man named Charles Burch, who wrote:
``Which group or movement in history do you admire that defined its
own rights on the premise that those same rights should be denied
to others?''
</P>
<P>
   You paint a Santa Rosa woman named Susan Lamont, who wrote that,
thanks to the latest election: ``Now, more than ever, it is
embarrassing to be a Californian.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking umbrage at several of the ballot measures approved last
week, Lamont sarcastically suggested that voters stop pussyfooting
around and do what they really want to do.
</P>
<P>
   For gays, she wrote, ``let's revive the stocks. State Sen. Pete
Knight, R-Palmdale, can throw the first tomato at his own son.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamont was referring to the lawmaker who was responsible for
getting Proposition 22 on the ballot. Four times he had failed to
get such a marriage declaration passed in the state Senate, so he
took his crusade to the voters.
</P>
<P>
   That Knight has a gay son and a gay brother who died of AIDS
caused a lot of people to wish he'd chosen a therapist's office
instead of the March 7 primary election to work out his personal
issues around homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't. And more than 4 million Californians supported
him. So the whole state is stuck, for now, with a ban on same-sex
marriages.
</P>
<P>
   All I'm saying is, before any of you non-Left Coasters think
about boycotting us for our homophobia or _ worse _ decide you
might move here because you HATE gay people and think you've found
Valhalla-by-the-Pacific, don't.
</P>
<P>
   That especially goes for you, Imus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
