<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIALEAH APPROACHES THE FINISH LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what is certainly the beginning of the end for storied
Hialeah Park, this season's 63-day Hialeah meeting, which begins
Friday, will be held at Gulfstream Park.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of speculation, Hialeah chairman John Brunetti made
the official announcement March 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 23 years, peace has come to Florida racing,'' said
Brunetti. ``There were too many complications to do it for more
than one year. There are regulatory matters to be worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are obvious challenges to overcome,'' said Doug Donn,
president of Gulfstream Park, which opened Jan. 3 and was slated to
close Thursday. ``We will be like a landlord. We will run the
physical plant, and maintain the turf course and main track.
Hialeah will run the race meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ``Hialeah at Gulfstream'' meeting opens, Donn will step
down as Gulfstream president to become chairman. David Romanik,
chief counsel for Gulfstream, will become president and general
manager, and run the daily operations.
</P>
<P>
   Hialeah was once the sparkling jewel of Florida racing,
unchallenged in its supremacy. In the 1970s, Gulfstream began to
creep up, and by the mid '80s, Gulfstream had surpassed Hialeah. A
fierce battle over the prime dates, January through March, ensued.
At one point, the two tracks alternated the best dates. Then came
deregulation. In 1993, the Florida tracks agreed to the current
arrangement on dates, which includes Calder running from May
23-Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line on all this is that Florida racing fell off the
map when Gulfstream closed, not to return until Gulfstream
reopened. The switch will be a financial boon to both horsemen and
bettors. By agreement, Hialeah's horsemen received $113,500 per day
in purses, but Gulfstream, with much higher handle potential, will
pay far more. In a misguided attempt to make up for sluggish
business, Hialeah long has had an onerous takeout structure, the
highest in thoroughbred racing. That, too, has been changed.
</P>
<P>
   It is not official that racing at Hialeah is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``For now, we don't want to go beyond a one-year deal,'' said
Brunetti. However, the situation is obvious, and it is the
charismatic Frank Stronach, who bought Gulfstream then turned his
attention to Hialeah, that made it happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, for one, feel that this is a new beginning and something I
have hoped for the last 10-15 years,'' said Brunetti.
``Unfortunately, the opportunity did not arise until now. But, with
the vision and cooperation of Mr. Frank Stronach, we are
proceeding. We don't have all the answers to all the questions, but
he and I are committed to try our best on all issues. The future
looks bright, and I look forward to the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Stronach eventually will buy out Brunetti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gulfstream Park looks forward to working with Hialeah Park in
making this new `Hialeah at Gulfstream' race meet a success, and a
positive step in the right direction for all of South Florida
racing,'' said Lonny Powell, executive vice president of Magna
Entertainment, which is the leisure arm of the financial empire
built by Stronach. ``Even though our leasing of our facility to
Hialeah is currently agreed upon for one season, we consider it to
be symbolic of the desire of our company and its chairman to work
with all segments of the Florida thoroughbed industry, including
Calder, the horsemen, and the breeders.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen what will happen to Hialeah, but it could
be transformed into a park, museum, and training center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flamingos stay,'' said Brunetti.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Racetrack publicity and the Daily Racing Form were used to prepare
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
