<HEADLINE>
CBS WILL BASKET WEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No sense beating around the bush with March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   The first game of the first round, between St. Bonaventure and
Kentucky, tips off Thursday at 12:20 p.m. on CBS (Channel 4). The
second game, starting around 3 or so, is Syracuse-Samford.
</P>
<P>
   The first-round night action starts at 7:55 p.m., with Maryland
vs. Iona, followed by St. John's and North Arizona around 10:30.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, CBS will switch to as many games as possible,
depending on the excitement, but as it stands, Central
Connecticut's game against Iowa State Thursday will be shown in the
Hartford area, but not Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's first-round women's game between Boston College and
Nebraska will not be shown on television, but you can monitor it on
BC's Web site, www.bceagles.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Silent treatment &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The war of the mikes rages on, as NBA ratings on NBC are down 42
percent, even with Vince Carter, from last year. The NBA and NBC
are trying to get coaches to wear microphones; and coaches are just
saying no.
</P>
<P>
   The latest embarrassment occurred Sunday when both Toronto
Raptors coach Butch Carter and Seattle SuperSonics coach Paul
Westphal refused. ``I just can't do it,'' Westphal told KJR radio.
``It's an unfair restriction on my ability to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, NBC aired a discussion about the idea during its
halftime show. Hannah Storm said that NBA commissioner David Stern
is in favor of it in part because viewers at home want to hear the
same things that people seated at courtside hear. Stern said
coaches have worn mikes for 20 years and the coaches association is
making ``a bad mistake'' in trying to ``push back the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Storm explained that the coaches' comments during games are
screened for profanity and coaches are allowed to turn off the
mikes during sensitive times as long as they wear them for the
majority of the game.
</P>
<P>
   So much for objective journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Carter explained his decision on NBC. ``I talked to Charles
Oakley and Antonio Davis,'' Carter said. ``They asked me not to
wear it. They thought it was an invasion. My general manager asked
me to wear the mike. I cannot afford to lose the respect of my
players. If I have to, I will pay the fine myself.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC analyst Peter Vecsey also took the company line.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years coaches and players have been getting away with
denying us access,'' he said. ``When I first started covering the
league 30 years ago, I was allowed in practices, I was allowed on
team buses, on team planes. Maybe that's why they won't allow
anybody in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got increasingly worse over the years. Now I think the
league is coming down on them a little hard. But it's not that
hard. They're trying to turn something benign, these coaches and
players _ some players _ into a controversy. To me that's just an
overreaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Isiah Thomas had a more practical assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may end up getting the access that you want in terms of
being in the huddle and everything else, but you may not get the
information that you're looking for, because a lot of the coaches
and a lot of the players, once they see the microphone _ just like
anyone else _ you know you talk different and you say things
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Vecsey had the last word:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of these coaches are so insecure and so paranoid
and such control freaks they're trying to control all the
information. Just relax. It's not going to be a big deal here. None
of this stuff is going to get out that you're so worried about.
Maybe they're worried about getting exposed that they can't
coach.''
</P>
<P>
   No word yet on whether the NBA will fine Westphal or Carter the
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demonic forces &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   St. John's point guard Erick Barkley explained his tiff with
teammate Bootsy Thornton to All Sports 1510's Dave Harbison. ``It's
just the devil coming into our home and just trying to do things to
us that weren't the truth and people trying to take us down, but we
all came together as a family and just stuck it to the person
whoever it was trying to do this,'' Barkley said after St. John won
the Big East crown. ``You know life goes on and I'm sure everyone's
just ready to play basketball.'' . . . ESPN2 airs ``Big League
Challenge,'' a home run contest, for 10 consecutive weeks beginning
next Monday at 5:30 p.m. Participating sluggers will be Mark
McGwire, Jose Canseco, Barry Bonds, Rafael Palmeiro, Jason Giambi,
Nomar Garciaparra, Alex Rodriguez, Shawn Green, Mike Piazza, Manny
Ramirez, Chipper Jones, and Andruw Jones. ``Our goal is to maintain
the charm and simplicity of the 1959 Home Run Derby series while
incorporating the technology of 2000,'' said Tim Scanlon, ESPN
coordinating producer. The show will use Bat Track, ESPN's
exclusive bat-speed measurement system, as well as Maskcam . . .
ABC's regional coverage of the NHL this Saturday includes
Bruins-Penguins at 3, and network officials said there will be
frequent break-ins to Colorado-Detroit so Boston viewers can see
Ray Bourque in action for the Avalanche. The Bruins game goes to 10
percent of the country while the Avalanche game will be shown in 57
percent. The third game is Rangers-Flyers . . . Former
``SportsCenter'' anchor Jack Edwards will be lead play-by-play
announcer for Major League Soccer telecasts on ESPN, ESPN2, and ABC
. . . The Patriots are scheduled to play the San Francisco 49ers on
ABC's first Monday night preseason game, the Hall of Fame Game July
31.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
