<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG THINGS EXPECTED OF GARCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ They dress next to each other in the Red Sox
clubhouse here, and soon their families will be year-round
neighbors in a Fort Myers subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just two doors away,'' Rich Garces said of moving into Derek
Lowe's slice of southwest Florida. ``I told him I'd teach him some
Spanish. He'll probably try to get me to play some golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe and Garces come into this season as the long and thick of
the Sox relief corps. The 6-foot-6-inch Lowe is all legs and
angles, with a pterodactyl's wing span. Garces, meanwhile, has the
shape and consistency of an arepa, the corn-flour tortilla so
popular in his native Venezuela. He's listed in the Sox media guide
at 215 pounds, but as one Sox staffer cracked earlier this spring,
``That's his birth weight.'' He's much closer to 260 than 215.
</P>
<P>
   But after a season in which Garces put more notches in the win
column (5) than he did in his belt, and his earned run average of
1.55 was a fraction of his weight, Garces figures to be a big man
in the pen for more than the obvious reasons. With Lowe promoted to
closer, Garces will be asked to assume a greater share of the setup
role Lowe performed with such aplomb last season.
</P>
<P>
   He may have begun to stake his claim to that job during Game 4
of the ALCS against the Yankees last October, when Jimy Williams
summoned him to face Scott Brosius and Chad Curtis with the bases
loaded in the eighth inning of a one-run game. Brosius popped out
to first and Garces struck out Curtis, ending the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best game I ever had in my life,'' said Garces, who is
still only 28 years old but first appeared in the big leagues for
Minnesota in 1990, a decade ago. ``It was a dream come true, a game
I'll never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when Sox general manager Dan Duquette, annoyed
that Garces had added a dozen pounds during camp, left him behind
and put him on the disabled list with a phantom groin strain. That
happened in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan jokes around with me now,'' Garces said. ``He asks me how
I'm doing, how's my pitching. I'm very slow. I'm not kidding
myself. But the most important thing is to keep my arm in shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people wonder, `That guy is big, he's fat, can he do
the job?' But I did the job. My father and my mother are big, three
times bigger than me. My brothers are all big. It's not easy for
me. But as long as I'm here and working out every day, it's OK,
because I'm going to be big, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Garces, who was coming off elbow surgery, did not join the Sox
last season until July, and even then his promotion was a mixed
blessing. His wife, Lisabeth, was about to have the couple's third
child, but instead of flying back to Venezuela, Garces joined the
Sox in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little sad about missing my daughter's birth,'' Garces
said, ``but Jimy called me into his office and said, `We need you
here. You're the guy we think can do the job here. That's why we
called you up, and we hope you'll help us get to the playoffs.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That was good he said that. It gave me confidence, and look
what happened. I'm very proud of what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Garces appeared in 30 games for the Sox, all but one after the
All-Star break. Besides his five wins, he had two saves. Lefties
hit just .197 against him, righties only .150. He gave up just one
home run in 40 2/3 innings, and only 3 of the 17 runners he
inherited scored.
</P>
<P>
   He abandoned his circle changeup in favor of a split-fingered
fastball that he found very effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I faced a lot of lefties _ Tino Martinez, Robbie
Alomar, Jim Thome _ and I put them away with the split,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garces did not make the trip here Monday for Boston's 8-6 win
over the Expos in 10 innings, but he'll be in the bullpen behind
Pedro Martinez Tuesday in Fort Myers when the Sox play the Toronto
Blue Jays. In his first three appearances, he has yet to allow a
run, giving up two hits while striking out four in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The games that I've pitched, I've been focused on every
pitch,'' said Garces, who will share setup duties for now with Rod
Beck and lefthanded specialist Rheal Cormier. ``Last year was the
first time I've ever been to the playoffs, and every single game
was so important. It was so exciting, and that's why I want to go
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on Garces and new neighbor Lowe, the Sox just might.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
