<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GRAY AREA IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- He has raised political money in California
pretty much the way George W. Bush has raised it throughout the
country _ without apology and on a scale essentially without
precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bush, he's also done it without serious legal challenge,
though ethicists and reformers howl at the sheer excess.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Bush, California Governor Gray Davis is an
experienced Democratic pol down to his shoes. And he does not share
the ``passion'' his man, Vice President Al Gore, says he has
developed in his effort to supplant John McCain as the leading
advocate of campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, Davis just finished a busy election season in
which he opposed the attempt to rewrite the state's anything-goes
election finance laws by referendum.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Proposition 25's demise, the governor may now
support an effort by the state's Democratic leaders to write
legislation focusing on limits on currently unregulated
contributions. But it is nowhere near the top of his priorities
list.
</P>
<P>
   It's Davis's detached, cold, borderline cynicism about the
national shouting match over political cash that makes him
interesting these days.
</P>
<P>
   The word Davis uses often to describe the argument about
limitless gifts of soft money and ``independent'' expenditures on
the side by interest groups and wealthy individuals is
``irrelevant.'' He figures that what matters most to California
voters is the health of the state's economy, which having made a
successful transition out of its Cold War dependance on aerospace
is no longer lagging behind the country's prosperity. That also
means continuing to clean up the air and keep the coast free of any
more oil rigs; it means a dropping crime rate and a continuing push
for more gun control; and it means defending a woman's right to
choose.
</P>
<P>
   With that mix, Davis figures Gore starts the campaign 8 to 10
points ahead of Bush here and the numbers back him up.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance reform, to Davis, is of consequence only if
campaign finance abuses can be connected to something in government
that is not happening that people strongly want to happen. Were
Gore and Bush to agree on some mutual restrictions on money this
fall (don't hold your breath), that wouldn't bother the governor;
nor would passage of new regulations by Congress or his own state's
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis says without flinching that he has seen no evidence
that reform is a top priority for the public.
</P>
<P>
   Where California is concerned, he and other Democrats make an
additional point. Bush may or may not score points going around the
country repeating two words that have magical status for his
handlers _ ``Buddhist temple.'' In this state, they figure every
time that happens, another Asian-American decides to vote for Gore.
This increasingly important segment of the voting population, once
up for grabs, has been realigning Democratic ever since the uproar
over the campaign sins of 1996 began exceeding the hard evidence of
malfeasance.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis's point about campaign money not meaning anything
without an issue connection that matters to ordinary people can be
answered. Taxes, HMO reform, tobacco industry crackdown, the
environment, and the minimum wage come to mind just for starters.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, things would be happening if special interests did
not continually trump the national interest, with campaign cash the
basic medium of exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Davis may have an unassailable point about what matters most to
voters, but the fact is that campaign finance reform can be made to
matter precisely by making the connection the governor tends to
dismiss.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office last year, Davis has become a walking
advertisement for reform. While his governance gets very high marks
and he couldn't be more popular, he wasted no time raising some $13
million for his political fund, an obscene amount that is on a
comparative par with Bush's now-dissipated $70 million. To make it
worse, Davis's money _ entirely within the law _ comes from every
corporation and union with an agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the money was raised in case the referendum that failed
last week had passed, and it will give Davis a huge headstart
should a reform measure pass later this year. And an initiative
adopted by the voters four years ago and tied up in the courts,
whose limits are positively draconian, may yet emerge intact.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has a point. Here and nationally, nothing tops the Big
Four issues he believes Gore can win on (the economy, crime and gun
control, choice, and the environment). Reform or nonreform, it pays
to focus on issues that matter most to people and never to lose
that focus.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not an argument for failing to pick up John McCain's
fallen standard. Davis's stance works for him, but it is not
president-worthy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
