<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6389 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DESIGN-AWARD16-COX     03-14 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGN-AWARD16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlantan's furniture wins national awards
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 16.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Michael Gilmartin first began making furniture in
the 1970s, it was anything goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just shot from the hip with lots of organic forms,'' the
Atlanta artist said. ``Now, what I'm trying to do is introduce lots
of sweeping curves to really balance the pieces out.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it's working. For the past two years, Gilmartin's
pieces have won prestigious national Awards for Design Excellence
presented by Design Journal, the most recent for his AVOS Armchair.
The piece, featured in the February issue, is made of a special
Douglas fir plywood and reminiscent of the work of modern designer
Charles Eames.
</P>
<P>
   ``I designed the chair back in the '80s around the `A' and `V'
shapes,'' said Gilmartin, who is among 250 craft artists chosen to
show their work in this weekend's American Craft Council Craft Show
at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The artist uses laminated, 13-ply-per-inch aircraft plywood made
specially for him. Not only is the material extremely stable for
sculpting, but it ages in the warm tones of cherry. The wood's
striation effect is enhanced by an oil-and-urethane finish.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmartin, 49, draws much of his inspiration from the modern
designers of the 20th century. ``They wanted to make pieces that
speak about today,'' he said. ``What I'm trying to do is to make
those pieces accessible to more people.''
</P>
<P>
   The artist operates a one-man studio in an old warehouse
district off Huff Road. It's a business that began more than 20
years ago when he moved to Atlanta from Philadelphia, shortly after
earning a master's of business administration degree. Despite the
advanced degree, ``I never got a real job,'' Gilmartin said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a friend asked him to form a business, and Gilmartin
built a career of designing and building custom furniture for homes
and businesses _ so custom that clients go to his studio to be
``fitted'' for his chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ergonomics is a buzzword, but the beauty of my chairs is that
you can shift your weight in them,'' he said, citing their
contoured backs and adjustable seats.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his most popular designs are the Gilmartin Chair, a
rocker that won a 1998 Award for Design Excellence, and the AVOS,
which beat out more than 1,600 entries in last year's residential
seating category.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent over two weeks judging this category, and if it were
not for a deadline, it would have been two months,'' said John
Moses, publisher of Design Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmartin has made about 15 of the AVOS chairs. It takes six to
eight weeks to produce one, and it sells for $3,450. The Gilmartin
rocker, now part of the permanent collection of the Mint Museum in
Charlotte, sells for $3,895.
</P>
<P>
   The artist doesn't claim a favorite item to craft. ``The AVOS
chair is fun to do, though, because of the stark linearity of it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   And as modern furnishings continue to experience a revival in
popularity, the design is bound to enjoy appeal among fans of fine
crafts. ``Most people want something that looks good and that they
can use,'' Gilmartin said.
</P>
<P>
   I F Y O U G O
</P>
<P>
   American Craft Council Craft Show
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When: 10 a.m.-6 p.m. Saturday, 10 a.m.-
</P>
<P>
   5 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where: Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cost: $6.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 404-892-4505, Ext. 111.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
