<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6390 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-METAL-DECOR16-COX     03-14 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METAL-DECOR16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Metal's sleek styling is showing up all over the house giving
any decor a dose of design impact
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday March 16.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Metal is back with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   After years of being limited to patio furniture and contemporary
pieces that blended best with modern decor, designers are creating
metal furnishings in every form imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   From tables to chairs, to bed frames, breakfast bars, desks,
lamps and candleholders, metal is one of the hottest materials in
the home furnishings market.
</P>
<P>
   But we're not talking about any metal. This is the season of
silver tones. The trend toward steel, aluminum, pewter, zinc and
polished iron is so strong it has spilled over into the paint
department. Designers are using faux metallic paint with a matte or
textured finish to give wood furniture and accessories the look of
metal.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the longest time, brass and glass were the mainstay,''
said Jackie Hirschhaut, vice president of the American Furniture
Manufacturers Association in High Point, N.C. ``But metal will be
very prevalent in the year 2000. We'll have 2,400 exhibitors this
year at High Point (the world's largest wholesale furniture
market), and I can assure you there will be plenty of metal
furniture within that mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Metal furniture and accessories accounted for $2.5 billion in
national furniture sales in 1999, or about 10 percent of the
industry total, and the figure is expected to grow.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the popularity of metal can be seen in the local
furniture industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has been very positive in Atlanta,'' said Jimmy
Huff, vice president of Huff Furniture in Buckhead. ``We've seen an
increase in sales in the last three years, basically because
there's more designs to choose from.''
</P>
<P>
   Business is so good that Gloria Ventura, a metro Atlanta artisan
who specializes in iron and aluminum works, stopped designing metal
fabrications for developers two years ago to focus solely on
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would consider Atlanta a traditional town, but metal
furniture sells very nicely,'' Ventura said. ``That's the style for
the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Strader, who owns Mercury Metals in Decatur, Ga., with his
twin brother, Todd, said the demand for metal is so strong that
lately he's been making more furniture than sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The furniture and other metal is what pays the bills,'' he
said, ``but there's no demand for sculptures. People will spend
$2,000 on a chair, but when it comes to a sculpture, forget about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for metal's heavy appeal is the price. A stainless
steel lamp, for example, can run from $79 to $1,500 at a furniture
or department store, making it affordable for consumers of various
income levels.
</P>
<P>
   Pottery Barn, based in California, has retro-inspired metal
office furniture in its spring collection. One of the
fastest-selling items in the group is a pair of zinc picture
frames, priced at $12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frames are so popular it's hard to keep them in stock,''
said Lesley McClendon, who manages the chain's Lenox Square store.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers like metal furnishings because they are durable and
come in smooth, sculpted lines that add to a room's architectural
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   They also like them because they fit into a variety of
decorating schemes, be it traditional, contemporary or eclectic,
and they blend well with wood and fabric. Finishes can be shiny and
smooth, brushed, rough or slightly rusty and dull, for a
distressed, antiquish look.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Klein, an Atlanta entrepreneur, has collected metal
objects and furniture since the mid-'70s. He says the newer pieces
he has purchased, such as a dining room table and stainless steel
chair, have a decidedly different look from his earlier items.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extremely modern back then, where now it's a little
more traditional and the design has gotten more sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's comfortable, but each piece stands on its own and makes a
statement. That's why I like it,'' said Klein.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Brotman, a professional tennis player in Alpharetta, Ga.,
accessorized his home with metal art and tables because he likes
the way metal contrasts with his furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my furniture is basically wood, but I've accessorized it
with metal because it gives it more of a clean, lofty look.
Everything I've bought I look at as a piece of art. It looks like
one-of-a-kind stuff,'' said Brotman.
</P>
<P>
   B U Y I N G T I P S
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Solid metal furniture is more durable than furniture made from
metal piping. Generally, the heavier the metal, the sturdier the
object.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Metal should be smoothly welded at the joints.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nicks indicate poor quality and could rust.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The base or legs of the furniture should have shoes, or
gliders, to prevent damage to the carpet or floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A finish, such as a powder or polyurethane coating, will
prevent rusting and give the furniture a smoother look and feel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hand-forged metal is more expensive than a welded or hammered
item because of the craftsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stainless steel, pewter and gunmetal are usually more
expensive than aluminum, chrome, zinc, regular steel and unfinished
iron.
</P>
<P>
   H O W T O C A R E F O R M E T A L
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't let an unfinished metal base come in contact with water
because it will rust.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clean finished or unfinished metal with a soft, dry cloth.
Occasional cleaning with a damp cloth is suitable for finished
objects.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
