<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6391 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-VOSKUHL-BOS &LR;      03-14 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VOSKUHL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD WORK WINS VOSKUHL RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two Jakes have lived with each other for four seasons now.
One Jake goes about his business on the University of Connecticut
campus, going to class, hanging out, driving the coeds crazy.
</P>
<P>
   The other Jake has been the starting center for coach Jim
Calhoun's Huskies for four years. He has played 136 games, starting
133 of them. No one has started more games in UConn history. And
few have ever worked harder than Jake Voskuhl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing,'' Calhoun said about the 6-foot-11-inch, 245-pound
man-child who roams in the pivot and helped bring a national
championship to Storrs in last year's magical season. ``His
development from where he was as a freshman to where he is now is
remarkable. And it's going to continue. He's going to be playing
somewhere next year and a lot of years after.''
</P>
<P>
   For Voskuhl, that can wait. He's still got a few games at UConn
to play, starting Friday when the Huskies play Utah State in an
NCAA first-round game in Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers that Voskhul puts up don't dazzle you; he is
averaging 6.2 points and 6.4 rebounds a game for his career.
Offensively, he's still a work in progress that may never be
completed. He has never had a 20-point game in his UConn career,
although he disputes a story floating around campus that he never
reached 20 points even in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' Voskuhl said with a laugh, shaking his
head. ``I scored 20 points a couple of times in high school.
Somehow that story got started and my dad kind of pushed it along.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he did score 20 in one game,'' said Voskuhl's high
school coach, Butch Sigler. ``In his defense, I must say he did
have a lot of 18s and 12s (points and rebounds).
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake's all about winning and team. Scoring's never been a big
thing to him. In high school, he played a similar role he plays for
UConn. He does all the little things that help you win.''
</P>
<P>
   You would think that since the 20-point barrier seems to loom so
large, Voskuhl would remember the date and circumstances of when he
broke it. Mysteriously, he does not.
</P>
<P>
   But that, too, is Voskuhl, always ready to have some fun, even
at his own expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out there,'' said Calhoun, who has yelled at and
counseled Voskuhl ever since seeing him in an AAU tournament in Las
Vegas. ``He just does his own thing. But he's a pretty tough kid.''
</P>
<P>
   What Calhoun liked was the intangible confidence that is bred
into players in winning programs.
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl is a classic case in point. He came to UConn from Strake
Jesuit Prep School in Houston, which won four consecutive state
championships, compiling an overall record of 105-15. Voskuhl was a
two-time All-State selection.
</P>
<P>
   At UConn, he is part of a team that has won 108 games, two Big
East regular-season titles, two Big East tournament titles, and an
NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Voskuhl was something different at UConn. He was
tall, he was blond, and he was from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A matinee idol,'' Calhoun said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl hears this compliment and laughs, coming close to
blushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got one girlfriend,'' he said. ``That's all I'm going to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl has always been reticent about talking about himself.
That is for others to do. He is deeply religious, which helped him
cope a year ago when a nagging foot injury plagued him through the
latter stage of the regular season and much of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Voskuhl's collegiate career is winding down, he looks
back in amazement at how quickly it has passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that it's gone this quickly,'' said Voskuhl,
who has quietly become one of the leaders on a team that had a
``rough trip'' this season. ``This season has worn us down.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Huskies went into a bit of a tailspin, losing
four games (they lost only nine all season).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just one of those things,'' said Voskuhl. ``We didn't
have everyone on the same page. I think we straightened that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason was Voskuhl. He developed more consistency on
offense, scoring in double figures five straight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a real consistent presence for us down low,'' said
guard Albert Mouring. ``And we've needed him to do that. We all
knew he could do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl can and will do it, but that is not what UConn needs
from him. Mouring, forward Kevin Freeman, and guard Khalid El-Amin
will provide the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl is more of a role player, one who can energize his
teammates by providing moments of instant offense or defense.
</P>
<P>
   His career, like his life, is in a state of transition. He knows
he can play at the next level but is in no hurry. The past two
summers, he has attended the Pete Newell Big Man camp in Hawaii,
one of the more prestigious summer camps. He said that helped him,
but what has helped him even more is simply maturing as a player
and a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see it in him over the past couple of years,'' said
UConn associate head coach Dave Leitao. ``He's more assertive. He's
still doing the things he has done here since Day One, but he's got
more confidence. He doesn't let bad games affect him as much.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of his college career is near, but Voskuhl isn't quite
ready to walk away from it yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think too many teams want to play us,'' he said. ``And
I say that with not any kind of arrogance. People just know we know
how to win games. We've won a championship. We know what to do when
the game is close. We feel we're going to win every game we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Pure Voskuhl. Calhoun calls him a rah-rah guy, but one who isn't
vocal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just his attitude,'' said Calhoun. ``Everything is always
upbeat. You feel good when you are around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl speaks so matter-of-factly that it doesn't sound like a
boast. It sounds like, well, Jake.
</P>
<P>
   Both of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
