<SLUG> BC-MA-SHARKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHING INDUSTRY SEES SHARKS RAW DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts fishermen thought they were being smart
when they started selling Cape sharks to the British for fish and
chips in the 1990s, turning New Bedford into America's
shark-fishing capital. Regulators had even urged them to net these
unwanted ``trash fish'' to ease pressure on the beleaguered cod.
</P>
<P>
   But now US Commerce Secretary Richard Daley is considering a
plan that would all but shut down the $8 million fishery amid
mounting evidence that the sharks, better known as spiny dogfish,
are in danger. Once again, say scientists, fishermen have caught
too many, driving another fish species to the brink of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The management plan has set off a bitter dispute between
conservationists and fishermen, who say they feel double-crossed
after federal officials encouraged the dogfish industry.
Massachusetts' senators and three members of Congress have
temporarily blocked the closure, arguing that more research is
needed to prove the dogfish are as bad off as biologists say.
</P>
<P>
   The federal plan ``basically puts these (dogfish) processors out
of the business and it's going to snuff out a lot of the day
fishermen,'' said Harvey B. Mickelson, attorney for the American
Dogfish Association, which represents three dogfish processing
plants in New Bedford as well as shark fishermen from Massachusetts
to North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   However, conservationists say that fishermen and New England
regulators can blame themselves because they blocked more modest
restrictions in earlier years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, conservationists say that Senators John F. Kerry and Edward
M. Kennedy and congressmen are protecting a local industry at the
shark's expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The short-term economic interests of one state are now
threatening an entire East Coast shark population, as well as the
shark conservation record of the nation,'' said Sonja Fordham,
fisheries project manager at the Center for Marine Conservation in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Dogfish, which seldom grow more than 3 feet long, have none of
the menace associated with sharks, but, like sharks, the females
take a long time to mature _ 12 years _ and then they carry their
fetuses for two years before giving birth. As a result, say
scientists, they have difficulty recovering from heavy fishing
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But that hardly seemed like a problem in the late 1980s when
dogfish were annoyingly common, often caught in nets that had been
set for cod or other fish. As New England fishing grounds crashed,
state and federal officials alike urged fishermen to find a market
for dogfish and other ``underutilized species,'' sometimes hosting
buffets for consumers to try these delicacies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on dogfish because the National Marine Fisheries Service
said some eight or nine years ago that they are a wonderful
underutilized resource. Go and develop a market,'' said fishermen's
attorney Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts fishermen took the advice to heart, accounting for
55 percent of the 49 million pounds of US dogfish landed in 1998.
Three of the four major processing plants are in New Bedford, while
47 to 90 percent of the fish landings in Chatham, Scituate, and
Plymouth were dogfish, virtually all of it bound for Europe and
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   However, scientists say that 10 years of unrestricted fishing
for dogfish has had a devastating effect, mainly because the
females are larger and fetch the highest price in the market. The
quantity of sexually mature females has dropped by more than 80
percent since 1990, imperiling the next generation of fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sustain a fishery very long if you target the
pregnant females,'' said John Musick, head of the vertebrate
ecology program at the Virginia Institute of Marine Science and an
authority on dogfish.
</P>
<P>
   But Fordham said efforts to regulate the dogfish catch over the
past five years have run into resistance from fishermen and the New
England Fishery Management Council, which jointly regulates Cape
shark fishing along with the Mid-Atlantic Fishery Management
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, last January, Secretary Daley approved a plan from the
two councils that set such low limits on the dogfish catch that it
would end direct fishing for the shark on May 1. The plan then sets
tight fishing limits for rebuilding the dogfish population over the
next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Senators Kennedy and Kerry, along with US
Representatives William Delahunt, Barney Frank, and James McGovern,
intervened, asking Daley to delay action on the plan until
mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   The members of Congress argued that, despite the supposed
crisis, dogfish are still enormously abundant, accounting for 40
percent of fish caught by federal scientists last summer. They also
pointed out that the New England Fishery Management Council
reversed its support for the plan after initially submitting it.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Daley, the members of Congress agreed on the need
for ``a very substantial reduction in the dogfish catch,'' but the
current plan will have a ``very severe impact . . . on one of the
few remaining . . . viable fisheries in New Bedford.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, with Daley's dogfish decision imminent,
representatives of the two regional fishing councils are scheduled
to meet in Annapolis, Md., to disuss a new conservation plan for
him to consider, with the New Englanders pushing for less
restrictive fishing limits.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't impress Fordham of the Center for Marine
Conservation. ``We are going to create a collapse that is going to
take decades to repair. That's just a huge shame, and a waste of
public resources,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
