<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6398 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-GUERRILLA-SCIENCE-HNS     03-14 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUERRILLA-SCIENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GIVING HOPE TO THOSE WITH LOU GEHRIG'S DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DALE O'REILLEY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDFORD, N.J. _ The actor Christopher Reeve is a proponent of
it. Michael J. Fox recently announced his retirement from a hit
television series to become a full-time activist for it. A number
of individuals and families affected by amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis (ALS), or Lou Gehrig's Disease, have started their own
initiatives on its various fronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' has been called ``guerrilla science'' _ a war on
incurable, often deadly, diseases. Though the terms are
militaristic, the goals are to save, not take, lives. The weapons
are ideas, money and research.
</P>
<P>
   Reeve, representing people with paralyzing spinal cord injuries,
has made no secret of his determination to walk again. He's not shy
about using his celebrity and show business friends to raise
awareness and the money needed for research he, advised by medical
specialists, deems most promising.
</P>
<P>
   Fox intends to do the same for Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   People with ALS don't have anyone that famous to focus attention
on the disease. We did _ actor David Niven. But he chose to keep
his disease secret until after his death.
</P>
<P>
   But average, everyday people with ALS are tired of waiting for
someone rich or famous. And all of us with incurable diseases are
tired of waiting for the pharmaceuticals companies or the
government to discover treatments or cures.
</P>
<P>
   The major drug companies are not even looking because there are
not enough of us with any one neurological disorder to make it
financially worth their while. Colds, obesity and allergies are
what guarantee drug sales. Or the big diseases like cancer and
heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The government, for the first time this year, has budgeted $3
million for motor neuron (the nerves that communicate with the
muscles) disease research, but the government process, and that of
major organizations like the ALS Association, is, of necessity,
slower. In the interest of fairness and to spread as wide as
possible a net, requests for proposals are made and then a panel of
experts reviews and rates the proposals before grants are made.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Abendroth, chairman of the ALS Association's Research
Committee, objects to being called slow. (In fact, any money I
raise personally, through my own research fund, I trust the ALS
Association to direct to the most promising work.)
</P>
<P>
   ``ALSA's approach to finding answers to this disease parallels,
but is much broader than, the various new private initiatives,''
Abendroth said. ``Although we believe that our multiple approach to
research is the most effective, ALSA is more than willing to work
with the new private initiatives in the expectation that we can
learn from each other, not duplicate or waste precious ALS research
dollars, and assure that all avenues of research are used to find
the answers for this disease.''
</P>
<P>
   But the private initiatives are faster. The people heading them
up have a special sense of urgency because they or a loved one are
affected personally by the diseases.
</P>
<P>
   They frequently come from a ``can-do'' business environment
where once a problem is identified, goals are quickly set,
resources gathered and the problem is attacked.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is not fairness, it's results, so the process is to
raise money, quickly and continuously, shortcut the scientific and
governmental bureaucracies and seek out the top scientists whom
they then attract, fund and motivate.
</P>
<P>
   One of the researchers who has been a prime target is Dr.
Jeffery Rothstein of Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore.
Rothstein said, ``My lab, and ... a few other large ALS labs, have
benefited greatly from this approach. We tend to use these
privately funded initiatives to begin new work on `high-risk,
high-impact' projects, those that will aggressively explore new
therapies ... without waiting for the slower, but still very
important NIH or ALSA-supported grants.''
</P>
<P>
   NIH is the National Institutes for Health, the government's
medical research branch. Dr. Kenneth Fischbeck, chief of
neurogenetics at the neurology arm of the NIH, speaking at a recent
research seminar in Philadelphia, said that his division's
leadership recognizes the federal government must supplement the
private research initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The private initiatives can be pro-active and aren't hampered
by the lengthy grant review process, which the NIH requires in the
interest of fairness and peer review, but which can slow down
funding for new and promising research approaches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Fischbeck and Rothstein urge caution, however. In
Rothstein's opinion, the people behind the private initiatives can
be aggressive, understandably so under the circumstances, and try
to intrude on or direct the research. They may also push to publish
results prematurely. Fischbeck is concerned that some of the
efforts may be redundant, or that expectations may be too high.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Clark (her son has ALS) of Michigan heads one of those
family foundations, ALS BioTeam (Foundation for Interdisciplinary
Motor Neuron Medicine). She objects to the term ``guerrilla
science.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark says, ``It implies, negatively, that we have suited up as
scientists. We make no such claim. Rather, we make informed
decisions about the use of our funds. We are investors, in some
instances offering strategic and management support. We are
`guerrilla strategists,' perhaps, `guerrilla activists,' perhaps,
bringing urgency into the priorities of ALS research and accepting
higher risks.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the label, the fact remains that the pushy private
initiatives have lighted fires under researchers, the government
and traditional organizations like ALSA _ fires that are fueled by
the hopes of thousands of people who are fed up with the words,
``I'm sorry. There's nothing we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   I cannot begin to describe the excitement you feel, as an
individual with one of the ``hopeless'' diseases, when you hear
someone like Rothstein speak about research with stem cells
actually regrowing those vital motor neurons, or when you see a
piece such as the recent one on the NBC Nightly News about a family
fighting for their sister's life, raising hundreds of thousands of
dollars for promising research (Project ALS, in New York), or when
a television ad shows Reeve ``walking.''
</P>
<P>
   False hope is an oxymoron. Real hope is just across the
laboratory table.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dale O'Reilley, who has had ALS for nine years, is on life
support and communicates by twitching a muscle near her mouth to
activate a computer. For more information about ALS research, visit
her Web site at
http://home.earthlink.net/(tilde)techplace/dale/index.htm)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
