   Despite its natural endowments, Bangalore, like most Indian
cities, is strikingly ill-governed. The power supply is inadequate
and erratic, with wild fluctuations in voltage; the air, which
should be perfumed by the millions of flowers, instead is poisoned
by the fumes of the thousands of rickshaws which run in place of
proper taxis.
</P>
<P>
   The last chief minister, J.H. Patel, didn't help much: he freely
confessed to the prime minister's task force on information
technology that he didn't understand the difference between
software and hardware.
</P>
<P>
   In Hyderabad, by contrast, the state's chief minister,
Chandrababu Naidu, is working overtime to ensure it becomes India's
first truly modern city, where high technology firms will function
with ease.
</P>
<P>
   By convincing Bill Gates, among other important foreigners, that
he really means it, and can pull it off, Naidu has gone a long way
to achieving his goal. Clinton's visit, if it transpires, will be
another milestone along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Microsoft opened a research and development center
on the top floor of Cyber Towers, Naidu's answer to Bangalore's
Electronics City. It was Microsoft's first research-and-development
facility outside corporate headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Cyber Towers looks set to succeed more smoothly than Bangalore's
equivalent. And the city displays a lucid appreciation of what IT
companies expect and need: totally dependable services, including
electricity, drinkable tap water, banks with ATMs, even speedy,
localized customs clearance.
</P>
<P>
   If it resembles a little node of extraterritoriality, almost a
colony, Naidu, recently voted man of the millennium by one national
newspaper, isn't bothered. The important thing is to give the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The speed with which he is transforming Hyderabad into a sort of
Indian Osaka or Shanghai is stunning.
</P>
<P>
   But although Naidu's achievement in Hyderabad displays much more
political muscularity than is the Indian norm, both he and his
recently elected opposite number in Bangalore, S.M. Krishna,
confront similar basic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Their substantially middle-class cities both sit amid vast
poverty-stricken hinterlands. The chief ministers babble of bytes
and hobnob with men worth billions. But millions of the people who
voted them into power have barely enough to eat, plough their
fields with the aid of bullocks, have no electricity and few
amenities of any sort.
</P>
<P>
   Many commit female infanticide or secretly sell girl babies to
escape the dowry trap.
</P>
<P>
   Literacy rates are low in both states. The north of Andhra
Pradesh, the state of which Hyderabad is capital, is racked by a
long-running insurgency by left extremists.
</P>
<P>
   India's permanent nightmare is of absolute polarization: of what
locally they call ``the creamy layer'' getting as rich as
middle-class consumers in the West _ richer, if you throw maids and
chauffeurs into the calculation _ while the outcasts, the bonded
laborers and poor farmers sink into permanent misery, or migrate to
the cities and scavenge what they can from the city's rubbish. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
