<HEADER>
A6411 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-JESSEJAMES-EXHUMATION     03-14 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESSEJAMES-EXHUMATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAVE DEBATE: EXHUMATION ORDERED OF BODY CLAIMED TO BE THAT OF
JESSE JAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRANBURY, Texas _ For many here, there's no doubt that the famed
outlaw Jesse James is buried in Granbury Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Even if history books say he died at the hands of Bob Ford on
April 3, 1882, in St. Joseph, Mo., they see the exhumation _ and
DNA testing _ as clinching proof that the accounts from their
childhood are true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't think it's even a possibility that it's not
him because I've talked to the grandsons,'' said Mary Kate Durham,
75, an authority on local history, referring to three retirees who
live in Oklahoma, Arkansas and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't agree with the tests, the grandsons might dig
him up and bury him somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Hood County Judge Linda Steen signed an exhumation
order, removing the last hurdle to exhuming a body buried here in
1951. The remains are those of J. Frank Dalton, who told Granbury
residents that he was James. If so, he would have been 104 when he
died.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family's position to me is they want to know who they are
and they have a right to that,'' said Steen, who counts herself
among those convinced that the real Jesse James is buried in
Granbury.
</P>
<P>
   Steen's predecessor, Don Cleveland, did not grant a similar
request in 1996, saying that the family did not provide a
compelling reason for an exhumation.
</P>
<P>
   The county judge's order comes despite DNA testing of remains
exhumed in 1995 from what historians and relatives have identified
as Jesse James' grave in Kearney, Mo. Experts said that results are
consistent with what is known of the 19th-century outlaw.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Hardcastle, an Oklahoma used-car salesman who represents the
purported grandsons, contends that the tests, by George Washington
University forensic scientist James Starrs, were inconclusive.
Moreover, he said, a tooth found in a museum, rather than one taken
from the grave, was used to determine the DNA match.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes as planned, the Granbury grave will be opened within
30 to 60 days, Hardcastle said.
</P>
<P>
   He asserts that James faked his death to elude authorities and
moved to Texas under the assumed name of Dalton. When Dalton died
in 1951, a ``visual'' autopsy by the Hood County sheriff listed at
least 16 bullet wounds, rope burns on a 17 1/2-inch neck, scarred
and burned feet, and the tip of the left index finger ``sawed
off.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Hood County seat, possessing the remains of the notorious
outlaw is a source of pride to some and a source of bemusement to
others.
</P>
<P>
   Jeannine Macon, owner of the Brazos River Trading Co., said
she's curious to see the results of DNA tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to find out if these stories are true,'' Macon said.
</P>
<P>
   Macon, who moved from Dallas 28 years ago, said it's possible
that James died in Granbury but concedes that there may have been
some embellishment along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people like a story. They enjoy folklore and take it
with a grain of salt,'' Macon said. ``Texans are famous for telling
tall tales.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse James is not the only infamous character who locals insist
had passed time in Granbury.
</P>
<P>
   John St. Helen, an unsuccessful Granbury saloon keeper, claimed
when he was close to death that he was really John Wilkes Booth,
the assassin of President Lincoln. St. Helen recovered and fled
Hood County, eventually dying in Oklahoma. A court denied a 1966
request to exhume remains from Booth's grave in Baltimore for DNA
testing.
</P>
<P>
   According to local legend, bandit queen Belle Starr maintained a
hideaway in northwest Hood County where she trafficked in horses
that she repeatedly sold and stole. Not far away in Hico, William
``Billy the Kid'' Bonney is supposedly buried under the alias
Brushy Bill Roberts _ not at Fort Sumner, N.M., as history holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Elvis sightings _ everybody loves a mystery,'' said
Carolyn Brennecka of the Jesse James Farm and Museum, which is on
the James farm six miles outside Kearney, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man in Granbury has probably been the most famous
imposter,'' Brennecka said. ``Whatever way this comes out, there
will probably be more claims surfacing later. But what we know is
this is the birthplace of Jesse James. Whatever tests they come up
with, they can't take that away.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
