   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BINGE-DRINKING (Washington) _ The Harvard survey that
popularized the term ``binge drinking'' to define excessive alcohol
consumption among college students now reports an increase in
frequent binge drinkers on campus. That's defined as downing four
or five drinks in a row on three or more occasions in two weeks.
But there's good news as well. The percentage of students
abstaining from alcohol is also on the rise. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-MAILING (Washington) _ The largest mass mailing in the
nation's history is under way. Nearly 100 million Census 2000
questionnaires are expected to be delivered to households across
the country this week, Census Bureau Director Kenneth Prewitt says.
At stake in the census are billions of dollars in federal and state
aid, as well as representation in Congress and state and local
governments. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ When a furious motorist grabbed Leo
the bichon from his owner's car and hurled him into traffic,
millions of Americans were horrified. We love our pets; mistreating
them is unthinkable. Reward money for finding Leo's cruel killer
has reached $100,000, a full-scale criminal investigation is under
way and Leo has posthumously become a celebrity. I understand how
the episode has touched so many people; I just lost my own beloved
bichon to cancer and the empty house is painful to bear. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
