<P>
   PRIMARY _ Voters are heading to the polls in six Southern states
to vote in presidential primaries today. The total available
delegates in the contests puts both Al Gore and George W. Bush in
position to win enough delegates to clench their party nominations.
(Herman/Austin American-Statesman), Crowley, Palm Beach Post). 30
</P>
<P>
   BALD-PRESIDENT _ On March 1, George W. Bush was cornered. David
Letterman was razzing him about international politics.
Specifically, about how the Republican presidential candidate
didn't know the leaders of some foreign countries. The punch line?
He asked Bush if he knew the name of the president of the Hair Club
for Men. Bush's response: ``You're not talking about ... Sy
Sperling, are you?'' While the audience laughed in New York,
Sperling almost fell off his treadmill in his Hillsboro Beach home.
``I flipped out. I couldn't believe it,'' Sperling says. ``I mean,
I know people know who I am, but this was
</P>
<P>
   amazing. I guess advertising works!'' But Sperling started
thinking about Bush's response. He started thinking about hair not
an uncommon thing to do, in his business. He made a connection, and
got the word out to The Media. ``There just may be a direct link
between having hair and becoming president,'' says an urgently
faxed press release from Hair Club for Men. ``It's a formula: The
candidate with most hair wins.... It's been documented that since
the dawn of the television age, every elected president since
Kennedy, and including Kennedy, has had hair.'' (Hutchins, Palm
Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
