   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BROADBAND _ FAIRFAX, Va. _ The federal government may deregulate
high-speed Internet service by the end of the year, two leaders of
the House Internet Caucus predicted Tuesday. Reps. Rick Boucher,
D-Va., and Bob Goodlatte, R-Va., told the Global Internet
Conference that lifting restrictions on the Baby Bellsphone
companies could accelerate the spread of broadband access
nationwide. (Glass, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-CHAPLAIN _ The Rev. Charles Wright, former senior pastor
of the North Avenue Presbyterian Church in Atlanta, is at the
center of an unprecedented political maelstrom over his appointment
to become House chaplain. Critics say the controversy reflects an
anti-Catholic bias on the part of some Republicans. (Carr, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   VETERANS _ WASHINGTON _ While support builds in Congress for a
bill that would restore to the country's oldest veterans a disputed
``promise'' of free medical care for life, the veterans have laid
their case before the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington, arguing
that a district judge was wrong when he ruled that the promise was
not a binding ``contract.'' (Nesmith, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-GHOST TOWN _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ In past years ``north of
the river'' meant mobile homes and public housing. After the
flooding from Hurricane Floyd, those neighborhoods in Greenville
have ceased to exist. Some neighborhoods here have been offered up
to a federal buyout program, meaning they can't be used for
building new homes. What will ``north of the river'' mean in years
to come? (Batchelor, Greenville Daily Reflector). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
