<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, March 15:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ELN-RDP (Undated) _ A roundup of voting in Tuesday's primaries.
Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi, Oklahoma, Tennessee and Texas are
having primaries for both Republicans and Democrats. Plus a look at
the financial, political and psychological advantages for both Bush
and Gore in getting over the top in their respective delegate
counts. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-REFORM (Austin, Texas) _ For Gov. George W. Bush, reform
has been a matter of legislative proposals rather than an
overriding political philosophy, which might explain why few people
in Texas would have picked the word reformer when asked to describe
the governor. For Bush, success has come when changes have been
modest or when he has not had to buck political interests or
popular will. When he has been boldest, he has fallen short of his
goals. By Jim Yardley and Richard A. Oppel Jr. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GA-CENSUS (Atlanta) _ Georgia, still reeling from last Census
undercount and loss of Federal funds, plays on its rivalry with the
North, especially New York, to get people to fill out their census
forms this time. By David Firestone. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPUS-DRINKING (Undated) _ Despite a decade of prevention
efforts, heavy drinking on college campuses continued apace
throughout the 1990s, according to a study by the Harvard School of
Public Health. Attitudes toward alcohol appear to have become more
polarized, with increases in both the number of abstainers, and of
frequent binge drinkers. By Jodi Wigoren. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTERS-HAMILTON (Undated) _ Sentencing on Tuesday for for
William Hamilton, the Teamster's former political director, for
campaign finance irregularities. By Steven Greenhouse. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   Editors, we are also monitoring for a possible verdict in
federal court in Miami on the Elian Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-MEDICARE (Washington) _ Moderate Democrats on the
Senate Finance Committee are drafting their own proposal to offer
prescription drugs to Medicare beneficiaries (as an alternative to
Clinton's plan), and they say it could be a basis for bipartisan
compromise. By Robert Pear. (950 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a' 'code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-ACCESS () _ President Clinton and British Prime
Minister Tony Blair announced on Tuesday they had agreed to openly
share data from a groundbreaking project to decode the human
genetic pattern _ a study that could serve as the foundation for
developing new medical cures and preventions. (Summary from wires)
By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PIG-CLONE (Undated) _ The group that created Dolly the
sheep, the world's first clone of an adult mammal, has produced the
first cloned pigs, raising hopes of a new source of transplants for
humans. PPL Therapeutics, which cloned Dolly three years ago, said
Tuesday that five healthy piglets were born March 5 in Blacksburg,
Va. They were cloned from an adult sow using a slightly different
technique than the one that produced Dolly. By Gina Kolatta.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (Washington) _ The United States released
Tuesday the full text of its breakthrough trade agreement with
China, hoping to shore up support for the pact in a skeptical
Congress. The accord lays out in full detail for the first time
China's market-opening commitments under an accord that would usher
Beijing into the World Trade Organization. (Summary from wires) By
Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
