<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA'S CONSERVATIVE STREAK MAY BODE WELL FOR BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZACHARY COILE and ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a strange way, the best news Texas Gov.
George W. Bush may have received from the California primary came
the next day, when 175 young people were arrested in San Francisco
protesting the passage of a tough-on-crime initiative that targets
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   That California voters so strongly embraced Proposition 21, and
other Republican-backed measures on last week's ballot, was yet
another reminder of just how conservative voters in California can
be. This is the state, after all, of Ronald Reagan and Richard
Nixon, the state that overwhelmingly rejected affirmative action,
shut off services to illegal immigrants, and snubbed gay and
lesbian marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Looking toward November, political analysts say the presumptive
Democratic Party nominee for president, Vice President Al Gore, has
the advantage over the Republican Bush in California. Many voters
here agree with Gore on issues such as gun control and protecting
the right to have an abortion. Despite President Clinton's
scandals, he and Gore remain tremendously popular. And most
Republican candidates in California have fared dismally in recent
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for Bush, there are some hopeful signs. Republicans, excited
by a close contest, voted in much greater numbers in the March 7
primary than Democrats. And GOP strategists believe that if the
Texas governor runs as a centrist, he could break the Democrats'
lock on California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe George W. has a very difficult task here in
California,'' said Republican consultant Allan Hoffenblum. ``But I
hope the Democrats continue in their smugness, because once you
take the electorate for granted in California, they surprise you.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary results show that Gore has plenty to be smug about:
He won big in the primary among the traditional Democratic voters _
women, union members, Hispanics and blacks. In exit polls, the vice
president received twice as much support as Bush from moderates and
centrists, the key swing vote in November's election.
</P>
<P>
   The strong showing by Gore has led some analysts to speculate
that the Texas governor will write off California and focus on
states more attuned to his conservative message _ and where
advertising costs far less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is California strategically the place he wants to do it?''
said Susan Rasky, a political scientist at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``He may be better off ceding it to Gore
(and) putting together an electoral majority without California.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore supporters are dismissive of Bush's chances in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush cannot win California. You heard it here
first,'' said Garry South, Gov. Gray Davis' chief strategist who is
an unpaid adviser to the Gore campaign. ``We haven't had a winning
top-of-the-ticket Republican who wasn't pro-choice since 1988. Not
for president, not for governor, not for senator. That is a strike
against him right there, and that could be the kiss of death in and
of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republican strategists believe Bush can succeed in
California if he doesn't waver again from the ``compassionate
conservative'' message he used early in his bid for the presidency.
He turned sharply to the right to halt the momentum of Arizona Sen.
John McCain, the self-declared reformer who threatened Bush by
reaching out to moderate Republicans and independents in states
such as New Hampshire, Massachusetts and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the nomination effectively his own, Bush is veering
back toward the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he finds his voice again and returns to compassionate
conservatism, which best exemplifies his record in Texas, and
communicates a message of less government ... in a way that
manifests tolerance and inclusion, then that is a compelling
message in the fall,'' said Steve Merksamer, a veteran Republican
strategist.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advertising emphasizes education and the overhaul of
managed care, and television spots show Bush with a variety of
ethnic groups. In speeches, Bush talks about how he reached out to
a variety of voters in Texas, where he received nearly 40 percent
of the Hispanic vote in his 1998 re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show more California voters identify themselves as
conservative than liberal, but by and large they are voting for
moderate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you dig a bit deeper, you'll find that they are Clinton
Democrats _ for welfare reform, tough on crime, fiscally
conservative, but socially libertarian,'' said Del Ali, the
pollster for Research 2000 of Rockville, Md., which has conducted
surveys in California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
