<P>
   &UR; THE ICEMEN COMETH AS GLACIERS MELT, BUT THE WORLD LOOKS AWAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Bill Hanlon and Warren Ward were out hunting on a
glacier in the far north of Canada last summer when they stumbled
on a human hip protruding from the ice. They looked down to see the
perfectly preserved body of a prehistoric man who had fallen into a
crevasse 12,000 years ago. The icemen have come back to humanity,
after thousands of years, because the glaciers that entombed them
are melting _ at an alarming rate _ all over the world. Glaciers
now are smaller than at any time in the past 5,000 years, while the
ice covers at both poles are melting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Geoffrey Lean, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., March 13) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Article can stand alone in 950 words; 1,100 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-GLOBAL-MELTDOWN-950&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `ASTONISHING' ARCTIC MELTDOWN AS ICE COVER SHRINKS BY HALF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Nearly half of the ice covering the Arctic has
melted, warns an authoritative report to be published in May. The
Worldwatch Institute report says that every two years an area the
size of Denmark vanishes from the ice sheet that covers the Arctic
Ocean around the North Pole. Meanwhile, the remaining ice has lost
nearly half its thickness. The overall volume of the ice could all
be gone ``in a matter of decades'' _ with catastrophic results for
mankind. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Geoffrey Lean, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., March 13) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (300 words _ SEE BC-Global-Meltdown, above, for longer version) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-ARCTIC-MELTDOWN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RAFSANJANI ORDERED MURDERS OF IRANIAN INTELLECTUALS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEHRAN _ In the wave of half-freedoms that have followed the
recent pro-reformist elections in Iran, the dark and sinister
political role of ex-president Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani _ once
the most powerful man in the Islamic Republic _ is at last being
revealed in Tehran. Rafsanjani is being linked to at least six
senior Iranian government officials who, during his 10-year
presidency, ordered the secret execution of more than 80 dissidents
and intellectuals. The names are known in Iran but have never been
printed before. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EXCLUSIVE: Note 5th graf) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Fisk, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., March 13) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words _ SEE related story,
BC-Assassins-Tehran-Independent) &QL;
</P>
