<P>
   &UR; BANGALORE OR HYDERABAD: TWO HIGH-TECH CITIES VIE FOR CLINTON
VISIT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DELHI _ Which is it to be, Mr. Clinton? The American president
comes to India on March 20, the first such visit for 22 years, and
the subcontinent's two most strenuously forward-looking cities,
Bangalore and Hyderabad, are competing furiously for his attention.
Both are vying to become the most important center of India's
booming software industry but he will only visit one of them. Which
will it be? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Clinton's March 20 visit to India!) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Popham, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., March 14) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-CYBER-INDIA-CLINTON-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONTENEGRO WARNS THAT MILOSEVIC IS UP TO HIS OLD TRICKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PODGORICA _ Montenegro's leaders have issued a stark warning to
the West that their embattled republic is being destabilized by
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic as a pretext for a full-scale
invasion by the Yugoslav army. Both the president and the prime
minister warned of the very real dangers of another Balkan
conflagration, perhaps as early as this spring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen Castle, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., March 14) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-SCARED-MONTENEGRO-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WARREN BUFFETT ADMITS TO ANNUS HORRIBILIS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Warren Buffett, the world's most famous investor,
announced that 1999 was his worst year ever. ``We had the worst
absolute performance of my tenure and, compared to the S&AMP;P, the
worst relative performance as well,'' he said in his famous letter
to shareholders, which is full of his usual flashes of wit and
wisdom. ``Even Inspector Clouseau could find last year's guilty
party: your chairman,'' Buffett acknowledged. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Marshall, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., March 14) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-POOR'OL-BUFFETT-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHOOTING OF KHATAMI FRIEND UNLOCKS IRAN'S `DUNGEON OF GHOSTS' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEHRAN _ Sunday morning, two men on a 1000cc motorbike shot and
critically wounded the editor-in-chief of an Iranian newspaper
which has repeatedly questioned the sinister activities of former
president Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani. The victim, Saeed
Hajjarian, is a close friend and adviser of the reformist
president, Mohamed Khatami. And the motorbike? In Iran, 1000cc
motorcycles can only be used, by law, by members of the security
forces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORS: Refer to BC-Killer-Rafsanjani-Independent) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Fisk, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., March 14) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-ASSASSINS-TEHRAN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSH TO VISIT EUROPEAN LEADERS. WILL THERE BE A QUIZ? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Plans are being laid for a visit by George W. Bush,
the GOP presidential candidate, to Europe ahead of this year's
election. The aim would be to help him get to know some of the
leading figures on the world stage, but also to reinforce his
stature. For Bush, a trip abroad is essential; his ignorance of
foreign affairs has become increasingly, and embarrassingly,
evident. Bush may be a fine man, but apparently he thinks that
Canada is run by a plate of chips and cottage cheese. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Marshall, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., March 13) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (925 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-BUSH-TO-EUROPE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
