<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSINESSES, LABOR UNITE TO EASE HOUSING SHORTAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RICHARD PAOLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A coalition representing businesses, labor,
housing advocates and legislators has announced a package of bills
to increase affordable housing in areas of California with high job
growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``In California, the mismatch between what people are earning
and what it takes to buy a home is staggering,'' said Allan
Zaremberg, president of the California Chamber of Commerce and a
chief member of the coalition supporting the Job Center Housing
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   High prices and low housing production over the past decade,
according to Zaremberg, compel many workers to seek lower-priced
homes at greater distances from their work or, in some cases, even
to seek work in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The California Department of Finance estimates that a
``healthy'' jobs-to-housing ratio is one new home for every 1.5
jobs created. In San Francisco, the ratio is one new unit of
housing for every 6.54 jobs created.
</P>
<P>
   Based on 10-year forecasts for employment and housing, the Bay
Area will have a shortage of more than 320,000 homes by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad irony of our time that thousands of the union
construction workers ... are helping to build homes they cannot
afford to buy,'' said Jim Earp, executive director of the
California Alliance for Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed legislation in the Job Center Housing package would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Establish rewards for communities with rapid job growth to
approve new housing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Establish a fair system to resolve construction disputes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Require full disclosure of impacts of local growth-control
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Promote timely use of redevelopment funds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Create a commission to study developing previously
contaminated sites.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increase funding for low- and moderate-income housing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
