<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Dancing around religion and
politics
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ My wife had been talking with a Pentecostal
preacher, and the subject of dancing came up.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't in favor of dancing, being a Pentecostal
preacher.
</P>
<P>
   She said she didn't dance, being a Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   He did amend his opinion for this exception: It's all right when
you are moved by the Spirit, as was King David in the Old
Testament.
</P>
<P>
   My wife was telling me about their talk. She knows I like to
dance. It's just her way of rubbing me the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   I told her whenever I think of King David, I think of George
Bush, the elder. I explained:
</P>
<P>
   As you may recall from Sunday school, David fell in love with
Bathsheba, the wife of Uriah the Hittite, a faithful soldier in the
king's army.
</P>
<P>
   To get rid of him, David had Uriah sent to the front lines of
the hottest battle. After he was killed, David married Bathsheba.
</P>
<P>
   But God sent the prophet Nathan before King David to accuse him.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan did so by relating a story of a rich man who had extended
flocks of sheep but who grew jealous of one poor man who possessed
only a single ewe, which he loved dearly.
</P>
<P>
   It was the rich man, Nathan told David, who had arranged to have
the other killed so that he could take the ewe.
</P>
<P>
   ``And David's anger,'' the Bible says, ``was greatly kindled
against the man; and he said to Nathan, As the Lord liveth, the man
that haith done this thing shall surely die ...
</P>
<P>
   ``And Nathan said to David, Thou (ital)art(endital) the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Skipping ahead, George Bush's first nomination for president
came in 1988 at the GOP convention in New Orleans. I was there and
remember it well.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who sometimes could come across as namby-pamby, gave a
powerful acceptance speech, listing one by one the qualities that
America needed in a president _ leadership, strength of purpose,
integrity, etc. _ punctuating each with this stirring proclamation:
</P>
<P>
   ``I (ital)AM(endital) that man!''
</P>
<P>
   I've always wondered if the speech writer was paraphrasing the
prophet Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   If so, it's funny how you could take a damnation and turn it
into an affirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's not so funny, politics being politics.
</P>
<P>
   But I did think it hilarious every time Bush would declare, ``I
(ital)AM(endital) that man!'' _ as if, it seemed to me, he were
bragging about having bedded Bathsheba.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I told my wife. I know she likes George Bush. That's
just my way of rubbing her the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   My wife was quiet for a moment. Then she said this: that perhaps
it would be better if from now on we didn't discuss politics or,
for that matter, the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Gee.
</P>
<P>
   Can't talk about religion. Can't talk about politics.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't leave much.
</P>
<P>
   Might as well. Can't dance.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; web site, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
