<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6488 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS &LR;      03-14 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISITING THE BIG DRIP _ VICTORIA FALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORIA FALLS, Zimbabwe _ Boston has the Big Dig. Zimbabwe has
the Big Drip (a.k.a. Victoria Falls). They are huge phenomena, and
maybe kindred spirits because their common theme seems to be
``eternally yours.''
</P>
<P>
   However, this gargantuan African jungle waterfall probably has
the better chance of moistly making it into the 22d century, even
though the Dig's overflow (in price) is currently pretty
impressive, and might take that long to be covered.
</P>
<P>
   Named for a lady of virtually permanent presence, Queen
Victoria, as were innumerable places of imposing natural and human
architecture during her 64 years on the British throne, the Drip is
surely the most glorious of them all. Noisy as an unending
cannonading salute to her majesty, and more majestic than anything
her poets laureate could have conjured, this wilderness Victoria _
Vicky of the Vines? _ descends with a crash surpassing the stock
market of '29. Yet that brute force splinters and reforms as silken
clouds wafting heavenward like angels' negligees.
</P>
<P>
   Am I getting carried away here? Swept over the brink like the
wide Zambezi River? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   A Jekyll-Hyde waterway, the Zambezi meanders placidly,
unsuspectingly to the edge . . . and then helplessly takes the
plunge, morphing into a foaming monster that seethes and rages 328
feet straight down the volcanic rock face.
</P>
<P>
   Gushing, rushing, flushing . . . .
</P>
<P>
   The rush of tons upon tons of water is transfixing for the
witness. Hypnotic. Mesmerizing. It is even cleansing, as the sight
of so much free-spirited water ought to be, a rinsing-out of the
neural mush.
</P>
<P>
   Unhesitatingly, this lusty hydrobabe, Vicky, throws herself in
your face. Full-frontal fluidity, and you can't take your damp eyes
off her. You're up-close and so personal that she's utterly
overpowering, twice as tall as Niagara Falls and a lot broader.
Your ringside location is no more than 150 to 200 feet away as you
make contact _ eyeball to high fall _ across a steep chasm.
</P>
<P>
   Splashing, dashing, bashing . . . .
</P>
<P>
   There's no stopping her perpetual commotion _ the hustle,
bustle, and muscle of this down-and-flirty goddess seducing your
senses. Water, water everywhere, and every drop makes you blink.
Actually, the falls is a two-country split with the shorter east
end next door as the property of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
   Although Victoria Falls is a tourist town where the T-shirt,
knick-knack, and postcard flourish in the usual manner, the falls
itself is considerably removed from commercialism in a
well-preserved World Heritage enclave, probably not much different
from 1855 when Scottish clergyman David Livingstone was supposedly
the first non-native to take in the vista. What is different is
that he's still surveying the scene he baptized in the name of his
queen _ as a statue. Since he was none other than the renowned
missionary-explorer, you may mutter, ``Dr. Livingstone, I
presume!'' while nodding to his bronze visage.
</P>
<P>
   Checking into the old, elegant Victoria Falls Hotel, a pillared
masterpiece of creamy stone left over from the days of Empire when
Zimbabwe was Rhodesia, you are urged to the immaculate gardens in
the rear for a ``first glimpse.''
</P>
<P>
   Glimpse of what? A forest fire, perhaps, as smoke rises above
the tree line a mile distant?
</P>
<P>
   Esther Gwekwerere, an excellent guide, laughs. ``Nothing's
burning. That's the mist the falls sends up. Some days it's so
dense you can't see the falls at all. But we'll be all right today.
Can't you hear them? The local people call it `the smoke that
thunders' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah _ there is a far-off throb, a prelude to the divine deluge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the purring of cheetahs,'' she says. ``Let's go. As we
move closer they will roar more like a pride of lions.''
</P>
<P>
   The pride of Zimbabwe is looming, booming, fuming. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Steam soars as though from a kettle of witch's brew. Decibels
increase to an incessant, throaty, deafening ``Wuuuuuhh!'' Esther
has seen the falls almost daily for 15 years, yet remains eager,
stimulated. ``It's different every time. Depends on the season, the
weather, the day. You want ear plugs?'' she asks with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   Rumbling, grumbling, tumbling . . ..
</P>
<P>
   Your water bill is $10 US. A sawbuck (for foreigners) to get
through the modest gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do I think I left the water running at the hotel?'' says
my friend Aurelio.
</P>
<P>
   Why do I think I should call a plumber?
</P>
<P>
   Quickly a walk through the trees brings us abruptly to the
initial confrontation, Devil's Cataract, pouring forth fiendishly
as an individual separated from the mainstreaming. A drenched,
slippery stairway leads down the cliff to a platform where you feel
inundated. Esther offers umbrellas. No thanks. So it's a re-take of
Goldie Hawn beneath the water bucket on ``Laugh-In''? But, what the
heck _ we didn't have time for a shower before catching the very
early plane from Harare.
</P>
<P>
   Soaking, smoking, stoking . . ..
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter's-eye-view is available. Exciting and informative,
it takes in the whole big picture, the falls in entirety for the
1.2-mile distance plus the Zambezi's Zs: the zigzagging gorges that
the river has dug while recovering from its cataclysmic fall and
coursing toward Mozambique, subsequently the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't have the intimacy of the walk near the wild side,
along a paved path that winds through a rain forest. A tangled,
tropical canopy of olives, strangler figs, ebony acacias, palms,
red milkwoods, and maiden hair ferns, it is infiltrated by
gossiping vervet monkeys and birds of many colors and songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baboons love the figs,'' says Esther, ``but let's have a few
they missed.'' A sweet snack. ``Lions have been known to show up to
gaze at the falls. And warthogs.''
</P>
<P>
   The path, moving eastward, exits the thicket at regular
intervals to arrive at observation posts and more head-on stares at
vigorous Vicky. She is an ever-lowering curtain, rippled like
chenille.
</P>
<P>
   Spraying, spewing, spitting . . ..
</P>
<P>
   At one point the audio remains solidly on loudest but the video
is blanked impenetrably by a whiteout, a frothy coverup. Spooky,
even on this sunny day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' says Esther. ``It'll be clear the rest of the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is. Horseshoe Falls, the principal aquatic avalanche, is
cascading brilliantly, impersonating a ski slope.
</P>
<P>
   Spilling, milling, thrilling . . ..
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, don't cry over spilt water,'' Aurelio chides me as I
kerchief my face.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not weeping. It's just the spray. But I know I'm gaping and
gawking. ``Zakanaka!'' I yip, having learned from Esther the Shona
word for beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Here the water seems to descend lazily, in slow motion,
declining to batter the river below as much, so you can tell that
it's pullman green. Misted trees and grass glisten silver in the
sunshine, and rainbows dance across the gorge like painted halos.
In this sector the delicate plumes of water are entrancing, liquid
loveliness taking on shapes of sprites and nymphs that frolic with
the rainbows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're waterlogged,'' says Aurelio. ``Overhydrated.''
</P>
<P>
   There is more to Vicky, but not in this country past Danger
Point, the rim of Zimbabwe. A deep cut separates Zimbabwe from
Zambia, and we can walk no farther east. Retracing our steps
slowly, we're in no hurry to leave.
</P>
<P>
   A taxi will take us over the Victoria Falls Bridge (location of
an idiot's delight bungee jump, 200 feet for $100) and into Zambia.
Ten bucks is the price of admission to this end of the falls, too,
buying a visa.
</P>
<P>
   As rainbows abound, the Zambian waterworks are no less fabulous
as Vicky, high, wide, and handsome, spreads herself wondrously
across borders. It's a wetter and louder stroll beside the Eastern
Cataract because the dipping, tilting path among hanging vines and
date palms is closer to the edge and the gap narrower. Ambling in a
rainstorm (even though it's not raining _ just misting mightily )
you are more cautious than before because the path (called Knife
Edge), slopes, and is banana-peel slick. Moreover, no fences
separate it from the precipice as they do over in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, when a Swede lost his footing and plummeted
fatally from the cliff and into the swirl called Boiling Pot, the
Swedish government offered to build railings. The Zambians said no
thanks, feeling that would be cheating, and opted to keep the
setting as natural as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally wonderful is the Big Drip. Never has H2O been more
ravishing.
</P>
<P>
   Dripping, ripping, gripping . . ..
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
