<HEADLINE>
TO SUCCEED, YOU MUST BE MARRIED TO `THE MASSACHUSETTS MAFIA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH   HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Their names are familiar. They control lots of money in
the neighborhood. They want first dibs on hot deals. And they don't
want you coming around again if performance is poor the first time
around.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and if you are performing, they want to own a piece of you
forever.
</P>
<P>
   People in the finance world call them ``the Massachusetts
Mafia.'' They're the handful of high-profile venture capital firms
that tend to dominate early-stage financing. They're the Who's Who
of start-up money, and every entrepreneur tries to wow them.
</P>
<P>
   Charter members of the club include Charles River Ventures,
Matrix Partners, North Bridge Venture Partners, Polaris Venture
Partners, and Battery Ventures. A few others that make the cut are
Greylock Management Corp., Alta Partners, and OneLiberty Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, these firms like to get in early, wield a
heavy influence on the companies in which they invest, and reap big
returns. They compete not just with their deep pockets but with the
management help and important talent introductions they offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is a commodity,'' said Andrew Payne, chief executive of
Revenio Inc., a marketing software company in Burlington. ``It's
the people that are special.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne wanted investors who would roll up their sleeves with him,
not those who wanted a more complete plan upfront: ``That's the old
world _ entrepreneurs, please form line here.''
</P>
<P>
   Revenio's first-round backers _ to the tune of $16 million _ are
none other than Charles River and Matrix. Payne went to the funding
table with the advantage of a track record. A founder of software
success Open Market Inc., he is called ``one of the brightest
talents'' in the industry by Charles River Principal Ted
Dintersmith. The firm waited a year to back his project.
</P>
<P>
   After more high-fat breakfast meetings than he cares to recall,
Payne says he ultimately judged the VCs on their experience and
contacts. Angel investors _ individuals who make early-stage
investments _ can't offer the same jump-start, he suggests. ``It
wasn't a step that I felt would speed us up.''
</P>
<P>
   Renan Levy, chief executive of eSupportNow, a Medford-based
provider of online customer service and sales, says he talked to
fewer than 10 venture firms before settling on Polaris and Atlas
Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking at tier one,'' he says. ``There are probably
five to 10 strong companies that, anywhere you go, you hear their
names.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy, too, had prior experience with a large company. When he
started eSupportNow, he went from managing 1,500 people to juggling
multiple duties as a one-man show. ``I was shoveling the snow in
front of the building. I was fixing the (light) bulbs, and making
sure the heat was working,'' Levy says.
</P>
<P>
   As he grew, people choices were important to him _ even when it
came to venture capital. ``You need to have the right chemistry
with the people,'' he says. ``They're going to be on your board.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Ingari, chief executive of Wheelhouse Corp., a Burlington
company that helps companies with online marketing strategy, landed
funding in a snap because of his prior experience as chief
executive of Shiva Corp. He got $8.3 million from Charles River and
Silicon Valley bigwigs Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers.
</P>
<P>
   But before starting Wheelhouse, he helped start-ups get
financing, so he knows the drill well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every town, there's a hierarchy of firms,'' Ingari says.
``Entrepreneurs often make the mistake that if they can't get into
Charles River or Polaris or Greylock, they can't live. It's just
not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip ``the Mafia'' if your research shows they shun your
business sector, or if they're already married to your biggest
rival. There are plenty of other good firms, Ingari notes, ``This
is a very, very strong venture capital town.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taqua lands $55m
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taqua Systems Inc., a Hyannis telecommunications equipment
maker, says it's landed $55 million in its third round of funding.
That makes a total of $80 million, and an IPO can't be too far off.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley's Bowman Capital is leading the deal. Locally,
Charles River and Bessemer Ventures were early backers.
</P>
<P>
   Taqua chief David Michaud says his company's next-generation
switches will help make the cost of telecommunications services
``drop through the floor.'' Spencer Punter, general partner at
Bowman, calls Taqua a ``dinosaur killer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
