<HEADLINE>
IT'S MAPLE SUGARING TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the sweetest time of year in New England _ maple sugaring
season.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, which leads the nation in maple syrup production
with 31 percent of the total crop, Governor Howard Dean officially
started the season this week with a tree-tapping ceremony at the
Trapp Family Lodge in Stowe.
</P>
<P>
   Once you try the real stuff, you'll never go back to the
supermarket flavoring on your pancakes. And maple syrup season is a
grand time to get a taste for the real stuff.
</P>
<P>
   From now through mid-April, sugarhouses throughout New England
will be welcoming visitors to see how the syrup is produced _ it
takes 40 gallons of maple sap to make one gallon of syrup _ and to
sample the product on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to make a quick getaway to watch this 300-year-old
tradition taking place. (The season is quiet, so you should have no
trouble finding room at some delightful country inns.) Trees are
tapped and buckets are hung from them to catch the syrup flow. The
syrup is then taken to a sugarhouse where it is boiled to produce
the final product.
</P>
<P>
   One of the treats when visiting a sugarhouse is to sample
``sugar on snow'': Syrup is thickened on a stove, then poured
quickly over fresh snow or ice crystals to create a tasty product
rather like taffy in its consistency. Besides the pure syrup, other
products include maple candy or maple cream, a table spread that is
delicious on breads or pastries.
</P>
<P>
   At Vermont's tree tapping, festivities begin at 9:30 a.m. at the
Trapp sugarhouse, with Dean, joined by members of the Lamoille
Maple Sugarmakers Association, tapping the first tree at 11 a.m.
Vermont has lots of sugarhouses. Vermont Welcome Centers, located
on major highways upon entering the state, have brochures on
locations and events as well as information on great places to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   Maple lovers will not want to miss St. Albans' 32d annual
Vermont Maple Festival, April 28-30. For more information on maple
season in Vermont, call 800-VERMONT and ask for a listing of farm
products, or check out www.state.vt.us/agric/vtfarms!/maple.htm.
</P>
<P>
   While Vermont is not that far away, right here in the Bay State,
there are plenty of sugarhouses. In Shrewsbury, Green Hill Farm
(508-842-2588) offers not only maple products but horse-drawn
sleigh rides to the sugarbush. A maple museum and sugarhouse tour
are found at Maple Corner Farm in Granville (413-357-8829). For
those who want to know more about maple sugaring and locations of
sugarhouses, call the Massachusetts Maple Producers Association at
(413) 628-3912 or log onto www.massmaple.org.
</P>
<P>
   The Salem Cross Inn in West Brookfield (508-867-2345) offers
Maple Gatherings each week during the sugaring season. These
multicourse dinners feature maple in creative entrees and
appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, the Rosewood Country Inn has a March 17-19
getaway that offers two nights' lodging, a chance to visit area
sugarhouses, sleigh rides, breakfasts, and more beginning at $129 a
person. Call 800-938-5273.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   St. Patrick's Day &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   St. Patrick's Weekend is a grand time to visit Boston, perhaps
the most Irish city in America. For March 17-19, there are lots of
things to do. Among them: a Faneuil Hall Marketplace party March
17; a St. Patrick's Cruise with Odyssey Cruises for Irish food,
music, and stepdancers;the annual Boston City Hall Plaza party
(with the ``best Irish coffee'' contest 11:30 a.m.-4 p.m.) March
18; and the St. Patrick's Parade on March 19 beginning at 1 p.m.
Other ideas for the weekend include following the Irish Heritage
Trail (for a map and information, on the Internet go to
www.IrishHeritageTrail.com), visiting the John F. Kennedy Library &AMP;
Museum, which honors the first Irish Catholic president (the museum
is showing a film about Kennedy's Irish ancestry); and viewing the
Irish Famine Memorial at the corner of School and Washington
streets. If you want to make a weekend of it, the Boston Park Plaza
Hotel has a St. Patrick's overnight that includes an Irish dinner,
breakfast, and a gift.
</P>
<P>
   For more on the weekend, call 888-SEE-BOSTON or visit
www.BostonUSA.com.
</P>
<P>
   March 17 is a legal holiday in Boston (Suffolk County), not for
St. Patrick but to mark Evacuation Day, when the Redcoats evacuated
the city 225 years ago. The local commander for George Washington
was General John Sullivan of Limerick. Guess what the password for
the Continental troops was that day? Limerick. In South Boston,
where the parade will be held, there's a towering monument marking
the spot where the cannons were placed to force the British out.
And when the first parade was held in 1901, many Bostonians were
against a St. Patrick's parade, so the parade was authorized ``as a
public commemoration of the evacuation of Boston in 1776.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyoke, in Western Massachusetts, claims the second-largest St.
Patrick's Parade in the United States. It takes place March 19.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cruise plus &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers age 50 or older looking to experience the greatest two
minutes in sports have the opportunity to take advantage of Saga
Holidays Two for One sale. Book a four-night cruise down the Ohio
River to the 126th running of the Kentucky Derby aboard the
legendary Delta Queen and receive a free seven-night holiday to
either Scottsdale, Ariz., or Bangkok. Prices begin at $2,999 a
person, including air fare. For details call 800-952-9590.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
