<HEADLINE>
RECESSION IN JAPAN SHRINKS GDP, NIKKEI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Japanese economy, which has struggled for eight years under
a start-and-stop recovery, has again taken a turn for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Economic Planning Agency reported Monday that the
economy contracted 1.4 percent in the October-December quarter,
officially sending the world's second-biggest economy back into
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said the decline highlighted Japan's difficulty
shaking off a slump triggered by a pop in the stock market and real
estate bubble more than a decade ago. Japan's economic slump,
officially dating since 1992, is the worst and longest endured by
an industrial country in the post-World War II period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic number indicates the worst isn't over yet,'' said
William Wendler, vice president of Rowe Price-Fleming
International, an investment adviser to mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to bad economic news, the Nikkei index of 225 stocks
plunged 560.47 Monday, or almost 3 percent, to close at 19,189.93.
</P>
<P>
   Other Asian markets followed, including Hong Kong's Hang Seng
index, which declined 735.18, or more than 4 percent, to 17,096.68.
</P>
<P>
   Despite strong gains in the Nikkei in 1999 _ gains driven by a
run-up in Japan's technology sector _ Japan's main stock index has
returned to only half of its all-time high of 38,915.87, achieved
in December 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-quarter slowdown reported Monday compounded the
effects of a third-quarter contraction. The official definition of
recession is two consecutive quarters of economic decline.
</P>
<P>
   The basic problem inf Japan's economy has been a failure of
consumer spending to ignite and gain momentum.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three months of 1999, consumer demand declined 1.6
percent, while housing investment, another measure of consumer
confidence, tumbled 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-quarter decline came as the effects of a huge public
works spending package and tax cuts passed in late 1998, which
stimulated demand by a national of 120 million people, began to
wear off, Japan experts said. Public investment, which includes
spending on public works, fell by 5.4 percent in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to soften the bad news, government officials have been
saying the economy could pull out of its slump this year as the
financial sector and old-line Japanese businesses begin to see
benefits from a sweeping restructuring of the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
   One of Japan's major newspapers, Nihon Keizai Shimbun, quoted a
government official over the weekend who said the government this
month would report the economy shows ``signs of staging a
self-sustaining recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are restructuring changes going on in the private and
government sector, and this we have to overcome so we expected some
hard times,'' said Ryuichi Hattori, head of economic affairs for
the Consulate General of Japan in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The government expects the economy to grow in the January-March
quarter, Hattori said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, growth has eluded Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The recession started in the third quarter of 1992, after a
collapse in stock and real estate prices began to drag down the
entire economy and weaken the banking sector, which had heavily
invested in stocks and property. Since then, the economy has
struggled through four recessions, which are punctuated by periods
of weak growth and hopes of a full-fledged recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Economists see bright signs in the government's latest economic
report, which said there was a 4.6 percent increase in capital
spending by businesses last quarter. It was the best quarter for
capital spending since mid-1995; Japanese companies followed the
example of their US counterparts by investing in computers and
information technology. Industrial production and machinery orders
have also increased over the past several months.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Posen, a Japan expert and senior fellow at the Institute
for International Economics in Washington, said the corporate
outlays were encouraging. He said a pickup in corporate spending
typically precedes a pickup in consumer spending as a country pulls
out of recession.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he noted that a decline in consumer spending was the
result of positive steps by Japanese companies to restructure,
which included cutting back on employee bonuses, overtime, and
wages overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are definitely bad, but people shouldn't look at
them as though we're going back into a terrible state,'' Posen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's minister of finance, Kiichi Miyazawa, made a similar
argument to the Diet in January, saying that Japan must reduce its
reliance on public-sector stimulus to the economy and ``pass the
baton from public to private demand and put the economy back onto a
path toward full recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hiromi Murakami, research associate for the Economic
Strategy Institute in Washington, said he was more pessimistic. He
argued the Japanese government needs to do more to foster economic
recovery, especially by restructuring an economy increasingly
viewed as rigid and outmoded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan has been suffering for such a long time,'' said
Murakami. A general election this year could prolong the
government's gridlock. The Liberal Democratic Party, which is
viewed as antireform and protective of farming and small-business
interests, is trying to hold onto its coalition in the lower Diet,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Government spending programs, such as those enacted two years
ago and again recently, ``can be a temporal effect like we saw in
early 1999, but it doesn't seem like the fundamental economic
recovery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
