<HEADLINE>
OLDER DOGS GETTING BACK ON TRACK WITH NEW TRICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Natural Microsystems is in the process of reinventing itself.
</P>
<P>
   The small Framingham, Mass. high-tech company has been around
since 1983 without much to show for its efforts. Profits have been
skimpy. The stock has been up and down. The downs have been awfully
low.
</P>
<P>
   But for the past few years Natural Microsystems has been
repositioning itself to get in on the boom in telecommunications.
Wall Street likes what it sees. The stock has gone from $3 last
April to $76.25 Monday and at least one analyst says there is more
to come. ``There is no reason this stock shouldn't reach $100 by
the end of the year,'' said Ted Jackson of US Bancorp Piper
Jaffray.
</P>
<P>
   Natural Microsystems is not an isolated case. While most of the
glory in high-tech has gone to start-ups, a few older companies
have managed to share in the wealth. Call them old dogs who have
learned new tricks. Like Natural Microsystems, they are small
companies that have struggled. More often than not, Wall Street has
ignored them. But by changing direction, sometimes radically, they
have managed to catch the latest waves in technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are smart and some are lucky,'' said Phil Fine, a
money manager with Loomis Sayles.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Interleaf certainly fits the bill. The Waltham software
company was facing delisting of its stock when it decided in 1997
to bet its future on XML, a hot new technology for Web publishing.
The stock, which dipped to $2 at the beginning of 1999, was trading
for $77.375 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   NetOptix Corp. of Sturbridge had tried and failed a series of
high-tech ventures before getting into the business of fiber-optic
communications. Its stock was trading at $159.875 Monday, up from
less than $4 a year ago. Both NetOptix and Interleaf recently have
been acquired, although neither deal has closed.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Interleaf, NetOptix, and Natural Microsystems all
lost money last year. None are bona fide success stories yet. But
on Wall Street, what counts is not where you've been, but where
you're going.
</P>
<P>
   For Natural Microsystems, that emphasis on the future is a good
thing because the company's past is nothing to write home about.
For most of its life the firm supplied telecommunications products
to businesses. By 1997 sales had reached $75 million. But chief
executive Robert Schecter decided bigger opportunities lay
elsewhere. Instead of selling to business customers, the company
had to sell gear to the Lucents, Nortels, and Siemens of the world,
the giant firms that are building the communications networks of
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be the arms merchants to those guys,'' said
Schecter.
</P>
<P>
   A Lotus veteran, Schecter had some experience with reinvention.
He was at Lotus when the software giant transformed itself from a
spreadsheet company to a communications company. That experience
taught him a lesson: Change is hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transitions are doable,'' said Schecter, ``but to pull them
off you have to go through some ugly times and recognize that not
everyone who was with you at the beginning will be with you at the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Natural Microsystems has experienced all of that. The company
had to retool its sales force and all its products. Its old
business tailed off as expected, but the new business took longer
to get going than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The result: major losses in 1998 and 1999 as Schecter spent
money on the new ventures before revenues materialized. Herbert
Tinger, an analyst with First Albany, said many on Wall Street,
himself included, urged the company to cut costs to help the bottom
line. Schecter stuck to his guns. ``He made the right decision,''
Tinger admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Schecter is proud of the fact that most of his core engineering
crew stuck with him ``as we managed our way through the abyss.''
</P>
<P>
   The pain has produced some gain. The stock price is way up, a
big plus for employees like Schecter, who last February, bought
6,000 shares at about $6 apiece. (Gain as of Monday: $420,000).
</P>
<P>
   Company revenue has turned up sharply in the past two quarters,
so has the backlog, and analysts think Natural Microsystems could
return to profitability as early as the second quarter of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of risks ahead. Schecter concedes that his
company has to prove it can execute its new plan. Orders from the
telecom giants are ramping up but they will need to climb
considerably for Natural Microsystems to achieve the 60 percent
annual growth Schecter envisions.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, at least, Wall Street is convinced this is one
old dog that has learned a new trick. Good boy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre 2918) and Charles Stein 2922) can be reached by e-mail
at boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
