<HEADLINE>
DRESS WACKILY AND WIN A CRUISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who wears wacky Bermuda shorts? If you do, you could win a
Boston-to-Bermuda cruise for two aboard the Norwegian Majesty.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,462-guest Majesty _ the only ship offering Bermuda cruises
round trip from Boston _ will return to Boston's Black Falcon
Terminal to begin its season of weekly Bermuda cruises beginning
April 7. So put on your wackiest pair of Bermuda shorts (even if
you have to create them), snap a photo (or use one you already
have), and send it to Mary Ann Campisano, Boston Globe Travel
Advertising Department, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Entry
deadline is April 17, and a week or two afterward we'll run a photo
of the winner (oh, the fame of it all).
</P>
<P>
   Here's what that winner will get: one seven-day cruise for two
to Bermuda, including an ocean-view stateroom and complimentary
meals and on-board entertainment. (The cruise must be taken by Oct.
15. The winning package excludes air fare, port charges, tips,
shore excursions, and other personal expenditures. You can't
transfer the cruise or redeem it for cash. The winner must be at
least 18.) The Majesty, by the way, was stretched last year by
being cut in half and having a new midsection added.
</P>
<P>
   So send in those photos. And remember: the wackier the better! &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of the Majesty: Harvey Robbins's All-Star Oldies But
Goodies Cruise takes place aboard the Norwegian Majesty May 21-28.
In addition to a lot of entertainment, a free ``Day of Beauty'' at
the Ashley Paige Day Spa will be given with every cabin booked. For
details and prices, call 978-256-6472. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: In what direction does the Nile River flow? (Answer
at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``My road leads me seaward to white dipping sails'' _
John Maesfield, British poet, journalist, and playwright. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel tales: Many cruise ships give departing guests color-coded
tags to put on their luggage. Thus, on the morning of departure,
there are announcements like, ``All passengers with green tags may
now leave the ship.'' One passenger, we are told, became so
flustered upon receiving his tags that he interrupted a meeting to
tell cruise people that his yellow tag had him scheduled to go to
Amarillo, Texas, and he didn't live anywhere near there! The
employees patiently explained that the tags were bilingual, and
that the Spanish word for ``yellow'' is ``amarillo.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Costly champagne: When Celebrity Cruises' Millennium makes its
maiden voyage in Europe in June, the ship's wine cellar will
proudly display three bottles of 1907 Heisdeck Monopole champagne.
The bottles, salvaged from a Swedish merchant ship in 1998, were
bought by Celebrity at auction for $7,050. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go: Before a cruise ship arrives in a given port, there
is usually a shore-excursion talk aboard the vessel, and passengers
are always urged to attend. An example of why attending is a good
idea occurred during a British Isles cruise on a Princess ship.
During a talk, which was rebroadcast on stateroom televisions, the
shore excurison manager mentioned several times that Guernsey in
the Channel Islands has its own currency, which cannot be exchanged
for American or English money aboard ship. She thus urged
passengers to ask for their change in English currency. Sure
enough, the day after the ship left the island, a passenger tried
to swap his Guernsey cash aboard ship and was told this could not
be done. ``Why didn't someone tell me?'' he moaned. Well, someone
did. More than once. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A penny saved . . .: A poll shows that 60 percent of truly wealthy
cruisegoers _ those with a net worth of more than $5 million _
choose midpriced lines, not the luxury ships. The rich, however,
are six times as likely to take a cruise. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Northward. Its flow in that direction is ``one of
the most famous attributes of this most famous of rivers,'' says
Miriam-Webster Inc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Compiled from wire service reports, news releases, books,
magazines, Web sites, and the deepest recesses of the author's
mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpenter(at)globe.com. Include
your name and community.)
</P>
</TEXT>
