<HEADLINE>
AKAMAI PUTS BOSTON ON THE MAP FOR VENTURE FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For a glimpse of the shine Akamai Technologies Inc. has
put on the Boston area's high-tech image, look no further than
Technology Square, once a quiet and dingy outpost of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Black Lincoln Town Cars pull up to the square each morning.
Venture capitalists and Web gurus chat on cell phones between
meetings. Saabs and Mercedes, toys of the newly wealthy, fill the
nearby garage.
</P>
<P>
   There are no espresso bars _ yet. This unglamorous spot between
Cambridge's Kendall and Central squares for years boasted only drab
1960s architecture and a greasy cafeteria for employees of MIT and
Polaroid Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But it is home to MIT's vaunted Lab for Computer Science, a
place where the school's best and brightest have batted out big
ideas for 36 years. It's where Akamai was born, and where the hot
Internet traffic-routing company has established its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Investors say Akamai has changed Boston. In particular, its
initial public offering last fall was the event that put this area
on the map for those underwriting the next generation of Net
development.
</P>
<P>
   Its searing IPO Oct. 29 raised MIT's profile as a hotbed of
new-economy innovation. And its headstart in the realm of boosting
Web speed belied those who
</P>
<P>
   dismissed this region as Silicon Valley's kid brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Akamai is a big deal,'' said Mark Langner, an analyst at J.P.
Morgan Securities in San Francisco. ``Aggressiveness and risk
taking _ Akamai's got all that. That's not always true of East
Coast companies.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Today &LR; , Akamai (pronounced ``Ah-kah-my'') is busy making its
brand a verb. Sites from Yahoo and AOL to marthastewart.com have
``akamaized,'' or signed up for the firm's system of directing Web
traffic more efficiently. Insiders are called ``Akamites,'' and the
``Akamighty'' are a few executives in the top ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai is a kind of Net traffic cop. It routes Web traffic
around the world through 2,000 servers, speeding up content
delivery time by two to 10 times the norm. And it prevents crashes
that can occur when a site is bombarded by an unusual number of
visits.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Benik, an analyst at the Yankee Group, a Boston
telecommunications and Internet research firm, said Akamai's
coming-out created the kind of excitement seldom seen in Boston.
But, he added: ``If we lived in San Francisco, this happens twice a
week there.''
</P>
<P>
   Few could have predicted the phenomenon that would grow out of
some complex math equations cooked up by an MIT professor and a
couple of graduate students. Two years since they were runners-up
in the school's $50,000 Entrepreneurship Competition, their company
is valued at $27.5 billion, and they're sitting on a stock that's
rocketed 1,000 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This tale of a quickly amassed fortune is not lost on the
venture capitalists, entrepreneurs, and investment bankers. If
stodgy New England was seen as sleeping through the
business-to-consumer boom, success stories such as Akamai have
cemented an impression that the region is serious about this year's
B2B Internet rage.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody in the investment world is looking for an Akamai.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Dagres is the general partner at Battery Ventures in
Waltham who stumbled upon Akamai's founders. One of many bounty
hunters who roam MIT's halls, he met Tom Leighton, professor of
applied mathematics, and students Daniel Lewin and Jonathan Seelig,
as they prepared for the $50k contest. They invited Dagres to be
their adviser, he said. He met with them several times and helped
them hone their pitch. By summer, he told them he thought they were
on to something.
</P>
<P>
   But Dagres wasn't in it alone for long. When September arrived,
he found himself in a horse race. Leighton &AMP; Co. had several
high-profile venture firms vying to finance them. Dagres wanted in.
He dug into the plans and numbers and signed on. He accompanied the
crew as they pitched their first customers, Disney and Playboy.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the competition for the first round of financing
came down to four names. The entrepreneurs wanted Battery and a
second firm. That second firm backed out, Dagres said, and ``to
this day, they probably get up in the  &UR; morning  &LR; and have to hide
the sharp things.''
</P>
<P>
   Akamai was the prize beyond any venture financier's wildest
dreams. Most VCs aim to make 10 times their money on an investment.
In the high-flying market of the past year, it's not uncommon to
have seen returns exceeding 100 percent. But Battery turned $8
million into more than $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there were motivation to keep a company on track,
Battery's got it. Those stock profits are only on paper so far. The
first opportunity IPO investors will have to sell their Akamai
shares comes April 26, at the end of the six-month lock-up period.
And analysts say venture firms rarely dump significant holdings all
at once.
</P>
<P>
   How long can Akamai _ Hawaiian for intelligent, clever, and cool
_ ride the crest of the Net infrastructure wave? Perhaps a while,
analysts and venture investors say.
</P>
<P>
   David Readerman, director of Internet strategy at Thomas Weisel
Partners in San Francisco, cites Akamai's ``first mover
advantage.'' By being first to the game and signing on such giant
customers as Lycos, Nasdaq, Time Inc., and Ticketmaster, Akamai is
going to be dominant for now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the company faces some competition, and some challenges down
the road. One company that has also been aggressive in speeding
Internet delivery has been Inktomi, which recently struck a
strategic alliance with Sandpiper Network. Its technologies are
somewhat different from Akamai's, yet analysts say they all could
be vulnerable at some point as high-speed data delivery becomes
cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Being a public company has bolstered Akamai's growth. The firm
jumped to 227 customers from 44 in the fourth quarter. Revenue hit
$4 million in 1999, up from ground zero in 1998, and analysts are
looking for $54 million this year. Akamai had 464 employees in
mid-February, from 227 in late September.
</P>
<P>
   There's likely to be stability at the top of the company for at
least a few years, because of ``strong financial incentives'' built
into chief executive George Conrades's pay, a venture capital
executive close to the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Like most start-ups, Akamai is not yet profitable. By the end of
1999, it had accumulated losses of $58.6 million. In a filing with
securities regulators, Akamai said it needs to grow revenues
rapidly in order to reach profitability. Company executives
declined to be interviewed, citing a government-imposed ``quiet
period'' as they complete an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Investors say they would rather Akamai continue to grow and
expand its capabilities than turn a profit right away.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai already has agreed to buy two firms since going public.
Both deals were aimed at improving the richness of the content the
company can deliver via the Web.
</P>
<P>
   InterVU Inc., a provider of live radio and broadcasting services
over the Net, was snapped up last month for $2.8 billion. In a
January deal, Akamai acquired Network 24 Communications for $200
million, giving it access to the company's fast telecommunications
connections for Web broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai also is investing $5 million in Seattle's Loudeye
Technologies Inc., which improves sound and video sent over the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Group's Benik said Akamai's future may depend on its
abilities to integrate new technologies such as these.
</P>
<P>
   He said a long-term threat will be that bandwidth, the
high-speed transmission of data, is getting cheaper. That means
that Akamai's customers may at some point be able to send their
data over the Web just as efficiently without Akamai's delivery
services.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Akamai has struck alliances with Apple
Computer, Microsoft Corp., and Cisco Systems Inc. All three are
important to Akamai's future, the company says in regulatory
filings, because they involve technology development and large
revenue streams. Last year, Apple accounted for 22 percent of
Akamai's revenue; Yahoo for 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai's shares have enjoyed a stunning ride to a lofty $296
level, fueled by Nasdaq's technology rally. Most Wall Street
analysts who follow Akamai still rate it a ``buy,'' despite the
run-up.
</P>
<P>
   While that's encouraging to investors, there is perhaps no
flattery more honest than that from rivals. Akamai last week was
named company of the year the Massachusetts Telecommunications
Council, a group of 300 companies.
</P>
<P>
   To win, executive director Katherine Raphaelson said, a firm
must have ``managed a changing market, stayed at the leading edge,
and made great strides in innovation.'' She noted: ``Akamai had by
far the most votes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
