<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OCEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCEAN PRINCESS SPARKLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Slowly and quietly, the Ocean Princess eased out of its docking
space at St. Thomas in the US Virgin Islands. And as the 77,000-ton
vessel moved, all one could hear was Angla singing ``A Time to Say
Goodbye.'' From our balcony 10 decks above the water, I could see
passengers on Celebrity Cruises' Galaxy lined up watching our
ship's movements. No tugs were in sight, as this vessel maneuvered
with its bow and stern thruster.
</P>
<P>
   Soon we had turned around, heading into the sunset as we left
the Virgin Islands, our final stop on a wonderful seven-day cruise
aboard the world's newest cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   Time slipped by so quickly. It was hard to believe that a
vacation that began on a snowy, blustery day was now winding down
in the warmth of the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   A cruise has a way of taking hold of you, freeing you from the
everyday cares, and comforting you with fine dining, new
friendships, new discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Voyager of the Seas, this ship has no ice skating
rink (I went to the Caribbean to escape snow and ice), no golf
course (it does have a golf simulator), no rock climbing wall (I'd
rather walk on one of the island beaches), and it's not so large
that you feel intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   On a ship like this, it's easy to make friends. On an island
tour my wife and I heard someone say, ``Worcester.'' ``Are you from
Worcester?'' I asked. ``Close by,'' was the answer. Soon we were
joining the couple for before-dinner drinks in an atrium lounge
aboard the ship.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of cruising's assets. You can meet people and get
together again and again in a relaxing atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   While this was the inaugural sailing of the Ocean Princess, it
was like returning home because this ship is the final one in this
class of ships that began with the Sun Princess, some five years
ago. Princess has embarked on a mammoth building program, with four
``grand class'' ships of 110,000 tons plus and two ships of 85,000
tons coming out in the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   When I sailed on the Sun Princess, I thought that the ship
designed to carry 1,900 passengers had a human scale about it _
lots of intimate public spaces. It didn't have the world's largest
casino, or theater, or anything else, just lots of space, lots of
people-friendly space in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Having sailed with Princess before, we were invited to the
Captain's Circle, a gathering of 906 passengers who had previously
cruised with Princess. I like cruising, and while Princess now
sails just about around the world, I also like to try other lines,
sampling their style. So it was amazing at this gathering to see
two people honored _ one for having sailed 42 times with Princess,
and the other for an almost unbelievable 111 cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising can take hold of you. And most lines boast of the
number of repeat passengers. Obviously Princess has found a high
percentage of those who ``return home.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the cruise even more inviting is Princess's high
percentage of staterooms with private balconies. Believe me, it's
worth the extra price to be able to relax or dine on your own
private veranda. Sometimes it's a bit disconcerting, though. In
Martinique, we ordered breakfast on our balcony, only to discover
when we pulled the curtains that the European cruise ship Mistral
was docked not only 50 or so feet away, but the bridge with all the
officers still on duty was directly across from our balcony. We
were eye to eye with the Mistral's captain. But, hey, we were on
vacation. And looking across, I could see Mistral passengers on
their private decks also dressed in robes.
</P>
<P>
   There are 975 staterooms; 603 have outside views. Of these, 408
have balconies. Our minisuite had a bedroom area along with a
separate living room, a bath with a whirlpool spa, a separate
shower, lots of marble, a separate toilet area, two televisions,
two telephones, a walk-in closet, a safe, terry-cloth robes, and a
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   The Ocean Princess sails on seven-day cruises out of San Juan,
offering a day at sea followed by visits to Trinidad, Barbados,
Antigua, Martinique, and St. Thomas. Trinidad was a new port for
both us and Princess. When the ship is docked along Port of Spain's
waterfront, the island presents a not-too-attractive picture.
Outside the city, though, it's quite nice. We took an island tour,
followed by a visit to a bird sanctuary where we spotted about 15
brilliant red scarlet ibises, the national bird. Others raved about
a rain-forest tour, and while no carts were available for golfing,
it was inexpensive to play and to hire caddies.
</P>
<P>
   On board, the ship offers all the amenities one could ask for.
There are four pools, expansive areas for sunbathing, quiet corners
to curl up on deck and read, a sports deck for basketball, etc.,
within the funnel structure, large children's areas (there were 200
children on board this school vacation week), a large ocean-view
gym, a spa, a fully equipped medical center, a card room, shops,
and a business center with a service for sending and receiving
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   When my wife went off to the library (well stocked and with
deep, comfortable leather chairs), I knew just where it was: the
same location as on the Sun Princess. That's what's nice about
sailing on a similar class ship (others in this class are the Dawn
and Sea Princess): You know where things are, you're at home, and
can relax even more.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, it was a lively scene. People were out strolling
(there's a nice open promenade deck) and heading to shows forward
and aft _ Princess has two nicely appointed theaters with two
different shows at the same time. Sometimes it's difficult to
decide which to attend. But since there's no admission or cover
charge, it's easy to take in a little of each show. And, besides,
walking between the two theaters after dinner is good for the
system. Although I'm not a gambler, I really liked the casino, not
only for its looks but also for its location, on Deck 8 above the
main traffic flow between lounges and theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Of the many nice lounges on the ship, we liked the Wheelhouse
Bar with its rosewood-paneled walls and nautical feel, as well as
the music, of course.
</P>
<P>
   As anyone who has taken a cruise will tell you, ``You'll never
go hungry.'' On the Ocean Princess you never have to worry about
when to dine _ meals are served 24 hours a day, and the food is
excellent.
</P>
<P>
   The ship has two main dining rooms with two sittings at set
hours. There is a good selection of meals for everyone, from
vegetarians to beef eaters. In addition to the regular menu, steak,
chicken, and fish, along with Caesar salad, are always available.
</P>
<P>
   Horizon Court, on Deck 14 overlooking the ocean, offers food 24
hours a day. It has nice buffet breakfasts and lunches, and in the
evening a bistro menu with table service into the wee hours.
Outside there's a place for hamburgers and hot dogs. And Princess
hasn't forgotten the pizza lovers. Fabio's, at the top of the
atrium, is the place for pizza _ sorry, no takeout, no room
service.
</P>
<P>
   The ship is nicely decorated with a vast collection of art. An
interesting mural behind the passenger service's desk is by Boston
artist Laurie Kaplowitz. The art contrasts dramatically with pieces
put up for almost daily auctions. We were enticed to attend with
promises of possibly winning thousands of dollars in art.
</P>
<P>
   Art auctions have become very popular on ships. But my feeling
is similar to that of buying at duty-free shops in the Caribbean.
Unless you have a good understanding of the products, and are
familiar with pricing at home, avoid them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
