<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6507 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS &LR;      03-14 0229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARMING UP TO BODY TEMPERATURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why do body temperatures vary so much among the various
species? Why do reptiles and fish, which also ingest food, have
such low body temperatures? Metabolism governs body temperature,
but why the great differences?
</P>
<P>
   F.H. Chelsea, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Animals all need some warmth to survive. In general, the
warmer they are, the faster the chemical reactions that make them
alive, and the faster they can move and react. For example, an
iguana at 35 degrees Celsius can run three times as fast as one at
20. Iguanas and other lizards, however, are not very good at
generating their own heat and to get warm they have to hope for a
sunny day and find a nice warm rock on which to sit. Mammals
evolved an alternative to the lizards'
``hope-for-a-sunny-day-and-sit-on-a-rock'' strategy: Generate a lot
of heat internally. This keeps the body's reactions going at a good
rate, but needs more careful regulation to avoid overheating, and
things like sweating and panting had to evolve concurrently. Fish
are stuck in a large amount of water at a pretty constant
temperature and they just go with the flow _ tropical fish have
warmer blood, and arctic fish have even developed blood that
contains antifreeze-like substances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1529EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6508 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-CRUISE-BOS &LR;      03-14 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRUISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE SHIPS TRAVEL EVERYWHERE THESE DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the start of a new century, it's a good time to seek new
horizons in your vacation plans.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising is providing new and far greater opportunities for new
destinations to broaden your horizons.
</P>
<P>
   It is the season to think about Europe, Baltic and Mediterranean
countries, the Pacific, South America, and, a long-time favorite,
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   With more ships setting sail _ this year ships will debut _
there are added reasons and opportunities for taking a cruise
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   While the Caribbean is still the number one cruise destination
in the world, there's reason to consider distant ports of call.
With a cruise vacation, it is as easy to tour the Mediterranean as
the Caribbean. And, in some cases, there is added value to the
vacation dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Mediterranean lie some of civilization's greatest
moments, greatest monuments to the past. It's a destination many
dream of seeing, but hold off for reasons of time or money.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Royal Olympic Voyager sets sail on one of the
greatest journeys of discovery. This 25,000-ton ship is heading for
some of the greatest destinations in the world, on three
continents, taking just a week to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it will only be a taste of what is offered, but what a
taste _ Athens; Turkey for Ephesus (one of the ancient world's
greatest cities, which even in ruins is magnificent); the isle of
Santorini, Greece; Alexandria, Egypt, for Cairo and the pyramids;
Ashdod, Israel, for Jerusalem; Istanbul; and Rhodes and Mykonos in
Greece. It will be a journey of a lifetime in seven relaxing days.
</P>
<P>
   That is a journey that could only be taken on a cruise ship. The
Voyager will be the world's fastest ship. Once on board, passengers
will never have to pack or unpack for each continent, each port of
call. The ship will offer every amenity one could ask for _ there's
even a Turkish bath on board. Adding to the experience will be
on-board, world-class lecturers to bring each destination to life.
</P>
<P>
   The Voyager is just one of the many ships that will be sailing
in Mediterranean waters. Holland America will sail its Rotterdam on
a series of 12-day cruises in the western Mediterranean. Classical
Cruises will offer a sailing ship, the Panorama, on cruises around
the Greek Islands. Costa Cruises' seventh ship, the CostaAtlantica,
will debut in July with a sailing from Venice to ports in Greece
and Turkey. The world's largest sailing vessel, the Royal Clipper,
will be sailing from Cannes, France, to Mediterranean ports.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of other cruises in Europe this summer:
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie &AMP; Kent's Explorer will cruise northern Europe.
Celebrity Cruises' new Millennium will depart from Amsterdam on
14-night cruises to St. Petersburg, Russia, and Baltic ports. The
Club Med 2, a tall-masted sailing vessel, will cruise the
Mediterranean, Norwegian fiords, and the Baltic. Costa Cruise Lines
will also offer sailings in the Black Sea aboard the CostaAllegra.
The CostaRiviera will offer seven-day sailings to France, Spain,
Italy, and Tunisia. The CostaRomantic will head for the Norwegian
fiords. Crystal Cruises' Symphony will feature 11- 13-night
itineraries in the Mediterranean, western Europe, and the Baltic
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   First European Cruises' Mistral will offer seven-night sails to
the Greek Isles from Venice; the Azur sails to Greece, Israel,
Egypt, Tunisia, Corsica, and Malta. Holland America's Maasdam will
offer cruises to European capitals and to northern Europe. Linblad
Special Expeditions' Caledonian Star will offer sailings throughout
Europe and into the Arctic waters.
</P>
<P>
   Orient Lines will have its Crown Odyssey in the Mediterranean
and Aegean, and the Marco Polo in the Baltic. Princess Cruises will
have its Crown Princess sailing 10-night Baltic cruises and the
Royal Princess will cruise to London, Iceland, and the Norwegian
fiords while the Grand Princess will offer 12-night cruises between
Barcelona and Istanbul. Radisson Seven Seas Cruises will have its
Radisson Diamond on Riviera and Baltic cruises. The Song of Flower
will ply the Mediterranean and Baltic seas.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance Cruises will offer 10-night cruises in the
Mediterranean. Royal Caribbean International will have its Legend
of the Seas and Splendour of the Seas in Europe. Seabourn Cruise
Lines will have the Seabourn Sun in the Black, Mediterranean, and
Baltic seas. The Seabourn Goddesses I and II will offer five- to
seven-night cruises in the Mediterranean and Adriatic, while the
Seabourn Legend, Pride, and Spirit will also cruise throughout
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Silversea Cruises will offer 10- 12-night cruises throughout
Europe aboard its Silver Cloud and Silver Wind. Swan Hellenic's
Minerva will offer sailings in Europe, the Mediterranean, and Black
seas. Windstar Cruises will offer seven-day sailings between Nice
and Rome, Lisbon and Barcelona, and the Greek isles.
</P>
<P>
   And Cunard will once again be the only line offering regular
trans-Atlantic service. The Queen Elizabeth 2 will also offer
sailings out of Boston this year. Cunard is offering free air fare
on both the QE2 sailings and the Caronia.
</P>
<P>
   The Caronia, formerly the Vistafjord, recently underwent a $5
million refurbishment. It will sail 12- 14-day European cruises.
Cunard is also offering savings of 25 to 38 percent on Caronia
sailings. With both the air fare and ship savings, bookings,
including a deposit, must be made by March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carona is a wonderful ship that is unfamiliar to cruise guests
in America,'' said Larry Pimentel, Cunard president. ``She has Old
World charm and a warm, hospitable British style that are
reminiscent of Europe's finest hotels. She's an excellent choice
for travelers who are not attracted to the glitter and glitz of the
newer crop of megaships.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaska will again have a mighty armada sailing its waters. From
big to small vessels, the choice is yours.
</P>
<P>
   Offering a small-boat experience is Alasks's Glacier Bay Tours
and Cruises. The line offers six- and seven-night cruises out of
Juneau. American Safari Cruises has eight-night itineraries between
Juneau and Sitka. Clipper Cruise Line will have its Yorktown
Clipper sailing the Inside Passage. Cruise West will offer
seven-night cruises between Skagway and Seattle and Juneau and
Ketchikan. Its Spirit of Columbia and Spirit of Glacier Bay will
have three-night sailings to Prince William Sound. Spending its
first summer in Alaska will be Radisson Seven Seas Cruises' Seven
Seas Navigator, with seven- to 11- night cruises. Lindblad Special
Expeditions will have its Sea Bird and Sea Lion vessels offering
seven-night sailings between Juneau and Sitka.
</P>
<P>
   Larger cruise ships plan these sailings:
</P>
<P>
   Carnival will have seven-night cruises in Alaska aboard the
Jubilee. Celebrity is sending its Galaxy on seven-night Inside
Passage cruises out of Vancouver, and the Mercury will sail
seven-night cruises between Vancouver and Seward. Chrystal Cruises
will place its Harmony in Alaskan waters for a series of 10-
12-night cruises with embarkation in either San Francisco or
Vancouver. Norwegian Cruise Line's Norwegian Wind will offer
cruises departing from Vancouver, and the Norwegian Sky will do
seven-night cruises from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the biggest operators of cruises in Alaska are Holland
America and Princess. Both lines also offer extensive land stays
that can be combined with the cruise.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pacific, cruises about the Hawaiian Islands and the
Society Islands from Tahiti are offered
</P>
<P>
   Quark Expeditions will take its polar icebreaker, the Yamal, on
voyages above the Arctic Circle. In China, there are cruises along
the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting experience for travelers considering cruising
around distant lands is Royal Caribbean Internation's Royal
Journeys program. The program, offered on sailings of the Legend of
the Seas, explores the world's oceans. During the cruise,
passengers have the option of taking an extended land stay at
various ports, and rejoining the ship a few days later. Passengers
also have the option of arriving early at the port of departure to
explore that area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
