<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6515 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SMALL-SCHOOLS-ART-BOS     03-14 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-SCHOOLS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 IN BIG SKY COUNTRY, SMALLER SCHOOLS ARE FAVORED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENTON LAKE SCHOOL DISTRICT, Mont. _ At the Benton Lake School,
there is only one male student, and only seven in all. Other
children are imported for Christmas plays. And teacher Dawn Dawson
moonlights as the janitor.
</P>
<P>
   But every day, several parents commute 40 miles roundtrip to
give their children a slice of education's newest hot commodity: a
small school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about individual attention,'' says Dawson.
</P>
<P>
   While Montana parents may have a penchant for really small
schools, a similar concept is playing out in Massachusetts as
charter schools and officials shaking up traditional schools strive
to offer students a smaller setting and a more personal touch.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bay State's small school movement _ always loyal to
local control _ is quickly colliding with new state standards that
dictate everything from minutes in a school day to fourth-grade
math tests. How can schools try out better teaching methods if they
have to worry about MCAS? teachers say.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Montana, some national educators say. State standards
are vague and local control is firm. Yet, students consistently
score in the top tier on national academic tests _ despite being in
the 13th poorest state in the nation. Ask almost anyone in Big Sky
country and they say the reason is clear _ the smaller the school,
the better. And less government intervention is even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Montana, we like to say what our community is about, our
schools,'' said Larry Stollfuss, school superintendent for Benton
Lake and other rural schools in the 4,000 square-mile Chouteau
County in the central plains of Montana. ``And we don't like anyone
telling us what to do. And we do fine, that's why parents come
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana, which can easily fit all six New England states in its
borders, is far from city traffic and overcrowded schools squeezed
for space. There is rarely a line at a restaurant, and a busy town
is one with one traffic light. With less than 1 million residents
and 160,000 public school students, almost every school, even in
big cities, is smaller than the 1,100-student Reading High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how big your school is, parents always want a small
one,'' Stollfuss said.
</P>
<P>
   While Benton Lake's story is extreme, officials say parents from
Helena to Missoula are transferring students to smaller public
school districts, usually in rural districts within driving
distance.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1900s, Montana's rural schools _ each little more
than a teacher's apartment, a classroom, a stage and hardwood
floors sketched with basketball boundary lines _ opened to educate
the children of homesteaders who were spreading across the plains.
</P>
<P>
   Existing even before most towns, there were some 3,000
independent Montana school districts in the 1930s. While a
controversial consolidation movement that continues to this day
lowered that number to around 450, a hodgepodge of tiny districts
still exist. Some sit smack on the edge of city limits; others have
their own elementary school districts, yet feed into one, two or
even three separate high school systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is a personal matter. And the more it looks like
manufacturing and production, the less likely you are to have an
education,'' said Craig Howley, a Ohio University researcher. He
recently co-published a report showing Montana's small schools in
some cases can override the effect of poverty on student
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple lesson, keep schools as small as you can,''
Howley said.
</P>
<P>
   Benton Lake School, next to an underground nuclear missile silo
and with only two homes dotting the horizon, is about as small as
it gets. One classroom. Seven desks, differing only in size. There
are three students in kindergarten and one each in grades 3, 4, 6,
and 7.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at her desk, Dawson, 26, answers a barrage of questions
from other students while trying to teach 5-year-old twins Kristen
and Savannah Huggins to count past 110. She helps Seth Maly with
his multiplication tables, without missing a word of Meagan
Huggins's oral book report on ``Flubber.''
</P>
<P>
   Shayne Maly is one of those parents who makes the long commute
from Great Falls so his two children can go to Benton Lake,
originally built for farm children scattered across the
wheat-brushed landscape. The school is so remote, it's not
officially in a town.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son was getting D's and F's last year in the city, and this
year, he's doing great,'' Maly said. ``The big schools don't give
them as much attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawson gets lonely, but rarely scared, in the building that sits
off ``Bootlegger Trail,'' a dirt road used by liquor smugglers
traveling from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   She is governed by a three-member board that meets with her the
first Monday of every month.
</P>
<P>
   There is a fierce determination to keep Benton Lake and other
rural schools running, even though fewer and fewer students are
from the area. Every now and then, the district is threatened to be
swallowed up by Great Falls or Fort Benton, another town about 20
miles away. The school was even closed for a year because of a lack
of students in the early 1990s, but reopened in 1993 with four
students, one being the teacher's son.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school is the town in a way,'' said Stollfuss. ``It's
everything to this area and people don't want to go to Great Falls
or anywhere else. They fight like hell to keep these schools
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Money plays into the equation too. It's often less expensive for
Benton Lake and other rural districts to run their own schools than
become part of a larger district where education taxes may be
higher. Rural school overhead is low _ most buildings are paid for
and new teachers make only around $18,500 a year _ and bureaucracy
is nonexistent. Most taxpayers can get away with paying only a few
hundred dollars for education every year.
</P>
<P>
   Even in districts where funds could be saved by consolidation,
the concept of a small school is held so dear that few want to make
the trade-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drive from the base every day to bring my three children,''
said Toni Huggins.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Brian, is being transferred to New Mexico next year
and she already envisions anonymous schools and teachers that don't
know her children's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small is always better for children,'' Huggins said. ``I see
it here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
