<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6521 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-GRANT-BOS &LR;      03-14 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GRANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LOOK AT AN OLD CIVIL WAR ICON, MORE TO COME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL LARKIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
ULYSSES S. GRANT 
Triumph Over Adversity, 1822-1865 
By Brooks D. Simpson 
Houghton Mifflin, 576 pp., illustrated, $35 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the acknowledgments beginning his new biography, ``Ulysses S.
Grant: Triumph over Adversity, 1822-1865,'' the historian Brooks D.
Simpson nods to the mountain facing him. He thanks William S.
McFeely for his support and the early counsel ``that the best way
for me to say what I wanted to say about Ulysses S. Grant was to
write my own book.''
</P>
<P>
   McFeely's beautifully written 1981 biography of the general won
a Pulitzer Prize and remains a primary reference for insight into
Grant's life and career. And it is only one _ though perhaps the
best _ of numerous books about one of the pivotal figures of
19th-century America.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there is Grant's autobiography, dictated in the final
months of his life in 1885. An immediate popular success,
``Personal Memoirs'' is an American classic, rich in personal and
political anecdotes and in detailed critiques of military campaigns
and individual battles. Thus, it is hard to conceive that anyone
could make a notable contribution to Grant-related literature at
the outset of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Simpson succeeds with this first volume of a two-part
biography, partly because of the extraordinary events of Grant's
life, partly because of Simpson's talents as a storyteller, and
partly because of his astute decision to focus on the family and
political dynamics that surrounded his subject.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Grant's growth, from his birth as the first child of a
loving if demanding father, and of a quiet, serious mother, to his
acclamation as victor of the Civil War, is a tale of resolute
determination in the face of ceaseless demands. Some innate melding
of kindness, stubbornness, and courage, evidenced early by young
Grant's talent for taming and riding horses, carried him though
financial hardship, bloody battle, and jealous intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, Grant also showed an unusual willingness to
accommodate others _ provided it served his longer-term goals.
Christened Hiram Ulysses (though called ``my Ulysses'' as a boy by
his father), he quickly consented to Ulysses S. Grant after a
clerical error renamed him on his appointment to the US Military
Academy.
</P>
<P>
   West Point itself was not the young man's idea; he ended up
there because his father was looking for a free education for
Ulysses after he refused to go into the family tannery business.
Neither envisioned a military career for the cadet who was willing
to be called Sam Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive to teasing since boyhood, Grant adopted a quiet
unpretentiousness and graduated, not surprisingly, very near the
middle of his class. After an incident in which he was ridiculed by
a street urchin, he lost any ease in full-dress uniforms, and he
avoided them for the rest of his life. Even after he had become a
four-star general, his appearance belied his achievements, and he
tried to pass unnoticed in camp, on the battlefield, and in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   His reserved nature prompted many adversaries to underestimate
his determination, and many allies _ Abraham Lincoln and William
Tecumseh Sherman among them _ to feel unthreatened by his success.
Numerous instances recounted by Simpson show that Grant's humility
was genuine, none more so than the legendary surrender at
Appomattox, when he quietly greeted a resplendently formal Robert
E. Lee in open tunic, long coat, and muddy boots _ and showed great
sympathy for the conquered Confederate general and his tattered
infantry.
</P>
<P>
   Before reaching that surrender, of course, Grant had survived
many attacks on his character and his abilities, despite regular
battlefield victories and steady progress toward his ultimate goal
of smashing the Confederacy. Although it describes the major
engagements with the enemy, ``Triumph over Adversity'' is not a
dissection of Grant's military tactics. Simpson holds the battle
analysis to a minimum _ don't look here for detailed maps and
second guessing _ and concentrates instead on the relationships
that shaped Grant as a man and leader.
</P>
<P>
   The general's life was full of prickly characters, from his
conniving father and contrarian father-in-law, to his loving but
often distant wife, to a legion of malevolent, ambitious Army
officers and politicians caught up in an unscripted drama of life
and death on a national stage.
</P>
<P>
   Grant's sure grasp of the social and military issues and
personalities slipped but few times once he received his
commission. He had, for example, admirable and steadfast policies
toward blacks as citizens and soldiers almost from the outset of
the conflict, even as the North debated whether the war was about
secession or slavery.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Grant came to regret his General Order No. 11
banning Jews from his command. The order was widely condemned as
anti-Semitic, and his wife referred to it as ``that obnoxious
order.'' On the military side, the brilliant strategist of the
Virginia campaign was the same man who ordered a disastrous frontal
assault at Cold Harbor that left hundreds of dying men trapped
between the lines for days.
</P>
<P>
   This latest biography confirms again the greatness of Grant: His
story is epic in every retelling; his humanity is complex and
fascinating. Simpson's second volume will be welcome if it is as
engaging and stylish as the first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1533EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
