<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD TIMES ROLL IN LOUISIANA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By Harry Shattuck 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Most folks would face a serious challenge in following
up the biggest yearlong party of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Not our neighbors to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Every day has cause for jubilation in Louisiana. So what do
residents do as an encore to the hundreds of special events that
comprised FrancoFete '99, commemorating the tricentennial of the
state's first permanent settlement?
</P>
<P>
   They simply strike up the band. And we're all invited to listen.
</P>
<P>
   Or, better yet, participate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FOCUSED ON THE MUSIC &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis this year, from Monroe to Houma, is on the rich
musical heritage of a state that has produced Louis ``Satchmo''
Armstrong and Britney Spears, Mahalia Jackson and Tim McGraw, Fats
Domino and Harry Connick Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Among other claims to fame (and keep in mind that Louisianans
aren't shy about making claims):
</P>
<P>
   _ The nation's first opera was performed in New Orleans in 1796;
</P>
<P>
   _ The name ``jazz'' was first given to the music of New Orleans
about a century ago;
</P>
<P>
   _ Guitarist Huddie ``Leadbelly'' Ledbetter became renowned as a
``father of the blues,'' singing his way out of prisons (in
Louisiana and Texas) during the early 20th century;
</P>
<P>
   _ Elvis Presley got his start at the Louisiana Hayride in
Shreveport in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrations this year include the Festival International de
Louisiane (April 26-30) in Lafayette; the New Orleans Jazz and
Heritage Festival (April 28-30 and May 4-7) in New Orleans; the
Cajun Fun Fest (May 4-7) in New Iberia; the Red River Revel (Sept.
30-Oct. 7) in Shreveport; and September zydeco festivals in
Opelousas, Lake Charles and St. Martinville.
</P>
<P>
   Or you could check out the Great Southern RV Park Bluegrass
Festival (April 20-22) in Angie; Mudbug Madness (May 25-28) in
Bossier City; or the Southern Pickin' and Ginnin' Festival (Sept.
16) in Rayville.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 600 fairs and festivals are devoted all or in part
to Louisiana music,'' says Dwight Landreneau, assistant secretary
for the Louisiana Department of Culture, Recreation and Tourism's
Office of State Parks.
</P>
<P>
   The parks system is heavily involved, too. ``All of our sites
offer an historical interpretation of music,'' Landreneau says.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel State Historic Site, situated near Marthaville (about a
half-hour drive from Natchitoches) and home to the Louisiana
Country Music Museum, will host the Louisiana Fiddlers'
Championship on April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are being formulated to stage an opera at
Longfellow-Evangeline State Historic Site in St. Martinville.
Eighteen miles to the southeast, Lake Fausse Pointe State Park is a
popular venue for Cajun bands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CAJUN INFLUENCE WORLDWIDE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm itching to mosey over to Eunice, near Lafayette, where an
informal get-together occurs every Saturday at the Savoy Music
Center, headquarters for master accordion maker (and player) Marc
Savoy and his wife, Ann, an accomplished guitarist.
</P>
<P>
   There, locals and visitors _ 40-50 people on an average
Saturday, as many as 200 on some occasions _ gather from 10 a.m.
until noon for an all-acoustic jam session, pausing only long
enough to enjoy free coffee and boudin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody plays together, and our only rule is that the oldest
person in attendance gets to decide what to play,'' Marc Savoy
says. ``I don't know if the heat is responsible, or maybe the
peppers we use to spice our food, but the music is always
energetic.''
</P>
<P>
   On one Saturday, Savoy says, ``We had 17 fiddlers show up.
Another time, a large contingent of Japanese tourists stopped by,
and they brought horns and instruments I've never seen before. They
sat in with us and played Cajun music.''
</P>
<P>
   Their influence was long-reaching. ``We've sold several
accordions to Japanese citizens,'' Savoy says. ``Cajun music is big
in Japan. I know of three Japanese Cajun bands, including the
Yokohama City Aces.''
</P>
<P>
   For regulars, the Savoy stop often is the second on a day-long
agenda that begins with a traditional Cajun breakfast (``Boudin and
beer,'' says Landreneau, laughing.) and musical accompaniment at
Fred's Lounge in nearby Mamou.
</P>
<P>
   There is no telling where an afternoon session will break out.
``The great thing about our part of Louisiana is that musicians are
very accessible,'' Savoy says. ``If you go to a person's house,
knock on the door and say, `I'd like to have a jam session on your
back porch,' chances are it'll happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at 6 p.m. on Saturdays, Eunice's famed Liberty Theater
is the setting for more music _ and a celebration of the area's
French language and heritage _ on the ``Rendezvous des Cajuns''
live radio broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music you hear is in its purest form, carried down from
Marc and Ann's ancestors,'' Landreneau says. ``But one great thing
about our state is that the music changes in each area.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the echoes of Cajun and zydeco; jazz and bluegrass; R&AMP;B,
gospel and opera, be certain of this, too: Louisianans already are
planning well into the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just leading up to 2003 and the 200-year anniversary of
the Louisiana Purchase,'' Landreneau says. ``That'll be our biggest
celebration yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
To request a free brochure that details Louisiana music festivals,
call 800-947-6711. Access www.louisianatravel.com on the Internet.
Call the Savoy Music Center at 337-457-9563.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
