<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6532 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-DEATH-ROW-HNS &LR;      03-14 0208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-ROW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGE DENIES DEATH ROW INMATE'S REQUEST FOR INDIAN CEREMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal judged ruled that death row inmate
Darrell Rich could not participate in an American Indian spiritual
ceremony to purify his soul before his scheduled execution early
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker issued his ruling Monday,
agreeing with arguments made by the state that guards could not
maintain adequate security during the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Foster, one of Rich's spiritual advisers, said, ``This
is an issue of denial of religious freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich, 45, was convicted of killing three women and a girl and
attacking five other women during a two-month rampage ending in
August 1978. His final crime was to throw 11-year-old Annette Selix
from a 105-foot bridge, killing her.
</P>
<P>
   Rich's execution was scheduled at 12:01 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After he was imprisoned, Rich discovered that his biological
father was part Cherokee. He adopted American Indian religious
rituals and now refers to himself as Darrell Edward Young Elk.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gov. Gray Davis denied clemency for the convicted
rapist-murderer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
