<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLA-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-(     03-14 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES SCHOOL VOUCHERS VIOLATE FLORIDA'S CONSTITUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Florida judge ruled Tuesday that the use of taxpayer money for
private school tuition is a violation of the state constitution.
The ruling curtails the nation's boldest experiment in using market
pressure to improve failing schools.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which the state said it would appeal, was the
second major legal setback for voucher proponents in recent months,
following a federal judge's ruling that Cleveland's voucher program
contravenes the First Amendment's separation of church and state,
</P>
<P>
   Florida's was the first statewide voucher program and the first
to tie voucher eligibility to schools' performance on standardized
tests. It serves as a model for a national voucher plan proposed by
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumptive Republican
presidential nominee, and has been copied by several of the 25
state legislatures currently considering new voucher initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling puts a stake in the heart of the voucher
movement,'' said Bob Chase, president of the National Education
Association, the teachers' union whose Florida affiliate was
involved with the lawsuit challenging vouchers. It sends a strong
signal to states across the nation that vouchers are no substitute
for a quality public education.''
</P>
<P>
   The 53 children in Pensacola, Fla., who are currently using
vouchers to attend private schools will be allowed to finish out
the semester, but the state will not pay their tuition next year.
The ruling also stops the program from expanding to as many as
60,000 students in 78 schools who would have become eligible for
vouchers in June if their schools were graded ``F'' for the second
time in four years.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragedy because this beacon of hope that has been
offered to parents as a way for their children to get a better
education has, at least temporarily, been snuffed out,'' said John
F. Kirtley, a Tampa venture capitalist who is on the board of
Floridians for School Choice, a pro-voucher group.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by Judge L. Ralph Smith Jr. of the Circuit Court of
Florida focuses on a provision of the Florida state constitution
that declares education a ``fundamental value'' of the state and
says it is a ``paramount duty'' to provide a ``uniform, efficient,
safe, secure and high quality system of free public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Voucher proponents had argued that since the state already
spends millions of dollars a year sending disabled and other
students with special needs to private schools, it could also do so
to help students escape low-performing schools. But Smith said that
since in the voucher program, private schools would be providing
the same services available in the public ones, it ``supplants the
system of free public schools mandated by the constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   While the ruling may be a catastrophic blow to Florida's
program, its impact nationally is limited because it turns on a
narrow provision of the state constitution, rather than the broader
question of whether vouchers, which are typically used at parochial
schools, violate the federal Constitution's separation of church
and state. A federal judge in Cleveland declared in December that
that city's voucher program is illegal on those grounds, a decision
that has been appealed and is expected to soon land before the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This is a blip in the voucher movement,'' said Clint Bolick, a
lawyer for the Washington-based Institute for Justice, a
conservative group that helped defend the lawsuit. ``There has not
been a single lawsuit yet where we have not had at least a
momentary setback. We have developed some serious stamina. At the
end of the day we have not lost a single voucher program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1622EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6582 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      03-14 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A WINERY, VALUE IS ALL IN THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he graduated from Holy Cross College in 1973, Mike Benziger
could have gone home to White Plains and built a nice life for
himself. He could have joined Park-Benziger, the wine importing
house founded in New York by his grandfather Joe 40 years earlier
and run by his father, Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   But no. He chose to go to California for postgraduate work in
skiing and surfing. To fill in the time between the slopes and the
Pacific, he worked in a wine shop, using the knowledge he had
acquired from the family business. He promptly fell in love with
California wine.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, he had lured his entire family west to share
his enthusiasm, including his parents and his six brothers and
sisters. Together, they founded the Glen Ellen Winery in 1981 on an
85-acre parcel of vineyard land just north of the town of Sonoma,
an hour's drive north of San Francisco. It turned out to be one of
the more successful gambles of the last two decades in the
California wine boom.
</P>
<P>
   Tasting, and drinking, about a dozen of the latest Benziger
releases recently, I was reminded of how innovative the Benzigers
have been. Starting with a handful of premium wines made from their
own grapes, they saw an opportunity that no one else in the
business had discerned when a huge surplus of good but inexpensive
varietal wines came on the market in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Glen Ellen and M.J. Vallejo labels, they produced
large quantities of varietal wines _ wines made from specific grape
varieties _ selling in the $4 to $5 range. By the late 1980s, Glen
Ellen, with a wine category that became known as ``fighting
varietals,'' which aggressively challenged the tradition of
expensive varietal wines, was the largest winery in Sonoma County,
with annual revenues of $135 million.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not what the Benzigers had come west to achieve.
And with a production of 4 million cases a year, they were also
getting into the ring with heavyweights like E.&AMP;J. Gallo, and to
stay in the high-volume low-cost game, they would have needed huge
infusions of capital.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, they sold the Glen Ellen business to Heublein for $80
million, changed the winery name to the Benziger Family Winery and
downsized the business to today's 180,000 cases. Now they were
going for quality rather than quantity.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when wine prices are appallingly high, the Benzigers
have managed to keep theirs within reason. Their wines represent
good value. I recently tried several 1997s, including a Sonoma
County merlot at $17 and a Sonoma cabernet sauvignon, $17. Both are
fruity, well-structured wines that match competitors costing at
least $10 more a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   I particularly liked a 1997 California pinot noir, $21, and also
tasted a 1998 Carneros Chardonnay, $13, and a 1997 Sonoma County
zinfandel, $21.
</P>
<P>
   In addition I tasted several wines of less-known varieties
produced in small quantities and available only at the winery,
including a white Burgundy, which I liked; a sangiovese; and a
petite sirah from the ``Imagery Collection.'' There is also a small
line of reserve wines and an even smaller group of single-vineyard
wines: three cabernet sauvignons and a chardonnay from California
and, from Oregon, a pinot noir and a pinot gris, none of which I
have tried yet.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to these small-batch wines, the standard Benziger
wines usually include grapes from many vineyards. The 1997 Sonoma
cabernet sauvignon, for example, includes 33 lots of grapes from 18
ranches.
</P>
<P>
   In California, grape growers call their farms ranches. A single
ranch may include several well-known vineyards. Each year, Benziger
buys 300 lots of grapes from more than 60 California ranches, from
Paso Robles in the south-central coastal region to Mendocino in the
north. This is in addition to the grapes grown in the 85-acre
Sonoma Mountain Estate home vineyard and its 65-acre Willamette
Valley Vineyards in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   With much fanfare, the family opened a small brewery in 1997 on
the Sonoma estate to produce 100,000 cases of premium beer for the
Sonoma Valley and San Francisco. It closed after a year. Mike
Benziger, the winery president, said, ``We opened for business just
as the microbrewery fad was peaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The brewery is being converted into a second winery that the
Benzigers say will allow them to increase production to 500,000
cases a year. It is set to open next month.
</P>
<P>
   The Benzigers are proud of their reasonable prices but are not
opposed to raising some of them. The top cabernet sauvignon sells
for around $45. ``I'd like that to go up,'' Mike Benziger said,
``and I'd like our vineyard-designated wines to range between $35
and $70 a bottle. But we've got to earn that.''
</P>
<P>
   As family wineries go, not even the Gallos can claim as large an
active clan. Only the Fetzers, who once had 10 children involved in
running their vineyards, can match the Benzigers.
</P>
<P>
   Of the other Benziger brothers, Bob handles business
development, Joe and Jerry are winemakers. Of the sisters, Patsy
manages a winery apprentice system, Chris is Midwest regional sales
manager and Kathy is Eastern sales manager. Patsy's husband, Tim
Wallace, is chief executive officer. Helen Benziger, mother of the
seven, manages VIP services. Bruno Benziger died in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   With husbands, wives and children, there are, Mike Benziger
said, ``more than two dozen Benzigers living in the Sonoma Valley
and involved in one way or another with the winery. Our strategy is
to stay family and stay small.'' With all those Benzigers making
and selling wine, that isn't going to be easy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
