<HEADLINE>
MUST RIESLING GROW DRIER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Though wine writers often extol the glory of fine
German rieslings, the American public has responded with a great
collective yawn. Many reasons are cited: the German labels are too
complex, the descriptive terminology is incomprehensible, the wines
are too sweet.
</P>
<P>
   The Rheingau region in southwest Germany has moved toward making
drier wines more in step with what the public is perceived to be
demanding. Count me among the riesling lovers, but I do not prefer
the drier style.
</P>
<P>
   The dry German rieslings I've tasted tend to be austere and
tight. But retain the sweetness, along with the lush flavors of the
grape and enough acidity to offset the sugar, and you have a wine
that transcends terms like dry and sweet. A better description for
the best German wines would be ``balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   German wines are rated by the sugar content of the grapes. Those
with a normal amount of sugar are called kabinett. Those that are
allowed to ripen further, and thus have more sugar, are known as
spatlese.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, kabinett wines have a slight amount of sweetness and
spatlese wines more, but that's not always so. Spatlese grapes are
sometimes fermented until the sugar is transformed into alcohol,
resulting in a spatlese that is dry and powerful rather than light
and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   The American fear of sweet wines, I think, comes from drinking
bad ones, like the syrupy stuff that stuck to the Passover table.
But tastes change. A century ago, rieslings from the Rheingau were
considered among the world's most glorious wines.
</P>
<P>
   When I was growing up, if people gave any thought to German wine
at all, it was to concoctions like liebfraumilch. Maybe tastes will
change again.
</P>
<P>
   The wines below are listed in order of preference within the
kabinett and spatlese categories. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHANNISHOF RIESLING KABINETT, JOHANNISBERGER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VOGELSANG, 1997 $12 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sumptuous with floral and mineral aromas, rich flavors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ABTEIHOF ST. NICOLAUS, RIESLING KABINETT, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHANNISBERGER VOGELSANG, 1998 $13.50 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both sweet and rich, with apricot flavors and a long finish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOSEF LEITZ, RIESLING KABINETT, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUDESHEIMER MAGDALENENKREUZ, 1998 $16 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mild orange and floral aromas, sweet and pleasant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PETER JAKOB KUHN, RIESLING SPATLESE, OESTRICHER LENCHEN, 1998
$19 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Golden color; sweet apple aroma, yet well balanced. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HANS LANG, RIESLING SPATLESE, 1997 $18 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lean aromas of honey and road tar; sweet pear and apricot
flavors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHANNISHOF, RIESLING SPATLESE, RUDESHEIMER BERG ROTTLAND, 1997
$18 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apple and rose petal aromas; light-bodied. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
