<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A SHAME THAT SO FEW GO TO SCHOOL OPEN HOUSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hey, where were you guys? There must have been some really
important stuff going on this past week because I was expecting to
see a bunch of you and hardly anyone showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, the faithful few were present but they were the same
faces that I see at every event. What's going on?
</P>
<P>
   I know Dennis Rodman got booted from the Mavericks, so I don't
think you had trouble tearing yourself away from the television.
Super Tuesday went exactly as predicted, so there was no political
David and Goliath to snare your attention. And the weather was
great this past week. So I just don't understand what happened.
</P>
<P>
   The public schools of our community hosted their traditional
open house this past week, and I'm just guessing, but it appeared
that fewer than half of the parents attended the two that I
attended. The halls were so empty you could see your shadow on the
floor. I've seen more people at school board meetings yelling and
screaming than I saw in those classrooms trying to establish a
relationship with the educators before problems arise.
</P>
<P>
   Now, hold on before you get your bloomers in a knot. I know many
of you had legitimate reasons for not attending. No, I have not
attended every single open house that my two sons were involved in.
Some of you had to work or you were out of town. Others had
conflicts in their schedules, and no one can be in two places at
the same time. A few people were ill or had transportation
problems. Some of you didn't even know about it because your child
didn't bring the notice home. I understand. I can't think of
everything, but I realize that there are valid excuses for missing
these events occasionally. Nevertheless, that laundry list doesn't
account for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, I work hard too. I went to two open houses this week and
both occurred after a nine-hour workday (and I am not including
lunch). I had a committee meeting, a board meeting and one son's
birthday week. Before and after my day job, I worked on three major
projects and typed a paper for my husband when I wasn't returning
calls, answering e-mails and responding to my pager.
</P>
<P>
   So what? So we're all busy and we're all tired.
</P>
<P>
   But guys, you should have been there.
</P>
<P>
   At my youngest son's school, the kids had each made a stuffed
doll using old clothes and huge, decorated grocery bags for the
head. The girls glued strings of yarn to the bags and curled it to
look like locks of hair. The dolls were sitting at the kids' desks
in their homerooms, all bright eyes and smiles just like I imagine
it must be when the first bell rings each day.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the dolls, was a mountain of our students' best work
in a notebook. On top of the notebook, was a lovely card made in
computer class that said, ``Mom and Dad, Welcome to our Open
House.'' It's not exactly Mardi Gras, but those children worked
really hard preparing for our visit to their classes.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the evening, we got to take the dolls home.
Imagine the disappointment of the youngsters who returned to school
the next day to find their desks exactly as they had left them,
complete with the lovely card to Mom and Dad.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers and principal were there, also tired I'm sure. Yet
they were smiling and saying pleasant things about the children.
This is our second round through the fifth grade, but I want the
teachers to see me when things are going right and not just when
there's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   My parents were educators and I'm telling you, it's better for
your child and you if you show some interest in education before
report cards are passed out. Teaching is hard work, and being a
student is hard work. Don't you enjoy it when someone admires and
appreciates your efforts, especially when they go out of their way
to do it? Of course, you do. We all do.
</P>
<P>
   So, next time, put the date of open house on your calendar early
like you do other important events. Let's fill the schools on that
night like we fill the stadiums when our favorite team makes the
playoffs. Not only is it important, but it's also free and open to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington
TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
