<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SHALLOTS-ART-2TAKES-N     03-14 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHALLOTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHALLOT CONQUERS THE KITCHEN, AND NOT A TEAR IS SHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shallots are like lingerie: a graceful and necessary
underpinning, more appreciated in France than in America, and
increasingly showing up in full view.
</P>
<P>
   The shallot, a member of the onion family that can be peeled,
sliced and chopped without driving the cook to tears, has long been
a crucial component in classic French sauces like bearnaise, Bercy,
bordelaise, beurre blanc, mignonnette, vinaigrette and marchand de
vin.
</P>
<P>
   But now, chefs in New York and elsewhere are showcasing
shallots, roasting, glazing and caramelizing them whole and using
them to garnish salads, vegetables, meat, fish and poultry.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Boulud, the chef and an owner of Daniel and a native of
Lyon, France, has noticed the change in attitude among his American
colleagues. ``Maybe it's because more of them are doing bistro
food,'' he said. ``But I also think they have a better
understanding of the subtleties and refinements of cooking. A
shallot is a step above an onion, and it will sustain its flavor
better in a reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Shallots ``round out a dish,'' said Kevin Penner, the chef at
Della Femina, who uses them in a mussel risotto and as a confit
with a buffalo fillet. ``They add that onion component that defines
Western cooking, but with more sweetness and less acidity than
onions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bieber, the chef at Eli's Restaurant, said regular onions
``tend to melt away,'' so he prefers richly caramelized shallots in
his custardy pudding. ``I never used them that much before,'' he
said. ``But I find they add a fuller flavor to a dish.'' Besides,
he added, ``shallots are more easily available now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even supermarket shoppers would agree. Shallots were once as
scarce as fresh ginger in American markets. In the first volume of
``Mastering the Art of French Cooking,'' published in 1964, Julia
Child said that the white part of scallions could be used as a
substitute for shallots, or even left out entirely. But as anyone
who has cooked with shallots knows, omitting their assertively
sweet pungency diminishes a dish.
</P>
<P>
   Most shallots sold in the United States are imported from
France, where they have been cultivated since Charlemagne's time.
Brittany, which grows 75 percent of France's more than 40,000 tons
each year, is the world's largest producer. Exports to America from
France have increased from none in 1980 to 4,525 tons last year,
according to the French National Center for Statistical Research, a
government agency.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are dozens of kinds of shallots, the ones most
frequently sold in America have tawny skins surrounding a pale
mauve bulb. Lately, markets have tended to offer larger and fresher
ones, with a single bulb instead of a cluster, making them much
easier to peel. Shallots are often pear-shaped or rounded, but some
from France are slender ovals.
</P>
<P>
   They can also be pale gold, like the organic ones grown in
upstate New York. Echalotes grises, prized in France, have a
particularly rich flavor and a tough grayish skin. And big, sweet
lavender oval ``torpedo'' shallots, a cross between shallots and
onions, are imported from Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   In Southeast Asia, where shallots are used with abandon, small
reddish ones, similar to the kind sold in Chinatown, are preferred.
In India, members of certain Buddhist sects who do not eat garlic
use shallots instead.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, shallots are used raw or deep-fried to give a stronger
flavor and a crunchy texture, said Jean-Georges Vongerichten, who
once worked in Thailand. ``And they're usually sliced differently
in Asia _ the long way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   James Chew, a chef and caterer who once worked with
Vongerichten, said shallots are used by the cupful in Vietnam and
Thailand in salads and in dishes like fried rice and mee krob, a
noodle mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Several Asian shops in Chinatown sell jars and cans of crisp
deep-fried shallots imported from Thailand. They do wonders for a
sour cream dip, on top of a string bean casserole or strewn on a
baked potato or a salad.
</P>
<P>
   Whole unpeeled shallots are easy to roast, brushed with oil and
wrapped in foil like garlic. They can be slowly caramelized in
butter with a little sugar, made into a tangy sweet-and-sour pickle
with sugar and vinegar, or cooked until they are soft for a kind of
savory marmalade. At Firebird the chef, Ari Nieminen, roasts them
with apricots to make a jamlike condiment.
</P>
<P>
   Shallots range from 99 cents to $5.99 a pound for organically
grown ones. French shallots are sold in many markets for $2 to $3 a
pound, even though they are subject to a 100 percent tariff imposed
by the government last July in retaliation for the European ban on
American beef with hormones.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Paffenroth, who owns Paffenroth Gardens in Warwick, N.Y.,
sells his shallots for $2 a pound at the Union Square Greenmarket
on Saturdays. He said the green shallot tops are popular among
Asians. Mike Kaloski, a farmer in Cutchogue, N.Y., grows shallots
that are sold in the summer for $1.50 to $2 a pound at farm stands
on the East End of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Colicchio, the chef at Gramercy Tavern, likes Paffenroth's
shallots because they are small. ``The big ones may be easier to
peel, but the little ones are nicer to bake,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boulud said that in summer, when shallots have just been
harvested, they have the best flavor for roasting whole. Penner
also prefers freshly harvested shallots, favoring those grown on
Long Island. ``The fresher the better,'' he said. ``When I lived in
East Hampton, I grew my own.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With shallots so widely available now, not just in summer but
all year, it pays to have a few on hand, kept in a cool, dry place
like potatoes and onions. And when a recipe calls for shallots,
there will be no need to substitute or omit. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHALLOT PUDDING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Eli's Restaurant &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter (more for buttering dish)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups peeled, sliced shallots
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   { cup shredded Gruyere cheese
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Butter a shallow 4-cup baking
dish, like a ceramic quiche pan.
</P>
<P>
   2. Melt butter in heavy skillet. Add shallots and saute,
stirring, over medium heat until richly browned. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Lightly beat eggs with salt and baking powder. Stir in cream
and cheese and fold in shallots. Pour in baking dish and bake about
35 minutes, until firm to touch and browned.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THAI SQUID SALAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Oriental Hotel, Bangkok &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons long-grain rice
</P>
<P>
   1 pound cleaned squid, sliced into rings
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Thai fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sliced peeled shallots
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sliced scallions
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon thinly sliced seeded fresh green chili
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 limes, cut in wedges. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place rice in a small dry skillet and cook over medium heat,
stirring gently about 3 minutes, until it turns nut brown.
Pulverize rice to a powder in blender or spice mill. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring saucepan of water to a boil; add squid, separating the
rings, and cook 30 seconds. Drain well and place in mixing bowl.
Combine fish sauce and lime juice in a small bowl. Add pepper
flakes, shallots and scallions. Pour over squid and mix well. Fold
in pulverized toasted rice.
</P>
<P>
   3. Transfer salad to a serving dish, scatter chili slices and
mint leaves on top and arrange lime wedges around it.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HANGER STEAK WITH SHALLOTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Cafe Boulud Cookbook'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Daniel Boulud and Dorie Greenspan (Scribner, 1999) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   6 hanger steaks, 6 to 7 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   8 medium shallots, peeled and sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   { cup dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped flat-leaf parsley. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place large, heavy skillet over high heat. Add oil. Season
steaks with salt and pepper and sear, turning once, to desired
degree of doneness, about 6 minutes for medium-rare. You may not be
able to cook all steaks at once. Transfer to warm serving dish.
</P>
<P>
   2. Lower heat to medium and add 1 tablespoon butter. Add
shallots and cook, stirring, 3 minutes, until soft but not brown.
Add vinegar and cook until it evaporates; then add wine. Boil until
reduced by half. Remove pan from heat and swirl in remaining
butter; then stir in parsley.
</P>
<P>
   3. Slice steaks and serve with sauce poured over.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED MUSHROOMS AND JERUSALEM ARTICHOKES WITH SHALLOT
VINAIGRETTE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Blanc Vite'' by Raymond Blanc (Headline, 1998) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 50 minutes  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   3 medium shallots, peeled and chopped fine
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   20 Jerusalem artichokes (about 2 pounds), peeled and halved
vertically
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons peanut or grape seed oil
</P>
<P>
   20 medium-size mushrooms (porcini, cremini or blue-foot), halved
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   20 small sprigs flat-leaf parsley. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place wine in saucepan and cook, reducing to 3 tablespoons.
Cool briefly and mix with shallots, olive oil and salt and pepper
to taste. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring a large pot of water to a boil. Add artichokes and boil
5 minutes. Drain well.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place large skillet over medium heat. Add 2 tablespoons
peanut oil and fry artichokes, turning, until golden brown.
Transfer to bowl and cover loosely. Add remaining oil to pan,
increase heat and saute mushrooms 2 minutes on each side, until
golden. Add butter and parsley and fry a minute longer. Add
artichokes. Season to taste with salt and pepper. Remove from heat.
Stir shallot sauce, pour over vegetables, fold lightly and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
