<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BROADBAND15-COX     03-14 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADBAND15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS SET TO FOSTER BROADBAND COMPETITION
 &HT;    410&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFAX, Va. _ Congress is likely approve a bill that would let
all businesses offer high-speed Internet access to U.S. homes on an
equal basis, the co-chairmen of the House Internet Caucus predicted
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by a series of mega-mergers, chances for passage of the
Internet Freedom Act have markedly improved in recent months, said
Reps. Bob Goodlatte, R-Va., and Rick Boucher, D-Va., who are
steering the measure through the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very close to getting the legislation out of the
committee and onto the House floor,'' Boucher told reporters after
speaking to the Global Internet Summit at George Mason University.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rate our chances for final passage this year at 50-50 or
better,'' Goodlatte said. House passage of the bill, which
Goodlatte forecast would occur in June, ``will motivate the Senate,
which has been in a wait-and-see posture,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The House Commerce Committee is also considering the bill. But
Boucher said that whether or not that panel acts, the measure will
reach the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   The lucrative broadband market is ripe for explosive growth in
coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research, a leading analyst of Internet trends,
estimates that the number of high-speed Internet home subscribers
will more than double, to about 6 million, by year's end and will
reach 27 million by 2003. Most of these services are being provided
by cable or telephone outlets, which remain regulated by the
Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The pending bill would impose antitrust penalties against cable
and telecom firms that ``knowingly and willfully fail to provide''
open access to their would-be competitors. It also makes it
unlawful for broadband access providers to compete unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be very cautious about what role the government
should play in the development of the Internet,'' Goodlatte argued.
``As lawmakers, we have to stand aside and let industry
self-regulation work to the maximum extent possible.''
</P>
<P>
   By letting consumers load Web pages almost instantly and enjoy
advanced features such as online video over a full-time connection,
high-speed access is seen as the key to making the Internet a part
of everyday life much like the telephone and television are today.
That, in turn, could unlock the full commercial potential of the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of broadband deregulation was hailed by Ivan
Seidenberg, chairman and chief executive officer of Bell Atlantic
Corp.. Seidenberg joined the two Virginia lawmakers on the summit
panel, along with Steve Case, who heads America Online Inc., the
world's leading Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regulation is needed to protect consumers,'' Seidenberg said.
``But the model of regulation needs to be changed lest it create
disincentives for (the telecommunications industry) to do what they
need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the regulatory scene shifted in Congress in
the wake of the merger agreement between Case's AOL and Time Warner
Inc. By combining Time Warner's cable modem services and
proprietary content with AOL's 22 million online subscribers, the
merged company is poised to become a broadband powerhouse. Its top
officers recently pledged to offer open access to its fat Internet
pipes to all would-be entrants in the market.
</P>
<P>
   In a deregulated climate, increased competition would aid such
competitors as Seidenberg's Bell Atlantic, as well as other
regional telecom firms, to step up their efforts to deliver
Internet connections at up to 50 times faster than current dial-up
service.
</P>
<P>
   And building these fatter pipes to the Web will create a need to
fill them with content, as Case pointed out to his summit audience.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
