u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      03-14 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SURPRISE CANDIDATE FOR ROASTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lamb shoulder is a bony cut of meat that can easily
be turned into a boneless roast by someone with the proper
experience. I'm not suggesting that you are that someone _ neither
am I _ but any butcher, including those who work in supermarkets,
can and will perform this task pretty quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a round, tied piece of meat with lovely crevices
into which you can stuff a simple seasoning mixture, like garlic
and parsley. This is a traditional combination for seasoning lamb,
and rightly so, because the flavors marry so well.
</P>
<P>
   What is not traditional, or at least not common, is roasting
lamb shoulder. I first had the dish at a bistro in Paris, and it
was lovely _ tender inside, crisp outside, and richly flavored.
When I decided to tackle it myself and asked colleagues for their
advice, I confirmed what I already knew: everyone braised lamb
shoulder. Outside my bistro experience, I'd never had it roasted
either.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this isn't surprising, because like the corresponding
cuts of pork and beef, lamb shoulder is fattier _ and more
flavorful _ than cuts from the hindquarter. Braising _ cooking
slowly in liquid _ renders the fat. It also tenderizes tougher
cuts, like chuck or brisket of beef.
</P>
<P>
   But lamb does not need to be braised to be tender.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the temperature is kept relatively low _ 300 degrees
is best _ roasting renders the fat just as well as braising. A
short boost of oven heat during the last 15 minutes or so of
roasting guarantees a browned, crisp exterior unlike anything you
can get from braising.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal degree of doneness is just short of well done, a stage
at which the meat achieves the best combination of tenderness,
flavor and leanness.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no denying that the shoulder is a fatty cut, so
it pays to ask the butcher to remove as much surface fat as
possible. (In my experience, it also pays to phone ahead, or to
plan to spend some time shopping while the butcher does his thing.)
Most shoulders weigh in at three to four pounds after boning,
making this simple roast enough to serve six to eight people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BONELESS LAMB ROAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 2 hours &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   4 medium or 2 large cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   About 2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 3- to 4-pound boned lamb shoulder, trimmed of surface fat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Mince parsley and garlic
together until quite fine (a small food processor will work for
this). Add a big pinch of salt, some pepper and enough olive oil to
make a slurry. Smear this on and into lamb, making sure to get it
in every nook and cranny possible. Put lamb in a roasting pan lined
with foil (to facilitate cleanup).
</P>
<P>
   2. Roast for about 1{ hours, basting with pan juices every 30
minutes or so. When internal temperature reaches 140 degrees, turn
heat to 400 degrees and roast about 10 minutes more, or until
internal temperature is 150 degrees and exterior has browned
nicely.
</P>
<P>
   3. Let roast sit for about 10 minutes, then carve and serve with
some of its juices.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: At least 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
