<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS BARBIE-STYLE DOLL LACKS STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Where can I purchase a ``Trailer Trash Barbie-type fashion
doll'' other than eBay?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.S., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The mail-order retailer Poor White Trash is selling a
``trailer trash doll'' for $48.
</P>
<P>
   The doll, the subject of several media reports, is a
Barbie-style doll complete with a cigarette, a blackened tooth,
curlers in her hair, a beer can and a ``dirty-faced baby on hip.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also sells a Ken-style doll that wears women's
clothing; a street-walking Barbie-style doll; and ``Dukes of
Hazzard'' memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   To order, write to Box 1239, Los Altos, CA 94023-1239, or visit
the Web site www.powhitetrash.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sycamore School Road in Fort Worth does not have a school on
it today. What was it named after?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.T., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: The road takes its name from a one- or two-room school that
was located at the corner of Sycamore School and Crowley roads for
50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Billy W. Sills, a volunteer archivist for the Fort Worth ISD,
found records on the school dating back to 1884. ``That area was
known as the Sycamore School District No. 64,'' Sills said. ``It
was probably named for Sycamore Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   The school appears to have closed in 1940, Sills said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On a recent episode of ``Once and Again,'' a book of poetry
was discussed, and I think the name was ``North River Wind'' or
something like that. Is it a real book?
</P>
<P>
   _ P.F., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: According to fans of the show on the rec.arts.tv Internet
discussion group, the poem featured on the show was ``George
Gray,'' from the book ``Spoon River Anthology'' by Edgar Lee
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   The book, first published in 1914, contains 244 monologues by
real and imagined inhabitants of Spoon River, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   You can read messages in the rec.arts.tv group on the Web site
www.deja.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
