<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6618 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CABLENET-TEENS-TEX     03-14 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLENET-TEENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERACTIVE CABLE NETWORK BEING GEARED TO SMART, COMPUTER-SAVVY
TEEN GIRLS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CABLE NET-SITES) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAVONNA MAY-MONS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a long day at school, Vanessa comes home and tosses her
backpack on the couch. She plops down on the floor, grabs her
keyboard and _ instantly _ she's in the middle of a chat with TV
star Jennifer Aniston about who should be president. In a flurry of
dancing fingers, she's zapping e-mails to Aniston and other
participants from around the world, voicing her views.
</P>
<P>
   The next minute, she's watching an animated soap opera in which
the characters are as varied and well, as real, as the people she
knows at school. Vanessa looks at the time and realizes she needs
to do her history homework, so she clicks over to her browser to
research the life of a local historical figure. All of this, from
her television.
</P>
<P>
   Think this is a teeny-bopper Web dream of the future? So wrong.
It's VOXXY, an interactive cable network geared to teen-age girls,
and a new dimension in grrrl entertainment that's coming to a
living room _ yours, maybe _ as soon as this year.
</P>
<P>
   VOXXY _ derived from the Latin word ``vox,'' meaning voice, and
the letters ``xx,'' which stand for the female chromosomes _ will
begin streaming its programming to the Web in late spring. Computer
software-supported boxes placed atop television sets, to be
introduced toward the end of this year, will allow viewers to watch
TV and interact on the Web at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``VOXXY is not just a Web site,'' says the network's co-founder,
Hillary Carlip. ``It's a fully interactive cable channel.'' VOXXY's
goal is to offer cutting-edge entertainment for young
Internet-savvy users, going beyond the realm of a Web site or cable
channel to provide a full package of smart, empowering
entertainment that will appeal to a diverse group of girls.
</P>
<P>
   Former MTV and network-television producer Kristi Kaylor teamed
up with Carlip, author of ``Girl Power: Young Women Speak Out,''
and Maxine Lapiduss, a Hollywood producer who has written for
``Ellen'', ``Roseanne'' and ``Home Improvement,'' to form an
alliance that has spawned this ambitious leap into high-tech girl
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly is VOXXY? The key words to describe the network
appear to be ``smart'' and ``authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlip describes the network as a place for girls who want
thought-provoking entertainment. ``We've found that there's really
not a place (on television) for smart girls,'' she says. ``A lot of
girls grew up on the Internet with a mouse in hand; they're living
and thriving on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she says, many teens can't relate to shows like
``90210'' and ``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give girls authentic programming where everyone
isn't a size 2 and perfect, and where everything isn't wrapped up
perfectly at the end of every episode,'' Carlip says.
</P>
<P>
   For example, she says, ``That's What Friends Are For,'' a dating
show, embodies the spirit of VOXXY. Instead of female contestants
asking questions directly to male contenders, the bachelor's mom,
best friend and ex-girlfriend will be quizzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is really interactive with viewers at home and on the
show,'' co-founder and VOXXY President Kaylor adds. Viewers _
possibly ex-girlfriends! _ may participate by sending V-mails
(that's what e-mails are called in VOXXY land) that instantly
appear on a plasma screen for the contestant to view. This, says
Kaylor, gives contestants a chance to get the real scoop before
making a choice.
</P>
<P>
   Other scheduled programming includes an animated teen soap
opera, live concerts and a bilingual sitcom produced by Galan
Entertainment. VOXXY will also promote satellite sites such as
www.girlpower.com, based on Carlip's nationally recognized book
that voices the hopes and dreams of girls ages 13 to 19 through
their stories, poems and letters. The site currently posts reviews
and excerpts from ``Girl Power: Young Women Speak Out,'' and Carlip
is in the process of gathering renowned authors to create writing
exercises for the Web site. The writers will be available for
online critiquing sessions.
</P>
<P>
   VOXXY's co-founders are also counting on star power to be a draw
for teens. This year, Jennifer Aniston of ``Friends'' fame agreed
to create 13 half-hour episodes of original programming, during
which she will interact with girls on a wide range of issues.
</P>
<P>
   Aniston was at the top of their wish list, both Kaylor and
Carlip say, because of what they see as the actress's genuineness
and her eagerness to make a difference in young girls' lives.
</P>
<P>
   It's important for girls to see that Aniston is just like them
in many ways, Kaylor says. ``Even though she's a star and has a
really cute boyfriend (Brad Pitt), she's still just a person, and
that's empowering.''
</P>
<P>
   Another key to VOXXY, say the women behind it, is that the
concept of girl empowerment spreads across racial and economic
lines in terms of programming content.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have characters of all sizes,'' Kaylor says. ``We have
black, Asian and Latino characters. It's not just your white,
middle-class girls. We're really trying to reach every girl
possible to make it a home and a community.''
</P>
<P>
   So that's what VOXXY is, but how will the high-tech network
work?
</P>
<P>
   VOXXY will begin as a strictly Web-based production. The
programming, heavy in short video streams, will be best viewed with
a high-speed computer modem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're building the Web experience for high-end users,'' says
Dewey Reid, creative director at Red Sky Interactive, the computer
software and network company that's creating VOXXY'S layout. But he
says that people with slower modems will still be able to enjoy
VOXXY's content _ they'll just miss out on some of the video
streams.
</P>
<P>
   Those with at least a 56K modem will have a good viewing
experience, while people with a Digital Subscriber Line (DSL) _ a
faster Internet connection _ will have a better one. (For the
high-tech challenged: DSL uses existing two-wire copper telephone
wiring and in most cases doesn't require an additional phone line.
It is available through Southwestern Bell, GTE, Charter
Communications, Internet America and AT&AMP;T.)
</P>
<P>
   Currently, AT&AMP;T is working to complete VOXXY's boxes, which are
to be set on top a TV; they should be available at the end of this
year or the beginning of 2001. Once construction of the set-top
boxes is finished, VOXXY will blossom into a dual experience,
combining Internet and television elements.
</P>
<P>
   VOXXY viewers will be able to attach keyboards to their
television, watch VOXXY's programming and log onto the Internet
from the same location. Those who don't have the set-top boxes will
simply use the television and Internet separately.
</P>
<P>
   Will VOXXY change the world with its grrrl empowerment message?
Probably not. But if the plans live up to expectations, the network
looks like a strong step in the direction of quality entertainment
for young women.
</P>
<P>
   ``VOXXY is a new generation of `Web TV,''' Kaylor says. ``We're
taking it a step beyond with unique ways for girls to empower
themselves. We came together to give girls a voice.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1713EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6619 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-BINGE-DRINKING-HNS &LR;      03-14 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BINGE-DRINKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FREQUENT BINGE DRINKING IS UP ON CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More and more college students are moving away from
moderate drinking and into either heavy drinking or total
abstention, according to a Harvard School of Public Health survey
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study of some 14,000 students at 119 four-year colleges
nationwide last year classified 22.7 percent of the respondents as
``frequent'' binge drinkers. Those are men consuming five drinks or
more in a row at least three times over two-weeks, or women
consuming four drinks or more with the same frequency over the same
time period.
</P>
<P>
   That 22.7 percent represents nearly a three-percentage-point
rise from the survey's 1993 figure of 19.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the population of tea-totaling college
students rose from 15.4 percent of respondents in 1993 to 19.2
percent in 1999, a rise of nearly four percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is growing polarization on drinking among college
students,'' said Henry Wechsler, a Harvard psychologist who
directed the study, speaking at a press conference in Boston.
``Nearly every college is thinking about this problem and
confronting it one way or another, but despite all the attention
there has been no national improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Wechsler first popularized the term ``binge drinking'' in a
study of Massachusetts college students published in 1992 in the
Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, binge drinking among college youth has become a
major issue on campus. Instances of students dying after heavy
drinking have received wide publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Among them: A University of Virginia senior who died in 1997
after consuming beer and margaritas and falling down a flight
stairs, and a Massachusetts Institute of Technology freshman who
drank himself to death at a fraternity party the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges and universities have responded with educational
programs and policies aimed at making it harder for students to
obtain quantities of alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   A second Harvard survey of 734 college administrators also
released Tuesday found that 96.6 percent reported instituting
alcohol education programs. Also, 98.2 percent reported banning
beer kegs in dorms; 87 percent banned kegs in fraternities and
sororities; 89.6 percent restricted advertising at home sports
events, and 62 percent offered students alcohol-free dorms or dorm
floors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these efforts, the overall binge-drinking level has
remained steady since 1993 at 44 percent, said Wechsler. That's
about two students in five.
</P>
<P>
   This category of binge drinking is defined as a man drinking
five drinks in a row at least once over two weeks or a woman
consuming four drinks over the same time period. It is distinct
from ``frequent'' binge drinking, which entails consuming the same
amounts at least three times in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My disappointment is that given all the attention placed on it
(by colleges and universities), it has remained remarkably
stable,'' Wechsler said.
</P>
<P>
   Many college students fall into binge drinking because they are
away from home and anxious to test the limits of their new-found
freedom, said Joel Wiegert, a University of Nebraska student and
self-described former binge drinker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the experimenter It was a scary time,'' he told the news
conference. Under the influence, Wiegert said, he insulted people,
said ``dumb things'' and broke a table.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to break away from a campus culture where ``drinking
is the focus of what's going on,'' Wiegert said. ``A party without
beer doesn't make much sense in that culture.''
</P>
<P>
   But gradually Wiegert stepped away from it, thanks to his
parents and the university's anti-alcohol educational efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Wiegert said he still likes ``to go out and have a beer with
friends but five or six, or 10 or 15 is not for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey showed that frequent binge drinking affects not just
those who are doing it. Among non-binge drinkers and abstainers, 58
percent reported being interrupted while studying or sleeping by
student carousing, 50 percent said they had taken care of a drunken
fellow student, and 29 percent reported being insulted or
humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, Wechsler said, is the easy availability of
relatively inexpensive alcohol, as well as bars near campuses that
lure students with specially priced drinks. And the students who
qualify in the survey as frequent binge drinkers mostly view
themselves as moderate drinkers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is the easy availability of phony ID cards
showing a student is 21 or older.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the major growth industries among some young
people,'' said Phillip Jones, vice president for student services
at the University of Iowa, who also took part in the press
conference. ``The ID problem is horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the answer to campus binge drinking is ``we have to
keep at it,'' Wechsler said. ``We can't suffer from attention
deficit disorder by worrying about it for a time and then
forgetting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Administrators must get municipal and community leaders in
college towns involved, Wechsler added. In the second survey, only
39.9 percent of administrators reported reaching cooperative
agreements with surrounding communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cannot be done by universities alone,'' Wechsler said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1713EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
