<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-14 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ROAD RAGE CLAIMS A CUDDLY VICTIM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When a furious motorist grabbed Leo the bichon
frise from his owner's car and hurled him into oncoming traffic in
San Jose, Calif., millions of Americans were horrified.
</P>
<P>
   It was a particularly vicious, senseless example of road rage.
What kind of monster would take out revenge for a fender-bender on
a harmless, adorable lapdog?
</P>
<P>
   White, fluffy Leo has posthumously become a celebrity, a
full-scale criminal investigation has been launched and reward
money offered for the killer has reached $100,000. In this country,
we take our pets seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of our pet population vary, but perhaps 54 million
dogs frolic in households across America, outnumbered only by
domestic cats, of which there are some 68 million. The feline
numerical superiority may be due to their tidier nature and the
fact they do not require leashes and regular walks. But it cannot
be because they offer more emotional gratification.
</P>
<P>
   A cat can be a friendly lap-sitting, purring companion, so long
as this happens strictly on his own terms. But a dog is an entire
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Leo's death caused a national sensation because dog owners
everywhere empathized with the suffering of this owner as she
watched her beloved pet crushed on a busy highway. We know that in
the normal course of events we will always outlive our dogs, who
have an average life span of 12 years. But that doesn't make the
loss easier to bear when the time comes.
</P>
<P>
   I just lost my own bichon frise to cancer. His caring and
competent veterinarian, Dr. Wesley Bayles, cried with us when
Charlie gave in to the malignant tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie was 13 years old and he ran the household, which
revolved around the fact that he loved being loved and reciprocated
at every opportunity. He stuck so close to us when we were home he
was constantly underfoot; we concluded he must think his name was
Movecharlie because that's what we said to him so often.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie demanded attention and we were happy to give it. He and
his resident brother, a tabby cat named Teddy, had a regular
routine of chasing, paw-waving, barking, meowing and generally
putting on a show for humans. Later, like buddies, they would lie
down next to each other and sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie's senior years were full of tail-wagging and curiosity
about the world around him, particularly about other dogs met and
sniffed on our walks. But he was no good as a watch dog. He was so
friendly that when a burglar broke into the back door, Charlie
didn't sound an alarm; the burglar brought doggie treats and a
grateful Charlie generously pointed out the direction to the
silverware.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I were goofy about our bichon; we miss him
horribly. He thought he was people, and we did too.
</P>
<P>
   We are not alone in the dedicated pampering of a pooch.
Americans tend to treat their pets almost like their children,
seeking the best for them in food, grooming and health care. Pricey
dog fashions _ coats, sweaters, collars _ were on display last year
at a Canine Couture show in New York. There are dog spas, dog gyms,
doggy day care and doggy menus at some carry-out cafes.
</P>
<P>
   The grocery store shelves of dog and cat food in my neighborhood
run along a whole aisle, catering to every taste. The pet food
industry is big business. Millions of Americans buy their dogs
Christmas presents, usually the edible variety. Lapdogs get bows in
their hair.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs are so popular that it is traditional for American
presidents to own dogs to humanize their image. President Clinton
didn't get a dog until well into his second term, when he acquired
Buddy, a chocolate Labrador. The delay was a mistake; Clinton
needed help and a cat named Socks didn't quite measure up.
</P>
<P>
   There is also an emerging field of animal rights law, which
seeks to set judicial standards for the humane treatment of both
domestic pets and animals in the wild by giving them ``legal
personhood.'' This sounds like a bit much to me, but the outrage
over Leo's death suggests why it may have some cultural traction.
</P>
<P>
   There are always people who dislike dogs, perhaps because they
have been bitten. It happens.
</P>
<P>
   But I feel sorry for them. We dog lovers would rather enjoy our
four-legged friends for a limited span than never to have had the
joy of their company at all. We may spoil them, but a wonderful
time is had by all.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1715EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
