<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6629 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-MERGER-TRIBUNE-CHANDL     03-14 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER-TRIBUNE-CHANDLER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTIS CHANDLER'S REVOLT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax,
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICK LYMAN  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    ``I do look back on my life for certain lessons that I have
learned,'' said Otis Chandler, the man who was publisher of The Los
Angeles Times for 20 years, from 1960 to 1980.
 &HT;    ``I do look back with great appreciation for the kind of life
I've led, which has been fascinating. But I tend to live in the
moment and look forward to the future. So I don't sit in an office
surrounded by Los Angeles Times photos and memorabilia and Pulitzer
Prizes. No, I don't.''
 &HT;    Which makes it all the more surprising that Otis Chandler has
emerged, after a self-imposed silence of almost a decade, as
something of a latter-day hero to many newspaper journalists around
the country, a prophet lamenting in the wilderness.
 &HT;    For more than a quarter-century, beginning with his unexpected
rise at age 33 to the position of publisher of The Los Angeles
Times, which had been run by his father and grandfather and
great-grandfather before him, Chandler was a figure of the first
importance in the nation's second most important metropolis.
 &HT;    Late last year Chandler spoke out, chastising his successors at
The Los Angeles Times and charging that its bottom-line, Wall
Street-oriented management had compromised the reputation and
editorial integrity of his family's paper. His words echoed through
hundreds of newsrooms.
 &HT;    And they played against a backdrop of great change and anxiety
in the newspaper business, as increasing corporate ownership has
led to an era of cost-cutting and an obsession with stock prices.
 &HT;    During his 20 years as publisher Chandler was instrumental in
transforming The LA Times from a dreadful newspaper into one of the
two or three best in the country.
 &HT;    If his power came with a certain reputation for oddness _
fueled, perhaps, by a clear preference for outdoor derring-do over
the trappings of media mogulhood, as well as an assortment of
rich-guy hobbies like racing Porsches and hunting big game _ well,
that just made him more interesting, harder to categorize.
 &HT;    Then in 1980, he relinquished the job unexpectedly, though he
continued to serve for the next five years as chairman of the
parent company.
 &HT;    By the 1990s, his trips to Los Angeles were increasingly rare,
mostly to attend board meetings (he remained a director until 1998)
or to visit his celebrated but by then infirm mother, Dorothy
Buffum Chandler, who died in 1997.
 &HT;    Chandler hasn't been inside the Los Angeles Times building since
his final annual shareholder's meeting two years ago, and he says
he no longer feels welcome there. Many of the people in its
newsroom these days have never laid eyes on him.
 &HT;    ``The truth is, Otis was a symbol from the day he took over The
Times until the day he left, and still is today,'' said Bill
Thomas, editor of the paper for almost 18 years, during much of the
period that it was being transformed.
 &HT;    Chandler, now 72, stepped onto the public stage again in
November to end his silence about the way The Los Angeles Times was
being run. The management team headed by Mark H. Willes, a former
General Mills executive with no newspaper experience, had vowed to
``reinvent'' the newspaper, soar its circulation and raise the
price of the stock.
 &HT;    Willes came to the paper in 1995 as CEO; in '97, Willes
appointed himself publisher, a title he kept until 1999, when he
gave it to Kathryn M. Downing, the former head of the company's
legal-book publishing division. Downing likewise had no newspaper
experience.
 &HT;    Chandler says he kept silent about what was going on for so long
because he thought the new management deserved a chance. He
overlooked what he felt was its naivete and arrogance, especially
the talk of ``reinventing'' the paper.
 &HT;    But only after it was revealed that Willes and Downing had
approved a profit-sharing scheme with the owners of the Staples
Center, a new local sports arena, in which the advertising revenues
from a special edition of the paper's Sunday magazine about the
center would be shared with the subject of the stories, did he
decide that the integrity of his newspaper had been placed at risk.
 &HT;    ``When I saw the Staples thing come down, I just lost it,''
Chandler said. Chandler, who rarely grants interviews, says he had
been paying close attention to the Willes regime for some time _ to
the closing of Times-Mirror's New York Newsday and Baltimore
Evening Sun, as well as to cutbacks in staff and news space at The
Los Angeles Times.
 &HT;    ``I'd been looking at all these things, and I'd been saying, I'm
not going to criticize,'' Chandler said. ``We had just gone out and
hired this wonderful new CEO, and he's seen fit to hire a woman
publisher who's never been on a newspaper, but maybe she'll learn,
be quick on the job training, maybe they'll get their act
together.''
 &HT;    As long as the issues were merely financial, as long as the
prestige of the paper was not being seriously called into question,
Chandler kept quiet. But it was beginning to wear on him.
 &HT;    Then the Staples Center fiasco erupted. ``He has always cared
deeply about how The Los Angeles Times was regarded on the East
Coast,'' said David Shaw, the paper's Pulitzer-winning media
writer, who conducted an internal investigation of the Staples
incident, resulting in a 14-page special section. ``Once editorial
integrity was being questioned, he couldn't stay silent.''
 &HT;    ``It's been kind of cooking for quite a while,'' said Chandler's
sister, Mia Chandler Frost. ``He's been trying to bite his
tongue.''
 &HT;    Two weeks after the special Staples edition of the Sunday
magazine appeared, and a week after Downing told the staff she had
no intention of resigning, Chandler decided to act. He telephoned a
surprised Bill Boyarsky, the city editor.
 &HT;    He began to dictate, and Boyarsky transcribed. As the afternoon
progressed and copies of the statement were faxed back and forth
between Chandler and Boyarsky, word began to get around the
newsroom.
 &HT;    Michael Parks, the paper's top editor, and several other editors
asked Boyarsky not to read Chandler's statement aloud. But at 5:45,
a message went out to the entire staff.
 &HT;    ``Quite a crowd gathered,'' Boyarsky said. ``Most of them had
probably never seen him or certainly had never worked for him. But
they knew who he was and what he had done.''
 &HT;    Chandler's statement, Boyarsky said, signaled to them that
``they were fighting one of the great, great battles of modern
journalism.''
 &HT;    And although the statement was greeted with thunderous applause,
it stirred Downing to issue an ill-considered statement of her own
calling Chandler ``angry and bitter'' and lamenting that it was
``too bad when some people get old, they get bitter.''
 &HT;    To his detractors it was self-serving and came much too late.
But to his supporters it was invigorating proof that, despite his
long silence, Chandler was still there, still fighting the good
fight.
 &HT;     c.2000 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Rick Lyman is a reporter in the Los Angeles Times bureau of
The New York Times.) &LR;
</P>
