47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax,
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICK LYMAN  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    ``I do look back on my life for certain lessons that I have
learned,'' said Otis Chandler, the man who was publisher of The Los
Angeles Times for 20 years, from 1960 to 1980.
 &HT;    ``I do look back with great appreciation for the kind of life
I've led, which has been fascinating. But I tend to live in the
moment and look forward to the future. So I don't sit in an office
surrounded by Los Angeles Times photos and memorabilia and Pulitzer
Prizes. No, I don't.''
 &HT;    Which makes it all the more surprising that Otis Chandler has
emerged, after a self-imposed silence of almost a decade, as
something of a latter-day hero to many newspaper journalists around
the country, a prophet lamenting in the wilderness.
 &HT;    For more than a quarter-century, beginning with his unexpected
rise at age 33 to the position of publisher of The Los Angeles
