<HEADER>
A6634 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-GENOME-ACCESS-NYT     03-14 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-ACCESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND BLAIR URGE ACCESS TO GENOME MAPPING RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calling the effort to decode the human genome ``one of the most
significant scientific projects of all time,'' President Clinton
and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain issued a joint statement
Tuesday saying the genome data ``should be made freely available to
scientists everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders praised the academic researchers who are making
their genome data publicly available and said, ``We commend other
scientists around the world to adopt this policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is a high-visibility endorsement of the policy
pursued by the public consortium of scientists decoding the
sequence of the three billion chemical units that comprise the
human genetic blueprint. The consortium is largely financed by the
U.S. National Institutes of Health and the Wellcome Trust of
London, a large medical charity.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium is competing intensely with its rival, the Celera
Corp. of Rockville, Md. Celera jumped into the race only in May
1998 and has already put itself in a position where it might be
able to claim victory. Both sides seem prepared to publish rival
`draft' sequences of the genome sometime this summer, with more
complete versions coming later.
</P>
<P>
   Celera and its president, Dr. J. Craig Venter, have long been in
competition with the leading scientists of the public consortium,
chiefly Dr. John Sulston of the Sanger Center in Britain and Dr.
Robert Waterston of Washington University in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Sparring between the two sides became so intense that in recent
merger talks between the two sides, now aborted, the public
consortium proposed as an article of agreement that ``The current
antagonism and excessive competition should be replaced with a more
collaborative spirt.''
</P>
<P>
   One matter of principle underlying the rivalry concerns public
access to the human genome data. Sulston and Waterston, together
with their financial backers, feel strongly that the human genome
should be made freely available to all researchers so as to speed
medical progress. They regularly place their new DNA sequences in
public data banks, and have urged Celera to do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative for the joint statement seems to have come from
the Wellcome Trust in London and to be aimed principally at Celera,
the consortium's rival. But Dr. Michael Dexter, director of the
Trust, said his concern was with overbroad patents being granted on
the genome sequence that might obstruct researchers' access.
</P>
<P>
   He said the raw sequence, the string of chemical units making up
the genome, was not patentable and that the Trust ``would fight any
patents based on sequence if they obstruct academic work and
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Venter has always said that Celera would make available a
consensus sequence of the human genome, a position he reiterated in
a statement Tuesday. Celera's business plan depends in part on
patenting new human genes it discovers and also on becoming a
principal holder of genomic information, charging fees for
companies to search and analyze its data base of human and other
genomes.
</P>
<P>
   Two other companies, Human Genome Sciences and Incyte, claim to
have captured much of the value of the human genome already through
a short-cut method that detects human genes.
</P>
<P>
   Only 3 percent of the DNA in the human genome encodes working
genes, the rest being largely useless filler material. Picking the
genes out is no trivial matter and the computer programs designed
to do so still work very inefficiently.
</P>
<P>
   But human cells can recognize the genes, and regularly make
transcripts of the genes whose information is required to make
proteins. These transcripts, known as messenger-RNAs, can be
captured and analyzed. Just a small portion of their sequence is
sufficient to identify the corresponding part of the gene from
which they come. These little snippets of genes, known as expressed
sequence tags or ESTs, are the basis of gene-searching approaches
used by Human Genome Sciences and Incyte.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Haseltine, president of Human Genome Sciences, said
Tuesday that his company had already identified 95 percent of the
human genes by the EST approach and had filed patents on 7,500
medically useful human genes. So far 2,500 of these patents have
been published, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Dexter and Dr. Rachel E. Levinson, a senior official at the
White House Office of Science and Technology Policy, said the joint
statement issued Tuesday acknowledged intellectual property rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
