<HEADER>
A6635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-ARTISANS-BOOK-REVIEW-     03-14 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTISANS-BOOK-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ITALIAN FOOD ARTISANS': FOODS THAT SCORN THE EFFICIENCY EXPERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's partly an attractive guide to Italian ingredients and
partly a collection of thumbnail biographies of the people who
produce them. But most of all, ``Italian Food Artisans'' by Pamela
Sheldon Johns (Chronicle Books, $24.95) provides behind-the-scenes
descriptions with alluring photographs to show how more than a
dozen traditional Italian foods are made.
</P>
<P>
   The author also outlines the qualities that set those foods
apart from their commonplace industrial versions.
</P>
<P>
   She writes, for example, of a fourth-generation company in
central Italy, Rustichella d'Abruzzo, which makes dry pasta with
handcrafted bronze molds, resulting in pasta with a roughened
texture that makes sauce cling invitingly to it. Unlike commercial
pasta, which is usually dried at high temperatures for about 12
hours, this pasta is slowly air-dried for more than four days,
which maintains the flavor of the wheat.
</P>
<P>
   Hand-made details and the time to do things right _ both of
which are costly and avoided by big companies _ are lavished on
many of the products described in the book, including deeply
flavorful cured meats, fine balsamic vinegar, rustic caciocavallo
cheese and fruity estate-bottled extra virgin olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Reading about culatello, a type of prosciutto that is adored by
connoisseurs but is not yet imported into the United States, I
wanted to book a trip to Parma.
</P>
<P>
   In a chapter about fresh truffles, Johns explains not only the
white ones, for which Italy is famous, but also the black variety,
which is gathered in Umbria. She gives advice about using truffles
and how to select truffle oils and pastes.
</P>
<P>
   The author, who works for the Avignonesi winery in Montepulciano
and who conducts culinary tours of Italy, pairs faces with the
foods.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Antonino Caravaglio from Salina, an Aeolian island
off Sicily, gathers and preserves capers in a fresh sea salt. The
capers contribute their salty tang to a lemon-dressed seafood
salad, to a spicy all-purpose red sauce, which takes minutes to
make, and to a luscious peperonata mixture of onions, bell peppers
and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Those are some of the mostly simple, regional recipes the author
gives for each of the foods. There are even restaurant recipes,
like one for the pasta Laura Galli makes at her Osteria Giusti in
Modena.
</P>
<P>
   Wedges of pizza rustica made with an olive oil crust and a
cheese and salami filling were delicious warm from the oven with a
glass of white wine. But an orange-scented olive oil cake was a bit
greasy and heavy, better the day after it was baked and even better
made with only one cup of oil and one cup of milk, instead of a cup
and a half of each.
</P>
<P>
   Johns understands the marketplace and appreciates that consumers
have come to depend on products, like commercial balsamic vinegar,
that are not made in traditional fashion. She gives the appropriate
uses for supermarket balsamic, in cooking and salad dressings, and
offers a tip on how to judge it: avoid brands that list additives.
</P>
<P>
   She also recognizes that there are other foods, including
prosciutto di Parma, that have become somewhat industrialized
without sacrificing high standards.
</P>
<P>
   This useful book also lists salamis and cheeses by region and
has a buying guide to food products in Italy and the United
States. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PIZZA RUSTICA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Italian Food Artisans'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour, plus flour for rolling
</P>
<P>
   } teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1} cups ricotta, preferably buffalo milk
</P>
<P>
   7 ounces fresh mozzarella, preferably buffalo, chopped
</P>
<P>
   \ pound Genoa salami, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat oven to 375 degrees. In large bowl or food processor,
mix flour, sugar and } teaspoon salt. Lightly beat one egg with
wine and oil, add to flour mixture, and blend with a fork or
process until dough forms. If dough is mixed by hand, knead
briefly. Set dough aside to rest 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine ricotta, mozzarella and salami in bowl with remaining
egg. Season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. Divide dough in half. On a lightly floured board, roll half
the dough in a circle to fit 10-inch pie pan, and place in pan.
Trim edge even with pan rim. Spread ricotta mixture in pan,
smoothing surface.
</P>
<P>
   4. Roll the remaining dough into a 5-by-10-inch rectangle. Using
a knife or a serrated pastry wheel, cut {-inch-wide strips of dough
lengthwise. Place the strips on top of filling about { inch apart
in a crisscross pattern, weaving to form a lattice top. Trim the
ends. Fold edge of bottom pastry back over ends of the lattice
strips, pleating it at regular intervals, to make a neat border.
</P>
<P>
   5. Bake about 45 minutes, until golden brown. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
