<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HUNTS-POINT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY'S PREMIER PRODUCE TERMINAL: PEANUTS AND MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT2 and 3 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(editors: optional sidebar at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By MATT LEE and TED LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few years ago, when we were new to this city, we
were desperate for raw peanuts to boil and eat as a snack as we did
growing up in South Carolina. But they seemed as scarce here as
fresh bagels in Beaufort. Fried's, the dried-fruit and nut dealer
next door to our Ludlow Street tenement, had hundreds of pounds of
peanuts _ all roasted. ``Try Hunts Point,'' the counterman advised,
then added, ``Wear your work boots.''
</P>
<P>
   We were dubious _ go shopping at the city's produce terminal? _
but we picked a wholesaler from the Yellow Pages and called anyway.
``Peanuts? Not us,'' he said. ``Try Armata.'' The clerk who
answered at E. Armata Inc. said the first fresh peanuts of the
season had just arrived from South Florida. And he encouraged us to
come up and buy: ``Get a pass at the gate and find us at Building
A. Anytime after 4 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was how we discovered the giant wholesale produce
market in the South Bronx _ the source of the palest endive,
wrapped in tissue; the most tender baby artichokes on their way to
a date with Jean-Georges Vongerichten; and clusters of moist green
peanuts, still perfumed with the rich earth they had left in the
Everglades the night before.
</P>
<P>
   The Hunts Point Terminal Market _ a razor-fenced thunder dome of
musclemen and machinery _ is the way station for the bulk of the
fresh vegetables and fruits offered in the city's restaurants and
greengrocers. But it is not solely the domain of professional
buyers. Although the public is officially discouraged from shopping
there, persistent souls are tolerated if they go prepared, and the
thrill of a bargain is enhanced by the awe of being at a crossroads
of world commerce, like Times Square or the floor of the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Hunts Point generates $1.5 billion in sales a year, according to
Myra Gordon, the executive director. It is the world's largest
wholesale produce market in volume, although its size, 125 acres,
is a fraction of Rungis in Paris or La Merced in Mexico City. And
it is likely to grow: in April, the city is expected to recommend
that the Fulton Fish Market in Manhattan move to a site beside it.
</P>
<P>
   Hunts Point could not be more different from the farm stands
where we bought raw peanuts down South, or even from the Fulton
Market, with its postcard-worthy paving stones and 18th-century
facades.
</P>
<P>
   Hunts Point looks startlingly like a prison, set among the scrap
metal yards and abandoned warehouses. A 14-foot-tall sheet-metal
fence topped by coils of razor wire stretches to the horizon. A
guard stationed at the gate sells day passes for $2. (We shouldn't
have been surprised: Hunts Point has long had a rough reputation,
and in February, seven federal food inspectors pleaded guilty to
taking bribes in a kickback scheme that allowed some wholesalers to
cheat the growers who supplied them.)
</P>
<P>
   Inside the gate, it is a dreary arena of asphalt, boxcars and
tractor-trailers. It is hard to imagine this desolate setting as
the source of the bunch of spinach at the corner greengrocer, the
basil in the marinara at a neighborhood trattoria, the rhubarb in a
four-star tart. And yet each of those items spends quality time in
a refrigerated storeroom at one of the market's 59 wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   On that first visit, navigating among the four huge buildings,
each as long as a freight train, we made our way to Armata, past
forklifts loaded head-high with crates swooping in and out of
curtained doorways, teetering and honking in an endless loop of
narrow misses. Thousand-pound pallets of onions crashed to the
concrete docks as buyers, seemingly oblivious of the clangor,
inspected the produce stacked outside each storeroom. The
cold-weather uniform here is hooded sweatshirts, quilted jackets
and insulated coveralls. Work boots, it turned out, are necessary _
to tread the sludge of pulverized produce and brake fluid
underfoot.
</P>
<P>
   Even before we saw Armata's sign, we spotted an open bushel of
peanuts nestled between a crate of bright-orange Israeli persimmons
and a hundred-pound burlap bag of Idaho potatoes. The salesman was
efficient, neither brusque nor polite. We inquired about a bag. He
nodded, barked a command to an unseen employee, made a stroke of a
pen on a form and passed it to the cashier. We handed over $32
(cash, of course). The salesman was already on to the next buyer, a
Korean grocer, when the dock hand emerged from the storeroom with
our 50-pound bag of peanuts slung over his shoulder. We returned to
the car with an almost illicit glee. We'd cheated both geography
and commerce, and scored a taste of home for less per pound than we
would have spent at a South Carolina farm stand.
</P>
<P>
   We have since found other, admittedly more expensive, sources
for fresh peanuts in Chinatown, but we still shop Hunts Point.
Buying in bulk makes sense when something is prohibitively
expensive or when we're canning and preserving (pickled peaches are
among our favorites in fall) or cooking for a throng (we served
pina coladas in coconuts from a $15 sack of 40 from the Dominican
Republic).
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, we were cooking with sour orange juice. The case
we got for $11.50 at the wholesale market weighed more than 20
pounds. At Dean &AMP; DeLuca, sour oranges are $3 a pound, more than
five times as much.
</P>
<P>
   The market's Internet site
(www.terminalmarkets.com/huntspoint.htm) includes Agriculture
Department reports on the going prices at Hunts Point. We always
check it before setting out, to determine whether it's worth the
trip. This week, for example, the page will tell you that a bushel
bucket of Texas savoy spinach will cost about $11, and 12 six-ounce
containers of California red raspberries are around $18.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   As intrepid as we feel, we're not the only ``civilians''
shopping at Hunts Point. Purveyors told us about cooperatives of
three or four families who alternate trips to the market. And then
there was the brave woman we saw on two recent visits, cruising the
docks on a bicycle with a basket modified to carry a single crate.
</P>
<P>
   The chaos we encountered on our first visit was actually the end
of the working day _ the lull, we learned on subsequent forays. The
market is open for business constantly from midday Sunday until
Friday afternoon; an intricate choreography of delivery and pickup
allows roughly 300,000 pounds of produce to move in and out each
day.
</P>
<P>
   Produce arrives at Hunts Point from all over North America by
truck and is flown in from more than 50 countries like New Zealand,
Chile and the Netherlands. Though it was conceived to serve the New
York area, Hunts Point buyers distribute its produce as far as the
Canadian border, Florida, Chicago and Barbados.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday mornings, before the market opens, refrigerated
tractor-trailers pull into the compound from places as far off as
Nogales, Ariz. (a transfer point for Mexican produce), and as near
as Kennedy Airport, delivering loads of Sonoran cucumbers and
blueberries just landed from Argentina. Those trucks depart by 6
p.m. to make way for boxcars full of durable vegetables like
onions, carrots, potatoes and broccoli _ what the trade calls
hardware. Around 10 p.m., the trucks of buyers for restaurants,
schools, hotels and other commercial enterprises swarm in and keep
the market bustling well beyond 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the market's director, said 1,500 to 1,800 independent
greengrocers shop at the market. But there are few chefs wandering
the docks. Nearly all restaurants pay purveyors to prowl the market
and deliver the goods to the backdoor. (Supermarket chains like A&AMP;P
and Key Food are supplied by their own warehouses.)
</P>
<P>
   The New York produce market dates from the 17th century, when
pushcarts in Lower Manhattan sold vegetables, meats, eggs and milk
from local farms. In 1812, the city centralized the market at
Washington, Fulton and Vesey Streets to ease the congestion on
downtown streets. Washington Market expanded through the early 20th
century, taking on more and more vendors, until the city
established the current market in 1967, exclusively for fruits and
vegetables, on a marshy site near the confluence of the Bronx and
East Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Several wholesalers at Hunts Point, like Rosenthal &AMP; Klein and
D'Arrigo Brothers, trace their roots to the Washington Market era,
when vendors specialized in a particular category of produce _
citrus, say, or leafy greens.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew and Stephen D'Arrigo, the patriarchs and founders of
D'Arrigo Brothers, emigrated from Messina, Italy, and in 1923 began
their empire by persuading farmers in California to cultivate the
broccoli, rape, fennel and cactus pears that they and other
Italian-Americans missed from the old country. The company now
carries a wide range of produce, from raspberries to purple
potatoes, but it is still known as a big mover of broccoli and
fennel.
</P>
<P>
   While the produce on display may appear remarkably similar from
vendor to vendor, there is enormous variability beneath the skin.
``The display doesn't mean a thing,'' cautions Joe Holtz, the
general manager of the Park Slope Food Co-op.
</P>
<P>
   He advises a ``taste first, buy later'' approach. And we noticed
that experienced buyers _ the ones who have rapport, and an
account, with a wholesaler _ will breeze past the displays to the
storerooms, clambering atop pallets of peppers to do spot tastings.
Occasional buyers, like us, would be hustled out of any storeroom
they dared to enter uninvited. In the wholesale world, customer
service is a courtesy, not an entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   We learned that quickly enough on that first trip. It took both
of us to wrestle that enormous yellow sack of peanuts across the
bustling dock and into the back seat of our car. The sun was just
rising over Queens as we crossed the Third Avenue bridge back into
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Outside our apartment building, we hoisted the 50-pound trophy
up onto the hood of our car and posed for a celebratory snapshot.
Minutes later, the peanuts were boiling and our tiny tenement was
filling with the beany, briny aroma of a South Carolina kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   After a morning of chaos and discovery, we had come home.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IF YOU GO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MATT LEE and TED LEE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even for shoppers hardened to the pre-Thanksgiving
rush at Fairway, the frenzied docks at Hunts Point present a
challenge. Here's how to navigate a trip:
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   The Hunts Point Terminal Market, also called the New York City
Terminal Market, occupies 125 acres off Halleck Street in the South
Bronx. It's open from 10 p.m. Sunday until 5 p.m. Friday. The best
time to visit is 6 to 11 a.m., after most commercial brokers have
made their purchases and activity has calmed down.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are determined to take public transit can catch the
No. 6 train to the Hunts Point Avenue stop, and transfer to the Bx6
bus for a short ride to a stop near the pedestrian entrance. But
since you must buy by the case, a vehicle of some sort is almost a
necessity. (And don't plan to fill shopping bags.)
</P>
<P>
   By car, follow the signs for Exit 1, Hunts Point Market, off the
Major Deegan Expressway. Drive beneath the Bruckner Expressway on
Bruckner Boulevard, following the signs to the market.
</P>
<P>
   Those without a market ID card must buy a $2 day pass and pay $1
to park a car. Parking spaces are always scarce. The most likely
area to find a spot is at the southern end, opposite the entrance,
in the lot outside Mike's Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the Trip
</P>
<P>
   You will have to tell the tollbooth guard the name of a
wholesaler you plan to visit; wholesalers are listed, with phone
numbers and locations, on a map of the market at
www.terminalmarkets.com/huntspoint.htm. You can print out the map
to take along. Vendors also offer online information like the
produce in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The proper attire is the same as for gardening or tuning up a
car. And you should have some smaller bills so you can pay exact
prices.
</P>
<P>
   At the Market
</P>
<P>
   Hunts Point comprises four buildings, each about three crosstown
blocks long, with a loading dock running the length of each
building. Along the dock, the wholesalers are virtually
indistinguishable from one another, marked only by a name on a
shingle _ another reason to take the map.
</P>
<P>
   Mike's Restaurant, really a diner, and Chosen Variety, the
adjoining store, are the closest things to amenities. Mike's serves
decent, hearty, short-order grill food. Chosen Variety sells
foul-weather gear, Hunts Point T-shirts, Statue of Liberty key
chains and _ if you just can't wait to cut into your freshly bought
Anjou pears _ jackknives.
</P>
</TEXT>
