<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONALD'S-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGALITE, FRATERNITE ET BURGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Denis Hennequin heads McDonald's France, whose 791 ``McDo''
restaurants have come under attack as an erosion of French culinary
tradition and a threat to French agriculture.) 
(DW) 
 By DENIS HENNEQUIN with VIVIENNE WALT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My grandmother was shocked when I went to work for McDonald's.
She thought I was cooking fries on Boulevard St.-Michel. It was
1984. McDonald's had 17 restaurants in France. Its headquarters was
in an apartment. But I thought if I wanted to get ahead, I should
join an American company. It would take me forever to run a French
company: I'd have to know all the right people.
</P>
<P>
   I was 39 when I became McDonald's president two years ago _
very, very unusual for France. When I was invited to the World Cup,
I sat in the box with French executives. I think they thought I was
there to serve the drinks. Then one asked: ``Is your chauffeur
waiting for you outside?'' I said: ``No, I have my subway ticket in
my pocket.'' He couldn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up in the Latin Quarter, the best place to be. I feel
like a refugee living on the Right Bank. I was 10 in 1968, during
the student revolt in Paris. I stood for hours on the balcony with
my ski goggles and a handkerchief to protect myself from the tear
gas, watching the students fight the police.
</P>
<P>
   You have to be a rebel sometime in your life. I think the young
French today aren't rebels. They are too worried about getting a
job.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, in my last year of high school, my friends and I
started this little magazine called Asbury Sound, after
Springsteen, of course. We typed all the articles and Xeroxed a few
copies at a shop. Then we got invited on a television show to talk
about our magazine, and we had so many requests for subscriptions
we couldn't handle it. So we just shut the whole thing down!
</P>
<P>
   Later, in 1981, I had a weekly radio show talking about jazz.
Thank God I didn't keep the tapes; it wasn't very good.
</P>
<P>
   From the age of 16, I had jobs. One summer, I worked for a
bookstore, and the manager said, ``If you have nothing to do, look
busy.'' So for hours we'd take all the books off the shelves and
put them all back again.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a real Paris boy. I couldn't live without the action of the
city. The greatest activity in the world is to sit outside a cafe
and watch the world go by. But every now and then, I just have to
get out. So we drive six hours west to this island off Brittany,
called Behat, where there are no cars.
</P>
<P>
   We have three children, a boy and two girls, and the cat,
Josephine. Not after Napoleon's Josephine, not at all! It's after a
French rock song. On Sundays I go Rollerblading with the kids.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing I miss in my job is doing something physical,
manual. So I fix the house. Actually, I am pretty bad at it.
</P>
<P>
   The protests against McDonald's? I really felt like a scapegoat.
The worst moment was when they tore down the restaurant. I ask:
What have the French been eating for three centuries? Steak frites!
Meat and potatoes, like McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   You know why McDonald's is such a success here? Try taking your
kids to a French cafe. There's cigarette smoke, and alcohol. And
there's nothing kids hate more than sitting for hours over a meal.
Adults always tell me: ``I go to McDonald's but only with the
grandchildren.'' But it's not true. Secretly, they go.
</P>
<P>
   I tell my employees: if you're bored, change jobs. The day I get
bored with this, I'll leave. You know, maybe I'll start a rock
label or something.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
