<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COTTON-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COTTON MARY': ACHING TO BE LADY OF THE HOUSE IN TWO CULTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Cotton Mary'' features the Merchant Ivory team's infamous
undercurrent of understated emotion, feelings so modestly rendered
that sometimes one is unsure if there is any emotion. It was
directed by Ismail Merchant, who is generally the producing half of
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Set in India in 1954, the story begins with a pair of nurses
strolling. Mary (Madhur Jaffrey) is talking with her young friend
Rosie (Sakina Jaffrey) about her dream. (The actors are mother and
daughter in real life.) Mary, a dark-skinned Indian with an English
father and an Indian mother, is foolishly proud of her European
heritage. She tells Rosie that she dreamed she had a white baby.
The trouble, such as it is, begins with that subconscious need to
fit in. But from the confident roll of Rosie's hips it's easy to
tell there are probably lots of different kinds of trouble to come
in this forlorn melodrama, which is low on drama and high on
mellow.
</P>
<P>
   Mary helps a hugely pregnant British woman, Lily MacIntosh
(Greta Scacchi), deliver her child. After the birth Lily is unable
to nurse her baby and Mary sneaks the infant to her handicapped
sister, Blossom (Neena Gupta), a wet nurse who feeds it. Mary takes
credit for the child care and insinuates her way into the MacIntosh
household. There she slowly takes over Lily's home, forcing out the
beloved family butler, Abraham (Prayag Raaj), and playing on the
new mother's guilt over being unable to nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cotton Mary'' has more obvious symbolism than a high school
musical production of ``Lord of the Flies.'' (The title refers to
Mary's nickname, which came about because of her preference for
British cotton over Indian cotton.) Poor Lily's inability to
produce milk for her child is so blatant a metaphor for England's
dying maternalism that it's no wonder the bags under Scacchi's eyes
seem to hang down to her waist; she is shouldering a great deal of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Muted and mindful, the film is a high-tea version of ``Imitation
of Life,'' in which the woman who desperately wants to pass is
driven mad by her desire to be a grand white lady. In this case,
however, Mary seems to be going goofy because she has access to a
broad-brimmed straw hat; she takes to dressing as the lady of the
house.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffrey's performance as Mary gets wilder and wilder, as though
she were trying to compensate for the film's air of mild gloom,
which never erupts into the surge of near-camp that is a tradition
of melodrama. We have to settle for scenes in which Lily's
patronizing club friends cluck and shake their heads over Mary's
presumptuousness: cliches that at least tell us where we are.
</P>
<P>
   Evenhandedness often hangs over Merchant Ivory productions like
a late spring thunderstorm, where at least one gets to revel in the
humidity. In ``Heat and Dust'' (1982) the young and paralyzingly
vivid Scacchi provided that dampness, a voluptuous overspill that
heightened the proceedings. There are elements of bigger drama in
``Cotton Mary,'' like the lustful entrances of Lily's husband, John
(James Wilby), a swaggering journalist who looks so hungry you're
almost afraid he is going to turn and wink at the camera. John gets
to show some vitality, and Rosie's saucy walk is a bright green
light to him.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctimonious without being contemptuous, ``Cotton Mary'' is
almost maddeningly indifferent: Tennessee Williams without the
gleeful insanity. It is so unfocused that it is one of those rare
films that cries out for a narrator _ maybe Lily's daughter (Laura
Lumley), who's the clearest-eyed _ to clarify things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cotton Mary'' is terminally marred by good taste; and
melodrama is like the Star-Kist commercial: people don't want tuna
with good taste; they want tuna that tastes good.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `COTTON MARY'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ismail Merchant; written by Alexandra Viets;
director of photography, Pierre Lhomme; edited by John David Allen;
music by Richard Robbins; production designer, Alison Riva;
produced by Nayeem Hafizka and Richard Hawley; released by Merchant
Ivory Productions and Universal Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 125 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Greta Scacchi (Lily MacIntosh), Madhur Jaffrey (Cotton
Mary), James Wilby (John MacIntosh), Sakina Jaffrey (Rosie), Neena
Gupta (Blossom), Prayag Raaj (Abraham) and Laura Lumley (Theresa).
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
