<HEADLINE>
&HT;     2000 CENSUS MOVES INTO HIGH GEAR WITH MASS MAILING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The largest mass mailing in the nation's history is
underway.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next week, the U.S. Postal Service will delivery almost
100 million Census 2000 questionnaires to households across the
country, Census Bureau Director Kenneth Prewitt announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At stake in the census is the allocation of billions of dollars
in federal and state aid, as well as representation in Congress and
state and local governments. In addition, countless private
organizations base decisions on census data.
</P>
<P>
   ``The census is now in the hands of the American people,''
Prewitt told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials want people to send back the questionnaires as
soon as they receive them. Reminder postcards will be sent to all
homes in a few weeks, and census workers will visit those who don't
return forms through the spring and early summer. ``We want to make
sure everybody is recognized,'' Prewitt said. ``Returning your
census form is one of the most important civic duties you'll do
over the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The director said only 2 percent of the census forms have been
returned, but that he expected between 50 and 60 million to arrive
at the Census Bureau within the next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a busy time around here,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said the bureau is hoping it can slow a decades-old
decline in the proportion of people who take the time to fill out
their census forms and mail them back. In 1990, 65 percent of
American households that received the form completed and returned
it, down from the 78 percent that did so in 1970. This year, the
bureau is planning on a 61 percent return rate. In particular, he
said, the bureau will attempt to encourage groups that are
historically undercounted to participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a problem that has vexed the Census Bureau for the
last 50 years,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 count _ which the Census Bureau says undercounted the
American population by more than 4 million _ was the first judged
to be less accurate than the preceding tally.Prewitt said census
officials have expressed concern over the accuracy of this year's
count since many of the factors that made the population hard to
count last time around have only gotten worse. The population is
larger, more mobile and more diverse than ever. Public apathy and
concerns over privacy also jeopardize the census tally. Prewitt
said that about half a million census takers will be dispatched to
interview the roughly 40 percent of households that do not return
the forms. Census statisticians will then tabulate the results for
months. The operation _ the largest peacetime mobilization effort
in U.S. history _ will send census takers to impoverished villages
on the Mexican border, to islands off Maine and to shanties erected
by homeless people in the nation's large cities. The importance of
counting everyone, Prewitt said, stems from the fact the census is
used to fix the number of House seats for each state, and that
states use the number to draw legislative districts. In addition,
billions of dollars in federal aid will be distributed on the basis
of how the population is counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't fill out the form, you lose out on money and
representation,'' he said, adding that an equitable distribution of
resources has been difficult because minorities, children and the
urban poor are missed at disproportionate levels in the census.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage these people to send in their forms, the Census
Bureau has spent more than $80 million on an advertising campaign _
the largest ever for a census _ aimed at members of minority
groups, people who rent and those living in mobile homes who tend
not to return their census forms. The bureau will spend another $20
million over the next six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of Young &AMP; Rubicam, the New York City advertising
firm that is handling the campaign, estimates that many
African-Americans will see the census commercials as many as 120
times, and that some Hispanics could see them as many 105 times by
the end of April. The bureau is also working with local governments
and community groups in an effort to convince people to return the
forms. This years' census is by far the most expensive in the
nation's history, even taking inflation into account. So far, the
cost of the 2000 census is estimated at $6.8 billion, a huge
increase over the $2.6 billion spent in 1990.The Census Bureau
cites higher marketing costs and over-all inflation for the steeply
higher costs this year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
