u e BC-ROYAL-BALLET-625&AMP;ADD-     03-14 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYAL-BALLET-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIAN WILL LEAD ROYAL BALLET 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Ross Stretton, director of the Australian Ballet, has
been chosen to become director of the Royal Ballet next year, it
was announced Tuesday. He will be the first non-Briton to hold the
post.
</P>
<P>
   Stretton, a 48-year-old Australian, will succeed Sir Anthony
Dowell, 57. Dowell said in June that he would step down in August
2001, after the company completes its first two seasons in the
richly reconstructed Royal Opera House in Covent Garden. The opera
house reopened in December after a three-year $360 million rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   Dowell took over as director in 1986, assuming the post first
held by Dame Ninette de Valois after she founded the company in
1931 and subsequently by such major figures in British dance as Sir
Frederick Ashton and Sir Kenneth MacMillan.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has been a principal dancer and artistic
administrator with companies in Melbourne and New York _ he was a
star at the American Ballet Theater for years _ Stretton comes to
the job a virtual unknown in London, with little of the
identification with the British dance traditions that his
predecessors created and that the Royal Ballet has long enshrined.
</P>
<P>
   Currently on national tour in Australia, Stretton is not due in
London until next week, but the Royal Ballet released a statement
of his aims Tuesday in which he promised to ``reinvigorate the
classical heritage and to develop the art form further.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been credited with reviving the fortunes of the
Australian Ballet since he became its artistic leader three years
ago by tidying up the company's style and cleaning up its classical
look. On the company's visit to New York last October, Anna
Kisselgoff, chief dance critic of The New York Times, called the
Australian Ballet ``virtually a company reborn,'' saying that
Stretton's leadership had produced ``terrific dancing, creativity
and a new ensemble spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   She found in his Australian dancers ``a greater classical
purity, especially impressive in the perfect body placement that
recalls his own noble style as a dancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Stretton's arrival in London will reunite him with Michael
Kaiser, an American who is the executive director of the Royal
Opera House and who held the same post at Ballet Theater, where
Stretton was assistant director to the artistic director, Kevin
McKenzie. McKenzie had been widely seen as a front-runner for the
job here but decided to remain in his current post in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the months after Dowell's announcement, speculation brought
forth the names of Mikhail Baryshnikov and Twyla Tharp, the Royal
Ballet stars Sylvie Guillem and Irek Mukhamedov and a longtime
Royal Ballet choreographer, Ashley Page. The two leading British
candidates were said to be David Bintley, whom press reports quoted
as saying that he preferred keeping his current job in England as
head of the Birmingham Royal Ballet, and Ross MacGibbon, a former
principal dancer at Covent Garden who is a television director and
producer and a member of the Royal Opera House board.
</P>
<P>
   Stretton was born in Canberra and trained at the Australian
Ballet School. He became a principal artist with the Australian
Ballet before moving to New York in 1979 to join the Joffrey.
Baryshnikov invited him to dance as a guest artist with Ballet
Theater during the 1980-81 season and then asked him to become a
permanent member.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dancing with Ballet Theater, he toured with
``Baryshnikov and Company.'' and performed as a guest artist with
many companies in the United States and abroad. He moved into dance
administration at Ballet Theater in 1990, becoming assistant
director in 1993. He went to Melbourne to take up his current post
in January 1997.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Royal Ballet has major crowd pleasers in dancers like Darcey
Bussell, Sarah Wildor, Deborah Bull, Adam Cooper, Guillem and
Carlos Acosta, a Cuban who joined last year. It ranks high on the
list of the world's top companies, which also includes the New York
City Ballet, Ballet Theater, the Paris Opera Ballet, the Kirov and
the Bolshoi.
</P>
<P>
   If there is an extra bounce in the British company's step these
days, it comes from relief that three years of having no permanent
home are over and that the new version of the house they have
performed in since 1946 is so much more accommodating to dance than
it was.
</P>
<P>
   In the reconstruction, the orchestra seating area was raked in
an effort to provide better sightlines for ballet viewers. The
company's 85 dancers will no longer have to rehearse and train in
three dimly lit rooms across town in West London: the new complex
includes five bright rehearsal studios, vastly improved backstage
conditions and physiotherapy and body conditioning suites.
</P>
<P>
   The house has reopened with programming that appears to go out
of its way to honor its past directors. Its production of Coppelia
is the one done by Ninette de Valois in 1954; it was last staged
here in 1970. And there are two three-ballet productions, ``The
MacMillan Inheritance'' and ``Ashton Revisited.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ashton trio includes the legendary ``Marguerite and
Armand,'' which opens Wednesday night with Sylvie Guillem and the
Paris Opera Ballet's Nicholas Le Riche in the roles created in 1963
as vehicles for Margot Fonteyn and Rudolf Nureyev and never danced
by anyone else since.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
