<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WILLIE-NELSON-NYTR &LR;      03-14 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIE-NELSON-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE WILLIE: NOBODY TELLS MUSIC LEGEND WILLIE NELSON WHAT TO DO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
(Attn: Tenn., Texas)  By BILL DeYOUNG   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since 1971, when he said goodbye to Nashville forever and went
home to his native Texas, Willie Nelson has had things pretty much
his way.
</P>
<P>
   He'd worn a suit and slicked-back hair for a decade, making
cookie-cutter country records that never hit. He hated it all _
suit, haircut and records _ so when he started working again, he
made it a point to look different and sound different. If Nashville
didn't like his attitude adjustment, well, there was always club
work around Austin, where the hippies loved him and believed him a
kindred spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The rest, of course, is history. Nelson was right, Nashville was
wrong. Today he is considered one of country's all-time greats. He
has recorded Western Swing, blues, jazz, reggae, salsa and
standards as well as quote-unquote traditional country music. He is
a revered songwriter, a movie star and a spokesman for farmers'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all Nelson has played 200 one-nighters every year
with virtually the same band. They may not be the same musicians on
all his records _ Nelson has collaborated with everyone from Frank
Sinatra to Carlos Santana _ but they're always behind him on stage.
It's called Willie Nelson and Family because that's what they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telepathy's a good word for it,'' Nelson, 66, says in a
telephone interview. ``We've played together so long that these
guys just kind of read my mind. They know what I'm gonna do _
whenever I hit the first note, they know what to do. I never have
to turn around and say we're gonna do this or that.''
</P>
<P>
   Guitarist Jody Payne and bassist Bee Spears joined the band 30
years ago, around the time Willie started reading Eastern
philosophy and let his red hair and beard grow out.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbie Nelson, Willie's younger sister, plays piano in the band,
in an old-time church style.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gospel piano,'' Nelson explains. ``It's home, it's where
I grew up. It's what I did growing up _ her and I played music
together all the time, in church, at home and school. And so I
really love the way she plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's drummer, Paul English, has been by his side since 1965,
when he filled in for a missing drummer on a radio show in Fort
Worth. English was the inspiration for one of Nelson's best
post-Nashville songs. ``Me and Paul,'' he says, is a true story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really got drunk in Buffalo, N.Y., at a show,'' Nelson
says. ``They had us closing it behind Charley Pride, and it was a
long show. I think Paul went out and got a No Parking sign and set
it up behind Kitty Wells on her show. It was one of those nights.''
Their carousing days are more or less behind them now.
</P>
<P>
   English's son Billy is the Family's percussionist. Just added is
Texas jazz guitar legend Jackie King, who made a duet album with
Nelson, ``Angel Eyes,'' nearly 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The band is as adept at the tricky time signatures of
``Stardust'' as it is with the tub-thumping ``Whiskey River.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's gotten better and better and better,'' Nelson
says of his band. ``We've always had real good musicians, but
there's been times when I thought the sound was a little too
cluttered, or a little this, a little that. But I think now it's
sounding as good, or better, than it ever sounded.''
</P>
<P>
   The Family backed Nelson on ``Night and Day,'' the
all-instrumental album he released last year. It was nominated for
a Grammy, as was Nelson's collaboration with Asleep at the Wheel
and Manhattan Transfer on the song ``Going Away Party.'' Neither
won, but Nelson himself was given a Lifetime Achievement Grammy.
</P>
<P>
   He is a member of the Country Music Hall of Fame and was one of
the recipients of the 1999 Kennedy Center Honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creative control'' has been an important phrase in every
record contract he's signed since he left Nashville. He doesn't
make concessions to garner radio play; they don't play him any
more, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   So he records what he wants. In the last six years, he's put out
an acoustic album (``Spirit''), an album with lush string
arrangements of popular songs (``Healing Hands of Time''), a Texas
dance-band album (``Just One Love''), a quirky, rhythmic effort
with Daniel Lanois and Emmylou Harris (``Teatro'') and the
instrumental set.
</P>
<P>
   Out in June, he says, will be ``Milk Cow Blues,'' a blues
recording featuring B.B. King, Keb Mo, Kenny Wayne Shepard and
others. He's halfway through another jazz album with his old buddy,
guitarist Paul Buskirk.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there are movies to make (he was last seen in
``Wag the Dog'') and endless rounds of golf to be played, which
after music, is his purest passion.
</P>
<P>
   The only person Nelson has to answer to is Annie, his fourth
wife, who takes care of things back at the Texas ranch. They have
two sons, ages 10 and 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been together over 10 years now, and it seems to be
working out OK,'' Nelson shrugs. ``But it takes a really special
kind of thinking, and a special kind of person, to live with
somebody like me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bill DeYoung writes for The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun. The
Gainesville Sun is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
