<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY _ Voters are heading to the polls in six Southern states
to vote in presidential primaries today. The total available
delegates in the contests puts both Al Gore and George W. Bush in
position to win enough delegates to clench their party nominations.
(Herman/Austin American-Statesman), Crowley, Palm Beach Post). 30
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS _ A look at the U.S. Senate races and which of the
little known Democratic challengers gets to take on Kay Bailey
Hutchison. (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BALD-PRESIDENT _ On March 1, George W. Bush was cornered. David
Letterman was razzing him about international politics.
Specifically, about how the Republican presidential candidate
didn't know the leaders of some foreign countries. The punch line?
He asked Bush if he knew the name of the president of the Hair Club
for Men. Bush's response: ``You're not talking about ... Sy
Sperling, are you?'' While the audience laughed in New York,
Sperling almost fell off his treadmill in his Hillsboro Beach home.
``I flipped out. I couldn't believe it,'' Sperling says. ``I mean,
I know people know who I am, but this was
</P>
<P>
   amazing. I guess advertising works!'' But Sperling started
thinking about Bush's response. He started thinking about hair not
an uncommon thing to do, in his business. He made a connection, and
got the word out to The Media. ``There just may be a direct link
between having hair and becoming president,'' says an urgently
faxed press release from Hair Club for Men. ``It's a formula: The
candidate with most hair wins.... It's been documented that since
the dawn of the television age, every elected president since
Kennedy, and including Kennedy, has had hair.'' (Hutchins, Palm
Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BROADBAND _ FAIRFAX, Va. _ The federal government may deregulate
high-speed Internet service by the end of the year, two leaders of
the House Internet Caucus predicted Tuesday. Reps. Rick Boucher,
D-Va., and Bob Goodlatte, R-Va., told the Global Internet
Conference that lifting restrictions on the Baby Bellsphone
companies could accelerate the spread of broadband access
nationwide. (Glass, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   VETERANS _ WASHINGTON _ While support builds in Congress for a
bill that would restore to the country's oldest veterans a disputed
``promise'' of free medical care for life, the veterans have laid
their case before the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington, arguing
that a district judge was wrong when he ruled that the promise was
not a binding ``contract.'' (Nesmith, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-GHOST TOWN _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ In past years ``north of
the river'' meant mobile homes and public housing. After the
flooding from Hurricane Floyd, those neighborhoods in Greenville
have ceased to exist. Some neighborhoods here have been offered up
to a federal buyout program, meaning they can't be used for
building new homes. What will ``north of the river'' mean in years
to come? (Batchelor, Greenville Daily Reflector). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: First of six installments looking at Eastern North
Carolina's recovery from Hurricane Floyd on the six-month
anniversary of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BHUTTO _ Interview with former Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto, who is visiting at Agnes Scott College. (Graham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
