<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6656 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-ROBB-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      03-14 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBB-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SHOULDN'T ATTEMPT TO PLAY MCCAIN'S GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT ROBB  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Conventional wisdom has it that George W. Bush now
needs to make peace with John McCain to bring him on board.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that there are far more dangers to Bush from
caving in to McCain on campaign finance reform than there are
benefits from adding what will be, in the best of circumstances, a
highly unenthusiastic supporter.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear what McCain is up to. He suspended his campaign; he
did not end it. He wished George W. Bush well; he did not say he
will support Bush for president.
</P>
<P>
   McCain himself probably does not know what he wants at this
point. It is not inconceivable that he will try to play Jesse
Jackson to Bush's Michael Dukakis: carry his fight to the
convention despite being clearly defeated, negotiating for platform
language and a role at the convention. This seriously hurt Dukakis
in 1988, and could hurt Bush this year.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why, whatever game McCain ultimately chooses, Bush
should refuse to play.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits talk about the ``McCain voters.'' But in the
conventional sense of such a phrase, voters loyal to the political
leadership of a particular person, there are very few ``McCain
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been a truly national political figure for only a
little over a month, propelled to that status by his stunning
victory in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did attract a lot of voters, particularly Democrats and
Independents. Undoubtedly some of this was due to his compelling
personal history and service to his country. And it was driven by a
couple of issues: restoring honor and integrity to the presidency;
and redressing a sense of disassociation with the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Although these voters were stimulated to vote for McCain, he is
not in a position to broker their support in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   They will make their own decisions, and George W. Bush can
appeal to them directly. He does not need John McCain to serve as
an intermediary.
</P>
<P>
   The American people are still making up their minds about George
W. Bush. And one of the questions they have is whether he is really
up to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the doubt about Bush is whether he has truly thought
through the issues, and whether he has, not even the courage of his
convictions, but merely the conviction of his convictions.
</P>
<P>
   During the presidential primaries, Bush sharply disagreed with
McCain about campaign finance reform. He said McCain's proposals
violated First Amendment rights and put the Republican Party at a
tactical disadvantage by leaving unions free to spend dues money on
campaigns without the express approval of their members.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush to now abandon those principles in a transparent deal
for McCain's support would simply reinforce the doubts the American
people have about him, and hurt him far more than McCain's
undoubtedly tepid support would help.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Bush should abandon the voters who found
McCain attractive. He has his own case to make about restoring
honor and integrity to the presidency, particularly running against
``No Controlling Authority'' Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush has his own case to make on redressing the sense of
disassociation with the federal government, although it is a more
complex argument than McCain's since it involves changing policies
rather than the election process.
</P>
<P>
   With respect to McCain, Bush should make it clear that while he
welcomes McCain's support, there are fundamental differences on
campaign finance reform that exist, and will continue to exist. He
should point out that McCain now faces the same choice as every
other American, whether Bush or Al Gore is better to lead the
country for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush should not bargain with McCain over a prominent,
prime-time speaking slot at the convention. Bush should simply give
it to McCain, saying that McCain has earned it with his success
during the primaries. Bush should also say that he fully expects
McCain to use his time to advocate campaign reform proposals with
which he disagrees, but the Republican Party is big enough to
harbor and air such disagreements.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's best hope to become president is to chart his own course.
And let John McCain decide for himself the extent to which he wants
to play the spoiler. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
