   JESSE JAMES-EXHUMATION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRANBURY, Texas _ For many here, there's no doubt that the famed
outlaw Jesse James is buried in Granbury Cemetery. Even if history
books say he died at the hands of Bob Ford on April 3, 1882, in St.
Joseph, Mo., they see the exhumation _ and DNA testing _ as
clinching proof that the accounts from their childhood are true. By
BILL HANNA. Story has moved in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS AT LARGE-CHAPMAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ There is a new historical marker in East Texas today.
It honors a Tennessee man who was arrested by the Spanish as a spy,
worked for the Mexican government, was a Texas sympathizer, and had
wives on both sides of the border. ``Anything going on that was
exciting, Ellis Bean took part in,'' said Bernard Mayfield of the
Cherokee County Historical Commission in Jacksonville. ``He wasn't
a leading historical figure in Texas history, but he was a colorful
one.'' By ART CHAPMAN. Story has moved in ``a'' general news
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
