<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUND BITE DOESN'T TELL THE TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Remember Sen. John McCain's testy dismissal of MSNBC
reporter Maria Shriver (``Please get out of here!'') when she asked
him how he felt on his way to concede Super Tuesday to George W.
Bush? An affirmation of the senator's gnarly, snarly temperament,
you thought? Well, context is everything.
</P>
<P>
   According to media analyst Seth Mnookin, Shriver and her camera
crew that night ignored repeated requests by McCain's staff to
vacate the stairwell. Then, when the McCain family appeared,
Shriver burst past his staff, and her camera crew knocked over
McCain's 8-year-old daughter, visibly upsetting Cindy McCain.
</P>
<P>
   It was then Shriver asked her insipid ``Senator McCain, how are
you feeling tonight?'' question.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Mnookin's investigation of the incident is accurate,
MSNBC and Shriver should be ashamed for having run that nasty
little snippet of film time and again without ever once revealing
the boorishness that precipitated it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1802EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6664 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER15-COX     03-14 2233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: A Southern-flavored `Super Tuesday'
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore and George W. Bush could wrap up the Democratic and
Republican nominations Tuesday in contests in six Southern states.
Voters were going to the polls in Gore's home state of Tennessee
and Bush's home state of Texas, as well as Florida, Mississippi,
Louisiana and Oklahoma. The six states were awarding 341 Republican
and 566 Democratic delegates Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   NOT NOW, BUT IN NOVEMBER
</P>
<P>
   Presidential preference voting in the South on Tuesday may be
anticlimactic, but presidential politics this year will still have
a drawl. The South exerted its influence on the nominations long
before the votes were cast. Each party will nominate a Southerner:
Democrat Al Gore of Tennessee and Republican George W. Bush of
Texas. Come November, though, the changing and increasingly
unpredictable region could be the decider on which one wins.
</P>
<P>
   NOT-SO-SOLID SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been gaining strength in the once solidly
Democratic South in the last two decades. But Democrats slowed
their progress in 1998 by winning governors races in Alabama and
South Carolina and retaining the Georgia governorship. Exit polls
suggest a big turnout of black voters combined with strong support
from independents and some crossover Republicans were key to
Democratic wins in 1998. Arkansan Bill Clinton was able to carve
away four of 11 Southern states: Arkansas, Tennessee and Louisiana
in both 1992 and 1996, plus Georgia in 1992 and Florida in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   THIS POLL PUTS BUSH ON TOP
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush holds a 49 percent to 43 percent edge over Al
Gore in the latest USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll. Other recent polls
have shown similarly close results, with Bush slightly ahead of
Gore and Gore slightly ahead of Bush in two polls released over the
weekend. The poll (taken Friday through Sunday, with a 5 percentage
point margin of error) found Bush picking up more of the McCain
supporters: McCain Republicans, 80 percent to 14 percent for Bush;
McCain independents, 46 percent to 37 percent for Bush; McCain
Democrats, 76 percent to 13 percent for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   BALLOT NOT SECRET WITH THESE GUYS
</P>
<P>
   After voting for himself in Carthage, Tenn., Al Gore was heading
later Tuesday to Tallahassee, Fla., George W. Bush, the Texas
governor, was tending to state business after voting for himself
last week by absentee ballot. He'll view the returns tonight from a
community center in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   HIS SON'S GOT HIS HEART
</P>
<P>
   Ex-President George Bush voted for his son, George W. Bush, on
Tuesday to follow in his footsteps. After casting ballots alongside
his wife, Barbara, in Houston, the elder Bush said his emotions
were hard to describe. ``It gets down to family and how lucky we
are,'' said the father, who insisted his recent bout of irregular
heartbeat wasn't related to the stress of his son's presidential
bid. ``Oh yeah,'' replied Mrs. Bush skeptically.
</P>
<P>
   CORPORATE BUCKS SWINGING BACK TO DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats are holding a fund-raising dinner tonight in
Washington and, the Wall Street Journal says, they're set to rake
in $7 million, more than double the take for the same event a year
ago. The change is because corporate donors who not long ago were
funneling most of their contributions to the Republicans, have now
split their giving. Representatives from AFLAC, BellSouth, General
Dynamics and AT&AMP;T all played prominent roles, according to the
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   FRIENDLY TAKEOVER
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party Chairman Jim Nicholson ``has begun turning the
party organization over'' to George W. Bush, The Denver Post
reported. Nicholson said he began discussing the transition with
Bush last Friday, but that details of the changes, including
Nicholson's role in the fall campaign, have yet to be determined.
ABC reported that Bush people also are expected to infiltrate the
RNC at lower levels _ something that will establish a presence at
the headquarters while reducing campaign overhead.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA ON GORE'S RADAR SCREEN
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, most polls showed Al Gore had no hope of beating
George W. Bush in Florida. Not only was Gore unpopular, but Bush
had an ace in the hole _ his brother, Jeb, Florida's popular
governor.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Gore is even with, if not leading, Bush in many
national polls, and Jeb Bush is running into local political
squalls, and Gore is suddenly thinking that Florida may be in play
in November. Monday marked Gore's seventh visit to Florida in the
last 12 months, and he was going back again Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   WIFELY INFLUENCE AND FUND-RAISING
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton was pondering whether to stop in
Pakistan during his upcoming visit to South Asia, a group of
Pakistani-Americans in New York with a keen interest in the
decision raised $50,000 for his wife's Senate campaign. There was
nothing illegal about the Feb. 22 fund-raiser, a $1,000-a-plate
dinner on Staten Island: All the donors were U.S. citizens, the
organizers said. And no evidence has emerged that Hillary Clinton,
who told people at the dinner that she hoped her husband would
visit Pakistan, had influenced her husband's decision last week to
do so. ``The first lady's views were not part of the
decision-making process,'' said White House spokesman Mike Hammer.
</P>
<P>
   CHIPPING AWAY AT DONATIONS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is about to mine the high-tech industry once
again to help rebuild his war chest. This time his targets are the
industry execs who shelled out for Bill Bradley. Bradley was second
to Bush last year in fund-raising from the high-tech industry: Bush
raised $1.6 million, Bradley $1.1 million, Al Gore $840,000, John
McCain $410,476, according to the San Jose Mercury News. ``We're
obviously hoping that a number of the folks who were in the Bradley
camp will come across,'' said venture capitalist Floyd Kvamme, one
of Bush's leading backers in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING ON THE CITY LEVEL
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore met in Nashville, Tenn., with 30 mayors from across the
country. His campaign is hoping they'll provide a counterweight to
the many Republican governors working for George W. Bush. The
mayors included Dennis Archer of Detroit; Jerry Brown of Oakland,
Calif.; Sharpe James of Newark, N.J.; Wellington Webb of Denver;
Marc Morial of New Orleans; and Thomas Menino of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   NADER GOING NATIONWIDE
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocate and Green Party presidential candidate Ralph
Nader predicted he'll qualify for the November ballot in all 50
states. Nader told about 100 people at the University of Nevada,
Reno, that while the Reform Party is somewhat fractured, his party
is ``growing quite readily'' as an alternative to the Democratic
and Republican parties _ ``which is really one party with two heads
wearing makeup.'' The progressive Green Party, founded in 1996,
shares Thomas Jefferson's and James Madison's view of government as
``a public check against the excesses of monied interests,'' Nader
said.
</P>
<P>
   VENTURA STILL TRYING TO RAISE MCCAIN
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, the Reform Party's highest elected
official until he quit the party last month, said he spoke to John
McCain by phone shortly before McCain suspended his presidential
campaign last week. Ventura said McCain told him he had no plans to
leave the Republican Party to run for president. McCain also has
said publicly said he didn't want to bolt the GOP. But Ventura said
that if McCain did run as a third-party candidate, ``He'd make it
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   CALL THIS A MAJOR COUP?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's campaign, which has spent the last week trying to
impress John McCain's voters, announced that McCain's Mississippi
coordinator, Jim Bass, has moved to the Gore camp. But at Bass'
news conference in Jackson on Monday, none of the assembled
political reporters had heard of Bass or knew that McCain had a
Mississippi organization. McCain had not visited the state to
campaign for Tuesday's primary, and had not opened a headquarters.
Bass said he had run for a state Senate seat a dozen years ago _ as
a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   PUTTING DEBATES IN HIBERNATION, TOO
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush again rebuffed Al Gore's offer to suspend all
advertising and hold twice-weekly debates. ``There is going to be
ample time to debate,'' Bush said. ``The best time to debate is
when people are paying attention. As much as we wish, America is
now going to go into a little hibernation period when it comes to
politics. They are going to go into the summer months and go on
vacation with their families.''
</P>
<P>
   REMEMBER WHAT VINCE LOMBARDI SAID
</P>
<P>
   John McCain fell just short of a moral victory in Washington
state, as election officials announced that he had lost the overall
vote total in the Feb. 29 primary by a fraction of a percentage
point, or 2,302 votes. George W. Bush was declared the top
vote-getter, with 402,278 votes, or 30.72 percent, to McCain's
399,976, or 30.55 percent. The only votes Republicans use for
selecting delegates are those of self-declared Republicans, and
Bush won that tally easily: 284,046 to 191,098.
</P>
<P>
   REFORMERS EVERYWHERE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore says he's learned from his campaign finance mistakes and
wants to rid the nation of big-money politics. George W. Bush calls
himself a ``reformer with results.'' Pat Buchanan insists he is the
truest reformer of all. Without John McCain and Bill Bradley, where
do reform-minded voters turn? ``There's nobody,'' says John
Longmire, the Reform Party's Kentucky chairman. ``Every time you
turn around these days, somebody's claiming to be a reformer. It's
enough to make you want to throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   GOING AFTER HENRY'S HIDE
</P>
<P>
   Aiming to topple one of the biggest names in Congress, two
relatively unknown Democrats are competing for the nomination to
oppose Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.). Lawyer Brent Christensen, 37,
first met Hyde when, as a college student in the 1980s, he
delivered him a pizza. Also running is Thomas Cramer, 52, a
business consultant who ran against Hyde two years ago. Both have
sought to portray Hyde, a strong opponent of abortion, as out of
step with a district that they regard as moderate on social issues.
Hyde led the House members who prosecuted President Clinton at his
Senate impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   EIGHT ARROWS SHOOTING TO SUCCEED ARCHER
</P>
<P>
   Eight Republicans are competing in the Texas primary for a
chance to replace retiring Rep. Bill Archer, chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee. The winner is considered a sure bet to
keep the seat in GOP hands. The solidly Republican 7th District is
centered in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   TEENS IRKED BY CIRCUMLOCUTION
</P>
<P>
   After receiving tepid applause from a diverse crowd at the Grace
King High School in Matairie, La., George W. Bush was confronted by
several teen-agers about his views on gay marriage, single mothers
and rumors of his own drug use. And it didn't take long for him to
make it clear he was irritated, by the last topic. ``There's a game
in politics that says, `Let's float a rumor and force somebody to
talk about it.' And I'm not playing the game,'' Bush said. ``I've
been investigated, they've had reporters all over my background.''
The Texas governor added: ``You can draw any conclusion you want,
but what you cannot draw is the conclusion that I have not brought
honor and respect when given the highest office in my state.''
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO MAYOR RACE SET
</P>
<P>
   A Superior Court judge narrowly beat out a wealthy banker to win
the second spot in the November runoff for mayor of San Diego. A
tally of absentee and other ballots that needed to be verified
showed Dick Murphy beat Peter Davis 41,874 to 41,705. Each polled
about 15.7 percent of the vote. The race had been too close to call
after the March 7 election. Of the 12 mayoral candidates, only
County Supervisor Ron Roberts had won enough support _ 26 percent _
to clearly advance to the runoff. All three are Republican. The
second round is needed because no one got at least 50 percent of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ARKANSAS TRAVELER, SHE'S NOT
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton appears to be avoiding any appearances in
Arkansas. Online magazine Salon notes that she hasn't appeared in
Arkansas for nearly two years. Even Rudy Giuliani has been there
more recently. Last July, he attended a $500-a-plate fund-raiser
there. So far, according to Salon, Giuliani has raised $29,800 in
Arkansas, much more than Clinton's $11,450.
</P>
<P>
   REALLY BARRED FROM VOTING TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Wightman-Cervantes, seeking to take on Texas Republican
Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, won't be out glad-handing voters or
passing out campaign leaflets at polling places Tuesday. He's in
jail. The gadfly lawyer, one of five little-known Democrats vying
for the nomination, was arrested at his Dallas home last week and
is serving a 90-day sentence for contempt of court. The case grew
out of a long-standing dispute with a local judge.
Wightman-Cervantes accused the Dallas judicial establishment of
incarcerating him because of his allegations of corruption on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
