<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6666 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-KUNZ-AZR &LR;      03-14 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUNZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMATEUR LIVES OUT EGYPTOLOGY DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Don on Kunz's first issue of `National Geographic`
transported him to ancient Egypt when he was 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was absolutely fascinated by what I read,'' he says. ``It
captivated me.''
</P>
<P>
   He dreamed of one day visiting the sphinx, the pyramids and the
burial grounds of the pharaohs _ perhaps on one of those tour buses
that rumble across the Sahara.
</P>
<P>
   What he never dreamed was that, 40 years later, he would be
crawling on his belly through the rubble of a tomb built 3,000
years ago by Ramses II and share credit for its discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix lawyer also discovered that a man can have two
careers and that boys from Dubuque, Iowa, can grow up to be Indiana
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   It was a quirk of fate that brought Kunz to Egypt. That first
issue of `National Geographic` inspired him to study the world's
first civilization, which predated by centuries the empires of
Rome, Greece and China.
</P>
<P>
   But he chose law as his vocation, first earning a degree in
English at the University of Iowa and then a law degree at the
University of Arizona. The amateur Egyptologist fell in love,
married and reared three daughters. Three weddings and three
college educations drained his vacation kitty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There went the Egypt fund,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   But fate intervened in 1978, when Kunz read in the `Los Angeles
Times` that Kent Weeks, professor of Egyptology at the University
of California at Berkeley, was planning to search for a ``lost''
tomb somewhere in Luxor, the modern site of ancient Thebes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, wouldn't that be fun,'' Kunz says.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote Weeks, offering to come along and pay his own way.
Weeks politely declined, suggesting no lawyers were needed on the
archaeological team.
</P>
<P>
   Kunz persisted. Finally, an amused Weeks agreed, telling Kunz he
could come for a month if he could track down the team's camp.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1, 1978, Kunz flew to Cairo, then Luxor, and with the
help of a local boy found the Weeks crew in a shabby hotel on the
edge of the Sahara. Weeks was surprised but gracious and welcomed
the Phoenix lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Kunz went to work as an assistant to Weeks and the surveyors
assigned to map all of the tombs in the famed Valley of the Kings.
The sites had been mapped before, but using inconsistent criteria
and bench marks.
</P>
<P>
   In the stifling heat, a desert climate similar to that of
Phoenix, Weeks' team explored the tombs of Ramses III, IV, VII and
XI that year. In the Valley of the Kings lie all the tombs of the
pharaohs, including the boy king, Tutankhamen, last ruler of the
18th dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   At each site, the scientists sifted through every inch of soil
they removed to preserve artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dirty and dusty work and I loved it,'' Kunz says. ``For
somebody who had been fascinated by this all his life and thought
he would go as a tourist, here I was with this group of
archaeologists, going through tombs room by room. . . . I was
extraordinarily lucky to be along at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be the first of nine trips he would make to the land of
his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The great Ramses II, who ruled in the 19th dynasty from 1279 to
1213 B.C., is believed to have reigned during the Jewish exodus
from Egypt. Before he died at about the age of 89, he built a tomb,
now known as KV5 (for Kings Valley tomb No. 5) for 50 sons he bore
with three royal wives and a harem.
</P>
<P>
   That tomb was first discovered in the 1820s by British explorer
James Burton, who sketched and then abandoned the debris-filled
mausoleum, ravaged by 3,000 years of silt-saturated floods.
</P>
<P>
   From what Burton could see, the undecorated walls and chambers
looted thousands of years before were unimpressive and would pale
in comparison to the nearby tomb and treasures of King Tut,
discovered by Howard Carter in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   KV5 was forsaken and its location forgotten until Weeks began
snooping around.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Kunz got a call from Weeks asking him to rejoin the
team in a search for KV5. The Egyptian government was planning to
build a new road through the Valley of the Kings, which might
forever bury or destroy the lost tomb. Weeks had six months to
locate the burial chambers of 50 princes of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kent had no idea what he was going to find,'' Kunz says, but
the discovery would turn out to be the greatest since Tut's
treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Working with only a narrow spade, Weeks' team began digging in
the rocky soil and sand. After several days, they heard the sound
of archaeological triumph _ spade scraping on stone that meant they
had found the steps leading to the entrance of the tomb. They
cleared a path to an entryway marked by the cartouche of Ramses II,
a kind of marquee protected by the wings of the goddess Isis.
</P>
<P>
   With the ceiling of the tomb falling down, they hesitated to
enter. But given a cautious go-ahead by an Egyptian geologist,
Weeks called for three volunteers who could fit into the narrow
tunnel burrowed through the hardened sludge. A student, Catharine
Roehrig, was the first to enter. An Egyptian worker named Nubie was
the third. An ecstatic Kunz entered between them.
</P>
<P>
   Slithering on their bellies, and ``swimming'' through the debris
with their arms, the three made their way past the entryway and
into the burial rooms. It was a risky adventure, but, Kunz says,
``I was so excited I wasn't scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Measuring the length of the walls as they went, they finally
reached chambers where they could stand up and discovered that
James Burton had left his signature on the ceiling written in
lampblack.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next eight years, Weeks, now a professor with the
American University in Cairo and one of the world's leading
Egyptologists, returned again and again to excavate KV5 as the
government relocated its roadway. In 1995, he announced his
discovery of the tomb believed to be the largest in the Valley of
the Kings and perhaps in all of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   About 108 of a possible 150 chambers have been uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Weeks published a book detailing his work, `The Lost
Tomb` (William Morrow &AMP; Co.).
</P>
<P>
   Weeks has since excavated a stairway leading away from the tomb
possibly connecting with the nearby tomb of Ramses II himself, so
that father and sons could visit each other in the afterlife. The
mummy of Ramses II is housed in an Egyptian museum.
</P>
<P>
   Kunz has been to KV5 three times, last in 1998. He plans to
return this summer with wife Edith.
</P>
<P>
   For a boy from Dubuque, it's been an amazing adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it means to me is we are living in a time when people can
indeed have two careers,'' Kunz says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to 45 years as a litigator, Kunz has satisfied his
passion for ancient Egypt and stood beside the most illustrious
figures in modern Egyptology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I am extremely fortunate to have had this
opportunity,'' he says. ``It has been a source of more than
pleasure to do something like this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
