<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, March 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than an inch of rain fell across portions of south-central
Texas on Tuesday as a moist flow of air from the Gulf of Mexico
spread into the region. Several thunderstorms also erupted as a
potent jet stream disturbance passing overhead augmented the ascent
of the humid air. This same disturbance will plod slowly eastward
Wednesday, shifting the zone of heavy showers and thunderstorms to
southeastern Texas and the lower Mississippi Valley. Though much of
the region has been recently dry, local flooding could occur in a
few spots.
</P>
<P>
   Breezes from the south and southwest will direct unseasonably
mild air into the Eastern states Wednesday. Spotty showers will
accompany the mild air across the southern Great Lakes and Ohio
Valley as a stream of moist flow arrives from Gulf states. Farther
east, partly to mostly sunny skies will persist near the Eastern
seaboard, where daytime readings will approach 60 degrees as far
north as New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Several inches of snow will accumulate Wednesday over portions
of the northern Great Lakes as a weak low pressure system crosses
the region. Snow will also fall in portions of Colorado as winds
from the east moisten and cool upon ascending the sloping terrain
of the Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Dry weather will prevail along the West Coast. Sunshine will be
plentiful across the region, though patchy clouds will linger near
the Olympic peninsula. Offshore breezes will promote unseasonably
warm conditions near the central and southern California coast,
where afternoon readings may reach the 70s in San Francisco and Los
Angeles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Weather Spotters Network &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many National Weather Service offices are currently sponsoring
severe- weather awareness weeks to prepare for the arrival of
thunderstorm season. While modern technology has increased greatly
the ability of meteorologists to observe and predict severe
thunderstorms and tornadoes, the weather service also maintains a
network of private citizens to watch for developing severe storms.
These so-called ``weather spotters'' spend hours learning the
important characteristics that distinguish developing severe storms
from otherwise harmless cloud formations. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
