<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6679 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-VETERANS15-COX     03-14 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERANS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COURT, CONGRESS CONSIDERING 'PROMISES' TO VETS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The question sounds simple: Must the Pentagon keep
promises that it admits its recruiters made decades ago to young
men and women considering careers in the military?
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated billions of dollars riding on the answer, it
is a question that has caused a group of aging military retirees to
muster up for one more fight, this time with court briefs and
congressional letter-writing campaigns as their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The Class Act Group argues that the government promised, and its
members earned, free medical care for life.
</P>
<P>
   That is not what they are getting. When military retirees reach
65 they are enrolled in Medicare and their right to free care at
military hospitals is terminated. They are eligible for free
medicine, provided the ones they need are on a given military
hospital's list of available drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A fight shaping up in Congress has two of the Senate's most
powerful Republicans, Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi and
Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner of Virginia, reading
increasingly angry mail from veterans in their states.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Lott nor Warner has signed onto a ``keep the promise''
bill introduced by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., Paul Coverdell,
R-Ga., and Tim Johnson, D-S.D., to provide the free medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Although a companion bill in the House has been endorsed by more
than enough members to pass it, there is serious question whether
it can pass the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   And a federal appeals court in Washington has just begun
consideration of arcane legal arguments over whether the military's
promise constituted a binding contract with the government.
</P>
<P>
   The Class Act Group is headed by Fort Walton Beach, Fla., lawyer
George (Bud) Day, a retired Medal of Honor-winning Air Force
colonel who was McCain's cellmate when both were prisoners of war
in North Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In a suit filed in federal court in Pensacola, Day has asked
that the Pentagon be required to provide the free medical care and
that ``Part B'' Medicare premiums they have paid be refunded. The
suit applies only to men and women who joined the military prior to
June 1956, when the Defense Department health care system was
reorganized, and only to those who are 65 or older.
</P>
<P>
   Although Day argued that by forcing the retirees into Medicare
the Defense Department was guilty of breach of contract, a federal
judge ruled he could not force the government to keep the promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must conclude that the plaintiffs certainly have a strong
equitable argument that the government should abide by its
promises,'' U.S. District Judge Roger Vinson wrote in August 1998.
``Regrettably, the law does not permit me to order the United
States to do so under the constitutional separation of powers.
Relief must come from Congress and not the judiciary.''
</P>
<P>
   Day appealed the decision to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
Federal District. In arguments before a three-judge panel last
week, Defense Department lawyers acknowledged that recruiters had
made promises of free medical care for life and that top military
officials in Washington had told them to.
</P>
<P>
   However, the government argued that without authorization from
Congress, the military could not have legally entered a binding
``contract'' with the enlistees and with officers considering
additional tours.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Judge Pauline Newman asked government lawyer Roy
Hawkins, ``You're not telling us that these promises were not made.
You're just saying they don't have to be kept?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's correct, your honor,'' Hawkins replied.
</P>
<P>
   The court may not issue a ruling on Day's appeal for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   With attention now on the bills in Congress, heat is growing on
Lott, who has introduced a bill to free up military hospital drugs
for retirees but has refused to support the ``keep the promise''
bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame Sen. Lott has chosen to turn his back on 23,846
retirees and their families in Mississippi, and also, as Senate
Majority Leader, on all the retirees in the nation,'' military
retiree Jim Whittington wrote in one of several letters published
by the the Biloxi Herald Sun this week.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
