<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6680 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-NIGERIA-RELIGION-ART-     03-14 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-RELIGION-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 KADUNA: the ashes.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the weekend in Sokoto, Christians continued to leave the
state. At the main bus station, Peter Ekeson, 37, an Ibo from the
southeast, was looking to buy tickets for his wife and child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived here for 20 years,'' Ekeson said. ``Most of us are
sending our wives and children back home. And many of the men have
left. They have sold their goods at moderate prices or are shipping
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind Ekeson, two large trucks waited to leave for the
southeast, piled high with refrigerators, televisions, mattresses,
drums and other pieces of furniture. A passenger bus also waited;
the lettering above its windshield announced: ``All over.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Mohammed Makarfi, the 43-year-old governor of Kaduna
state, said the conflict could have been over in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have been avoided if the right thing had been done
at the right time,'' said Makarfi, who belongs to the same party as
Obasanjo, the People's Democratic Party. ``The federal government
should have been decisive and sent the issue to the Supreme Court.
The court would issue a decision on Sharia and the executive would
enforce it. And it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a suggestion that many in Nigeria, including members of
the national legislature, have made. But so far, Obasanjo has
steadfastly resisted it, arguing ``that a legal solution may carry
in its wake chaos, pandemonium and further communal hostilities
which is undesirable,'' his spokesman, Okupe, said over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Most people believe, though, that Obasanjo has acted cautiously
because of his own particular place in Nigerian history and his
increasingly delicate relationship with the northern Muslim elite.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the death of the dictator Gen. Sani Abacha in June
1998, Moshood K.O. Abiola, a Yoruba businessman who had been denied
a victory in the 1993 presidential elections by the military, also
died suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   Many Yoruba _ who are one of Nigeria's three main ethnic groups,
with the Hausa and Ibo _ talked of breaking away from Nigeria. In
order to pacify the Yoruba, the northern Muslim elite agreed on a
``power shift'' _ they would yield the presidency to a southerner,
though not any southerner.
</P>
<P>
   Their candidate was Obasanjo, who had served as president of
Nigeria for the first time from 1976 to 1979 after Gen. Murtala
Muhammad, a northerner, was killed in a failed coup. During that
tenure, Obasanjo was seen to have preserved the status quo, thereby
earning the north's enduring trust and his own people's mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   The result was that in last year's elections, Obasanjo was
elected with votes from the north and the southeast. His own
people, the Yoruba, rejected him unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``But Obasanjo was no longer the Obasanjo of 1979,'' said Julius
Okolo, a professor of political science at Usman dan Fodio
University in Sokoto, pointing out the widely held belief that the
real power during his first presidency lay with a northern general,
Shehu Yar'Adua. ``Now he is his own man.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after taking office, Obasanjo embarked on aggressive
campaigns to clean up the military, re-examine past abuses, and
flush out corruption. Describing himself as a ``detribalized''
politician, he made appointments by choosing names from all over
the country. For instance, a Muslim Hausa from the northern half of
the state typically received a ministerial position in the past;
this time, it was a Christian from southern Kaduna who became a
minister.
</P>
<P>
   The moves angered many northerners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obasanjo has tried to reach out to everyone,'' said Aliko
Mohammed, 65, a prominent northern businessman who once served as
president of Nigeria's stock exchange. ``The north is surprised
that Obasanjo is not acting like a typical Nigerian politician _
winner-take-all. Having got the support of the north, he is now
rewarding his own people, who did not even vote for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his own independence, Obasanjo is now faced with trying
to hold together a nation that since its own independence in 1960
has been a country of competing forces. The military rulers
concentrated power in an increasingly small number of hands, even
as centrifugal forces created more and more divisions.
</P>
<P>
   From three regions in 1960, the number of states has climbed
gradually over the years, to its current number of 36. Three
decades ago, a million people were killed in the Biafran civil war,
when the Ibo tried to secede.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between 1967 when Biafra started and now, we have not solved
the fundamental problem that threatens the existence of Nigeria,''
said Dr. Abayomi Ferreira, a medical doctor who served in the war
and who is involved in politics. ``The history of Nigeria has been
the recurrent struggle of one group after another fighting for
self-determination.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Ferreira and many others in Nigeria are now calling
for a restructuring of the country. Many _ including the governors
of all five Ibo states _ are proposing that Nigeria become a
country of a few large, autonomous regions, with a relatively weak
federal government.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Obasanjo has rejected the proposal, saying that its proponents
were exploiting the current situation with ``unfounded claims of
marginalization.''
</P>
<P>
   But those claims have gotten louder. Separatist groups have
mushroomed. Ralph Uwazuruike, 41, an Ibo lawyer, founded his
organization, the Movement for the Actualization of the Sovereign
State of Biafra, a few months ago. The Ibo had supported Obasanjo
in the elections, but had not benefited enough in his
administration, he said, voicing a common complaint of his ethnic
group.
</P>
<P>
   So Uwazuruike wanted out of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody to his tent,'' he said. ``Things fall apart if the
center cannot hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever structural changes the politicians might adopt for
Nigeria, the people have already started going into their tents.
</P>
<P>
   In Kaduna, Muslims have traditionally lived in the northern half
of the city and Christians in the south, separated by the River
Kaduna. But Nigerians of both faiths lived together in the two
biggest slums, Rigasa and Narahi, which suffered the greatest
devastation during last month's upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Since the riots, separated by fear, Christians living in the
northern slum of Rigasa have moved to Narahi in the south; Muslims
have migrated in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday prayers, a truck laden with furniture rumbled along
the main road here, heading toward southern Kaduna. Half a dozen
Christians sat atop the heap, above a sign in the back that
proclaimed in bold, green letters: ``One Nigeria.''
</P>
</TEXT>
