<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA GAMES ARE A SINKER 
BIG GAME HUNTING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When NBC signed its latest deal with the National Basketball
Association three years ago, the network paid a huge increase in
its rights fee to a total of $1.75 billion, up from $750 million in
the previous four-year deal. But Dick Ebersol, the president of NBC
Sports, was elated, saying, ``The value of the NBA is only
increasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Garth Ancier may not agree. The president of NBC Entertainment,
who is responsible for NBC's prime-time schedule, has a big problem
on his hands right now, and it begins with the letters N-B-A.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a woeful performance in prime time by the NBA games
on Sunday night, NBC recorded the lowest rating the network has
ever scored in prime time during a television season.
</P>
<P>
   The games broadcast by NBC _ one involving the Knicks and the
San Antonio Spurs, a rematch of last year's finals, and the other
between Toronto and Seattle, featuring the league's latest great
Michael Jordan hope, Vince Carter _ reached only 4.6 million
viewers in more than two hours of prime-time Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   That led into NBC's movie for the night, ``Donnie Brasco,''
which was a similar disaster, reaching fewer than 6 million
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA games are of particular concern both because of the cost
to NBC and because it has become the network's primary sports
franchise. NBC abandoned its deal with the National Football League
two years ago partly because it had such confidence in the strength
of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But the NFL has continued to be a strong television attraction,
both on Sunday afternoons and in prime time. The NBA meanwhile is
off more than 15 percent in the afternoons, and the prime-time
numbers have been so bad, shows on cable have been beating the
games.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, both the highly promoted ``Raising the Mammoth''
special on Discovery and the latest episode of ``The Sopranos'' on
HBO dwarfed the audience for the NBA. The ``Mammoth'' special
pulled in more than 10 million viewers. Even though HBO is only
available in about a quarter as many homes as NBC is, ``The
Sopranos'' attracted more than 7 million viewers. (That also easily
beat ``Donnie Brasco,'' proving that it is a special kind of folly
to schedule a mob movie against what critics call the best mob
television show ever produced.)
</P>
<P>
   Had it counted as a network program, even a new series on
Nickelodeon, ``Caitlin's Way,'' would have left the NBA in the
dust. That show, the first real action-adventure series Nickelodeon
has tried, scored the best rating of any series in that channel's
history. It pulled in more than 6 million viewers on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA games have been killing NBC's chances for Sunday night,
the most heavily viewed night of television. The shows that have
followed invariably have suffered because of the poor lead-ins from
the games.
</P>
<P>
   NBC had a much stronger lineup on Sundays in the fall with
``Dateline'' at 7 and ``Third Watch'' at 8. While neither of those
shows had huge ratings, they kept NBC respectable on Sunday. Now
``Dateline'' is sometimes reduced to a half-hour or even as little
as 10 minutes on Sunday because of the length of the basketball
games. ``Third Watch'' is now on Mondays and thriving.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has few options for Sunday for the rest of its NBA deal. It
is obligated to put at least seven games in prime time before the
playoffs. That may make it a long, cold spring for the network on
Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said in a telephone interview Tuesday that he was
concerned about the poor performance of the games in prime time but
not worried for the long-term health of NBC's relationship with the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA has been extremely successful in prime time for more
than a decade,'' Ebersol said. ``We look at this as a transitional
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The transition, he said, is from the Jordan years to an era in
which the league will be dominated by other stars like Carter and
Kobe Bryant of the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA will continue to perform well in prime time in the
future,'' Ebersol said. He added that he had confidence in David
Stern, the NBA commissioner, to address the league's problems.
</P>
<P>
   The first step Stern has taken to juice up interest in the
broadcasts is a controversial one: He is ordering coaches to wear
microphones during games, and if they refuse he is fining their
teams $100,000. Several coaches have already refused.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said: ``I'm not a fair weather programmer. I believe in
this franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Big Game Hunting
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery Channel even surprised itself with the success of
``Raising the Mammoth'' on Sunday, logging the highest number of
viewers in the channel's 15-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery asserted it was the most watched documentary in cable
television history.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour documentary, about an expedition last fall that
pulled a 20,300-year-old woolly mammoth from the Siberian tundra,
averaged 10.1 million viewers during its 8 p.m. showing, an
impressive audience for a show on cable. If the documentary had
appeared on one of the broadcast networks, it would have ranked
50th for the week of March 6, tied with ABC's ``Two Guys and a
Girl'' and ahead of CBS's ``48 Hours'' (9.8 million) and NBC's
``Will &AMP; Grace'' (9.6 million).
</P>
<P>
   Lynn McReynolds, a Discovery Channel spokeswoman, said the
documentary attracted the highest number of viewers of any
nonsporting event on cable so far this television season. The only
show that has ever come close for Discovery was ``Titanic: Anatomy
of a Disaster,'' which had about 4.9 million viewers when it was
first shown in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think even we anticipated the magnitude of the
response,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds said the network did not promote the documentary more
than any other major presentation in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Crucial to the program's success, she said, was that viewers
tended to stay with it after they tuned in.
</P>
<P>
   That was apparently because compelling scenes showed the small
expedition _ financed in part by the Discovery Channel _ battling
blizzards and arctic temperatures as they struggled to unearth the
mammoth. ``But I do think people have an interest in large,
ancient, extinct animals like the mammoth,'' McReynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   Or, on a Sunday night at least, in something other than ``The
X-Files,'' ``The Practice'' or some old movie.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
</TEXT>
