<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, March 15. Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with
layout description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   GENOME-IMPACT (Undated) _ Technology stocks tumbled Tuesday
after President Clinton and Britain's Tony Blair jointly declared
that scientists around the world should have free access to
research on the mapping of human genes. They called research into
the human genetic blueprint was ``one of the most significant
scientific projects of all time.'' This prompted investors to sell
biotechnology shares on worries the companies' proprietary
information may be made public. The biotech pullback spread into
other tech sectors, pushing the Nasdaq composite index down 4.09
percent. By Floyd Norris with Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: an early version of this story _ SCI-GENOME-ACCESS _ has
moved; the full A1 story is scheduled to move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-ALLIANCE (Undated) _ First Alliance, a home-equity lender,
has been accused by scores of consumers of using a deceptive sales
pitch to lure homeowners into high-cost loans that expose them to
the threat of foreclosure and financial ruin. While the company,
which steadfastly denies wrongdoing, has increasingly come under
scrutiny by regulators, it still has some very important support:
Wall Street. Investment banks have pumped hundreds of millions of
dollars more into First Alliance in recent years, even as civil
lawsuits and state investigations have raised increasingly
troubling questions about its business practices. The money raised
by Wall Street for First Alliance and dozens of similar companies
has fueled a quiet revolution in the financial habits of millions
of Americans, known as ``subprime borrowers,'' whose low incomes or
blemished credit histories otherwise prevented them from obtaining
conventional loans. A Special Report based on an investigation by
The Times and the ABC news program ``20/20.'' By Diana B. Henriques
and Lowell Bergman. (6000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT12.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, ``20/20'' will be televised Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-VOUCHERS (Undated) _ A Florida judge has ruled that the
state's constitution bars students from using taxpayer money for
private school tuition, curtailing the state's voucher program, the
nation's boldest experiment at using market pressure to improve
failing schools. The decision, which the state says it will appeal,
is the second major legal setback for voucher proponents in recent
months, following a federal judge's ruling that Cleveland's voucher
program contravenes the First Amendment's separation of church and
state. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: an early version of this story has moved; a
1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-RELIGION (Kaduna, Nigeria) _ The proximity of the mosque
and church was once a bright symbol of Kaduna, a cosmopolitan
meeting place for all Nigerians and one of the best hopes for a
unified Nigeria. Today, both are burned out, and Kaduna has become
a center in a national battle which, on the surface, is over
states' rights to adopt Islamic law, but which is really about raw
political power in Africa's most populous nation. By Norimitsu
Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (Washington) _ Raw fur skins of mink, whole,
with or without head, tail or paws. Monolithic digital integrated
circuits obtained by MOS technology. These are the substance of
diplomatic progress between world superpowers. These days, when the
United States and China take confidence-building measures, they
deal in provisionally preserved capers, not submarine-based
missiles. The Clinton administration, responding to congressional
pressure, Tuesday declassified and released a 250-page document:
``Agreement on Market Access Between the People's Republic of China
and the United States of America.'' By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: an early version of this story has moved; the
1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-CHICAGO (Chicago) _ Looking at how media synergies
really work in Chicagoland. What are the advantages to the Tribune
Co. owning television and radio stations, a newspaper and an
Internet site in one market. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI-FUNDRAISING (New York) _ A look at Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's fund raising in his campaign for the U.S. Senate. By
Clifford J. Levy.
</P>
