<SLUG> BC-SKAKEL-ARRAIGNMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKAKEL TELLS VICTIM'S MOTHER: `YOU'VE GOT THE WRONG GUY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ ``I feel your pain, but you've got the wrong
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   With those words, spoken softly Tuesday in a tiny courtroom,
Michael Skakel shook his head and reintroduced himself to the
mother of the Greenwich teenager he is accused of savagely
murdering nearly 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dorthy Moxley stared at Skakel, with no apparent emotion, and
did not answer her onetime neighbor, a man she had not seen since
her 15-year-old daughter, Martha, was found bludgeoned and stabbed
in October 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The response was left to John Moxley, the victim's brother:
``We'll find out in court.''
</P>
<P>
   With that exchange, the parties left Juvenile Court and faced a
horde of reporters, microphones and television cameras drawn to the
case's mix of celebrity, weath and mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The judicial progress Tuesday was only incremental: Skakel, the
39-year-old nephew of Ethel Kennedy, will return to court June 20
for a hearing to determine if he will be tried as an adult for a
crime he allegedly committed as a 15-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Moxleys, the importance of the court appearance was
immense. ``It's like breathing again,'' said John Moxley, who lives
in Shore Hills, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like a miracle that we are where we are today,''
said Dorthy Moxley, who also lives in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Moxley, whose body was discovered under low-hanging tree
branches on her family's estate, had been beaten with a 6-iron and
stabbed in the throat with the golf club's broken shaft. The weapon
has been matched to a set of golf clubs owned by the Skakel family.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's gesture Tuesday, which took defense attorney Michael
``Mickey'' Sherman by surprise, did not influence the Moxleys'
belief that Skakel killed Martha.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, heavens no,'' the victim's mother said when asked if
Skakel's comments had changed her thinking. ``I thought it was a
practiced statement. I really feel I know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   John Moxley was more blunt. ``I think it's pretty consistent
with the way they've been for 24 years,'' Moxley said of Skakel and
his family. ``It's, `We're larger than life; here we are.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they're going to have to play by the rules. For the first
time in 24 years, we're swimming with the current.''
</P>
<P>
   Such thinking, that Skakel was shielded by his family's wealth
and power, has clouded a case that ran into dead-ends for more than
two decades. But in January, after a grand jury considered new
evidence that Skakel may have told others he committed the crime,
an arrest warrant was issued.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Tuesday called the state's evidence flimsy, outdated,
and inconsistent. And he said he is undaunted by the prospect of
holding a trial in Superior Court, where Skakel could be sentenced
to life imprisonment if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to hide behind the juvenile court system,''
Sherman said. ``He has no idea who committed this crime. I think
I've met with him more than any other client ... and you get a gut
instinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Michael Skakel. I believe him, and I believe in
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman also said that Skakel's statement to the Moxleys was
genuine. ``He truly meant that. He does feel her pain,'' Sherman
said. ``He did not say it in any contrived manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Skakel was not asked by Juvenile Judge Maureen Dennis to enter a
plea Tuesday. He is free to return to his home in Hobe Sound, Fla.,
until his next court appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The new evidence against Skakel reportedly includes statements
from his former classmates at a Maine school that he admitted
killing Moxley, his neighbor in the exclusive Belle Haven enclave
of Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman, however, said he has criss-crossed the country
interviewing former students from the Elan School for troubled
adolescents, and has not found evidence of any criminal admission.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Ricci, who owns and runs the Elan School and unsuccessfully
fought a subpoena for his testimony before the grand jury in this
case, told The Boston Globe in an earlier interview that Skakel
never confessed to killing Moxley. ``These people are lying,'' he
said of the former Elan students who said Skakel had confessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Skakel has never confessed to this crime,'' said
Sherman, ``not to a student at the Elan School, not to a priest ...
not to no one.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, however, also are suspicious of changes that
Skakel reportedly has made to the initial account of his activities
on the night of Moxley's death. Sherman said he is unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have a credibility problem. He has spin problems
because of the books that have been written,'' Sherman said. Author
Dominick Dunne, former Los Angeles police detective Mark Fuhrman,
and a former Greenwich newspaper reporter, have published books
about the slaying. Fuhrman's analysis, titled ``Murder in
Greenwich,'' identified Skakel as the likely killer and appeared
one month before Superior Court Judge George Thim was appointed as
a single-person grand jury in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Thim found probable cause to support the murder arrest warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman, whose racial comments prompted a storm of controversy
in the O.J. Simpson murder trial, said Tuesday outside the
Connecticut courthouse that he believes Skakel will be convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the evidence was flimsy at best, what are we doing here?''
said Fuhrman, who is working as a consultant for ABC News. He said
he does not fault Greenwich's relatively inexperienced
investigators, although at least one of them has conceded the probe
may have been less aggressive because of the influence enjoyed by
the people and neighborhood involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1856EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
