<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6703 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-SOUTHERN-PRIMARIES-BO     03-14 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-PRIMARIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH NO SURE THING FOR BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANT CITY, Fla. _ As he travels from state to state, the
candidate calls every place he stops ``Bush Country,'' with giant
posters and bumper stickers to match. And nowhere does the moniker
seem more fitting than here, in the land of the other Governor
Bush, where voters picked a Bush for president in 1992, when the
majority of the country did not.
</P>
<P>
   All of which has raised an obvious question in recent days: Why
is Governor George W. Bush already campaigning in Florida, if he
has it sewn up?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, Republican strategists admit, is that he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as Bush heads into eight months of battle with Vice
President Al Gore, it appears he will have to continue wooing
voters all across the South _ a crucial voting region, with 147
electoral college votes. Despite decades of growing Republican
strength in the region, despite the Texas governor's ties there,
and despite his sweep in Tuesday's southern primaries, Bush cannot
assume he will beat Gore in a majority of southern states, several
strategists, political scientists and Bush advisors said.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, his own brother conceded the Florida race will be
``competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to take it for granted. It's a swing state,''
Florida Governor Jeb Bush said while campaigning outside Tampa.
``Bill Clinton won this state. George is going to get elected. But
it's going to take a lot of hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, delighted with a narrowing gap in the Florida polls since
last fall, is promising not to make it easier for Bush. Tuesday
night, Gore chose Florida as the site of his primary-night party,
while Bush stayed home in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   In the South as a whole, the reasons for the shift are partly
demographic and economic, and have evolved over the last two
election cycles, as the black population has grown and prosperity
has, in some sections, exploded. The religious right has lost some
of its clout. Democrats have regained some of theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting local political crosscurrents have also played a role,
but the facts remain: Three southern states have elected Democratic
governors in the last six years. And in the last two presidential
elections, nearly half of the original 11 southern states of the
Old Confederacy voted for Bill Clinton and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's focus on Florida as a state he could win is perhaps most
surprising, given the Bush family ties to the state, and George W.
Bush's own pride in being a son of the South.
</P>
<P>
   According to a poll conducted in early March by Mason-Dixon
Polling &AMP; Reserch Inc., Bush leads Gore by 45 to 37 percent. But he
trailed Gore among women, and the poll indicated Gore had narrowed
the gap in Florida from a poll in October, when he trailed Bush by
13 percentage points. A separate Florida Voter poll taken in
January, before Bush's overwhelming loss in the New Hampshire
primary, showed Bush beating Gore by a mere five points.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has raised significantly more money than his Democratic
opponent in the state _ some $4.3 million, compared with $1.4
million for Gore. And now that Bush has depleted nearly all of his
original $70 million war chest, he is returning to his brother's
stomping ground for more fundraisers, including one in Palm Beach
next week. But he is not there to simply pick up checks; according
to spokeswoman Mindy Tucker, Florida is already considered a ``key
battleground state.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's politics are complex in part because the state is not
entirely southern in the traditional sense. Filled with elderly
retirees on Medicare, transplants from the the Northeast and a
large share of the region's immigrants, the state has long stood
somewhat apart, culturally, from the rest of the region. It is a
demographic phenomenon with political side-effects: While much of
the South was furiously ousting the old Democratic guard in the
1980s, Florida elected Senator Bob Graham, a Democrat, in 1986.
This year, a Democrat may win the other Senate seat, too.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Florida was one of four southern states that
swung in favor of the Clinton-Gore ticket in 1996. And Gore, who
moved his campaign headquarters to Nashville last year, prides
himself on being a son of the South as much as Bush does. Those
factors give Gore aides confidence they at least have a shot _ not
just in Florida, but in Georgia and North Carolina as well. (Like
Bush, Gore assumes he'll win his home state).
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that when this campaign season began, George W.
put Florida in the win column,'' Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said.
``But I think as people have gotten to know him (Bush) better, and
they've gotten to know Al Gore better, the fact that George W. is
so far out of the mainstream has had an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered Ron Kaufman, a former political director to President
George Bush: ``Florida is absolutely Bush country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's every reason in the world to make sure the people of
Florida are taken care of,'' he said, in explaining why Bush is
bothering to visit the state at all. ``You do that now versus
October.''
</P>
<P>
   One political hurdle for Bush may be what many also consider his
greatest Florida asset: His brother.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, the fraternal bond between candidate
and governor ``would be an asset,'' said professor Earl Black, an
expert in southern politics at Rice University in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Governor Bush has been controversial because of his One
Florida program,'' he said. The One Florida proposal would prohibit
using race as a factor in state university admissions or in
awarding state contracts. Blacks _ who are overwhelmingly
Democratic throughout the South _ and Hispanics have already
protested the initiative, and are threatening to turn out at the
polls to embarrass Jeb Bush by defeating his brother next fall,
several analysts said. But the younger Bush has stood resolute.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that's going to do is maximize black turnout in
Florida,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, where blacks comprise only about one-tenth of the
population, the impact of a high black turnout could be relatively
small.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the case elsewhere in the South, however. And Gore
is counting on it.
</P>
<P>
   In places such as Georgia and South Carolina, Democrats who win
90 percent of the black vote need only 40 percent of the white vote
to secure a political seat, according to professor Merle Black of
Emory University in Atlanta. Clinton capitalized on that pattern to
break the Republican stronghold in the region, and Gore aides say
they are hoping to use the same strategy throughout the South: draw
white voters, dominate among blacks.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, it is likely Gore will touch on the issues of race
and class that marked the GOP primary, perhaps even undescoring the
image that John McCain used to define Bush for weeks, his visit to
Bob Jones University in South Carolina. Such a tack by Gore would
likely Bush to pay extra attention to the southern states. Bush,
Merle Black said, ``needs to campaign in Florida, Georgia and North
Carolina as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These big states, he can't take them for granted,'' Black
said. ``But we won't see him in South Carolina anymore this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
