<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-BEANS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;       
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Baking Better Butter Beans: Feta, parsley 
 punch up Greek-inspired dish from Palo Alto's Evvia  By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Few dishes are as satisfying as these Greek style
beans from Evvia, the upscale Greek restaurant in Palo Alto.
<P>
   Created by Jean Alberti, who is also the chef at its San
Francisco sister restaurant Kokkari, the hardest thing about making
this recipe is finding the butter beans, which are about the size
and texture of dried lima beans. But don't sweat the small stuff _
I've made them with smaller white beans and even cranberry beans,
with equal success. The only difference is that cooking time may
vary, depending on the variety of bean.
</P>
<P>
   The beans are combined with olive oil, tomatoes, garlic onion
and spices. After cooking, the beans are cooled and transferred to
a baking dish. They're topped with tangy feta cheese and fresh
parsley and baked until hot.
</P>
<P>
   These beans are great as a vegetarian main course, or as a side
dish to grilled or roasted meats. When we had them at Evvia the
beans were served as a starter, but they're also a great side dish
to accompany the grilled lamb chops or spit-roasted chicken.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the wood-fired oven and rotisserie that produce the
chops and chicken are the centerpiece of the menu, and a massive
fireplace opposite the open kitchen has become the focal point of
the sophisticated 120-seat dining room. The flames throw a soft
glow over the rustic interior _ a perfect complement to the
Greek-inspired food.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Evvia, 420 Emerson St. (near University Avenue), Palo Alto; &LR; 
 &LR; (650) 326-0983. Lunch weekdays; dinner nightly.cq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cooking beans with vegetables and seasonings. &LR;  This helps to
infuse more flavor into the beans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cooling the beans before baking. &LR;  This process adds an even
more concentrated flavor, with the alluring contrast of the feta
cheese melted over the top.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BEANS WITH FETA
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound large dried butter beans (lima beans), or other dried
beans
</P>
<P>
   10 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ripe tomatoes, peeled, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano, or 1 tablespoon chopped fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces Greek feta, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons minced Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the beans in a large pot. Add enough water to cover the
beans. Soak for at least 4 hours or overnight. Drain and rinse the
beans.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large saucepan over medium-high heat. Add the
onion and saute until it begins to caramelize, about 5 to 7
minutes. Add the garlic and saute 2 minutes. Add the tomatoes,
beans, oregano and bay leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Add enough water to barely cover the beans. Gently simmer until
the beans are just tender, about 1 to 11/2 hours, adding salt and
pepper the last 30 minutes of cooking. If the mixture is too soupy,
turn up the heat and boil until most of the liquid has evaporated.
Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the bean mixture to a casserole and top with feta
cheese and chopped parsley. Bake until the beans are warm and the
feta melts, about 15 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 550 calories, &LR;   &LR; 22 g protein, 54 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 30 g fat (7 g saturated), 25 mg cholesterol, 334 mg
sodium, 24 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1903EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
