<SLUG> BC-BESTSALMON-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods. 
 
 BEST WAY: Sauteing Salmon   By Noel Advincula  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Salmon's distinctive flavor, its moist texture,
attractive color, year-round availability make it a very popular
fish. It's also high in vitamin A, B complex and omega-3 oils,
making it a good source of nutrients.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are many ways to prepare salmon, but for this test we
picked stove-top sauteing. We used a 5-ounce skinless salmon
fillet, 11/2-inches thick, and cooked it to medium doneness. Each
fillet was checked for pinbones and seasoned with 1/8 teaspoon salt
and 1/8 teaspoon white pepper.
</P>
<P>
   The first step in finding the best way to saute salmon was
determining which fat to use. We tested olive oil, canola oil,
sweet whole butter, a mixture of olive oil and butter, using 2
tablespoons of fat per pan. We also used vegetable oil spray, just
enough to thoroughly coat the bottom of the pan. We then cooked the
fish over medium heat.
</P>
<P>
   The Food staff didn't care much for the salmon cooked in olive
or canola oil, and just about everyone disliked pan spray. The
unanimous choice was that sweet whole butter produced the best
tasting salmon. Second place went to the fillet cooked in the olive
oil and butter combination.
</P>
<P>
   We then tried various types of pans for cooking. An aluminum pan
browned the butter too quickly and left the fish an unappealing
dark color. A cast-iron pan lso cooked the fish very quickly and
browned the exterior almost immediately after contact. A 6-inch
heavy-duty non-stick pan, with the butter reduced to 1 tablespoon,
cooked the fish evenly through and produced the best overall
result.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the proper cooking temperature and time were the
trickiest parts of the test, and we tried several combinations.
Sauteing the fish for 11/2 minutes on each side over medium-high
heat produced a golden brown exterior and some staffers liked. But
the overall favorite was the fillet cooked at a medium temperature
for 11/2 minutes each side. It had the most flavor and was very
moist.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we tested the best way to season the salmon. The fillet
that was seasoned before cooking tasted the best compared to the
one seasoned after or during the cooking process.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For moist and rich-tasting salmon, melt 1 tablespoon butter in a
6-inch heavy-duty non-stick pan over medium heat. Add a 5-ounce
salmon fillet, seasoned with salt and white pepper, and cook 11/2
minutes per side. Take the salmon out of the pan and let it rest
for 1 minute before serving _ this allows the fillet to arrive at
medium doneness. The salmon is perfectly cooked when the flesh is
opaque, firm and moist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AN APPEALING ALTERNATIVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you have a non-stick grill pan, use it instead of a regular
pan. It will add attractive grill marks to the fillet and produces
the same results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1904EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
