<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-RICE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 LEARNING TO COOK: Versatile Dish Blends White and Brown Rice   By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Here is a rice dish that is a good example of home
cooking at its best.
<P>
   Simple, versatile, inexpensive and healthful, serve it hot,
paired with toasted cheese sandwiches, for a satisfying supper. Or
serve it chilled or at room temperature for a main-dish salad. You
can also reheat it in a little olive oil, then add some grated
cheese for another pleasing meal.
</P>
<P>
   The most valuable step in cooking at home is to learn to taste
every dish as you prepare it. Anyone can critically taste, and
everyone has likes and dislikes about food. The bonus of being your
own cook is that you can please your own palate _ if you remember
to taste as you are cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes have many variables. My stove and oven may work
differently from yours. My ingredients may be a different brand
than the ones you use. So, when you learn to taste as you are
making a dish you can see what timing works best in your own
kitchen and do what's necessary to create foods that you like. And
don't forget: You you can also eat most of your mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RICE WITH FRESH VEGETABLES
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup brown rice
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 cup long-grain white rice
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch scallions (also called green onions)
</P>
<P>
   1 small green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 small red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 celery stalks
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cooking the rice:  &LR; Combine the brown rice, chicken broth and
soy sauce in a 4- or 5-quart pot. Bring to a boil. Watch carefully
and reduce the heat to low as soon as the broth boils. Simmer for
10 minutes. Add the white rice. Stir, cover and cook for 15
minutes. It may take another 5 minutes for the rice to be done.
Test it for doneness by scooping out a few grains of rice and
tasting them. If they are tender, the rice is done.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the vegetables:  &LR; Start preparing the vegetables while
the rice is cooking. Peel off and discard the papery outer skin of
the onion. Cut off the stem top and root bottom of the onion. Cut
the onion in half through the stem end. Place each onion half
cut-side down on a cutting board. Cut each half into 1/4-inch
slices horizontally, then cut into 1/4-inch slices vertically, then
cut into 1/4-inch pieces crosswise. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off the coarse green tops of the scallions, leaving a little
green if it looks fresh. Holding the scallions together, cut off
the roots and discard. Cut the scallions into small pieces; set
aside with the onion.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off the stems of the peppers, then cut each pepper in half
lengthwise. Cut out and discard the white veins and seeds. Cut each
pepper half into 1/4-inch strips. Hold the bundle of strips
together and cut crosswise into small pieces. Add to the onions.
</P>
<P>
   Trim off all the leaves from the celery. Slice each celery rib
lengthwise from top to bottom into 1/4-inch strips. Holding the
strips together, slice crosswise into small pieces. Add to the
onions and peppers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The dressing:  &LR; Combine the vinegar and oil in a small bowl and
stir briskly to blend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Finishing the dish:  &LR; Using a fork, stir the cooked rice so the
brown and white grains are mixed together. Add all of the fresh
vegetables and mix into the rice. Add the vinegar and oil, then
season with salt and pepper. Using a fork and large spoon, toss and
mix everything together. Taste and add more salt and pepper if
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 10 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CUP: &LR;   &LR; 300 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 33 g carbohydrate, 17
g &LR;   &LR; fat (2 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 117 mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1904EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
