<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: The Best Chips Off the Chocolate Block   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Some people prefer milk chocolate chips to the
semisweet variety _ not so much for baking as for snacking. So
today's panel tasted five different milk chocolate chips.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The panel didn't reach a consensus on a favorite, but they
agreed they liked the majority of chips.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Belgian Recipe Gourmet &LR;  (500 grams, $6.75 at Draeger's) _ by
far the most expensive brand _ took first place. Panelists noted
the nontraditional drop shape instead of chip, but most liked the
chocolate flavor. One dissenter thought the chip tasted more like
sweetened condensed milk than chocolate. Another felt the chip was
too soft. Three would buy it; two might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to locally made  &UR; Guittard &LR;  (11.5 ounces,
$2.19-$2.69 at many supermarkets). Some panelists liked the bigger
chip, but most of the panelists thought it was too sweet. Most
liked the chocolate flavor, however. One would buy it, three might
buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nestle &LR;  (11.5 ounces, $2.49 at Andronico's) came in third. One
panelist described it as ``sweet even for milk chocolate,'' but
another thought it was less sweet than other brands. Three
described it as a good chip to bake in cookies. Two would buy it,
two might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ghirardelli &LR;  (11.5 ounces, $2.69-$2.75 at many supermarkets)
came in fourth. One panelist liked that she could taste the
chocolate flavor instead of just the sweetness. But others thought
the chip lacked purity; one thought it tasted more like
butterscotch than chocolate. One would buy it, two might buy it,
and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth place went to  &UR; Hershey's &LR;  (11.5 ounces, $3.09 at Cala).
One panelist liked the ``snappy texture,'' but all detected
overtones other than chocolate such as cinnamon and vanilla. One
panelist wrote that it's ``not what I want in a chocolate chip.''
Another panelist thought it would be fine in cookies, but not for
snacking. One would buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Donna Katzl,
chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot,
chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and
Menlo Park; Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; and Kirk Webber,
chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are tasted
blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1905EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6712 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-GASTAX-BOS &LR;      03-14 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GASTAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEEDED ROAD REVENUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson is right to resist
congressional impulses to cut gasoline taxes as a response to the
recent rebound in prices. America's need to maintain funding for
pressing infrastructure needs outweighs the effect those prices
have on most consumers.
</P>
<P>
   A number of factors justify keeping the tax at its current level
of 18.4 cents a gallon _ the most visible of which is to be seen in
the Big Dig here. But federally funded projects all over the
country are essential to keeping roads and bridges in good
condition. Work delayed today will simply be more work to be done
later at higher costs brought on by further deterioration and
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress want to suspend 4.3 cents of the federal
tax, adopted in 1993. Loss of that revenue would deprive the
federal highway fund of $600 million monthly, a significant figure.
By contrast, 4.3 cents less in gasoline taxes would provide a
typical driver who travels 10,000 miles a year in a car averaging
20 miles a gallon with $21.50 _ less than $2 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The spike in gasoline prices looks more dramatic in contrast
with the extreme lows of only 15 months ago, when prices dipped
below $1 a gallon. At that level, gasoline was cheaper in real
terms _ adjusted for inflation _ than at any time in history. A
combination of curtailed production by OPEC, the international oil
cartel, and lower inventories has driven prices for crude oil to
more than $30 a barrel now. But even at $30 a barrel, oil is far
below its peak in 1980, when it reached the equivalent of $70 a
barrel, adjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers may not be impressed by these inflation-adjusted
figures. They see $1.60 a gallon at the gas pump, and that's higher
than what they are used to. But serious policymakers in Washington
_ and on Beacon Hill _ have an obligation to keep these realities
of inflation in mind as they mull responses to changing conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers are hurt by rising prices _ notably older people
on fixed incomes. They may need assistance, and they should get it.
But that is no reason for dismantling the revenue system necessary
to maintain an essential transportation network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
