<HEADER>
A6713 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-POTPOURRI-SFCHRON &LR;      03-14 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics.  WINE POTPOURRI: Journey to a Pinot Promised Land  
   
 By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  As the popularity of Chardonnay and Pinot Noir
continues to grow, consumers seek out different styles of both
wines. Today's Chronicle wine selections feature Carneros Pinot
Noirs, which are distinctive.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carneros sprawls across Napa and Sonoma counties just along the
northern edge of San Francisco Bay. The combination of cool climate
and low natural moisture produce mature Pinot grapes without the
loss of freshness. When young, Carneros Pinot Noir has the inviting
scent and flavor of fresh raspberry and tart cherry, with
underlying spice. With age, the wines develop earthy, mushroom and
tobacco flavors.
</P>
<P>
   The name Carneros comes from the Spanish word for rams or sheep,
because the rolling terrain was once lined with sheep ranches.
</P>
<P>
   Today Carneros is where the water ends and the wine begins. The
only sheep remaining are a few static ones, statues posing as art
in the vineyards, gazing with fixed stares from their meadow in
front of Winery Lake Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Carneros became the promised land for winemakers
looking for cool-climate Chardonnay and Pinot Noir. Large Napa
Valley wineries like Robert Mondavi, Charles Krug, Cuvaison,
Sterling Vineyards and Clos du Val had vineyards in the Napa part
of Carneros. Carneros also attracted a small but important
community of sparkling wine producers, with Gloria Ferrer in
Sonoma-Carneros and Domaine Carneros and Codorniu Napa in
Napa-Carneros. Mumm Napa Valley and Domaine Chandon, both Napa
Valley sparkling wine producers, have vineyards in Carneros.
</P>
<P>
   Carneros' rolling terrain is mainly low-lying, moderated by a
maritime climate and a combination of cool, foggy mornings and
warm, sunny afternoons. Wine grapes thrive in this kind of climate,
and growers have been successful with Chardonnay, Pinot Noir,
Merlot and Syrah.
</P>
<P>
   Carneros is one of the oldest vineyard regions in the state,
with vines being planted as early as the mid-1800s. But strong
winds and fog made grape growing difficult, and in the late 1880s
phylloxera, a plant louse that destroys vines, hit Carneros hard,
nearly wiping out the fledgling industry. Later, Prohibition,
delivered the knockout punch and Carneros as a wine district,
slipped into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1940s, two Napa pioneers, Andre Tchelistcheff (then
winemaker at Beaulieu Vineyard) and Louis M. Martini established
vineyards in Carneros. Rene diRosa followed 20 years later with
Winery Lake Vineyard and other noted growers like Ira Lee and the
Sangiacomo family began to grow Carneros grapes that soon were in
demand by many wineries.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, a growing collection of wineries invested their
future in Carneros, including Buena Vista, Saintsbury, Carneros
Creek Winery, Bouchaine, Mont St. John, Acacia, Kent Rasmussen,
Schug and Roche.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no other grape variety is more representative of the
Carneros style than Pinot Noir. It was the early Pinots that
Tchelistcheff made at Beaulieu Vineyard from Carneros fruit that
caused a Cabernet Sauvignon-focused wine community to recognize
that there was another viable red wine. Fact is, the lush and
fruity Carneros Pinot Noirs gave rise to the rumor that some
Cabernet fans had Pinot envy.
</P>
<P>
   The wineries and growers of the Carneros region work together
under a group known as the Carneros Quality Alliance. If you would
like more information about Carneros and its wines, call CQA, (707)
938-5906.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Abacus Counts &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, I was standing against the wall of the blending
room at the Johnnie Walker Scotch Whisky distillery in Scotland, my
mouth agape. I was watching the master blender taste hundreds of
samples of single malt and grain whiskies to decide which to
include in the blend that would become Johnnie Walker whisky.
</P>
<P>
   It was an astounding exercise that convinced me how important
blending is to whisky and wine. In fact, most wine people consider
blending to be the ultimate expression of a winemaker. To bring
together the various components of a wine, like a Bordeaux blend of
five different varieties, is a skill and an art.
</P>
<P>
   So it shouldn't be surprising that ZD Wines is charging $250 for
a bottle of Abacus, a blend of ZD Reserve Cabernet Sauvignons from
1992 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In what has to be the only California red wine aged in a solera,
winemaker Robert deLeuze has created a unique wine. Spaniards use
the solera method to produce sherry. It is a series of barrels,
usually in three stacked rows or scales. A specific amount of aged
sherry is drawn from the bottom scale and bottled. A like amount is
then drawn from the scale above up  &LR; and poured into the bottom
scale. New wine eventually is put into the top scale. The Spaniards
say the old wine in the solera ``educates'' the young wine.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1992-1998 Napa Valley Abacus, deLeuze used 15 percent of
the solera, placing the remaining 85 percent back into the barrel
to age and await the addition of the youthful fruit of the 1999
vintage.
</P>
<P>
   The first release of Abacus is sold out, but 200 more cases will
be released in November. Contact the winery at (707) 963-5188 for
information.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Napa Auction 2000 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Folks in the Napa Valley are gearing up for Kaleidoscope 2000,
the 20th Annual Napa Valley Wine Auction, June 1-4 at Meadowood
Napa Valley, sponsored by the Napa Valley Vintners Association.
</P>
<P>
   The complete auction package is $2,000 per couple. A limited
number of day passes are available. For more information or to
request an auction invitation package, call (800) 982-1371, then
press 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Basics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Merlot is fast becoming one of America's most popular red wines,
but it isn't without controversy. Once a blending grape in Bordeaux
that stood in the shadow of Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot is more
widely planted there now than Cabernet. The shift is mainly due to
changing worldwide tastes for softer consumer-friendly red wines.
</P>
<P>
   Merlot from the best Pomerol chateaus, such as Petrus, will age
for 30 years, producing an elegant wine with great depth. But
so-called New World Merlots, especially from California, are softer
and rounder.
</P>
<P>
   Merlot is grown in all of California's main wine regions and
does well in Eastern Washington, Southern Oregon and New York's
Long Island. Popular Merlots also are available from Chile and
Northern Italy. New Zealand Merlots and Merlot-Cabernet blends from
Hawkes Bay are the latest finds from the Southern Hemisphere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1906EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
