<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 THE WORKING COOK: Exotic Spices Put Pizzazz in Fish   By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  On its own, the fish in this week's Fast &AMP; Fresh
recipe, Fish Brochettes with Saffron Orzo &AMP; Charmoula, is mild,
almost bland. On a bed of buttery saffron orzo, things start
getting better.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But what really makes this dish zing is a drizzle of charmoula,
a traditional Middle Eastern condiment. Cumin and a dash of cayenne
in the sauce provide smoky heat, while lemon juice and parsley make
the flaky fish taste fresh and light.
</P>
<P>
   Simplicity is key in the next dish, Pan-Roasted Chicken with
Coriander Vegetables. The coriander-scented fennel, carrot and red
onion provide sweet and astringent flavors and a colorful backdrop
to a simple chicken breast, which is buttered up with a quick pan
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure to season the chicken breast well and don't dry it out
too much in the oven. A quick searing over moderately high heat and
a zap in a hot oven will do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   The Portobello Moussaka recipe is more complicated but well
worth the time it takes to prepare _ about two hours, including
cooking time. Make it ahead for a dinner party or stash part of it
in your freezer for later.
</P>
<P>
   The allspice and cumin-flavored tomato sauce goes nicely with
bechamel, which also is infused with sweet spices like nutmeg and
cloves. These two thick sauces make for a gooey dish, but roasted
portobellos create a meaty base, and breadcrumbs add an essential
contrast in texture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FISH BROCHETTES WITH SAFFRON ORZO &AMP; CHARMOULA
</P>
<P>
   Charmoula is a piquant Middle Eastern sauce or marinade. This
one packs a punch; have diners add it to both the fish and orzo to
taste.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound orzo pasta
</P>
<P>
   3 cups low-salt chicken or vegetable broth
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pinch saffron
</P>
<P>
   1 pound firm white fish
</P>
<P>
   Pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   About 4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oven to broil. Soak 8 wooden skewers in a large bowl of
water. Line a baking sheet (one that will fit under your broiler)
with foil and brush it lightly with olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Mince the shallot. Melt the butter in a skillet. Add the shallot
and saute over medium heat until just tender, about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the orzo and stir to coat with the butter, about 1 minute.
Add the broth and 1 teaspoon salt. Bring to a boil and stir in the
saffron. Cover and simmer until the orzo is al dente, following
package directions.
</P>
<P>
   While the orzo cooks, cut the fish into 11/2-inch cubes. Season
lightly with salt and pepper and place 4 pieces on each skewer.
Place on the baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Place directly under the broiler and broil 4 minutes. Turn and
broil until flaky, about 4 more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the fish cooks, make the charmoula. Combine the parsley,
lemon juice, cayenne and cumin. Whisk in the olive oil and season
with salt. Transfer to a small serving bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the brochettes on a bed of saffron orzo, and drizzle with
charmoula.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 495 calories, &LR;   &LR; 33 g protein, 48 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 19 g fat (4 g saturated), 50 mg cholesterol, 1,100
mg sodium, 3 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; 30-MINUTE MAIN DISH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PAN-ROASTED CHICKEN WITH CORIANDER VEGETABLES
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 medium fennel bulb
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot
</P>
<P>
   1/4 large red onion
</P>
<P>
   4 small skinless chicken half-breasts (1 to 11/4 pounds &LR;  total) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander seed
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the fennel into quarters, then remove the core with a
diagonal cut. Thinly slice the fennel. Thinly julienne the carrot
and the red onion.
</P>
<P>
   Season the chicken breasts with salt and pepper on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Place a large skillet over medium-high heat. When hot, add the
oil. When the oil is very hot, add the chicken breasts. Sear on one
side.
</P>
<P>
   Place breasts browned-side up on a small baking sheet and roast
until cooked through, about 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, discard all but 1 or 2 tablespoons of oil in the
skillet. Place the pan over medium heat. Add the coriander and stir
until fragrant, 1 minute. Stir in the onion, fennel, carrot and bay
leaf. Add the wine and increase heat to high to deglaze. Add the
stock and reduce to a simmer. Keep at a steady simmer until the
vegetables are crisp-tender, about 3 minutes. Adjust seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Using a slotted spoon, divide the vegetables among serving
plates, then top with a chicken half-breast. Whisk the butter into
the sauce and drizzle over each serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 300 calories, &LR;   &LR; 29 g protein, 7 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 15 g fat (4 g saturated), 76 mg cholesterol, 138 mg sodium, 2 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PORTOBELLO MOUSSAKA
</P>
<P>
   Moussaka is a classic Greek casserole of sliced eggplant and
ground lamb, which often are layered with tomato sauce and
bechamel. This meatless version substitutes roasted Portobello
mushrooms for lamb.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   21/2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   6 large portobello mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 onions
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 whole clove
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts milk
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces unsalted butter, cut into pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup + 1 tablespoon flour
</P>
<P>
   White pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pinch nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated Parmesan
</P>
<P>
   8 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon allspice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 (26-ounce) boxes Pomi chopped tomatoes, or canned tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 450 degrees. Line 2 baking sheets with
aluminum foil and grease with olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the stems from the portobellos. Cut the caps into
1/4-inch-thick slices. Place on the baking sheets and season with
salt. Roast until very tender and slightly browned, 20 to 25
minutes. Set aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Cut 1 onion in half through the stem end. Attach the bay leaf to
the outside of the onion by piercing it with the clove. Place the
onion and the milk in a heavy saucepan and bring to a steady
simmer. Simmer for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a heavy skillet over low heat. Stir in the
flour. Cook this roux over very low heat, stirring often, for about
10 minutes. Do not let it brown.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the milk; discard the onion. Return milk to a clean
saucepan and whisk in the roux. Season with salt _ enough to bring
out the buttery flavor. Add a hint of white pepper and nutmeg.
Simmer gently for 20 minutes. When done, remove from the heat and
stir in the cheese. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; While the sauce simmers, chop the remaining onions and the
garlic. Heat 2 tablespoons olive oil in a large skillet. Add the
onions and saute over medium-low heat for 5 minutes. Add the
garlic, allspice and cumin and saute for 10 minutes. Add the
tomatoes and sugar and simmer until the sauce is fairly thick,
about 20 minutes. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce oven temperature to 350.
</P>
<P>
   Layer the mushrooms in two 3-quart casseroles, overlapping the
slices if necessary. Top each layer with half of the tomato sauce,
then half of the cheese sauce. Top each with breadcrumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Bake about 20 minutes, until heated through and golden brown on
top.
</P>
<P>
   Let cool for a few minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 300 calories, &LR;   &LR; 10 g protein, 30 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 16 g fat (8 g saturated), 37 mg cholesterol, 494 mg
sodium, 3 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
