<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6716 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-BOOKHAZAN-SFCHRON &LR;      03-14 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKHAZAN-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOK'S BOOKS: Hazan Targets Busy Home Cooks With `Every
Night  Italian'  By Noel Advincula 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Giuliano Hazan, heir to the traditions established
by his mother Marcella, the prima donna of Italian cooking, has
reached out to harried and hurried cooks in his second book,
``Every Night Italian.''
<P>
   Hazan's new book attempts to make Italian cooking easy and fast
without sacrificing flavor and integrity. ``I'd like to show
Americans how they, too, can prepare delicious meals every day,''
he writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple'' is an apt description of the book. From the cover to
the ingredients and the recipe instructions, it's straightforward
and step by step. The book even contains illustrations on kitchen
basics such as chopping an onion, trimming artichokes, de-boning a
chicken, and sharpening a knife.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes I tested were true to the specified cooking times.
 &LR; Frittata alle Cipolline &LR; , an open faced omelet, was good, easy to
prepare and took just 25 minutes.  &LR; Crostata all'Arancia &LR; , a
Sicilian Orange Tart is more involved and good for company. It took
an hour and 40 minutes, but that included baking time, and the
result was beautiful and fresh-tasting. However, the bottom crust
got a gummy and could use more time in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   If one thing is missing from the book, it is photographs. Only
16 of the the 120 recipes have pictures, and a few more showing the
finished dishes would make things easier for the cook.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trying to imitate his mother's technique, Hazan has
developed his own style throughout years of catering, being a chef,
teaching and consulting. Born and raised in the United States, he
understands the needs of the average American home cook and
addresses these needs by keeping the menu simple, easy and
delicious.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``Every Night Italian: 120 Simple Delicious Recipes You Can &LR; 
 &LR; Make in 45 Minutes or Less,'' by Giuliano Hazan (Scribner; 256 &LR; 
 &LR; pages, hardcover; $25) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ITALIAN OPEN-FACED OMELET WITH SCALLIONS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   16 scallions
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons finely chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces Montasio, cream Havarti, or mild cheddar
</P>
<P>
   8 extra-large eggs
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Remove the dark green tops of the scallions (approximately the
top third) and trim the root ends. Cut the scallions lengthwise in
half, then crosswise into 1/2-inch pieces. Rinse well in a strainer
under cold water.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Put 1 tablespoon of the butter
and the vegetable oil in an ovenproof 9- or 10-inch skillet,
preferably nonstick. Place over medium heat and add the scallions.
Season with salt and pepper and saute until they are tender and
have colored lightly.
</P>
<P>
   While the scallions are cooking, chop the parsley and grate the
cheese. Break the eggs into a mixing bowl and beat until the whites
and yolks are well mixed. Add the parsley, cheese and a little salt
and pepper. Lift the scallions out of the skillet with a slotted
spoon, leaving as much of the oil in the pan as possible, and stir
them into the egg mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Put the remaining 1/2 tablespoon butter in the skillet and
return it to medium heat. When the butter is hot, add the egg
mixture and cook, without stirring, for about 5 minutes to set the
bottom. Transfer the skillet to the oven and continue cooking until
the frittata looks firm when the pan is shaken, about 10 minutes.
Remove from the oven and slide the frittata onto a plate. Serve hot
or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 225 calories, &LR;   &LR; 14 g protein, 2 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 19 g fat (8 g saturated), 309 mg cholesterol, 231 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SICILIAN ORANGE TART
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Crust &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest of 2 oranges
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons unsalted butter, cut into a dozen pieces
</P>
<P>
   3 extra-large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ice water, or more if needed
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Filling &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2 extra-large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup freshly squeezed orange juice (juice from the 2 oranges
is usually sufficient)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the crust &LR; : Grate the orange zest using a light pressure on
the grater so as not to dig into the white pith, which is bitter.
Make the pastry shell by placing the flour, sugar, butter, egg
yolks, orange zest and salt in a food processor and running it
until the ingredients are well mixed. Add the ice water and run the
processor until a dough is formed. If the mixture is too dry and
does not hold together, add a little more ice water, 1 teaspoon at
a time.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the dough from the bowl of the processor (carefully
taking out the blade first) and place it on the removable bottom of
a shallow 11-inch tart pan. Using a rolling pin, roll out the dough
until it is no more than 1/4 inch thick, allowing the dough to
extend over the edge. Slide the dough and tart pan bottom off the
edge of the work surface, placing a hand under the metal bottom,
and lower it into the outer ring of the tart pan. Press the dough
against the sides of the pan and trim the overhang.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the dough with a sheet of aluminum foil and weight it with
some rice or dried beans. Place the tart pan in the preheated oven
and bake for 10 minutes. Remove the foil with the rice or beans and
bake uncovered for another 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the crust is baking, make the filling. Put the eggs and
sugar in the bowl of a mixer. Beat at high speed until pale yellow
ribbons form, 2 to 3 minutes. Reduce the speed of the mixer and
slowly pour in the orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the mixture into the baked crust and place the tart in the
oven. Bake until the top is browned and the filling appears firm
when the pan is shaken gently, about 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Allow the tart to cool completely before serving. I prefer it
after it has been chilled in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 285 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 40 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 12 g fat (7 g saturated), 130 mg cholesterol, 107 mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
