<HEADLINE>
A FALSE CHOICE ON GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wayne LaPierre, executive vice president of the National Rifle
Association, must be frustrated to the point of distraction with
President Clinton's refusal to heel to the commands of the gun
lobby. How else to explain the outrageous accusation LaPierre made
on national television Sunday, that Clinton ``needs a certain level
of violence in this country'' to further his gun-control agenda?
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre's remark was just an overheated slice of the rhetoric
the NRA has been ratcheting up of late in an advertising campaign
featuring NRA President Charlton Heston. The ads accuse Clinton of
lying about the NRA's position on gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA is desperately trying to change the subject from
Clinton's call for reasonable gun-control measures to a debate on
better enforcement of existing gun laws. But this is a false
choice. In fact, Clinton's gun-control package calls for $280
million in new law enforcement personnel, including 1,100 state and
federal prosecutors and some 500 agents and inspectors for the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms. There is no earthly
reason why sincere opponents of gun violence can't get behind both
tougher enforcement and broader prevention.
</P>
<P>
   A good example is the proposal to register all newly purchased
guns and license the owners, something the NRA vehemently rejects.
Registration would make it easier to trace guns used in crimes,
whether they have been stolen, carelessly sold, or traded through
the huge loopholes that filigree the nation's gun laws. Would such
a system be considered a prevention or enforcement measure? Does it
matter?
</P>
<P>
   The average citizen doesn't really care whether gun deaths among
children are declining due to Child Access Prevention laws that are
now in 17 states or because the Eddie Eagle program run by the NRA
is teaching school kids the safe way to handle rifles _ or whether
politicians are pandering to the suburban-woman or angry-male vote.
The state of violence in America is a state of emergency. The
correct course is whatever takes guns out of the wrong hands, and
getting there requires plenty of work from everyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1908EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
