<SLUG> BC-TREATING-ANEURYSMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS REPAIR ANEURYSM FROM INSIDE BLOOD VESSEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bulging aorta running through William Olohan's abdomen had
reached a critical size: the weakened blood vessel could burst
fatally at any time and the risk was increasing. But the normal
operation to repair it is traumatic and might overburden the
61-year-old man's weakened heart.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tough call for the patient and doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you just have to bite the bullet'' and attempt the
major repair operation rather than leave the patient with a ticking
time bomb, said Dr. James Estes, a vascular surgeon at New England
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   But now there's a new alternative _ a minimally invasive
procedure that doesn't require the large abdominal incision of the
standard operation, and doesn't cause the patient the postoperative
pain and many weeks of recovery. It's done by sliding an expandable
Dacron graft through a catheter into the aneurysm (the widened,
weak section of aorta), to replace the ballooned-out portion of the
vessel with a strong synthetic tube.
</P>
<P>
   Approved for wide use last year, the procedure _ endovascular
grafting for abdominal aortic aneurysm _ could be done on many of
the thousands of people who need the repair. It's estimated that
1.5 million Americans have this type of aneurysm, but because
they're often asymptomatic until the aneurysms get dangerously
large, only about 200,000 are diagnosed. Some 15,000 die from
ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysms each year.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Einstein died from one in 1955 when he was 76.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons at NEMC were among the first in the Boston area to
perform the procedure and have done about 10, said Estes. Several
other large Boston teaching hospitals also do the endovascular
repair.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Estes did the procedure on Olohan, guiding the
expandable Dacron graft, furled like an umbrella, through a large
catheter in the Stow, Mass. man's groin and into the weakened
section of aorta.
</P>
<P>
   The tubular graft looks like a piece of thin cloth with a ring
of tiny metal hooks at each end, and hardly looks high- tech: but
the cost of each graft is a whopping $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Using controls on the handle of the catheter, which looks like a
fishing rod, Estes got the collapsed graft to unfurl until it was a
tube about an inch in diameter and several inches long. At each end
of the graft the circle of metal hooks bites into the wall of the
healthy aorta above and below the weakened part, anchoring the
graft. Estes said the most critical part of the procedure is
ensuring there are no leaks at the upper part of the graft.
</P>
<P>
   Then the catheter is withdrawn, leaving the graft in place.
</P>
<P>
   Within 48 hours of the procedure, Olohan was home. Had he
undergone the standard operation, he would have spent at least 5 or
6 days in the hospital with a long scar on his abdomen, and would
have needed two or three months to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am delighted to have it fixed,'' Olohan said Tuesday after
coming to NEMC for a routine post-surgical visit. ``I feel fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Another patient, Michael Knowles, 53, of New Bedford, Mass., had
the procedure on March 6 as an alternative to surgery because he
has diabetes and kidney failure. For him, recovery ws a breeze.
``I've had worse experiences in the dentist's chair,'' he said.
``It's incredible. It really is.''
</P>
<P>
   In the standard repair operation, surgeons work through a large
incision to replace the weakened, expanded part of the aorta with a
Dacron graft. There can be a variety of complications, and death in
about 4 percent of patients, Estes said. The endovascular graft
operation sometimes has to be abandoned if surgeons run into
problems or puncture an artery with the catheter; in such a case
they would quickly change to the standard operation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Olohan is 61, Estes said he would not ordinarily
recommend the new procedure for someone in that age range _ which
is considered young _ unless he or she had other health problems
that would make standard surgery too risky. The long-term
durability of the endovascular graft isn't yet known.
</P>
<P>
   Patients are already learning about the endovascular option from
the Internet and are demanding it from their doctors, said Dr.
Albert Hakaim, a vascular surgeon at the Mayo Clinic in
Jacksonville, Fla. ``Nationally, there's a big, patient-driven push
to offer the graft'' for abdominal aneuryms, said Hakaim, adding
that 32 have been performed at the clinic, with one death, which he
said was unrelated to the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Two endovascular devices have been approved by the US Food and
Drug Administration. The one implanted in Olohan at NEMC is made by
Guidant Corp. of Indianopolis; the other is made by Medtronic Inc.
of Minneapolis. Some centers, like the Mayo Clinic in Jacksonville,
also use grafts they make themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The graft has to be sized exactly to mate with the patient's
blood vessels and to accommodate to individual anatomy. Before the
procedure is done, doctors inject a dye into the blood vessels and
take x-rays that reveal the exact location, size and configuration
of the aneurysm.
</P>
<P>
   Then, those measurements are sent to the companies, where a
graft is made to order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1910EST &QL; 
