<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6719 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-HOBBSSHORE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-14 2007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOBBSSHORE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Hobbs' Bacon Business Is Smokin': Economist's hobby turns
meats  into millions   By Janet Fletcher  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN RAFAEL, Calif. _  Twenty years ago, Hobbs Shore retired from a
career as an economist and moved to the sleepy west Marin town of
Marshall. But the tiny village proved to have even less of a pulse
than Shore imagined, and two years into retirement, he was
thoroughly bored.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the urging of a commercial fisherman friend, Shore turned an
old refrigerator into a smoker and began smoking salmon and the
occasional ham or turkey for friends.
</P>
<P>
   One Monday morning, a few days after he had made some smoked
meats for a friend's dinner party, he got the call that brought
retirement to an abrupt end.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Bradley Ogden,'' said the caller, the chef-owner of
the Lark Creek Inn in Larkspur. ``Can I place an order?''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hobbs Applewood Smoked Meat is a $4.5 million business
with customers from California to Florida's Disney World. Thomas
Keller of the French Laundry in Yountville calls Hobbs' bacon the
best in the world. Ogden uses 50 pounds of his ham hocks a week at
the Lark Creek Inn. Insalata's in San Anselmo, Bay Wolf and Caffe
817 in Oakland, and Bizou, Boulevard and Park Chow in San Francisco
are among the restaurants that have made Hobbs' name almost as
common on local menus as garlic. In an industry dominated by
meat-processing giants, Shore's experience reflects, in part, how a
small business can thrive by addressing Bay Area chefs' concerns
about how their raw materials are produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we use prosciutto at all, his is the one we use,'' says
Michael Wild of Bay Wolf. ``It's the one that's actually made by a
human being with some kind of care.''
</P>
<P>
   At Park Chow, where Hobbs' pepperoni tops the pizza, chef-owner
Tony Gulisano is another enthusiast. ``We can't touch the pepperoni
pizza,'' Gulisano says. ``It's really, really good. It's so clean
when you eat it, it feels healthful. It feels like you've eaten
food that's been taken care of. Let alone all the love that (Shore)
puts into it. I believe you can taste that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   For a 78-year-old who says the best part of his business is
hanging out with chefs, the approval of these demanding clients is
a huge ego boost. When Keller, who reportedly has time for no one,
stands around with him in the French Laundry kitchen debating
whether to put truffle oil on Hobbs' bundnerfleisch, Shore is in
heaven. When he recalls bringing liverwurst to Boulevard's Nancy
Oakes and watching her and her staff eat it all on the spot, his
elfin face lights up with delight.
</P>
<P>
   Although his second career as a  &LR; charcutier &LR;  happened by chance,
in a sense Shore had trained for it since childhood. Raised in the
Bensonhurst section of Brooklyn, with Italian, French, Swedish and
Norwegian neighbors, he grew up eating Italian coppa and French
saucisson when neighborhood families would gather on the sandlot
for meals. ``It was a quiltwork of Europeans,'' he says, ``and we
were all poor in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   To get him out of the city in the summers and away from polio
epidemics, his parents sent their young son to his grandfather's
farm in upstate New York. There, the first summer, he anticipated
weeks of swimming, sunning and fishing. But his Norwegian
grandfather put him to work in his smokehouse, moving the apple
wood-filled smoke wagon around so the bacon, hams and fish smoked
evenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a vacation,'' Shore says ruefully. ``I thought, I'll
never look another smokehouse in the face again.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he helped his grandfather for eight summers, and
although he never liked doing it and never thought he had learned
anything, he would sporadically smoke a ham or some fish in
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Ogden called to say he had tasted Shore's meats at
a dinner party, the phone rang again. Kelly Mills, then the chef at
the Clift Hotel, had been at the same party. Would Shore sell him
some bacon?
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I don't do this,' '' Shore recalls. He was supposed
to be retired, spending time with his wife. She would surely resent
it if he launched a little sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I went to my wife,'' Shore recalls, ``and said, `Would it
be OK if maybe a couple of times a week I went to the city?' And
she said, `Thank God. You're driving me crazy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Today he makes around four dozen different products in his
Oakland facility, all in small amounts and almost all for the
restaurant trade. (See ``Finding Hobbs'' for the few retail stores
that carry at least some of his products.) He has no sales force;
his business grows each year by word of mouth and the inevitable
migration of chefs from job to job. No special request is too small
if it intrigues him. When chef Laurent Manrique joined Campton
Place and wanted Toulouse-style sausage for his cassoulet, Shore
turned to his childhood taste memories of Bensonhurst and created
one. The liverwurst, which he makes when the mood strikes,
apparently never makes it past the chef.
</P>
<P>
   To guarantee the quality of his main ingredient, Shore gets his
pork from a small Canadian family farm. He is the farm's only
customer and the pigs are raised to his specifications. During
their final weeks, the animals are fed barley instead of mash to
give the meat a tighter grain, and the leaner the animal's fatback,
the more Shore pays. American pigs are too large and the meat
inconsistent, he says. When the price goes down, farmers hold the
hogs off the market and continue to feed them, waiting for a better
price, so when the hogs finally reach market, they're too fat.
</P>
<P>
   The other crucial ingredient in his recipe, Shore believes, is
his hands-on approach. ``You can't let machines get between you and
the product,'' he says. It is sight, touch, taste and smell _ not a
formula _ that tells him when the prosciutto or air-dried salami is
right.
</P>
<P>
   Each of Hobbs' chef-customers has a favorite among his growing
repertoire. Heidi Krahling, chef-owner of Insalata's, loves the
Iberian air-dried chorizo, which she uses in cataplana, a Spanish
clam, sausage and tomato dish. Wild waxes poetic about the smoked
ham hocks, which his kitchen pairs with fava beans in the spring
and fresh lima beans in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the most delicate, absolutely pristine,'' Wild says.
``Most of the hocks you find here are frozen and oversmoked and
taste like chemicals. These are sweet and succulent, like those
little hocks in France that you never see here.''
</P>
<P>
   At Caffe 817, owner Sandro Rossi makes a charcuterie plate with
Hobbs' soppressata, coppa, mortadella and prosciutto, sliced to
order and served with house-cured baby artichokes. He puts the
prosciutto cotto in a garbanzo soup with spinach, and serves Hobbs'
whiskey-fennel sausages with polenta.
</P>
<P>
   Gulisano likes the herb and garlic pork loin, which goes on a
Park Chow sandwich with caramelized onions and Crescenza cheese.
Shore showed him how to steam the meat briefly to release the
juices, the way delis do in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The company may have no sales force, but the genial Shore
relishes his kitchen visits, and chefs profess a fondness for him
that surpasses the typical supplier-chef bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of man that, when he comes in, you want to get
him a slice of pie and a cup of coffee,'' says Boulevard's Oakes,
whose husband is rival sausagemaker Bruce Aidells. Her sausage
business goes elsewhere, of course, but she uses a lot of Hobbs'
bacon and his ``smoky and mysterious'' Westphalian ham, which she
calls the best American substitute for prosciutto.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sort of like a mad scientist, father and great supporter
all rolled into one,'' Krahling says. ``When he comes into the
kitchen, he ponies up next to you and talks and gives you pearls of
wisdom. He's just a magical man.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (Sidebar and recipes follow in optional trim) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FINDING HOBBS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The following Bay Area merchants carry some of Hobbs Shore's
products.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; A.G. Ferrari &LR;  (applewood-smoked bacon, prosciutto, smoked
hams, sausages). Stores in San Francisco, Corte Madera, Danville,
Lafayette, Berkeley, Oakland, Montclair and Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Draeger's &LR;  (applewood-smoked bacon). Stores in San Mateo,
Menlo Park, Los Altos.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ernie's Meats &LR;  (prosciutto, smoked chicken, pepperoni). 1320
Main St., St. Helena; (707) 963-9608.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Mollie Stone's &LR;  (applewood-smoked bacon). Burlingame store
only: 1477 Chapin Ave. (at El Camino Real); (650) 558-9992.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Oakville Grocery &LR; . Oakville, Healdsburg, Walnut Creek, Palo
Alto and Los Gatos.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Pasta Shop &LR;  (applewood-smoked bacon, pancetta). Oakland store
only: 5655 College Ave. (at Shafter); (650) 547-4005.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; INSALATA'S CATAPLANA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A Portuguese clam, chorizo and tomato saute from chef Heidi
Krahling of Insalata's.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces smoked chorizo, skinned, sliced diagonally 1/4 inch
thick
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 Roma tomatoes, peeled, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   Pinch hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound manila clams, scrubbed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup marinara sauce, preferably homemade
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a medium saute pan over moderate heat. Add
the chorizo and brown on both sides. Remove the chorizo to paper
towels. Add the garlic, wine, tomatoes and pepper flakes to the
pan. Cook for 1 minute, stirring. Add the clams and marinara sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and simmer until the clams open; discard any clams that
fail to open. Add the chorizo and parsley. Taste and adjust
seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with country-style bread.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 as a first course, 2 as a main course.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER MAIN-COURSE SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 480 calories, &LR;   &LR; 22 g protein, 21 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 31 g fat (7 g saturated), 53 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 1,003
mg sodium, 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BAY WOLF'S DANDELION SALAD WITH PANCETTA, EGGS &AMP; GARLIC CROUTONS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, peeled and smashed
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil + olive oil to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 loaf pain levain, crust removed, cut into small cubes
</P>
<P>
   4 slices pancetta, cut like thick-sliced bacon
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches young dandelion greens, thick stems removed
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the wine, vinegar, 1 garlic clove and the thyme in a
small saucepan. Simmer over moderate heat until reduced to 1/3 cup.
</P>
<P>
   Put the shallots in a bowl and pour the hot wine mixture over
them. Season with salt and pepper and let macerate for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1 tablespoon olive oil in a small saute pan over moderate
heat. Add the remaining garlic clove and saute until the oil is
fragrant, then discard the garlic. Toss the bread cubes with the
oil, then arrange on a baking sheet. Bake until golden and crisp,
about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Place the pancetta in a saute pan and cook over moderate heat
until some of the fat renders; do not let the pancetta crisp.
Transfer the pancetta to paper towels to drain, then break into
smaller pieces; set aside. Reserve the fat in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Place the eggs (in their shells) in a small saucepan; add water
to cover. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and let stand for 6
minutes. Drain, peel and cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   Finish the vinaigrette by whisking in the reserved pancetta fat.
If the vinaigrette is still too acidic, add olive oil to taste.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble the salad:  &LR; Gently heat a large stainless-steel
bowl over moderately low heat. Add some of the vinaigrette (you
will not need it all), then the pancetta and greens. Toss until the
greens are wilted, adding more vinaigrette if needed; add the
croutons and toss again. Taste and adjust seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm, garnishing each portion with an egg half.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 250 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g protein, 19 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 14 g fat (5 g saturated), 114 mg cholesterol, 282 mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
