<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6721 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-JUNKFOOD-SFCHRON &LR;      03-14 1567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNKFOOD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Pssst! Wanna Buy a Twinkie? Why America nurses a secret
passion  for junk food   By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _   `What's that sizzling sound I hear? Get Up! 
 It's Spam and eggs, my dear!'' _  Advertising slogan from the
1940s.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
San Francisco nightclub owner Harry Denton's devil is a quart of
cold whole milk and a package of Hostess Sno Balls. Pink or white,
doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   John Kowalski, a 37-year-old chemist from San Francisco, has a
hidden passion for Kraft macaroni and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Fararo, 42, is a Berkeley free-lance journalist who is so
picky about food that she'll only drink lattes from Alice Water's
Cafe Fanny. But some afternoons, when no one is looking, she stirs
up a pot of chicken-flavored Rice-A-Roni.
</P>
<P>
   They are not alone. The Bay Area has a secret palate for
processed all-American junk. Sure, we make fun of Spam and sneer at
Velveeta. But we suck them down at astounding rates. Finding a
person raised in the United States who isn't secretly fond of some
sort of junk food is as hard as finding an Italian who doesn't like
pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Says Fararo: ``Everybody's got their Rice-A-Roni.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a paradox. America is a country of health-obsessed
exercise fanatics. The government spends billions of dollars
wrangling with the safety and purity of the food supply. American
restaurants boast some of the best chefs in the world, yet 500
million Twinkies are consumed each year.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the hallowed halls of academia, the love of junk food
runs deep. In dining halls at the University of California at
Berkeley, the food service staff met resistance when they tried to
break the student body's 1,200-servings-a-week Jell-O habit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to take it off the menu for a little variety and it
was like, `Hey, where's the Jell-O?' '' says dining service
director Nancy Jurich. The favorite flavor? Blueberry.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason may be that we're a country affluent enough
to eat whatever we want. But a stronger draw is the reason people
like Kowalski put a box of Hostess Ho-Hos in his cart when he
shopped at Safeway in San Francisco's Diamond Heights district
earlier this month. ``I always picture my Mom packing my lunch
every time I eat these,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgia is a powerful force in choosing the food we eat, says
Syracuse University professor Robert Thompson, president of the
4,000-member Popular Culture Association. And in a nation as young
and rootless as America, icons that bring us back to our past are
revered, even if they are full of fat, sugar and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids eat this stuff simply because it tastes good,'' he says.
``Then when they grow up and eat a Twinkie, every bite is like a
piece of their childhood. A Ho-Ho isn't just a little snack; it's a
special friend.''
</P>
<P>
   But we can't explain away Spam, Twinkies and Jell-O as pure
nostalgia. ``Nearly all the classic processed food offers something
else besides just food,'' he says. ``Jiffy Pop is dramatic
entertainment. Jell-O is the texture of children's playthings. Spam
is a food that could be eaten anywhere on this or any other planet.
This stuff is fun. It's magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Junk food is easy on the brain and perfect for people who think
instant gratification takes too long, says Marc Halperin of the
Center for Culinary Development in San Francisco. ``The Twinkie is
soft, it's sweet, it's moist, it fills your mouth and your stomach
very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Halperin admits an occasional indulgence in French crullers and
A &AMP; W root beer floats, although not necessarily at the same time.
``Donuts and Spam don't require a lot of cogitation. You don't need
to think about what you're eating.''
</P>
<P>
   For Denton of the Starlight Room, junk food offers a certain
naughty appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a comfort food and it's the devil in everybody,'' he
says. ``No one wants to be perfect, so it's good when you want to
be a little bad.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   For chefs who place a high value on seasonal and regional
ingredients and who likely wouldn't be caught dead with a Ho-Ho,
how all this stuff got on grocery store shelves in the first place
is the question.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Rodgers at Zuni Cafe is among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says something about the commercial evolution of this
country,'' she says, adding that America may have been ripe for
junk food because it didn't have the deep-seated cultural roots of
Asian or European countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In France, homemade mayonnaise dies a little harder,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the story of modern American junk food encompasses
100 years of history, culture, science and technology. Many of the
foods we hate to love have their roots in early mechanical and
preservation advances like canning. Borden, for example, started
canning milk in 1860. J.L. Kraft company began canning cheese in
1914, and Velveeta was introduced in 1928. Hormel started canning
ham in 1926 and 11 years later gave birth to Spam.
</P>
<P>
   Those shelf-stable products turned out to be handy for feeding
soldiers, and both world wars served to imprint certain canned
foods on the American palate. Residents of Hawaii, where more Spam
is eaten per capita than any other state, can trace their love of
the product back to World War II. To this day, Spam sushi can be
purchased almost everywhere in Hawaii, including 7-Elevens.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of mass-market advertising also helped sear certain
products into America's collective consciousness. By the 1940s,
radio jingles had become became the thing, and products like Spam
sponsored popular shows like Burns and Allen.
</P>
<P>
   The next leap in fast food came in the '50s, when television,
advances in chemical research and a fascination with science all
took hold of America. Between 1949 and 1959, chemists came up with
more than 400 additives to help foods survive increasingly complex
mass production techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone searching for the perfect food icon for the '50s might
look to the TV dinner. Swanson trademarked its first _ turkey and
mashed potatoes _ in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Baby Boom was in full effect. Settling in and
raising a family was the nation's preoccupation. Women were
beginning to enter the work force and a whole slew of new
``modern'' kitchen appliances and foods fed the country's
fascination with convenience.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '60s and early '70s, innovation and grabbing market
share gave the junk food market a hard twist. Goofy, gimmicky food,
like Funyuns and Ding Dongs, crowded the market. Ethnic influences
also made their way into junk food circles, with pork rinds and
nacho-flavored Doritos gaining popularity.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to 2000. Despite the growth of the organic foods
industry and the demonstrable connection between diet and health,
not to mention the battle over genetically engineered foods,
Chee-tos and Hostess Cupcakes continue to fill grocery store carts.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cycle that may take generations to break. Or it may be
that junk food is such a part of the American diet and culture that
it will never die. Junk food encompasses America's triumphs in war,
commerce and technology _ underpinnings of the nation's culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that this stuff is bite-sized America,''
Professor Thompson says. ``It is the American myth there for the
taking. A good bite of a Twinkie is a profound American
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Chronicle Food department intern Noel Advincula contributed &LR; 
 &LR; to this report. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; JUNK FOOD JIVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Twinkies &LR;  were born in 1930, when Continental Baking Co.
manager James Dewar of Illinois decided Depression-idled baking
pans might be used to create a cheap snack. He took the name from
an ad for Twinkle Toe Shoes, and charged a nickel for a pack of
two. The original filling was banana cream, which was abandoned for
vanilla during the banana shortage of 1940.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Spam &LR; , the first meat product that did not need
refrigeration, was invented by Hormel in 1937, but it really came
into its own during World War II. The military liked it because it
was shelf-stable, and consumers could have their fill because it
wasn't rationed like beef.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jell-O &LR;  was born in 1897 when New York cough syrup
manufacturer Pearl Wait adapted Charles Knox's patent for gelatin
sheets into a sweet, fruit-flavored dessert and called it Jell-O,
after Grain-O, a popular coffee substitute. Wait sold the patent to
his neighbor, orator Francis Woodward, for $450; Woodward turned
Jell-0 into a million-dollar empire. Today, Jell-O manufacturer
General Foods Co. estimates that 13 boxes are sold every second.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Velveeta &LR;  grew out of the process for making the canned
cheese that nourished American troops in World War I. It was
launched by Kraft in 1928 with the slogan, ``Digestible as Milk
Itself!'' Kraft's Macaroni and Cheese Dinner followed in 1937, then
the Kraft Deluxe processed cheese slices in 1950, and Cheez Whiz in
1952.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Wonder Bread &LR;  got its name in 1921 when Taggert Baking Co.
executive Elmer Cline saw hundreds of balloons fill the sky and was
filled with, well, wonder. A decade later, sliced loaves were
introduced and a great clich &LR; e &LR;  was invented. In 1940, the Food and
Drug Administration mandated that vitamins like iron and thiamine
be added to white flour. Wonder Bread's vitamin-enriched formula
and slogan _ it ``helps build strong bodies'' _ remain popular
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
