<P>
   GENOME-IMPACT (Undated) _ Technology stocks tumbled Tuesday
after President Clinton and Britain's Tony Blair jointly declared
that scientists around the world should have free access to
research on the mapping of human genes. They called research into
the human genetic blueprint was ``one of the most significant
scientific projects of all time.'' This prompted investors to sell
biotechnology shares on worries the companies' proprietary
information may be made public. The biotech pullback spread into
other tech sectors, pushing the Nasdaq composite index down 4.09
percent. By Floyd Norris with Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story _ SCI-GENOME-ACCESS _ has moved;
the reworked version is scheduled to move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISPLAY:
</P>
<P>
   PLATT-STARTING-OVER (Santa Rosa, Calif.) _ In one of the more
unusual corporate job changes in years, Lewis E. Platt, 58, left
Hewlett-Packard last year after 33 years, including a seven-year
term as chief executive, and promptly took the top job at
Kendall-Jackson Wine Estates. While Platt's new job certainly seems
romantic, his switch has also brought a management problem that the
textbooks do not discuss: how does an executive who has already
climbed his way to the top, and grown used to the trappings that
come with one of corporate America's plum jobs, start anew? The
question is particularly relevant because both the average age and
the tenure of chief executives at large companies are dropping. By
David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphics.)
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT SIDE:
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-WILLES (Undated) _ Looking at the legacy that Mark
Willes leaves behind. As a consumer products executive, he sought
to shake up Times Mirror and its way of thinking of newspapers as a
business. Was it a failure? How he reshaped Times Mirror. By
Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo.)
</P>
