<P>
   Here are tonight's columns, other features:
</P>
<P>
   MERGER-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ The three partners in the world's
newest giant ad agency gathered on Tuesday for an unusual event
that was part pep rally, part christening, part mixer and part Wall
Street warm-up. The gathering, at a partner agency headquarters in
Chicago, was to formalize the creation of the ad agency company
born on Jan. 31, when Leo and MacManus merged and then sold a stake
of approximately 20 percent to Dentsu for an estimated $400
million. The merged entity plans an initial public offering in the
next 12 to 18 months, and Dentsu plans one in the fall of 2001. By
Stuart Elliot.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDER-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ In the first criminal case of
swapping inside stock information over the Internet, federal
authorities charged on Tuesday that 19 people earned $8.4 million
on illegal tips from a part-time graphics clerk on Wall Street who
passed some of the tips through private chat rooms and America
Online's instant messaging system. By Christopher Drew.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Digest of the day's financial stories.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   We also call your attention to the following, on NYT Page 1:
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-ALLIANCE (Undated) _ First Alliance, a home-equity lender,
has been accused by scores of consumers of using a deceptive sales
pitch to lure homeowners into high-cost loans that expose them to
the threat of foreclosure and financial ruin. While the company,
which steadfastly denies wrongdoing, has increasingly come under
scrutiny by regulators, it still has some very important support:
Wall Street. Investment banks have pumped hundreds of millions of
dollars more into First Alliance in recent years, even as civil
lawsuits and state investigations have raised increasingly
troubling questions about its business practices. The money raised
by Wall Street for First Alliance and dozens of similar companies
has fueled a quiet revolution in the financial habits of millions
of Americans, known as ``subprime borrowers,'' whose low incomes or
blemished credit histories otherwise prevented them from obtaining
conventional loans. A Special Report based on an investigation by
The Times and the ABC news program ``20/20.'' By Diana B. Henriques
and Lowell Bergman. (6000 words)
</P>
<P>
   (With photo, NYT12.)
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
