<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6738 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-BROCKOVICH-REVIEW-LAD     03-14 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROCKOVICH-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT DEEP, BUT TOTALLY JULIA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Friday, March 17 or later. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Erin Brockovich, legal assistant extraordinaire, has an uncanny
way of digging up information that would elude the most experienced
lawyers and the best private detectives. Her boss, Ed Masry, a
disheveled attorney nearing the end of his career, wonders just how
Brockovich does it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how these places are run,'' Masry says. ``They're a
mess. What makes you think you can just walk in there and find what
you need?''
</P>
<P>
   Answers Brockovich: ``They're called boobs, Ed.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Roberts' boobs _ along with her considerable charisma _
are on fine display in ``Erin Brockovich,'' an enjoyable lark of a
movie that finds director Steven Soderbergh working hard to deliver
crowd-pleasing entertainment. And while the movie certainly
delivers a rousing good time, it never comes close to being
believable as a true story. And the problem isn't in the film's
facts, which are close enough by Hollywood standards, but in the
way Roberts' imposing presence subverts what is essentially a
David-and-Goliath tale.
</P>
<P>
   Brockovich begins the movie as a twice-divorced mother of three
young children who's desperate for work. She eventually lands at
the law offices of Masry (Albert Finney), who once represented her
(unsuccessfully). Masry gives Brockovich a clerical job after she
threatens to make a scene. Making scenes is what Brockovich does
best; Masry at one point tells her that charm school, not law
school, would be of greatest benefit to her personal growth.
</P>
<P>
   Brockovich's attitude and her appearance (all the plunging
necklines, push-up bras and leather mini-skirts makes it look like
Roberts' has raided her ``Pretty Woman'' wardrobe trunk) don't
exactly endear her to her female co-workers. She calls one
overweight woman ``Krispy Kreme'' and reduces others to shocked
silence with various risque put-downs.
</P>
<P>
   A higher calling eventually arrives when Brockovich begins
investigating health problems afflicting families in the California
desert community of Hinkley. Brockovich traces the illnesses to a
deadly chemical that Pacific Gas and Electric used in its local
plant. Employing nothing more than her street smarts and
conspicuous cleavage, Brockovich begins to gather damning evidence,
pressing Masry to take the case to trial.
</P>
<P>
   The facts of the case make ``Erin Brockovich'' sound like the re
cent tepid legal drama ``A Civil Action,'' but this movie is more
like ``Norma Rae'' anchored in underwire. There are the requi site
scenes of lives that have been ravaged by corporate greed (Marg
Helgenberger and Cherry Jones have some nice moments), but they're
overshadowed by Brockovich's coming-of-age tale.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not necessarily a bad thing. Certainly, we've had
enough solemn and teary court room theatrics in movies to last us a
lifetime. Soderbergh, work ing from a snappy screenplay by Susannah
Grant (with an un credited rewrite by Richard LaGravanese), seems
to under stand this, and ignores most of the genre's cliches. The
result is an energetic, briskly directed, knockabout effort that
tells its story in a different, although hardly unique, way.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and Finney make a great team, and an unrecognizable
Aaron Eckhart also has some potent chemistry with Roberts, playing
Brockovich's biker boy friend who becomes a full-time baby sitter
to her kids.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' star power is what you'll remember most, though, which
is both the movie's greatest strength and its one glaring weakness.
Roberts is at ease with the film's comic and dra matic requirements
and she's at her romantic best with Eckhart. But we never forget
she's Julia Roberts. It all makes for a great Julia Roberts movie,
but an iffy biopic, which is a little discon certing for a movie
called ``Erin Brockovich.'' &QL; 
_________ &QL; 
The film: ``Erin Brockovich'' (R; language). &QL; 
The stars: Julia Roberts, Albert Finney, Aaron Eckhart. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Steven Soderbergh. Screenplay by
Susannah Grant. Released by Universal Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: Two hours, 11 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
