<SLUG> BC-PTEK15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PTEK unit invests in BuyTrek, capitalizing on e-commerce surge
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ PTEK Holdings, a company recently reshaped and
renamed, has made yet another investment in a small but ambitious
high-tech start-up.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced fourth-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   PTEK subsidiary PTEK Ventures has led a $2.5 million
institutional investment round in BuyTrek, plunking down about $2
million for a piece of an Atlanta-based company that aims to
capitalize on the surge of interest in electronic commerce via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   BuyTrek's plan is to provide visitors to a Web site with a
system for Web shopping. When a buyer searches for an item, BuyTrek
takes the consumer to the item they are looking for within a
merchant's site. BuyTrek then will allow the buyer to view the same
item at other sites, enabling the user to compare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are excited to make BuyTrek the latest addition to our
rapidly growing network of Internet-based companies,'' said Boland
T. Jones, PTEK Holdings founder, chairman and chief executive. ``We
are confident that the company has the technical expertise,
executive leadership and industry knowledge to achieve tremendous
success.''
</P>
<P>
   PTEK, which until February was known as Premiere Technologies,
was itself once a hot, high-tech up-and-comer. The company ran into
some trouble after making a series of acquisitions. Its stock value
fell, along with its earnings. The company lost money through most
of the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   PTEK reported revenue Tuesday of $114.9 million for the fourth
quarter of 1999 compared with $116.9 million during the same period
a year earlier. PTEK reported an operating loss of $32.4 million
compared with $41.7 million. The company reported net income of
$1.23 basic earnings per share in contrast with a
79-cents-per-share loss during the same quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding gains from the sale of investments or one-time
charges, the company lost 68 cents per share in the last quarter,
compared with a 52-cents-per-share loss in the fourth quarter of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The company is now split in four: PTEK Ventures, as well as
units for fax business, messaging and phone conferencing.
</P>
<P>
   The PTEK Ventures Portfolio includes Healtheon/WebMD,
VerticalOne, USA.Net, Derivion, S1 Corp., Webforia and i2Go.com.
The company recently ran a contest in which SingleShop.com, IKimbo,
Chutney and WorldWideTesting won the rights to a PTEK investment,
but terms are still being negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
