<HEADER>
A6749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-ART-NY     03-14 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL BOMBS ARMED PALESTINIAN CAMPS FOR THE FIRST TIME SINCE '86 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Israeli jets attacked targets in Lebanon for
the second day in a row Tuesday, giving what Arabic-language
newspapers here described as a military riposte to the 22-nation
Arab League for its weekend meeting in Beirut and its harsh
denunciation of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese guerrillas of Hezbollah, the Party of God,
responded with rocket and artillery attacks against Israeli
military positions in the border area.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli air raids have generally been held back since a bombing
on Feb. 8 destroyed three electricity generators. That assault
stirred widespread anger in the Arab world and prompted the Arab
League to switch its previously scheduled foreign ministers'
meeting to Beirut from Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Hezbollah appeared to have scaled back attacks on
Israeli military posts in southern Lebanon that had killed seven
Israeli soldiers over 18 days.
</P>
<P>
   But that restraint appears to have been thrown to the wind.
</P>
<P>
   No fresh casualties among Israel's 1,500-member occupation force
were reported. But Lebanese military statements said that a
Lebanese soldier and a civilian were killed by artillery on Monday
and that others were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese military officials reported more than 20 Israeli
bombing raids in the 24 hours from Monday morning to Tuesday and
dozens of artillery barrages, by far the heaviest onslaught since
the power plants were bombed.
</P>
<P>
   The targets included suspected Hezbollah bases close to the
nine-mile zone occupied by Israel in southern Lebanon; bases of
another Islamic radical group, Amal; and, in one artillery attack
that was apparently the work of a Christian-led Lebanese militia
group allied to the Israeli forces, a Lebanese army checkpoint near
southern Tyre.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most significant Israeli strikes _ and certainly the
ones that carried the clearest political message _ were attacks
Monday on two armed Palestinian camps close to the border between
Lebanon and Syria, 40 miles east of Beirut. The camps, near Yanta
and Koussaya, each less than 2 miles from the border, are
controlled by hard-line Palestinian groups that have rejected
Yasser Arafat's peace negotiations with Israel, the Popular Front
for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command and Fatah-Uprising,
another radical splinter group.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese military officials said the attacks on the camps were
Israel's first since 1986. They appeared to have been Israel's
answer to a warning from the Arab League over the weekend. The
League condemned Israeli ``aggression'' against Lebanon and said
that armed Palestinians based in Lebanon could resume attacks on
Israel after Israel's planned withdrawal from southern Lebanon this
year, unless Israel agreed to accompany the pullout with
negotiations for repatriating the huge Palestinian refugee
population in camps in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has always refused to countenance the return of the
Palestinians, most of whom are from families that became refugees
in the 1948 war that led to the founding of Israel. Israel has
instead demanded that Lebanon give the Palestinians permanent
residence and civic rights, like permission to work freely.
</P>
<P>
   In a communique on Saturday, the Arab League, at the behest of
Lebanon, said the 360,000 Palestinians that Lebanon says live in
the camps would be a ``time-bomb'' threatening Israel unless their
plight was resolved as part of a security deal covering the
pullout, which is scheduled to be carried out by early July.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli ministers mocked the demand, describing it as surreal
and worse. Former Prime Minister Shimon Peres suggested that it was
the first time in history that a nation had been threatened by an
occupied country for announcing that it was withdrawing its troops.
In the Israeli view, Lebanon and Syria, the two Arab nations
bordering Israel that have not signed peace agreements with the
government in Jerusalem, are trying to use the pullout announcement
to extract concessions on other long-running issues that need to be
addressed separately.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, which exercises de facto control in Lebanon through its
own military force of 35,000 troops, has in recent weeks appeared
to have been encouraging increased guerrilla pressures on the
Israeli troops in Lebanon as a means of pushing Israel toward
concessions for the Golan Heights, the Syrian territory that Israel
seized in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's demand for an unconditional return of the heights led to
the collapse of peace talks between the two countries in January.
</P>
<P>
   By attacking two Palestinian camps close to the Syrian border,
Israel appeared to have been sending a pointed message to Syria.
Although reporters were denied access to the two camps after the
bombings, there were signs that both suffered serious damage and,
possibly, casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Several Beirut newspapers reported seeing the smoldering ruins
of a jeep, an artillery piece and what appeared to be an arms depot
at the Popular Front base at Yanta, as well as what appeared to be
bloodstains on the ground at the entrance to the base.
</P>
<P>
   A commander at the base, using the nom de guerre of Abu Kifah,
acknowledged the accuracy of the strike. ``They scored direct
hits,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
