<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TROPICANA-FIELD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROPICANA FIELD TO GET NEW PLAYING SURFACE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRIS ANDERSON   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla. 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The Tampa Bay Devil Rays are installing a
$1 million artificial playing surface at Tropicana Field that looks
and plays more like natural grass than the current AstroTurf
surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would defy anyone to say it's not grass,'' Vince Naimoli,
owner of the Devil Rays, said.
</P>
<P>
   A product of FieldTurf, the surface will be the only one of its
kind in the major leagues. It is the same surface used at the
University of Nebraska's football stadium. Naimoli said the surface
will be in place at the indoor stadium for Tampa Bay's home opener
on April 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get it as close to an outdoor stadium as we can and
this accomplishes that,'' Naimoli said.
</P>
<P>
   The new surface should make a dramatic difference for players.
Several Devil Rays have taken ground balls on the turf and said it
is not as fast or as bouncy as the old one. The shortstop Kevin
Stocker said it is ``100 times'' better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did about every test we could and it passed with flying
colors,'' the Tampa Bay Manager Larry Rothschild said.
</P>
<P>
   The AstroTurf surface, used for the last two years, gave
Tropicana Field one of the hardest and fastest surfaces in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The all-dirt basepaths will remain. Stocker said there will
still be some tricky hops with balls bouncing from turf to dirt.
However, the new surface will be much softer and should lessen the
stress on players' knees. Fly balls hit into the outfield should no
longer jump over a player's head.
</P>
<P>
   Naimoli said the life expectancy of the new infield surface is
eight to 10 years. The outfield is expected to last up to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The new surface is made from a synthetic blend of fibers that
are crafted into a pattern similar to natural grass. It is put down
over a base of sand and rubber recycled from old tires and shoes.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
