<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCANTA15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Incanta strikes high-speed deal
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Incanta Inc. this week announced a pact with San
Francisco-based Northpoint Communications Group, aimed at
delivering music and video services over high-speed lines.
</P>
<P>
   Incanta, a 6-month-old, Atlanta-based start-up, will provide
technology to Northpoint that will be used over networks using
digital subscriber lines _ DSL _ in 33 markets. The companies
released no financial details, other than to say that the agreement
calls for them to share revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Incanta, an ambitious, 30-employee company founded by former
executives of Nortel Networks, aims to provide the technology
behind the delivery of top-quality music and video to users of
high-speed Internet services. However, Incanta will likely not be a
household name to most users, since the company will sell its
systems to Internet service providers that will, in turn, use them
to deliver services to subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Trial versions of Incanta's music player have been in use for
about five months. Prestige Cable TV Inc. has been conducting a
similar trial with some of its customers in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to release similar technologies for use with
video later this year. Incanta says the software, which users will
download from their ISP, will permit those users to receive
personalized programming, including sportscasts that include only
highlights and stories the user requests.
</P>
<P>
   Incanta's technology is designed for use on high-speed lines
like cable modems or DSL, service known as broadband for its
ability to handle the great quantities of data needed for video and
digital audio.
</P>
<P>
   Incanta cites studies by International Data Group showing the
market for broadband growing 80 percent a year through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   IDC predicts that one-third of all households will have
broadband links to the Net by that year. IDC also believes that
entertainment will likely account for the lion's share of broadband
use.
</P>
<P>
   Cyber Dialogue, another research firm, says 61.5 million people
use the Internet, and that 70 percent of them search for
entertainment-related content. Cyber Dialogue concludes that
entertainment has evolved into the ``unifying force of modern
commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Creaxion, an Atlanta-based marketing company, said it has been
hired by Incanta to handle the launch of the company's music
service. Creaxion plans ads in print and online starting March
19th. The ad campaign is planned for Atlanta, Austin, San Antonio
and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
