<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPUS-BINGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BINGE-DRINKING CONTINUES APACE ON CAMPUSES, SURVEY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   College students are still drinking to get drunk. Despite
efforts to curb drinking on campus, the percentage of students
indulging in alcohol binges has stayed roughly the same through the
1990s, and the percentage of frequent bingers has increased,
researchers said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the percentage of teetotalers also increased somewhat,
according to the survey released Tuesday by the Harvard School of
Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   Those who do binge the most tend to be white, live in a
fraternity or sorority, and have a history of drinking in high
school, according to the study led by Henry Wechsler, a social
psychologist who followed up is 1993 and 1997 drinking studies.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-area colleges and universities increased attention and
efforts to curb college campus drinking after well-publicized
incidents such as the death of MIT freshman Scott Krueger in 1997.
Last November, an MIT fraternity was disbanded after six Wellesley
College freshman were served alcohol at the fraternity. Last week
the Licensing Board for the City of Boston unanimously voted to
suspend the rock club Paradise's license for six months for
violations, including serving alcohol to minors.
</P>
<P>
   But Wechsler said efforts decrease college drinking haven't
worked yet. ``It may be too early. I may be expecting too much,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, Wechsler defined a binge drinker as a man who
drank at least five drinks in a row, or a woman who drank four, at
least once in the two weeks before the survey. A frequent binge
drinker had binged three or more times in the two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 study found the population of binge drinkers had stayed
the same since 1997, at 44 percent, and frequent binge drinkers
rose last year to 22.7 percent of the student population, up from
19.8 percent in 1993 and 20.9 percent in 1997. Among fraternity or
sorority houses, Wechsler's study found that 78.9 percent of
students living in fraternity or sorority housing were binge
drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   More than 14,000 college students at 119 four-year colleges
nationwide filled out the surveys that were mailed to them by
Wechsler and his colleagues. The project was sponsored by the
Robert Wood Johnson Foundation and the survey has a margin of error
was plus or minus 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make the situation harder for college administrators, most
of these students do not feel they have a problem, and the large
majority consider themselves moderate drinkers,'' said Wechsler.
But he pointed out that the majority of college students are not
binge drinkers and one-third are living in alcohol-free residence
halls.
</P>
<P>
   But others have questioned if Wechsler's definition, which does
not take into account body weight or time, has perpetrated a notion
that college students are drinking more than they really are.
</P>
<P>
   William DeJong, director of the Higher Education Center for
Alcohol and Other Drug Prevention, said clinicians define
binge-drinking to be an ``out-of-control'' drinking habit, and said
that students could reasonably consumer five drinks over a night
with food and not be drunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students have hooted at the notion that five drinks is
considered a binge,'' DeJong said.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Phalen, program director for alcohol and other drug
education at Northeastern University, one of the universities in
Wechsler's study, said that one of the newest ways to targeting
students is social marketing, and telling students about the huge
gap in perception and reality of college drinking. Phalen said that
although alcohol is the number one problem on college campuses, the
notion that everybody is drinking heavily feeds into the
misconception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal use on (the Northeastern) campus is moderation or
non-use,'' said Phalen. In a 1998 survey, Phalen said that 72
percent of Northeastern students drank five or less drinks on an
average week, and 25 percent didn't drink.
</P>
<P>
   Although colleges are talking about incorporating more alcohol
education, MIT junior Todd Esguerra said that students won't
listen. ``When you are told not to drink, that makes you want to do
it more,'' said Esguerra.
</P>
<P>
   But the percentage of students who don't drink at all has been
rising steadily, from 15.4 percent in 1993 to 18.9 percent in 1997
and finally, 19.2 percent in 1999, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   Ed McGlothin, a junior at Florida State University and describes
himself as an occasional drinker, said that after pledging into a
fraternity during his freshman year, he became disgusted with
taking care of other students who became sick from drinking.
Students like McGlothin are working with school administrators
brainstorm ideas to curb college drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Campbell, spokesman for MIT, said that two years ago, the
budget for student events was tripled to $300,000 a year to plan
more alcohol-free events.
</P>
<P>
   While the study found students who take part in ``industrial
strength alcohol consumption'' have increased risks of missing
class, getting in trouble, damaging property or getting hurt, it
also found that such drinkers have ``secondhand effects'' on their
peers.
</P>
<P>
   Students at high-binge campuses were twice as likely to report
being assaulted, awakened, or kept from studying by drinking
students than were nonbinge drinkers at campuses where it was less
common.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Wiegert, a University of Nebraska-Lincoln senior and Beta
Theta Pi fraternity member who used to drink more than 10 drinks a
night, said he quit drinking excessively when he realized he often
said stupid things while drunk and once broke a table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a cost-benefit analysis for me,'' the economics major
said. ``I have yet to come up with one benefit to high-risk
drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Corey Dulling contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
