<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ITC DeltaCom in pact with IBM to give customers Net support
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ITC DeltaCom has announced a deal in which the company
can use IBM to provide customers with Internet support, including
the capability of sending certified mail via the Net.
</P>
<P>
   The service continues efforts by West Point-based ITC DeltaCom
to shift toward sectors that are among the hottest in
telecommunications, the demand for data and Internet services. ITC
DeltaCom has a network that includes 8,250 miles of fiber-optic
lines, but the pact announced this week is more about service that
will be provided through e-DeltaCom, the new company created
recently by ITC DeltaCom to focus on the data and Internet
business.
</P>
<P>
   ITC DeltaCom expects to invest about $250 million during the
next 36 months to develop the e-DeltaCom subsidiary, said Andrew M.
Walker, chief executive officer of ITC DeltaCom.
</P>
<P>
   Combining with IBM enhances e-DeltaCom's offering to customers,
Walker said. ``This relationship fulfills a marketplace demand by
bringing together the two companies' networking and technology
expertise to create a one-stop shop for integrated, hosted
e-business solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The new ITC DeltaCom subsidiary will be based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is planning to open data centers elsewhere in
Georgia, as well as in Florida and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ITC DeltaCom also announced that Morgan Stanley Senior Funding,
Banc of America Securities and Goldman Sachs Credit Partners will
underwrite a $160 million senior secured credit facility.
</P>
<P>
   The company will use the money to fund e-DeltaCom, as well as
other needs in the company, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
