<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6758 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CENTRAL-ASIA-BOOK-REV     03-14 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTRAL-ASIA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOURNAMENT OF SHADOWS': IMPERIALISM AT ANY COST IN THE MONGOL LAND
MASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) (Michael
Rosenthal is the author of ``The Character Factory: Baden-Powell's
Boy Scouts and the Imperatives of Empire.'') (DW) 
 By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1904, the British geographer Halford J. Mackinder delivered
an influential lecture proclaiming the geopolitical importance of
what he identified as the ``heart-land of Euro- Asia.'' Pointing
ominously toward the Russians, he suggested that mastery of this
land mass could produce another vast Mongol empire capable of world
domination.
</P>
<P>
   But even without his official warning, the British had been
maneuvering for almost a century to prevent Russian control of
Central Asia. ``Tournament of Shadows,'' a Russian count, K.V.
Nesselrode, called the struggle. For the British, it was the Great
Game.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tribute to Rudyard Kipling's artistry that the Great
Game became forever etched in the Western imagination through his
1901 novel, ``Kim,'' depicting the successful efforts of his young
orphan hero, Kimball O'Hara, to resist Russian incursions in India.
If Kipling popularized the term, however, he didn't invent it.
Credit for that goes to Arthur Conolly, a young British officer
devoted to the game (``a great game, a noble game,'' he wrote to a
friend) and one of its grisliest losers.
</P>
<P>
   Committed to the sacred calling of frustrating Russian
ambitions, Conolly managed to insist in 1842 that he be allowed to
try to persuade the unpleasant Emir of Bukhara to support British
interests and in the process release a fellow officer whom he had
imprisoned. For his efforts Conolly was subjected for many months
to the Emir's infamous bug pit, after which his public beheading
probably came as a relief.
</P>
<P>
   An illuminating and engaging history of the Game, ``Tournament
of Shadows'' is interested primarily in the players _ the spies,
explorers, soldiers, cartographers, mystics, biologists and museum
collectors, among others _ who risked and not infrequently lost
their lives while participating in it.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing upon an immense range of secondary sources as well as
original archival research, the authors, Karl E. Meyer and Shareen
Blair Brysac, scour the mountains and deserts of Central Asia
pursuing the exploits of the intrepid, possessed and often
pathological men immersed in the dreams of empire and adventure.
</P>
<P>
   The specimens of behavior that Meyer, a former editorial writer
for The New York Times, and Brysac, his wife and a producer of
television documentaries, bring back from their travels are as
exotic as any of the rare flora their subjects discovered in the
hills. We meet the ruthless Nikolai Mikhailovich Przhevalsky,
considered Russia's greatest explorer, who loathed the Asian people
whose land he traversed in four expeditions. An implacable big-game
hunter who mourned the death of his dogs, an army officer who
disliked the army, he was celebrated by Chekhov, used as a model
for a character by Nabokov in ``The Gift,'' and even reputed to be
Stalin's biological father. His last book suggested exterminating
all Mongolians and Tibetans and replacing them with Cossacks.
</P>
<P>
   We follow Col. Francis Younghusband's manipulations of the
British government until, for no particularly compelling reason, he
is finally given permission in 1904 to invade the legendary
``forbidden'' Tibetan city of Lhasa. To support a force of 2,000
fighting men he assembled some 7,000 mules, 5,200 bullocks, 1,500
Tibetan yaks and 2,900 Nepalese yaks, along with 10,000 porters.
His own personal effects, packed in 29 containers, included 67
shirts, 19 coats (including a full-dress coat, a morning coat, an
Assam silk coat, two jaeger coats, a Chesterfield coat, a poshteen
long coat and a Chinese fur coat), as well as at least five hats.
Younghusband was clearly a man who liked to be prepared, as the
slaughter of some 800 Tibetans at the cost of 14 British wounded in
two preliminary skirmishes indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing primarily (and appropriately) on the classic Great Game
confrontation of Russian and British, ``Tournament of Shadows''
also attends to American dabblings in the region. We are introduced
to Januarius MacGahan, whose reporting of Turkish massacres of
Bulgarians led to the Russo-Turkish War, and to William Rockhill,
translator of Tibetan texts, friend of Theodore Roosevelt and the
first American to advise the Dalai Lama. Rockhill's 10-month,
8,000-mile journey through Tibet in 1891 came to an end when he ran
out of food and had to subsist on tea for a number of days.
</P>
<P>
   We meet Roosevelt's two sons, Kermit and Theodore, and their
friend Suydam Cutting, who collected birds and animals from their
Tibetan expeditions for American museums. Agreeing to help market
Tibetan wool in the United States, Cutting received three pairs of
Lhasa apsos from the grateful Dalai Lama, and promptly returned to
this country to become the dogs' first breeder.
</P>
<P>
   Most enigmatic of all, we encounter the Russian mystic and
artist Nicholas Roerich, whose friendship with the American
Secretary of Agriculture (and future presidential candidate) Henry
Wallace led him on an expedition to Central Asia in 1933 in search
of drought-resistant grass to replant the disastrous American Dust
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   With all the scheming and the spying, the interfering and the
blundering (my favorite anecdote concerns a British agent who so
confused the Bolshevik secret police in Turkestan that they
recruited him to hunt for himself), were there any unequivocal
benefits that emerged from the Great Game?
</P>
<P>
   For Meyer and Brysac, the answer is simple: knowledge. However
nefarious or self-serving their motives, the men who endured severe
hardships crisscrossing unknown terrain generated precious
information about Central Asia's physical and cultural geography.
They measured the heights of mountain passes, determined the
sources of rivers, produced detailed maps and took valuable
photographs. Whatever else they achieved, it is their letters,
diaries, charts and sketches that constitute, as the authors nicely
put it, ``the authentic jewels in the imperial crown.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the geopolitical advantages sought by the two main
competitors, the results are less auspicious. Nothing could save
Tibet from being swallowed by China. The irony is not lost upon
Meyer and Brysac that when the ultimate British nightmare came to
pass and the Soviet Union invaded Afghanistan, its major
consequence was to speed up the dissolution of the Soviet empire. A
Great Game to be sure, but in retrospect perhaps not the sort that
could ever be won. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `TOURNAMENT OF SHADOWS'
</P>
<P>
   The Great Game and the Race for Empire in Central Asia
</P>
<P>
   By Karl E. Meyer and Shareen Blair Brysac
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 646 pages. Counterpoint. $35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1947EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
