<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-BACKLOG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY, OTHERS, STRUGGLE TO HANDLE THE BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hell hath no fury like an anxious investor who can't
make a trade.
</P>
<P>
   A wave of anger is sweeping the nation's growing ranks of online
brokerage customers as Fidelity Investments and other major brokers
are facing such high volumes of online trading and phone calls that
they can barely keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity spokesman Jim Griffin said that, on average, the Boston
investment giant's customers are making 170,000 trades a day this
month, up from 94,000 per day a year ago. The company has seen its
25 heaviest trading days ever since Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously are aware of the volume increases, and we are
trying to do the best that we can to service the customer,''
Griffin said. The company is calling on its ``corporate reserve''
staff to pitch in handling customer calls. It's also plans to add
several hundred people to its 3,200 phone staff over the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
   That won't be soon enough to satisfy Alan Cohen. The investor
said he's yanking his six-figure account out of Fidelity after
waiting on hold for more than 20 minutes recently for a service
representative. His complaints fell on deaf ears, he said, and even
his urgent request to shift some money to a separate account took
two business days, instead of one, as Fidelity had promised him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's dangerous,'' Cohen said. ``What was supposed to get
done, didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen is hardly alone in his ire. Do-it-yourself investors are
trading and checking accounts online and via automated phone
services as never before. The discount brokerage business has
quadrupled since 1995, to $1.4 trillion. More than half of that is
now invested online, according to Cerulli Associates Inc., a Boston
research firm. By 2004, Cerulli estimates, those assets will hit $3
trillion, with 85 percent of trades handled online.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of growth, it's no surprise that, when Web sites
falter, and when the stock market is particularly volatile,
discount brokers' phone lines clog fast.
</P>
<P>
   John Payne, a Cerulli consultant, said, ``All the online brokers
are struggling to keep pace with the demand, and their service
groups are falling behind.''
</P>
<P>
   DLJ Direct has had trouble with its Web site for two days. A
message posted there Monday directed online investors to call a rep
to make their trades. Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., the king of online
brokerage, concedes it's having major service trouble lately too.
</P>
<P>
   Said a senior spokesman at Schwab, ``During periods of extreme
market volatility, our customers have been forced to wait much
longer periods of time than we would like.'' He added, ``It's
frustrating to our clients and it's frustrating to us as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab logged 3.5 million customer phone calls in February,
compared to 2.5 million a year earlier. The company is hiring 300
new service representatives a month this year to add to its 7,000
base.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity attributes its jump in calls to the many recent days of
100- to 200-point dips and hops of the Nasdaq and the Dow. Tax
season always brings more customer demand for personal help,
Griffin said. And hot stock offerings and the bull market in
technology stocks have piqued investor interest across the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Fidelity's experience when Palm Inc., the maker of
trendy handheld computers, went public early this month. Fidelity
got about 2,000 calls around 10 p.m. _ a normally quiet time _ from
customers who wanted to know what the IPO price was and to submit
buy orders.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the challenge discount brokers face in this steamy
market. ``Customer service is being redefined in the Internet
age,'' Cerulli's Payne observed. ``They expect the same level of
service they would get from a full-service broker.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 1947EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
