u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-PERFECT-BO     03-14 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PERFECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFECT DAY FOR THE SOX _ 6 TIMES OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ When Toronto's Chris Woodward hit a shot to
left with one out in the ninth inning Tuesday _ a shot that seemed
ready, willing, and able to clear the left field fence _ Red Sox
pitcher Rod Beck wasn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been watching batting practice,'' said the reliever, ``and
I said, `This ball's not going out today.' That wind was gusting
all day and balls were crushed in batting practice and they weren't
going out. I said, `If the ball's in the air, it's not going out.'
''
</P>
<P>
   On a warm and still July afternoon in Fenway Park, Woodward's
drive might have struck the Citgo sign in Kenmore Square. But
Tuesday? Beck merely shrugged as he watched the flight of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, back in the Red Sox clubhouse, some nine or 10 of the
players were screaming at the television, Jose Offerman the
loudest. Offerman was there with Nomar Garciaparra and a handful of
other starters whose spring training day was done early.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Woodward hit the ball to the fence, Offerman helped keep
it in the park by screaming at the TV,'' said Red Sox pitcher Dan
Smith. ``Offerman's taking credit for it.''
</P>
<P>
   For saving ``it.''
</P>
<P>
   A perfect game for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it means something,'' said Smith, one of the perfect
pitchers in the Red Sox' 5-0 win. ``Has this ever happened? Six
guys pitching? Who knows? It might never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooperstown has yet to call, but six Red Sox pitchers
accomplished a feat that _ spring training or no spring training _
is still remarkable. Twenty-seven Blue Jays went up to the plate _
to face Pedro Martinez at the start and Beck at the end _ and 27
Blue Jays were retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what was going on,'' said Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams. ``You see three eggs on the wall, you're hoping to see
nine before it.'' True enough, the three goose eggs for hits, runs,
and errors were on the scoreboard, but so were the nine goose eggs
for innings played.
</P>
<P>
   No longtime Red Sox watcher could remember the team ever
throwing a no-hitter in spring training, let alone a perfect game.
Nor could veteran baseball watchers recall a spring training
perfect game by any team. The Elias Sports Bureau said it does not
keep track of spring training statistics, although the last
no-hitter in spring training came four years ago when the Angels
beat San Francisco, 15-0.
</P>
<P>
   The last Red Sox perfect game was that famous (or infamous)
perfect game with an asterisk, back on June 23, 1917, when Babe
Ruth started for Boston and walked the first batter. Ruth
complained about the call on ball four, was tossed out of the game
by the umpires, and Ernie Shore came on to retire the next 27
Washington Senators he faced. Shore was credited with a perfect
game.
</P>
<P>
   The only other Red Sox perfect game came on May 5, 1904, when Cy
Young himself mowed down all 27 Philadelphia A's.
</P>
<P>
   Spring training or no, perfect games by the Red Sox are as rare
as . . . well, World Series wins by the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched a perfect game! I pitched a perfect game!,''
Martinez screamed in mock excitement after Beck retired the 27th
Blue Jay, Alberto Castillo, on a strikeout. Perhaps most remarkable
of all, it was only then that Beck learned what he and the other
five Red Sox pitchers had accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't find out about it until I turned around to shake the
guys' hands and I looked up and I saw it on the board,'' said Beck.
``I saw, `perfect game,' and I said, `Hey, pretty cool.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Beck had seen the first six innings ``and I knew we had a
no-hitter but then I had to go and stretch, and you can't see
what's going on from where I was. They're moving players in and
out, they're changing pitchers, you can't see from our bullpen, so
it's a hard thing to keep track of. So I didn't know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when he took the mound in the ninth?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Beck, ``and I'm kind of embarrassed about that, to
tell you the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Four times Martinez went to 3-and-2 counts in his three innings
and each time retired the batter. Fernando De La Cruz, who pitched
the fourth and fifth innings, said he knew about the perfect game
``and it feels good to pitch in one. It feels very good.''
</P>
<P>
   But Smith, Rheal Cormier, Rich Garces, and Beck, all of whom
pitched one inning each, said they did not know of the perfect game
when they took the mound. And each said maybe it's better that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went out there to get my 1-2-3 outs,'' said Garces. ``I
was here in the clubhouse before I pitched and I went out there not
realizing what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as soon as I get to the weight room, it was like all the
guys were saying, mostly Nomar, `Hey, man, we've got a perfect game
going.' And they say, `You pitched a perfect game.' And I say,
`OK.' Hopefully now, it happens in the real season.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was with the Expos last July when the Yankees' David Cone
pitched a perfect game against Montreal ``and it's two in two years
for me now,'' said the righty, who pitched the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a streak going now, but one of these years, I'd like
to do it myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went running after my inning, and then I worked out and then
I got here in the clubhouse in the ninth and I heard on TV it was a
perfect game. I had no clue.''
</P>
<P>
   Better that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw a 3-and-2 slider to get the last guy out I faced
(Castillo in the sixth),'' said Smith of the pitch that caught the
Toronto catcher looking at strike three. ``I thought it was over
the plate but I don't think he did. And then Beck says to me after
the game, `A 3-and-2 slider, huh?' and I say, `I didn't know . . .
perfect game . . . I didn't know.' I don't know if I'd throw a
3-and-2 slider in a perfect game.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston reserve Joe Siddall, who caught the final three innings,
said, ``It's a great achievement, even if it's a spring training
game. This is a great feat, no matter what. Everybody strives for
perfection, and to achieve it in this game is pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the pitchers Siddall caught was Cormier, who said he was
clueless as well. After he pitched the seventh, Cormier ran, ``and
then I went out to see my wife in the parking lot. I didn't know
anything about a perfect game. I had no clue. Somebody just told me
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Clueless or not, the six Red Sox pitchers who put ``three eggs
on the wall,'' as Williams called it, accomplished a feat. Even if
they don't get that call from Cooperstown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
