<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TENNIS-TIPS-ONLINE-NY     03-14 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENNIS-TIPS-ONLINE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOLLETTIERI POINTERS FOR FREE? AT LEAST FOR NOW  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW SAUER   
 Herald-Journal, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ Nick Bollettieri, who has trained seven No. 1
tennis players, is the first big name at the Mysportsguru.com site,
which will link customers with ``gurus'' from their favorite
sports.
</P>
<P>
   The site, scheduled to debut in early April, will offer the
information for free for the time being. Consider that in the
context of Bollettieri's $1,500-per-hour fee for an hour of
one-on-one coaching or his $500-per-hour charge if you take the
step to enroll at his Bradenton-based tennis academy in Bradenton.
</P>
<P>
   The Fairfield, Conn.-based Internet company says it will display
Bollettieri's philosophy, animated demonstrations of his ideal
forehands, backhands, serves and other fundamentals and weekly tips
from the man who trained, among others, Andre Agassi, Boris Becker,
Jim Courier and Monica Seles.
</P>
<P>
   Bollettieri and International Management Group, a major sports
talent agency that owns the tennis academy, are partners in
Mysportsguru.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bollettieri estimated that he has spent between 2,000 and 3,000
hours working with the Internet company's managers developing his
portion of the site. He found the virtual coach idea intriguing.
``I'm going to be able to be the coach no matter where you are,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, right now, Bollettieri can't see how a student he has
coached via the Internet is doing. Eventually, though, personal
attention might come. Mysportsguru.com. is developing a one-on-one,
paid instructional format that would feature a live Bollettieri or
other coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might not get Nick every time, but you could get a
Bollettieri instructor,'' said John Ragland, the Web site's
36-year-old founder and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The site also seeks to personalize instruction based on
someone's experience.
</P>
<P>
   Mysportsguru.com is backed by venture capital from investors
with Ragland, who has launched other companies, leading the way.
Besides IMG, the site has enlisted the International Performance
Institute and the David Leadbetter Golf Academy, in addition to yet
undisclosed partners and gurus.
</P>
<P>
   The site has competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Brilliant Digital Entertainment, a Woodland Hills, Calif.
company, is designing animated sports tutorials using
``motion-capture'' technology similar to that of Mysportsguru.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bollettieri and fellow coach Greg Hill traveled to a studio in
Brooklyn, New York, last year for the site. Hill, wired with about
40 sensors, went through various tennis moves captured by the
sensors and on video to be converted into a digital format by
computers.
</P>
<P>
   While Hill will appear in various forms _ and for that matter,
genders _ on Mysportsguru.com, it remains his moves under the
animation, Ragland said.
</P>
<P>
   The animation is two-dimensional and fairly short. That allows
the images to be quickly downloaded on a modem. Speed was important
for a site trying to get as big a slice as possible of the 140
million people in the United States who play sports.
</P>
<P>
   So how will the site make money?
</P>
<P>
   One way is advertising content. Another is selling actual goods,
including Bollettieri's videos, books and other paraphernalia, but
also equipment and apparel tied to specific sports. That helps ease
the notion for Bollettieri of releasing, for free, some of the
techniques he has developed during the last 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run they will develop dollars through
advertisement, sponsors and things like that, and hopefully we'll
go public or be bought out by a major company,'' Bollettieri said.
``I'm certainly not putting thousands and thousands of dollars into
something if I don't think it's going to be a success
business-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Sauer writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.
The Herald-Tribune is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
