<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6767 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WEB-HOTELSUPPLIES15-C     03-14 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-HOTELSUPPLIES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New supply line for hotels
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Triplicate? Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   A dot-com start-up is taking the paperwork out of procurement
for hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Hsupply.com, which was launched earlier this year, offers online
procurement services to the lodging industry, drastically
streamlining the often frustrating and time-consuming flow of
faxes, snail mail and phone calls between buyers and sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Procurement is ``very people and paper intensive,'' said Ravi
Kalakota, the company's 32-year-old founder and chief executive. He
said hotels spend about $16 billion annually on supplies and
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, as labor gets tighter and tighter, people look for
technology-based solutions.'' An expert in electronic commerce and
a former Eminent Scholar at Georgia State University, Kalakota
estimates that managers who do it the old way spend an average of
$100 in labor costs for a purchase order to work its way through
the process. The order takes about five sheets of paper _ each
going to a different person.
</P>
<P>
   Kalakota is betting an opportunity to streamline that process
will hook his company up with a hunger in many industries and will
tap into the lucrative and burgeoning business-to-business use of
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company is in the process of raising $20 million to
$30 million in additional capital.
</P>
<P>
   Once the system is perfected, Kalakota hopes to go after even
bigger clients and has his eye on companies such as behemoth Bass
Hotels &AMP; Resorts, which has headquarters for its Americas
operations in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a ways to go,'' he said. ``You have to think of
this as electricity. Initially, when electricity came out, people
were skeptical. The same thing is happening with respect to
(online) procurement. Procurement is the foundation on which
business is built. Without procurement there is no business.''
</P>
<P>
   And swift, inexpensive procurement may increase the
profitability of a company.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Brian Rafferty's experience blazing the paper trail of
procurement.
</P>
<P>
   Rafferty, former general manager of the Comfort Suites Duluth,
used to spend five to six hours a week ordering supplies and
processing invoices.
</P>
<P>
   There was soap, shampoo, linens and cleaning supplies that
needed to be ordered twice a week or monthly. And don't forget the
bagels, fruit and coffee for the continental breakfast. That had to
be done three to four times a week using several vendors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time worrying whether the order was going to
come in right,'' said Rafferty, now an area manager for Noble
Investment Group, one of hsupply.com's early clients. Noble is
testing the service in five hotels. ``I was faxing back and forth
and playing phone tag with voice mail.''
</P>
<P>
   But now with just the click of a mouse, there's a ``tremendous
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafferty, who is Noble's liaison with hsupply.com, said many of
his headaches have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tracking is really the biggest plus,'' he said. ``You can see
past performance and ordering history and gauge what you need. And
I have a very high comfort level that when you place an order, it
will be on time and consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   The process has worked so well that Noble plans to roll it out
systemwide to its 25 hotels by midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   Hsupply.com is also offering the service to customers on the go.
</P>
<P>
   The company is making its service reachable by hand-held mobile
devices. With its new wireless capability, the company will enable
busy executives to make, approve and check the status of orders
instantly _ all without going back to the office.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also developing regional distribution points to
shorten supply lines to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say I have taken e-business research to another stage,
and we plan to devote the better part of the next 10 years refining
procurement sites like
</P>
<P>
   hsupply,'' said Kalakota, who was the chair professor of
electronic commerce of the Georgia Research Alliance and director
of the Center for Digital Commerce at Georgia State University. He
has since left those jobs to devote his energy full-time to the new
Internet-based business.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Woodworth, executive managing director of PKF Consulting's
hospitality research group, said the hotel industry has a mixed
experience with e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, it's let me get three bids for every item that I am
going to buy,'' he said. ``Then I have to evaluate the bid, make a
decision and make the purchase order. That has to be approved, then
I send the bill to accounting and they process it. There are lots
of steps.''
</P>
<P>
   The value of companies like hsupply is obvious in terms of
efficiencies and cost savings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't that many online companies out there, so in my
opinion, they haven't begun to even scratch the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's focus is on large operators and clients, including
US Franchise Systems, the Atlanta-based owner of the Best Inns &AMP;
Suites, Hawthorn Suites and Microtel Inns &AMP; Suites brands.
</P>
<P>
   And Kalakota is the perfect person to jump-start this area of
the lodging industry, said Woodworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ravi is one of those people who absolutely see the future
before the other 99.9 percent of the rest of us do,'' he said.
``Ravi literally wrote the book on e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalakota started the business a year ago with four partners, two
of whom had extensive experience in the hotel industry. His
second-in-command is President and Chief Operating Officer Lawrence
W. Hall, former COO of Talus Solutions Inc., a leading revenue
management firm for the hotel, airline, rental car and cruise line
industries. He was also director of hotel systems and
telecommunications worldwide for Sheraton Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The two were brought together by Noro-Moseley Partners, one of
hsupply's venture capital investors. ``I wanted somebody who was an
operator to help me run the company,'' Kalakota said. ``It's been
very complementary. I'm more of the strategist and also responsible
for raising money. Larry's more internally focused on operating the
day-to-day operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Kalakota, who grew up in southern India, received
about $600,000 in critical seed money from angel investors.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the company landed on the radar screens of venture
capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, Noro-Moseley Partners and Mellon Ventures each
invested $2.5 million into the start-up. At the time, hsupply had
eight employees. That's since grown to 70.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Taetle, a general partner with Noro-Moseley, said many
traditional industries, including the once stodgy automotive
industry, are conducting more and more business online.
</P>
<P>
   Taetle said the lodging industry is just the company's first
target. He said the technology can also be applied to other areas
including assisted living, restaurants and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone is embracing the fact that e-commerce is
going to deliver tremendous cost savings because this will simplify
the supply chain under which most of these companies operate,'' he
said. ``Even those industries that are less technologically
receptive than the hotel industry have embraced e-commerce already,
and with the hsupply solution, it's just going to accelerate the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Ernest Holsendolph
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
