u f BC-EUROPE-U.S.-PRIVACY-N     03-14 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-U.S.-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND EUROPE REACH ACCORD ON DATA PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) By JERI CLAUSING    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States and Europe completed the wording on Tuesday
for a data privacy agreement that will put strict new controls on
how American companies collect personal information about European
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which was reached in principle last month, would
require American companies that gather personal information from
Europeans to join so-called ``safe harbor'' programs, under which
they would agree not to gather or use personal information about
European consumers without the consumers' express consent.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which has been under negotiation for nearly two
years, will be put to the European Union's 15 member states for
preliminary approval March 31, union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reached an important stage today,'' the European Union's
negotiator, John Mogg, said at a news conference in Brussels. ``I
feel ready to recommend to authorities that the safe harbor meets
our criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was negotiated in response to a 1998 data privacy
law that gives European Union nations the right to halt certain
information from being sent to countries that do not have adequate
data protection. The United States does not have similar data
protection guidelines. It relies mainly on a system in which
businesses regulate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of the agreement deals mainly with transfers of data
between offices of multinational companies. Two more complicated
issues _ how that directive will apply to financial services and
cyberspace _ remain in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Mogg said the European Union decided to move forward with an
agreement that excluded financial services because legislation on
that issue was still pending in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As for cyberspace, the European Union nations themselves remain
in dispute as to whether the directive applies to businesses
outside of Europe that collect information online from European
consumers, said Gerard de Graf, an official in the union's
Washington office.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Clinton administration official said that Web sites
would be encouraged to follow the safe-harbor proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement does not try to solve the issue of
jurisdiction,'' the officials said. ``What the safe harbor idea
does is advise our industry as to what to do to conduct business
with Europe and not run afoul of their laws. This advice applies
equally to Web sites,'' who he said would have an ``enormous
advantage'' in Europe by following the rules.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is not expected to take effect until summer, with
the first review of whether or not it meets Europe's expectations
planned a year after that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
