<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6780 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BALD-PRESIDENT-COX     03-14 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALD-PRESIDENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hair to the chief
 &HT;    By Chris Hutchins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On March 1, George W. Bush was cornered. David Letterman was
razzing him about international politics. Specifically, about how
the Republican presidential candidate didn't know the leaders of
some foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   The punch line? He asked Bush if he knew the name of the
president of the Hair Club for Men. Bush's response:
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not talking about ... Sy Sperling, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   While the audience laughed in New York, Sperling almost fell off
his treadmill in his Hillsboro Beach home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I flipped out. I couldn't believe it,'' Sperling says. ``I
mean, I know people know who I am, but this was amazing. I guess
advertising works!''
</P>
<P>
   But Sperling started thinking about Bush's response. He started
thinking about hair _ not an uncommon thing to do, in his business.
He made a connection, and got the word out to The Media.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just may be a direct link between having hair and
becoming president,'' says an urgently faxed press release from
Hair Club for Men. ``It's a formula: The candidate with most hair
wins.... It's been documented that since the dawn of the television
age, every elected president since Kennedy, and including Kennedy,
has had hair.''
</P>
<P>
   The two exceptions, Gerald Ford and Lyndon Johnson, ``were not
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from this year's primaries, Sperling could be on to
something. Al Gore, despite a ``sandtrap'' in the back, has great
hair _ and balding Bill Bradley is out of the race. And Bush? He's
got more than that shiny-scalped McCain fellow.
</P>
<P>
   Is Sperling's theory fact ... or a follicle fallacy? The Post
called some pundits in Washington to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Bill Clinton did have industrial-strength hair,'' admits
Terry Michael, executive director of the Washington Center for
Politics and Journalism. ``But most presidents in our television
era have had hair problems. Johnson, Nixon, they had hair loss. I
don't think you need hair to be president. And in some cases, you
don't need anything under the hair to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn Ververs, managing editor at The Hotline _ an online
political news service _ disagrees. There could be some truth to
this hair business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physical appearance has so much to do with a candidate,'' he
says. ``In the modern television world, you gotta have a good
image. You gotta look good, man. It's like what Billy Crystal used
to say: `You look mah-velous. It doesn't matter how you feel, baby.
It's how you look that counts.'''
</P>
<P>
   And if the look doesn't work, adapt. Take Al Gore: Our
Washington-types say they've noticed a change in his hair. That
sandtrap has been getting smaller since last fall, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something's going on,'' Ververs says. ``It's shrinking. Either
he's got a great hairstylist, or he's buying a lot of that
hair-in-a-can stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels agrees: ``They've clearly made a conscious decision
that hair is important, that (Gore's) hair loss was somehow
interfering with his voter appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Ratcliff, of the Vice President's Press Office, tried to
quash the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing new to report,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That's a crock, quips Ververs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Americans knew how all this political stuff really worked,
they'd be mortified. Image is everything here,'' he says. ``And
something as simple as hair could help someone win an election.
Think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling already has. And he should know: He's also a client.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are hair-conscious,'' he says. ``It's just the nature of
the beast.''
</P>
<P>
   chrishutchins(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
