<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6781 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-JUDGES-DISCLOSE-NYT     03-14 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-DISCLOSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDICIAL FINANCIAL REPORTS WILL BE ALLOWED ON INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The judges who set policy for the federal judiciary
announced on Tuesday that the judges' annual financial disclosure
statements would no longer be withheld from organizations that want
to put the information on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The action taken by the Judicial Conference of the United States
repudiated a policy adopted in December by its own financial
disclosure committee, which refused to provide the reports to
APBnews.com, an Internet site that requested them. The Web site,
based in New York, then filed a federal lawsuit accusing the
committee and the conference of violating both the First Amendment
and the Ethics in Government Act, which requires public disclosure
of the annual reports.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sauter, APB's chief executive, said in an interview on
Tuesday that the judges' turnabout marked ``a good day for the
public's right to know about some of the most important people in
our government.'' He said the Internet ``is not just a legitimate
means, but a superior means of disseminating these documents.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Zaid, the Web site's lawyer, said other issues needed to be
resolved before the lawsuit could be dismissed, including APB's
request for a waiver of the $2,500.16 the federal courts'
administrative office charged for copies of all 1,600 disclosure
reports.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Tuesday following the Judicial
Conference's closed-door meeting at the Supreme Court, the head of
the conference's executive committee, Chief Judge Ralph K. Winter
Jr. of the federal appeals court in New York, said that given the
statutory requirement for public disclosure, it was ``not
sustainable'' to deny access to the reports ``simply because they
are going to be placed on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that under procedures adopted at the meeting Tuesday,
judges who are afraid that the disclosure of personal information _
like children's names or the location of a spouse's workplace _ can
ask that the information be withheld. ``This is a matter of great
concern to an awful lot of judges'' who regularly receive threats
from ``dangerous and deluded individuals,'' Winter said.
</P>
<P>
   But he indicated that information about a judge's actual
financial holdings _ the point of the statute, he noted _ would not
be subject to requests for nondisclosure. In fact, Winter said, the
Judicial Conference is considering ways to get information about
judges' finances before the public on an ongoing basis, rather than
once a year as the Ethics in Government Act provides.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, judges are barred from participating in cases
in which they or immediate family members have a financial
interest. In recent years, journalists and others scrutinizing
lists of judges' holdings have found instances of violations, often
inadvertent but nonetheless embarrassing for the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the action on Tuesday that the financial
disclosure committee's response to APB's Internet request had also
become an embarrassment, sharply criticized in Congress and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Winter, who sits on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second
Circuit, said that while the Judicial Conference's action on
Tuesday was ``not a public relations decision,'' it was nonetheless
true that ``any time the Judicial Conference of the United States
doesn't comply with a statute, it's safe to say it would be
politically disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, who is the chairman of the
Judicial Conference, was sharply critical of the financial
disclosure committee's action in an internal memo the court
released Tuesday. He said, in effect, that the committee had not
only misinterpreted the law but had overstepped its own authority
within the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Judicial Conference has 27 members, including a seven-member
executive committee, which voted unanimously to oppose the
financial disclosure committee's position. The vote by the whole
conference Tuesday was 16 to 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
