<HEADER>
A6783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEAMSTERS-HAMILTON-NY     03-14 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-HAMILTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-TEAMSTERS OFFICIAL SENTENCED TO 3 YEARS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas)   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The former political director of the Teamsters union
was sentenced to three years in prison Tuesday after being
convicted of taking part in a scheme to siphon union money into the
1996 campaign of the Teamsters' former president, Ron Carey.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Griesa of U.S. District Court in Manhattan ordered
the sentence for William Hamilton, the former official, after he
concluded that decades of public service by Hamilton justified
ordering a prison term somewhat less than called for by federal
guidelines. The sentencing guidelines recommend 46 months to 57
months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In November, a federal jury convicted Hamilton on six counts,
punishable by up to five years each, for helping steer $885,000 in
Teamsters money to liberal groups as part of a scheme in which
donors to those groups later contributed to Carey's campaign.
Federal monitors overturned Carey's 1996 victory over James P.
Hoffa because of the campaign finance fraud, and Hoffa has since
won a rerun election for the union's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   For close to an hour, Hamilton's lawyer, G. Robert Gage Jr.,
implored the judge to depart from the sentencing guidelines as he
emphasized that Hamilton had not benefited financially from the
embezzlement, had parents who were ill and elderly and had spent
decades working in public service.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton led civil rights demonstrations as a student at the
University of Texas, was a top aide to former U.S. Sen. Ralph
Yarborough of Texas, headed Planned Parenthood's Washington office
and was chief of staff at the American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This for me has been degrading and humiliating,'' Hamilton
said in brief, somber remarks, as his two grown children looked on.
``I am deeply ashamed and angry at myself that it has come to
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said he had such bad memories of the Teamsters when it
was mob-infested and led by Hoffa's father, James R. Hoffa, that he
was desperately eager to insure that Hoffa lost to Carey, whom
Hamilton said he viewed as an honest reformer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to see the union go back to the days of
corruption,'' he said. ``Sometimes you want to do something so
deeply, you do something dumb _ you cross the line.'' He added, ``I
had the best of intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   Stressing the seriousness of the crime, Griesa said: ``It was a
large embezzlement. It was not merely the loss of $885,000 to the
Teamsters, it was conduct which had a very damaging effect on the
union.'' But he said he was lightening the sentence for one reason:
Hamilton's public service. ``He has indeed led an exemplary life,''
the judge said, except for the 1996 campaign-finance scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Six people have been convicted in the Teamsters campaign finance
scheme. Hamilton was the first of theconvicted to receive a prison
term. One other defendant was sentenced to probation, while four
others have not been sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the prosecutor's office said they were continuing
their investigation. Hamilton has declined to cooperate with the
prosecutors investigating other figures, including Carey and
Richard Trumka, the AFL-CIO's secretary-treasurer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2005EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6785 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-FLOYD-GHOSTTOWN-COX     03-14 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-GHOSTTOWN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ghost Town: North of the River
 &HT;    Editor's Note: Today marks six months since Hurricane Floyd
ravaged an already-soaked eastern North Carolina. The water's gone
now, but many here are still feeling the impact of the storm and
the floods that followed. The Daily Reflector takes a look at how
Greenville and Pitt County residents are coping with Floyd's
aftermath. This is the first part in a seven-part series.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By T. Scott Batchelor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Flooding from Hurricane Floyd illustrated in
dramatic fashion how tenuous one of society's fundamental
frameworks can be.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, brown river water crept across the floodplain
and turned vibrant neighborhoods into ghost towns.
</P>
<P>
   Names such as East Meadowbrook, West Meadowbrook and Pinecrest
Mobile Home Park echo in the wake of the state's worst natural
disaster, when the Tar River and its tributaries escaped their
banks and engulfed homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Row upon row, block after block of abandoned houses and mobile
homes bear dingy waterlines marking the deluge's progress on its
destructive journey.
</P>
<P>
   Communities once full of life now sit spookily empty _ no
streetlamps or glowing windows pierce the inky darkness at night.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, it seemed the wiped-out neighborhoods would be lost
forever. That suited city officials, who want the inundated
neighborhoods in the floodplain to remain vacant so they can be
torn down and spared future catastrophes.
</P>
<P>
   But, here and there, a few residents have returned to reclaim
their homes and try to rebuild their communities.
</P>
<P>
   Janie Roberson lives in East Meadowbrook, one of the hardest-hit
areas in Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   She, her husband, Bobby, and the 15-year-old granddaughter who
lives with them fled their Van Dyke Street home when the Tar
overflowed its banks.
</P>
<P>
   Roberson applied for the federal buyout program, which allows
homeowners to sell their flood-damaged homes to the government and
have them leveled for free. That helps the city establish
``conservation spaces'' that can be converted to uses such as boat
docks and nature trails that don't put lives and property in peril
when it floods.
</P>
<P>
   Since applying, however, Roberson has accepted an offer by a
church group to refurbish the home she has lived in for more than
25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a plethora of volunteers was busy inside the home,
nailing up fresh drywall, replacing once-waterlogged fiberglass
insulation and rewiring electrical outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Roberson was beaming _ happy that her house was taking shape _
but that joy was tempered by the lines of vacant homes that
stretched in every direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel lonesome,'' she said. ``I'm missing my neighbors. I
want them to come home like I want to come home. I'm hoping
somebody will come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Houses by themselves do not a neighborhood make, Roberson
realizes. Children playing in yards and biking down streets,
evening strollers chatting as they walk, a little harmless gossip
across a fence _ these transform mere dwellings into a real
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sweet old lady, she'd come to the fence. We'd talk at the
fence,'' Roberson said. ``I miss her.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson's was one of 1,753 single-family homes, mobile homes,
apartments and duplexes in Greenville that took at least a foot of
water above the floors. Of these, 55 percent were condemned or
deemed uninhabitable.
</P>
<P>
   Monetary losses in the city were estimated at $65.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The church volunteers who were working on Roberson's home had
recently completed a renovation of Floyd Clemons' place on Mumford
Road.
</P>
<P>
   He was busy last week putting the finishing touches on the
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we're coming back,'' the ordained minister said. ``It was
hard, but we're coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get everybody back in here. Everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemons, who lived in a small trailer set up on his property
while the renovations were being completed, has lived in his home
for more than 20 years and is optimistic about the neighborhood's
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I believe, it's going to be finer than it's ever been
before,'' Clemons said. ``We're going to shake hands with one
another and be good neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   That resolve is frustrating the plans of city officials, who
want the housing developments that were in the 100-year floodplain
to be torn down to make the flood buffer zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to clean out those neighborhoods that were totally
devastated,'' said Andy Harris, director of planning and community
development. ``Most are participating in the buyout program,
especially in East Meadowbrook.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real possibility that East Meadowbrook could be a
park in the future, a really nice park,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   The money that the city is forced to spend on destroyed and
damaged property is part of the reason for the push, but the
biggest factor is human safety, Harris said. If need be, the city
can take homes to create the conservation spaces, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man will never be able to control disasters,'' Harris said.
``It is a floodplain, and at some point in time, people are going
to recognize that.''
</P>
<P>
   That rankles Clemons, who doesn't want to see East Meadowbrook
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not giving it up,'' he said of his home.
</P>
<P>
   And if houses around him start coming down under the buyout
program, all the better, Clemons said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll just increase my view, give me a good view,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Across Greene Street, the community on West Gum Road is also
slowly coming back to life.
</P>
<P>
   Huey Harrison and his family were driven from the home they had
lived in since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   About 16 families lived in the small settlement before the
floodwaters rolled over the land, floating furniture and personal
mementos and ruining homes inside and out.
</P>
<P>
   A single-wide mobile home, jacked up 3 feet in the air to comply
with the city's post-flood regulations, is the Harrisons' residence
while they wait for demolition crews to take over where the flood
left off. They have a new double-wide ready to be placed on the
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, who is disabled, sat by himself last week in the quiet
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's lonely,'' he said. ``Our neighborhood was disrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   He misses people walking down the street and children playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a good neighborhood,'' Harrison said. When he returned
to the homestead after the water receded, the area was decimated
``like a plague or something.''
</P>
<P>
   But things are changing on Gum Road. Harrison said about five
families have moved back so far.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks the neighborhood will be reborn, but with different
people.
</P>
<P>
   Roberson is hopeful too, but she is realistic about the final
look of East Meadowbrook.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be like it was,'' she said. ``It's going to
be like the county almost _ one (house) here and one yonder.''
</P>
<P>
   The loyalty to a neighborhood does have its limits. Roberson
said her granddaughter was a little nervous about moving back to
the home she fled from in fear six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   What if another flood comes, the girl asked her grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll leave,'' Roberson said, ``and we probably won't look
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
