<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6789 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-NET-RECRUITING-COX     03-14 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-RECRUITING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recruiters still want face to face contact with applicants
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet may be the hot new way to find workers, but for
recruiter Alan Thornton, there's nothing like eye contact and body
language for sizing up potential hires.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much you can tell from looking people in the eye
and body language is so important in an interview,'' said Thornton,
who works for two Atlanta area recruiting firms. ``You can't get
that over a telephone or the Internet.'' He uses online job boards
to narrow his prospects for technical writers and others with
high-tech backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   A new study on online recruiting backs up Thornton's summation:
The Internet may have the high-tech advantage of reaching a lot of
people, but it's still no match for old-fashioned, face-to-face
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   With online recruiting projected to become a $2.5 billion
business by 2003, more recruiters and human resource professionals
at small and large companies are using the Internet to find
workers. But many of them are frustrated by the impersonal feel of
online job boards, according to the study conducted by Yankelovich
Partners. The study was commissioned by kforce.com, an online
staffing service that polled 300 human resources managers at large
U.S.-based businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still place tremendous value on face-to-face interactions
in the hiring process,'' said David Dunkel, chief executive of
kforce.com.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't stopped companies from taking a chance on the
Internet _ and getting results, however mixed:
</P>
<P>
   About 75 percent of the companies surveyed post jobs on
third-party Web sites, such as Monster.com, Atlanta's
computerjobs.com or headhunter.net. Job search Web sites number in
the hundreds. Conversely, because of the Internet's far-reaching
exposure, companies complained that they're inundated with resumes,
many of which aren't that impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, two out of five companies surveyed said they will
pour more money into online recruiting during the next year. More
than half of the companies not using their Web sites for recruiting
plan to do so in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Large businesses had an average of two in-house recruiters
dedicated solely to online job recruiting. Most large firms list
jobs on their own Web site vs. an outside job board. There are
thousands of recruiting sites, according to Charlene Li, an
Internet analyst at Cambridge, Mass.-based Forrester Research. The
average fee for posting a job is about $100 a month, Li said.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of companies using their own sites will increase in
the future, says Carl Van Horn of the John J. Heldrich Center for
Workforce Development at Rutgers University. Van Horn noted that
many of the Fortune 500 firms he deals with said they're getting
about a fifth of their new hires through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still talk to them'' face to face, Van Horn said. But
``they identify them on the Internet. Five years ago, that was
practically zero. It's going to continue to increase because people
want it and employers will push for it.''
</P>
<P>
   One in 10 new hires at the companies surveyed was a direct
result of online recruiting. Most of the hires were for permanent
jobs as opposed to contract work.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, the study found, also has become the great
equalizer between small and large firms.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Steve Derezinski.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday at 3 p.m., Derezinski went online to look for software
developers for his start-up company called smallbizplanet.com, a
Midtown-based online information service for small businesses. By
4:30, he had five prospects to his posting, ``two of which are
excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   He's already hired two people using the Internet and will likely
make another Internet hire in the next couple of weeks, if e-mail
responses and interviews work out. He has used traditional
recruiters but now prefers online recruiting. With traditional
recruiters, you end up ``interviewing the interviewer,'' and that
takes time away from finding workers. The Internet gets faster
results, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies on the Internet, regardless of size, are able to
compete more effectively,'' he said. ``Anybody who's smart enough
to leverage the Internet to their advantage is going to be more
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, Scientific-Atlanta, a Norcross-based developer
of interactive digital cable TV boxes, launched a nationwide search
for engineers, sales and marketing people via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who work at Scientific-Atlanta are part of an
Internet-savvy software environment mixed with the successful
digital interactive platforms and networks the company has built
for more than a decade,'' Scientific-Atlanta Chief Executive
Officer Jim McDonald said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Online recruiting is forecast to grow rapidly in the next two to
three years as more job seekers go online to speed up their job
search and companies respond in kind, says Van Horn of Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rutgers study of American workers last month found that
workers ages 18-20 _ the chief source of workers in the future _
are the most likely to use the Internet to find a job as opposed to
workers over the age of 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge growth potential in e-recruiting strategies,
because the access to computers is expanding and young people are
the ones most likely to be looking for jobs,'' Van Horn said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
