<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6790 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FETALTISSUE-KAN &LR;      03-14 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FETAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEE'S SUMMIT DOCTOR RECOMMENDS TECHNICIAN ALSO BE INVESTIGATED BY
FBI 
</HEADLINE>
 TISSUE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Lee's Summit, Mo., doctor at the center of an FBI
probe of fetal tissue marketing has surfaced long enough to ask
that a key accuser be investigated for ``corporate espionage.''
</P>
<P>
   Pathologist Miles Jones wrote letters Monday to Attorney General
Janet Reno and FBI Director Louis Freeh asking that medical
technician Lawrence Dean Alberty Jr. be investigated for giving
private medical records to an anti-abortion group that paid him
more than $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Life Dynamics _ a Texas organization for which Alberty spied
while employed by Jones at an Overland Park, Kan., clinic _ should
also be investigated, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violations of patient and corporate confidentiality are
serious offenses,'' Jones said in letters he provided to The Kansas
City Star. Jones said he thought the offenses were a ``serious case
of corporate espionage.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' letters mark his first public reaction to allegations of
possible fetal tissue profiteering.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to be interviewed by a reporter, but he implied
Tuesday in a two-paragraph e-mail to The Star that the allegations
were racially motivated. Jones, 47, is black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh to be in Salem or under the spreading Southern oak tree,''
he wrote, apparently referring to witch hunts and lynchings.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Jones did not answer a subpoena from a U.S. House
subcommittee that held a hearing on whether fetal tissue and organs
were being marketed in violation of federal law. He could face a
contempt of Congress charge.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Justice Department said Tuesday she didn't
know whether Reno and Freeh had received Jones' letters. Alberty's
attorney, David Stout of Kansas City, Mo., declined to comment on
Jones' allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI in Kansas City is investigating the removal and
marketing of fetal tissue at Comprehensive Health, an Overland Park
clinic affiliated with Planned Parenthood of Kansas and
Mid-Missouri. Tissue is provided for research in treatment of
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Health and Environment Subcommittee called for
the probe last week after Jones told an undercover ABC News
reporter that the harvesting of fetal brains, kidneys, livers and
other organs can bring ``what you can sell it for.''
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, fetal organs can be donated but not sold.
Reasonable costs can be recovered for staff, facility and
transportation costs. Jones' company, Opening Lines, had a price
brochure for fetal organs.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Lines was under contract with Planned Parenthood for
about 10 weeks in 1998 to remove fetal tissue and organs.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty worked for Opening Lines to help remove and ship tissue.
He did similar work at the clinic for a previous contractor from
Georgia, Anatomic Gift Foundation. Planned Parenthood ended both
contracts and now has no one doing tissue removal.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony to the House subcommittee last week, Alberty
admitted accepting more than $10,000 in payments and $11,000 in
travel expenses from Life Dynamics, to gather information about
fetal tissue work.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty said he had become horrified at the procedures and
decided to help expose the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty wore a woman's disguise and videotaped about five hours
of interviews with Life Dynamics about fetal tissue being removed
from viable fetuses and sold. Alberty admitted under oath and in an
affidavit, however, that he made some false statements on the tape
and knew little about fetal viability or sales.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to relating what he saw in the clinic, Alberty
admitted taking some Anatomic Gift documents marked
``confidential'' that listed procedures used in removing fetal
organs, types of organs ordered and names of researchers. He turned
them over to Life Dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that when investigated, evidence of violations of
federal law will be uncovered,'' Jones wrote Reno and Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty also said in a deposition that he provided Jones with
the names of potential clients, some of the researchers who had
previously used Anatomic Gift.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer specializing in corporate crime said Tuesday that
someone in Alberty's situation could face investigation but that
espionage would likely not be the charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly are other things that can be considered when
employees who owe a duty to a corporation in good faith, breach
that good faith,'' said St. Louis lawyer Burt Shostak, chairman of
the White Collar Crime Committee of the National Association of
Criminal Defense Attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could be talking about mail fraud, wire fraud, conspiracy,
stealing by deceit,'' Shostak said. ``Whether it rises to level of
a criminal act is for a prosecutor to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Anatomic Gift, now located in Maryland, sued Alberty in federal
court in Kansas City last year for breaching a confidentiality
agreement. Company attorney Fay Clayton said Tuesday the lawsuit
has been settled, and she would not say if Alberty should be
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Mr. Alberty has learned his lesson, I certainly hope he
has,'' Clayton said. ``Now, if Mr. Jones would only learn his.''
</P>
<P>
   The fetal tissue probe is expected to come up again today when
the House Commerce Committee votes on whether to recommend the
House hold Jones in contempt for failing to appear before its
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Should the House approve a contempt charge, the Justice
Department could seek to indict Jones and have him arrested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
