<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6792 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GA-CENSUS-NYT &LR;      03-14 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-CENSUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGIA TAKES AIM AT NEW YORK IN CENSUS PROMOTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ten years ago, Georgia missed out on a new
congressional seat when state leaders did not bother to persuade
enough residents to turn in their census forms. This year, the
easygoing Southern gentility is gone. The state is playing
hardball, and the opponent is a familiar one.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your census form comes, fill it out and mail it in,''
says Georgia Gov. Roy E. Barnes, in a new statewide television ad.
``Or Georgia money will be educating New York children for another
10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The state lost $2 billion because 140,000 Georgians did not fill
out their forms, Barnes says in the advertisement _ ``money that
should have come to Georgia for schools and health care. Instead,
it's gone to other states _ from Connecticut to California.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most aggressive ``get out the forms'' efforts in
the country, the state is spending nearly $1.4 million on
television, radio and newspaper ads, and on phone banks, to make
sure that residents mail back their census forms this year. And
what better way to stimulate action than to pretend as if the state
is in direct competition with New York?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's baseball or broadcasting, politics or plays, New
York is the standard we all measure ourselves against,'' said
Howard Mead, the governor's communications director, explaining the
advertisement's geographical choice. In fact, New York has always
been the chosen archetype of everything that Georgia is not, and
the ad's creators knew exactly what its effect would be.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Georgia sat back while other states spent money to push
their residents to raise their hands and be counted, said Robert
Giacomini, the research director of Georgia Tech's State Data and
Research Center, which was hired by the state as its lead agency
for improving Georgia's census count. As a result, it had an
undercount that the Census Bureau estimated at 2.1 percent, higher
than the national average of 1.6 percent (but not nearly as bad as
the 2.7 percent in Texas and California, two states with
hard-to-count Hispanic populations). Although Georgia gained a
congressional seat that year, it would have had another one if the
extra 140,000 residents had been counted, Giacomini said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the state's enormous growth guarantees it another
seat, but it believes it can get two with an aggressive census
effort. The governor formed a committee, the Legislature approved
the money, and when Giacomini and his colleagues began talking to
people around the state, they realized the most effective way to
stimulate participation was to point out who would win if Georgia
loses. The next step was ridiculously obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is the traditional rivalry,'' Giacomini said. ``It
has the biggest city, the powerhouse everyone looks at. It just
stands for all those northern states with better counts than
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's undercount was worse than New York state's, which was
estimated at 1.5 percent. (In New York City, one of the
hardest-to-count cities in the country, the bureau missed an
estimated 3.2 percent.) But in an emotional campaign like this one,
the numbers do not really matter. What's important is getting
across the sense that Georgia is losing out, preferably to a hated
rival.
</P>
<P>
   People here have not forgotten the moment in 1997 when New York
state officials removed the Georgia flag from the Capitol in Albany
because it contained the Confederate battle symbol, which was
followed by the removal of the New York flag from the Capitol in
Georgia. There has also been the frequent jostling between New
York's baseball teams and the Atlanta Braves, punctuated by John
Rocker's outburst.
</P>
<P>
   And in Tuesday morning's Atlanta Constitution, Ted Turner was
asked whether he ever considered moving his Turner Broadcasting
System to New York. His derisive response: ``New York? It's bad
enough to go up there and visit.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the technique is a bit ancient and a bit cynical, the
stakes are enormous. PricewaterhouseCoopers, which recently studied
the matter for the Census Monitoring Board, an oversight committee,
estimated that half the states could lose a total of $9.1 billion
if the Census Bureau undercounts people at the same rate as in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   And, because the number of House seats is fixed at 435, any seat
gained by one state during reapportionment is lost by another. New
York and Connecticut, to cite two states named by Barnes, are
considered likely to lose two seats and one seat, respectively,
according to a projection by the Republican National Committee. At
the same time, Georgia, Texas and Arizona are the best bets to gain
two seats each.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many states are stepping up their efforts to
produce a larger count, supplemented by the Census Bureau's own
unprecedented $103 million advertising budget. California has
allocated $24.5 million in state money for census ads. Nevada is
spending $700,000. New York's budget of $347,000 is rather paltry
by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, having spent almost nothing 10 years ago, is leaving
little to chance this year. About 80 percent of its counties now
have census count committees. Pastors have been urged to use their
pulpits to get congregants to fill out their forms. The Rev. Jesse
Jackson has taped a radio ad for use on black stations. And Barnes,
in another radio ad, has even begun to imitate Regis Philbin.
</P>
<P>
   ``So here's your next question,'' he says, in yet another
imitation of Philbin's television quiz show. ``What costs nothing
but pays dividends for years? Your census forms. Fill it out and
mail it in. That's my final answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
