<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6795 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HEASTERCOLUMN-KAN &LR;      03-14 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST YOU DON'T HAVE TO WORRY ABOUT LONG LINES FOR GASOLINE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If soaring gasoline prices have made you fretful, look on the
bright side: At least you're able to buy all you want without
tedious waits for pumps that may or may not be pumping when you get
there.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's the way it was a generation ago when foreign oil
producers created shortages that not only spurred prices but also
created for some Americans the now unthinkable plight of gasoline
being temporarily unavailable at any price.
</P>
<P>
   About half the U.S. population, however, is too young to have a
memory of those terrible times. This helps explain why so many
Americans fail to appreciate how much worse the current
unpleasantness could be. That it's not worse is due to a valuable
lesson Americans learned from the '70s oil disruptions. What we
learned is that government's well-intentioned marketplace
intrusions can't abrogate the law of supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, an oil shortage was created by major exporters
curbing and withholding supply. This move caused prices to rise and
thus should have resulted in more production from domestic
producers. It didn't happen, though, because laws and regulations
designed to ``protect'' Americans from high fuel prices prevented
alternative producers from maximizing profits.
</P>
<P>
   When this restrictive structure was dismantled, the market began
to work again, and within a few years Americans had all the gas
they wanted at steadily declining prices. As the '90s drew to a
close, gas prices reached their lowest inflation-adjusted level
since cars became a significant factor in American life.
</P>
<P>
   The market was working as intended when prices were falling
because of plentiful supply. It's also working as gas prices are
rising. The price mechanism is the most critical component of a
market economy. It's the signal that keeps supply and demand in
relative balance.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel market is tight because overseas producers again have
decided to curb production. When they cut output, however, prices
were historically low. This meant it was going to take a fairly
long time for prices to go up enough to encourage domestic oil
producers to increase production.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a rough couple of decades for the U.S. oil industry.
Low prices have put a lot of players out of business and caused
others to abandon development of new supply sources. This won't
change until the price mechanism signals to the oil patch there's a
reasonable expectation of long-term decent profits from producing
additional oil.
</P>
<P>
   If political leaders can resist the urge to try to ``fix'' the
problem by delivering fuel to voters at below-market prices, the
situation will sort itself out. It might not sort itself out to the
satisfaction of those who think cheap gas is a birthright, but
there are worse things than relatively expensive gasoline. One is
inadequate supplies of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, expensive is a relative thing. Motorists in Europe and
Japan have been paying $4 or more a gallon for a number of years.
They've adjusted, it seems, without experiencing the end of the
world as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   America's run of cheap gas was a good one, but certainly not
something that could have been expected to last forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2019EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0302 </DOCNO>
