<HEADER>
A6801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OFFICE-POOLS-(TRIMS)-     03-14 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICE-POOLS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW BIG A PART OF GDP ARE OFFICE POOLS? MAKE A BET?  
(HM)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOBERT E. ABUEVA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't try calling Jake Williams right now about his company's
product line. Williams, a manager at Furnimex, a distributor of
home textiles based in Dallas, is working furiously against a
deadline of noon Thursday to complete a special project.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, faxes began piling up on his desk, his voice
mail light started blinking and messages began clogging his e-mail.
As in years past, Williams is spending much of his workday
confirming the orders pouring in and collecting cash from
customers.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of them are Furnimex customers. Williams organizes
an office betting pool for the granddaddy event of them all: the
National Collegiate Athletic Association basketball championship
playoffs, a.k.a. March Madness, with 64 of the nation's top men's
teams battling it out throughout the next two and a half weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And here is the twist: Williams says his role as numbers man is
good for business, good for workplace morale and even good for his
family life since he enlists the help of his wife and son in the
tabulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets everyone excited and talking around the water cooler,
regardless of their function and position in the company,''
Williams said. It is also a lifeline to customers old and new, he
said. When his previous employer moved him from New York to Dallas
12 years ago, he said, ``Everyone identified me as  &UR; the &LR;  sports
fan, and, as many colleagues remained in New York, they wanted to
know whether the tradition would be maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   They did not have to worry. Even though he took a job with
Furnimex six years ago, the office pool he organizes around March
Madness gives him a chance to renew old contacts. ``It's an annual
high moment that so many busy partners and friends look forward to,
year in and year out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of business consultants agree with him. Many corporate
bosses have long tolerated office pools on sporting events and
award shows as harmless diversions. But some say the pools are much
more than that because they increase camaraderie and encourage
interaction in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The betting pool, as a shared experience, gives co-workers an
excuse to see each other face to face in a world where technology
has put efficiency, but distance, in our work relationships,'' said
Bob Nelson, a consultant and author of ``1001 Ways To Take
Initiative at Work'' (Workman, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Matt Weinstein, founder of Playfair, a management consulting
firm in Berkeley, Calif., and author of ``Work Like Your Dog''
(Villiard, 1999), says betting pools can make the workplace more
fun _ an important consideration for retaining employees in the
current job market. They can also add a light touch to otherwise
humdrum activities. ``Pools run the gamut from what time the UPS
deliveryman will arrive to how many pie charts a vice president
will use during his presentation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Williams' pools have sometimes produced results that warm the
hearts of even the losers. Once, a secretary who was eight months
pregnant took the top prize. Another year, it was a 15-year-old
high school sophomore, the son of one of Williams' customers. And
once it was a top industry executive, who split the money among
three clerks who had entered losing sheets.
</P>
<P>
   For Peter Bielby, a design engineer in Ann Arbor, Mich., betting
pools are just part of the work landscape. ``Pools exist everywhere
I've worked _ Texas, Georgia and now back in Michigan,'' he said.
``People look forward to it. It acts as a morale booster.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the opening tap at the NCAA tournament's first-round game
Thursday afternoon until the April 3 championship in Indianapolis,
millions of workers with a stake in the outcome will be monitoring
each game, rooting for the ``right'' team combination. As in years
past, many will crowd into office conference rooms with television
sets or flip on a radio on the factory floor to catch the action.
</P>
<P>
   The entry fee of $10 a sheet for Williams' pool has not changed
since its inception, he said. The number of participants has grown,
though, to 450 last year. That is a pot of $4,500, with the top
winner getting $3,000; the first runner-up, $900, and the second,
$600. This is still small potatoes compared with Wall Street pots,
which investment bankers say can go to five or even six figures. In
all, it has been estimated that $6 billion changes hands annually
in office pools around the nation, led by the Super Bowl and March
Madness in dollar volume.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The volume is big enough to support a few software packages and
a growing number of World Wide Web sites. The March Madness
Tournament Tracker, for example, which can be downloaded from
sportsdatatech.com, can track and rank up to 1,000 entries, saving
organizers endless paperwork _ an efficiency the bosses of America
no doubt appreciate. Williams, though, happily remains in the Dark
Ages, keeping score by hand.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Web sites like Gamesville.com and Easypool.com are
for an assortment of pools. And the NCAA Web site,
ncaachampionships.com, offers printouts of team seeds and pairings
as well as updates.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the Final Four games on April 1, Williams will work out
all the possibilities and advise the front-runners of their chances
of winning. ``This is always fun because loyalties can change in an
instant, even against one's alma mater,'' he said. It also becomes
a chance for Williams to set up appointments with Furnimex
customers in the pool once the tournament ends.
</P>
<P>
   So, does he face an emotional letdown when the madness is over?
Not really. He and other regulars in the NCAA pool are already
preparing for the draft next month for fantasy, or Rotisserie,
baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
