<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ASIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT URGES INDIA TO CURB NUCLEAR WEAPONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Setting a high bar for President Clinton's
approaching trip to South Asia, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said Tuesday that India must curb its nuclear weapons
program before relations with the United States can be markedly
improved.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the nuclear brinksmanship represented by the 1998
weapons tests by India and then Pakistan, two long-time enemies,
were ``a historic mistake.'' While India's nuclear weapons are not
a direct threat to the United States, she said, ``we do regard
(nuclear) proliferation anywhere as our No. 1 security concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for this reason, we must accept that significant progress
in this area is necessary before India and the United States can
realize fully the vast potential of our relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright's comments, what the international relations Ph.D.
called ``a wonky speech,'' were delivered to an Asia Society
briefing tied to Clinton's trip to India, Bangladesh and Pakistan.
The president departs Sunday and is expected to be gone a week.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions set by Albright, although hardly surprising,
could have a dampening effect on India's attitude toward Clinton's
visit, the first in 22 years by a U.S. president to the world's
most populous democracy. A U.S. president has not been to Pakistan
in almost 31 years and had never visited Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have questioned whether Clinton's visit to the region
should be focused on nuclear arms policy, an approach that has been
a hallmark of the president's frequent international travels during
his seven years in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president needs to avoid the temptation ... to shape the
agenda with both India and Pakistan around nuclear goals,'' said
Richard Haas, director of international programs at the Brookings
Institution. While important, he said, ``it can't be a gateway''
for the U.S. relationship with either nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These countries are not about to get out of the nuclear
business,'' said Haas, a National Security Council official in the
Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said that the United States and India ``have not yet
found a way to create sufficient common ground on these issues. But
I'm convinced that our relationship today has the strength and
breadth to keep working through our differences and find a way
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   She called on India to recognize that its nuclear program could
spark a continentwide arms race and military buildup, and has
repercussions outside of its long-tortured relations with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prudence and clarity in India's plans and doctrines could
yield great benefits, for a pattern of steeply rising defense
budgets in Asia would serve neither the continents security
interests nor its development needs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the United States seeks ``a qualitatively
different and better relationship with India, not a simple return
to the status quo before the tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ability to attain this goal will depend largely on what
India does. ... Our approach to nonproliferation is global. We
cannot abandon it simply because we desire an improved
relationship'' with India.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Cold War coolness in U.S.-Indian relations, Clinton
administration officials have stressed that the president will
focus on improving ties to India, the subcontinent's giant, which
is expected to pass China and become the world's most populous
nation early in this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president will seek to begin a new chapter in our
relations with one of the world's leading countries and oldest
civilizations,'' Albright said. ``And I can think of few greater
gifts to the future than a strong and cooperative strategic
relationship between India and the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright pointed out that Clinton's five days in India will be
not only the first since the Carter administration but also the
most extensive visit ever to the region by a U.S. president.
</P>
<P>
   Albright made no secret of Clinton's interest in abetting
growing U.S.-Indian trade ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent years, software exports have jumped 50 percent
annually with no end in sight,'' she said. ``American companies
from Apple and Texas Instruments to Oracle and Microsoft have come
to India for its high-tech and high skills. And while other
countries beat a path to India's door, it continues to enrich the
globe with talent.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
