<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: HOLDING ON TO VILLAGE
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak decided against transferring a West
Bank village abutting Jerusalem to Palestinian control after
rightists said the move would erode Israel's hold on the city and
endanger Jewish neighborhoods. Anata, where Palestinians already
run civil affairs, was to have come under full Palestinian control
as part of a planned handover of another 6.1 percent of the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS: ISRAELIS ON SYLLABUS
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian culture minister, Yasser Abed Rabbo, said he
would introduce Israeli authors into the Palestinian curriculum
after a storm in Israel over the addition of a Palestinian poet to
the high school syllabus. Yossi Sarid, Israel's education minister,
said he and Abed Rabbo were ``partners in the struggle against
people living in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: MISSILE DEFENSE DEPLOYS
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Arrow 2 antiballistic missile defense system was
formally placed in operation, culminating a 14-year, $1.3 billion
development program underwritten by Israel and the United States.
Designed to intercept incoming missiles in the stratosphere, the
Arrow 2 missiles are made by the state-owned Israel Aircrcraft
Industries.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: HOPE VOICED FOR REFORMIST
</P>
<P>
   Saeed Hajjarian, the leading figure in the reform movement who
was shot on a Tehran street, remains in grave condition, but a
small sign of hope came with a statement by an Iranian-American
brain surgeon, Dr. Jamshid Ghamjar, that the bullet that struck his
head ``did not pass through the brain.''
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: FUGITIVE FOUND
</P>
<P>
   A former Elf-Acquitaine oil executive, considered vital to
unraveling a wide-ranging French corruption scandal, has been
located in the Philippines, French justice officials say. Alfred
Sirven, 73, who has been on the run for three years, is accused of
paying off leading politicians as part of rampant corruption said
to have taken place in the 1990s at the formerly state-owned
petroleum giant.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: CHRETIEN DEFIANT
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jean Chretien, defying an opinion poll in which
61 percent said someone else should lead the Liberal Party into the
next election, goes into a party conference Thursday, vowing in two
newspaper interviews to run for a third term. Chretien, 66, was
first elected in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: IMPORT CURB RELAXED
</P>
<P>
   Starting April 1, in a measure designed to help low-income
farmers, Mexico will relax a trade barrier and allow imports of
used U.S. and Canadian pickup trucks that are more than 10 years
old, the Commerce Ministry announced. Officials reiterated that
they would not allow owners of more than 1.5 million illegally
imported newer vehicles to be registered.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN'S ROLE
</P>
<P>
   More than 440 non-government organizations called for a review
of the Vatican's observer status at the United Nations, which is
based on the Holy See's claim to territory in Rome, not on its
status as the head of the Roman Catholic Church. Frances Kissling,
president of Catholics for a Free Choice, said the church ``debases
its own nature when it seeks secular power as a state.''
Resolutions opposing a review have been introduced in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: WHITES SUE
</P>
<P>
   The Commercial Farmers' Union petitioned the High Court for help
in halting a rash of farm invasions. Thousands of people, led by
veterans of the 1970s struggle against white minority rule, have
occupied hundreds of white-owned farms, which they say belong to
the blacks whose families' land was stolen by whites decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: DEBT PLEA
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting with President Joaquim Chissano, six African
presidents called on the international community to cancel
Mozambique's foreign debt so that it can rebuild its flood-ravaged
economy, where hundreds have died and more than 200,000 are
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: SHARIF LAWYERS RELENT
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the ousted prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, have agreed
to return to court, dropping demands to shift his hijacking trial
out of Karachi. The lawyers had asked for the change after Iqbal
Raad, a defense team member, was shot dead.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: SUHARTO IS EXAMINED
</P>
<P>
   Former President Suharto was examined at a hospital to see
whether he is healthy enough to face questioning in court over
accusations of corruption. His lawyers had argued that he was too
weak even to visit a hospital, but he was shown on television
walking, smiling and waving to a crowd of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: GUILTY IN ANWAR ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   The former chief of the national police force, Abdul Rahim Noor,
was convicted of assaulting the former deputy prime minister, Anwar
Ibrahim, on the night of Anwar's arrest in September 1998. The
assault left Anwar, who is still on trial on sex charges, with a
much-publicized black eye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
