<HEADER>
A6819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PLATT-STARTING-OVER-A     03-14 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLATT-STARTING-OVER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AFTERLIFE OF A POWERFUL CHIEF
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(fb) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ It was about noon on a Wednesday, and the
retired Silicon Valley executive in a black V-neck sweater was
considering a much more relaxed range of choices than he was
accustomed to: Should he start with a merlot? Or perhaps a cabernet
sauvignon? And should it be a recent vintage or an older, riskier
one?
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he dived in, nose first, and after a long sniff took
a generous sip of the 1988 merlot. Pronouncing it acceptable, he
moved on to the 1990, 1991 and 1994 versions. Then came the
cabernets and finally a single chardonnay to wrap up the tasting.
</P>
<P>
   After each tilt of a glass, however, came a clue that this was
not a typical northern California retiree. The man swished the wine
around in his mouth and then spit it into a red plastic cup. It was
still before lunch, after all, and the man, Lewis E. Platt, had
hours more work in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Platt, it turns out, is retired only from Silicon Valley, not
from the business world. In one of the more unusual corporate job
changes in years, Platt, 58, left Hewlett-Packard last year after
33 years, including an up-and-down seven-year term as chief
executive, and promptly took the top job at Kendall-Jackson Wine
Estates.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a transition. Since December, he has moved from
Palo Alto and a global company with 124,000 employees at the center
of the new economy, to Wine Country and a private firm with 1,200
workers in one of the world's oldest industries.
</P>
<P>
   When Platt accepted the Kendall-Jackson job late last year
rather than take the more common path of sitting on corporate
boards, teaching business school classes or leading a foundation,
he generated a buzz among executives around the country. Gerard R.
Roche, the headhunter who selected him, said he had since received
calls from at least six ``big-name CEO's'' asking for help in
finding similar posts when they retire.
</P>
<P>
   One executive said, ``Get me something like that. What a way to
go out,'' according to Roche, the chairman of the search firm
Heidrick &AMP; Struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Platt's new job certainly seems romantic. A wine enthusiast with
a 2,500-bottle cellar at home, he works in Kendall-Jackson's
headquarters here, about 60 miles north of San Francisco, with a
first-floor corner office that looks out on a vineyard and the
mountains that separate Napa and Sonoma counties. He has come to
the industry in good times, when the long economic expansion has
inspired many Americans to drink more expensive wine.
Kendall-Jackson has been one of the main beneficiaries, becoming
perhaps the biggest California success story of the last decade on
the strength of its $10 chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   But Platt's switch has also brought a management problem the
textbooks do not discuss: How does an executive who has already
climbed to the top _ and grown used to the trappings that come with
one of corporate America's plum jobs _ start anew? The question is
particularly relevant because both the average age and the average
tenure of chief executives at large companies are dropping. As the
calls to Roche indicate, even those chiefs with sterling resumes
and lots of energy will be pondering what to do in the coming
years.
</P>
<P>
   Platt's answer has been to sublimate his ego, forget about the
trappings and pretend that he is 20 years younger, running a
division of Hewlett-Packard. He has thrown himself into the number
crunching and small decisions that he once relegated to underlings.
``I'm actually back doing things,'' the burly, mild-mannered Platt
said with satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   In his previous life, he made millions, dined with President
Clinton and swapped ideas with foreign leaders at the World
Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland. Now, Platt says, he wants to
turn his attention to one of his passions and get the satisfaction
that comes from having direct responsibility for products.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, he had plenty of reasons to take up fishing, one of
his hobbies, after leaving Hewlett-Packard. Though the company
flourished under him at first, profits slumped in his final years.
Some employees and investors blamed his relaxed style, contrasting
him with more aggressive corporate leaders who have remade
hidebound companies. His successor, Carleton S. Fiorina, has even
become the star of Hewlett-Packard's current advertising campaign,
saying, ``The original start-up will act like one again.''
</P>
<P>
   At Kendall-Jackson, Platt has taken over a company with a
firebrand of its own. Jess Jackson, a San Francisco trial attorney
who founded the winery, and his former wife, Jane, were the only
people ever to have run it, and he remains its chairman. ``Jess
Jackson took KJ from a small, second-tier producer and placed it
squarely among the top 10 premium producers in California,'' said
David I. Freed, the chairman of Silverado Premium Properties, a
firm in Napa, Calif., that sells grapes to wineries. (Kendall is a
family name of Jackson's former wife, who is no longer in
management.)
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has the strong entrepreneurial personality and will not
have an easy time relinquishing control, say people who have worked
with him. Platt, in other words, went from the undisputed head of a
$50 billion company to one of two bosses at a $400 million concern.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
