<HEADER>
A6821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PLATT-STARTING-OVER-A     03-14 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLATT-STARTING-OVER-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
SANTA ROSA: million concern.
<TEXT>
<P>
   All of which has led some industry analysts to speculate that
Platt is mostly window-dressing to help Kendall-Jackson go public,
a move that it has been considering for two years. Even some of his
friends think his venture into the wine business is something of a
lark, Platt says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had more trouble convincing my friends this is work _
they think I sit around and do tastings all day long,'' he said.
Not so, he said: ``This is a real job.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his first tasks has been to tinker with parts of his
management style to fit his new job. Although Hewlett-Packard is a
relatively flat organization where all executives work out of
cubicles, Platt still relied on dozens of analysts to comb through
information for him. Though he is known for his mild manners, he
once stood up in front of a crowd of managers, told them they were
falling down on the job, asked them for new ideas and then blasted
those new ideas the next day.
</P>
<P>
   At Kendall-Jackson, by contrast, he has stepped gingerly. He has
told his new employees that he does not consider himself a wine
industry expert simply because he is a collector. On a tour of
Kendall-Jackson's storage rooms and bottling plant, for example, he
met some employees for the first time and spoke to them as if he
were a tourist visiting the winery, asking them about everything
from the speed of a conveyer belt to the level of tannic acid in a
wine. During the tasting of merlots and cabernets, he proclaimed
his judgment of various vintages, but then turned to
Kendall-Jackson's winemaster to see how close to the truth he was.
</P>
<P>
   Only when Platt stepped into a laboratory and noticed a
Hewlett-Packard chemicals machine did he try to show off some of
his own knowledge. ``I actually managed Hewlett-Packard's chemicals
business for many years,'' he said, smiling, to the workers in the
room.
</P>
<P>
   He has brought a similar care to his relationship with Jackson.
The two speak frequently, and Platt says he has been mindful of not
grabbing the reins too quickly. ``There are always some issues when
the owner or founder is still involved,'' said Platt, who was
Hewlett-Packard's chief when David Packard was still chairman.
``You can't just storm in and take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said, ``Lew has a selflessness about his leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has the kind of corporate experience that almost every
other professional oenophile lacks, and in a few ways he is trying
to reshape Kendall-Jackson instead of himself. His laid-back
approach, he hopes, will allow him to bring discipline to an
enterprise that has sprouted some bureaucracy as it has grown.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in January, Platt found an approval process for
travel and other expenditures that often required five signatures
for a single trip. Kendall-Jackson also had little in the way of a
formal bonus plan, and employees say they received extra money
largely at the whim of their bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all employees know their bonus depends on some combination
of their year-end review, their department's performance and the
company's profits. And managers receive a budget and can spend
money on travel as they see fit. ``As you start to give people a
little more freedom,'' Platt said, ``you can actually transfer a
lot of responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   (One byproduct of bureaucracy that Platt will not eliminate is
the door to his office. This is the first time he has ever had one,
he said.)
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Platt says he has been enjoying taking more
direct responsibility for the nuts-and-bolts decisions of running a
company. He is studying Kendall-Jackson's vineyards to determine
those that can be replanted to produce red wine, which became much
more popular in the 1990's as some doctors credited moderate
drinking of it with lowering the risk of heart disease. More than
70 percent of Kendall-Jackson's wine is now chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   Another priority is to sell more Kendall-Jackson wine overseas.
Now, just 3 percent of its output leaves the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, his current education resembles his intense
introduction to wine in the 1980's. Shortly after moving to
California for Hewlett-Packard, he immersed himself in the subject,
buying books, attending tastings and pumping for information from
his boss at the time, who was Hewlett-Packard's chief operating
officer and a wine aficionado.
</P>
<P>
   It was all a reaction to the first dinner parties he gave in his
new state and the wine he served. ``People made fun of me,'' he
remembers, ``and I didn't like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
