<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-760-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE ICE GETS THINNER FOR SMITH 
</HEADLINE>
  (hm) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the trade deadline, the Rangers did what they have been doing
all season: nothing. The Devils did what they needed to do:
something.
</P>
<P>
   With only 11 games remaining in their National Hockey League
schedule, the Rangers seem doomed to miss the Stanley Cup playoffs
for the third straight year. But they didn't, or couldn't, make a
deal to improve their chances.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, meanwhile, acquired what they lacked the last two
years in being upset in the first round of the playoffs: a
goal-scoring sniper, Alexander Mogilny.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the Rangers, with their tedious 28-33-10 record,
were somehow to scramble into the playoffs, it would merely
represent a pacifier, not a panacea.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rangers were a stock on Wall Street, their $61 million
payroll would prompt an investigation for fraud, considering the
exorbitant prices of Garden tickets.
</P>
<P>
   For $61 million, the Garden's corporate honchos surely expected
a return to the playoffs along with the promise of a developing
Stanley Cup contender. Instead, the honchos got a team that is
under .500 and, as presently constituted, is not a guarantee to be
much better in the future.
</P>
<P>
   All this has put Neil Smith, the general manager responsible for
assembling this sorry squad, on thinner ice than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, that ice was as solid as the memory of the 1994
Stanley Cup champions that Smith put together, acquiring Mark
Messier and swinging the trade-deadline deals that bolstered the
Rangers' run to the cup. And for all the contract commotion around
Messier's departure three years later, Smith deserved the
opportunity to rebuild the Rangers into a cup contender.
</P>
<P>
   With that 1994 Stanley Cup on his resume, Smith also deserved
the benefit of the doubt on hockey decisions from his boss, Dave
Checketts, the Garden president.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts, after all, is basically a basketball guy, not a
hockey guy. He operated the Utah Jazz before taking over the Knicks
and then moving upstairs as the Garden president. Quite naturally,
and quite understandably, he deferred to Smith's judgment on hockey
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Smith signed Wayne Gretzky, but after the Great One's one season
with Messier ended in the 1997 conference final, Messier was gone
to Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rangers slumped, Smith changed coaches, firing Colin
Campbell and hiring John Muckler, but that hasn't made a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   After missing the playoffs again last year, Smith signed Theo
Fleury, who was expected to score anywhere from 35 to 40 goals. He
has scored 14.
</P>
<P>
   With the Rangers on a treadmill for the third straight year,
Smith's judgment is now more than suspect; it's expendable. If the
Rangers were somehow to salvage a playoff berth, he might survive.
But if they miss the playoffs with their $61 million payroll, his
ice should melt.
</P>
<P>
   And Smith seems to know it.
</P>
<P>
   After the Rangers wasted a 3-1 lead in Monday night's eventual
4-3 loss to the cup champion Dallas Stars at the Garden, Smith
quietly wandered into the dressing area of the locker room with its
soft chairs, soft drinks, a bowl of fruit and a coffee dispenser.
</P>
<P>
   With his head down, the general manager apparently did not want
to make eye contact with any reporters who might ask a question. He
made himself a cup of coffee and departed without a word about the
team that had lost another game it should have won.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to win all the close games,'' said Brian Leetch, the
Ranger captain. ``We haven't been able to win, 3-2 or 2-1. We've
left a lot of points out there. All the top teams seem to be able
to win those close games.''
</P>
<P>
   In seven of their 11 remaining games, the Rangers will be
playing such top teams as Dallas, Detroit, Philadelphia and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But after the trade deadline passed Tuesday without a Ranger
deal, Smith stubbornly insisted that ``this team has the quality to
be well into the playoffs,'' although he wouldn't explain why this
team with so much ``quality'' has won only five games since the
All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't answer that off the cuff,'' he said. Later he said:
``These players have a responsibility. They've been treated well
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Treated by Neil Smith to a total of $61 million in salaries that
too many of them haven't earned in another sad season for the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
