u w BC-CLINTON-GUNS-(TRIMS)-     03-14 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND GORE SYNCHRONIZE MESSAGES ON GUN CONTROL AND MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARC LACEY 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton squeezed the issue into a recent
speech on China's entry into the World Trade Organization. He
inserted a few lines on the matter while discussing the need for
vaccines in Africa. He added it to his call for prescription drug
benefits for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Since one first-grader killed another two weeks ago in Michigan,
Clinton has pressed the need for tougher gun laws from the
presidential lectern in a nonstop barrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went and met with the families that lost their children at
Columbine, out in Springfield, Oregon, and Jonesboro, Arkansas. I
didn't like that,'' Clinton said at a Monday evening fund-raiser in
Chicago. ``I've met with a lot of people who died from violence or
whose loved ones died from violence. I'm just trying to keep more
people alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Out on the campaign trail, Vice President Al Gore has been just
as pointed in urging congressional Republicans to back tougher gun
laws. ``If there are shootings in the first-grade and still they
are not willing to support child trigger locks, what will it
take?'' he asked last week at a rally in Buffalo. ``Shootings in
kindergarten? Shootings in nursery school?''
</P>
<P>
   Expect to hear Clinton and Gore echoing each other more and more
between now and Election Day, whether the subject is gun
legislation, prescription drug benefits or the threat to the
economy of excessive tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and the Gore campaign are in daily contact to
coordinate their messages, and advisers to Clinton and Gore have
come to see benefits to their respective bosses, and to Democratic
candidates in general, in speaking from the same page.
</P>
<P>
   Since the shooting at Theo J. Buell Elementary School in Mount
Morris Township, Mich., Clinton has bashed the National Rifle
Association every chance he gets. He laments the tragedy of another
child slain. He urges Congress to get on with legislation. Ditto
for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the president goes out and talks about guns, he's
essentially saying A, you need a Democratic president and B, you
need to change the Congress,'' said Mark Penn, a Democratic
pollster.
</P>
<P>
   Penn said that gun control opponents traditionally have been a
small but extremely motivated voting bloc. But in this election,
because of the recent shootings, Penn said that ``suburban women
voters have come to feel the same intensity'' in favor of gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   The president's stepped-up advocacy of gun control illustrates a
White House strategy that is aimed both at moving whatever
legislation he can get through in the remaining months of his
presidency and ensuring that his agenda continues under Gore's
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Although the gun legislation is stalled because of a dispute
over checks at gun shows, aides to Clinton believe the president's
barrage could force a compromise. But even if the status quo
remains, Gore and other Democrats on the ticket will enter the fall
with a prime election issue in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``A president's power comes from the ability to frame the debate
and President Clinton is very good at that,'' said Al From,
president of the Democratic Leadership Council. ``He'd like to have
this as one of his final year legislative achievements. But if he
can't have it, he can help frame the debate to help his party.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seized on gun control as the issue du jour at a
fund-raiser in West Palm Beach, Fla., hours after news of the
school shooting in Michigan broke on Feb. 29. He has continued with
a fury ever since in appearances in Miami; Ashburn, Va.; San Jose,
Calif.; San Francisco; Cleveland and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on the public attention surrounding the incident,
Clinton called lawmakers to the White House to urge them to break
the legislative logjam. Hours later, he was meeting with the mother
of the young Michigan girl who was killed.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers vehemently dispute the notion that they want
the impasse between Congress and the White House to continue on gun
control or any other issue.
</P>
<P>
   And they reacted furiously to the suggestion by Wayne LaPierre,
vice president of the National Rifle Association, that the
president is politicking instead of working to resolve the issue
and is ``willing to accept a certain level of killing to further
his political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Reed, the White House domestic policy adviser, said the
president would much prefer to sign gun legislation than argue
about it through the election. But Clinton has made clear that he
is willing to do the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president and Gov. Bush have dramatically different
positions on the whole issue of guns and I think it ought to be a
big issue in the presidential election,'' Clinton said in an
interview Sunday on ABC's ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, he also has raised the issue of guns in
interviews on the ``CBS Evening News,'' NBC's ``Today Show,'' and
CNN's ``Burden of Proof.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Gore began their joint crusade on the gun issue long
before Kayla Renee Rolland was shot by a first-grade classmate.
</P>
<P>
   At the president's State of the Union address, Clinton endorsed
Gore's plan to require photo licenses for new gun buyers instead of
former Sen. Bill Bradley's more ambitious proposal to register
every handgun. He endorsed Gore's plan knowing it stood no chance
of being enacted during his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a president who truly wants his vice president to
succeed him, probably more than any other president before him,''
said Stephen Hess, an expert on the presidency at the Brookings
Institution in Washington. ``He sees that as part of his legacy,
particularly because his legacy is a little shaky. What you're
seeing on gun control, you're going to see with virtually every
other issue.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has taken a stance supported by the NRA, is prepared
for the president's intervention on the issue, according to aides.
Bush advisers said Clinton's high-voltage rhetoric represents a
marked contrast from how Bush would handle the gun control issue _
through compromise aimed at getting results.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the president's priorities in his second term is to
give Al Gore what would amount to a third term,'' said Bush
spokesman Ari Fleischer. ``We expect that. We're ready for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6826 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-BONUS-401(K)-900&AMP;SIDE     03-14 1980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONUS-401(K)-900&AMP;SIDEBAR-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT PAYS TO PLOD: A HARE-AND-TORTOISE RACE TO RETIREMENT WEALTH  
  
 (NOTE: OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS AT END OF STORY)  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Personal-Finance Editors)   (This consumer-friendly 900-word ``separate-buy'' financial story _
WITH SIDEBAR _ is from the March issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To
publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: THIS 900-WORD STORY OFFERS A 1,625-WORD SIDEBAR,
COMPARING THE EVEN-BETTER-THAN-ADVERTISED RETURNS OF 24 TOP 401(K)
MUTUAL FUNDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By SCOTT BURNS  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retirement savers have enjoyed a pretty good run lately _
probably even better than they think. Or so I concluded after
studying the performance of 24 leading mutual funds used in 401(k)
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Most investors collected a nice ``installment bonus'' on their
401(k)-plan investments. Not because they invested brilliantly but
because they invested methodically, making regular tax-deductible
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of an installment bonus comes from San Antonio
investment adviser Jaye C. Jarrett and WAT$, his software for
studying stock-market returns. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: TO LEARN MORE ABOUT THE BONUS THAT COMES FROM
INVESTING ON THE INSTALLMENT PLAN, SEE SCOTT BURNS'S ARTICLE, ``THE
MOLEHILL-TO-MOUNTAIN MYTH OF RETIREMENT SAVINGS,'' FROM THE
FEBRUARY ``WORTH'' MAGAZINE, VIA THE NEW YORK TIMES SPECIAL
FEATURES. STORY IS SLUGGED
BC-BADNEWS-BOOMER-MATH-750&AMP;add-WORTH-NYTSF.) &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While trying to develop spending rules for the portfolios of
retirees and charitable institutions, Jarrett discovered that if
you are making regular withdrawals from a portfolio, your actual
return will trail the advertised rate of return about 60 percent of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are making regular additions, your return will exceed
the advertised rate about 60 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The reason this happens is simple. While most investment returns
are calculated on the basis of a single, onetime investment, most
people build their 401(k) portfolios by making a lot of small
investments over a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Over a ten-year stretch, they don't invest once; they invest 120
times _ once a month _ in the same assets.
</P>
<P>
   Since investment performance varies from month to month, they
are, in effect, dollar-cost averaging: buying more shares when
prices are down and fewer when prices are down and fewer when
prices are up.
</P>
<P>
   In retirement, the whole process runs in reverse: They sell more
shares when prices are down and fewer when they are up. The net
effect is that retirement savers tend to earn a
higher-than-expected return when building up their accounts and
lower-than-expected return when drawing them down.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you had committed to investing $100 a month in Vanguard
Index 500 starting Dec. 1, 1989. Over the next ten years you would
have invested $12,000 and accumulated $31,848, assuming you earned
the annual total return of 17.37 percent that Vanguard reported for
the ten years ended Nov. 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Your account statement, however, would show a different number:
$35,901. That's a bonus of $4,053 _ an amount equal to 40 months of
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Similar installment bonuses were produced by 19 of 24 funds
popular among 401(k) investors. Each fund's installment bonus (or
penalty) was calculated using Jaye Jarrett's WAT$ software.
</P>
<P>
   The results point up some dramatic performance gaps. At $39.895,
second-ranked American Century Ultra is about $4,000 _ 40 monthly
contributions _ ahead of Vanguard Index 500 and more than $10,000
ahead of Fidelity Equity-Income.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard Primecap, the top-performing fund on the list of
$43,476, topped American Century Select by 124 monthly installments
_ quite a feat, considering that the period being measured was only
120 months long.
</P>
<P>
   There was little correlation between a fund's advertised return
and its installment bonus. And in the case of Fidelity Contrafund,
an installment penalty seemed to be the price of a constantly
escalating net asset value.
</P>
<P>
   There are other surprises hidden in the numbers. Look at where
Vanguard Index 500, which mirrors the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Stock
Index, ranks on the list _ 9th out of 22 equity funds (Fidelity
Puritan and Dodge &AMP; Cox Balanced are balanced funds.)
</P>
<P>
   This means that 36 percent of the leading 401(k) funds beat the
market.
</P>
<P>
   During the same ten-year period _ one that marked the rise of
index investing _ only 16.4 percent of all domestic equity funds
could make that claim.
</P>
<P>
   In this connection, it's worth pointing out that the average
domestic equity fund now has an expense ratio of 1.43 percent a
year, but not one of the funds on this list has an expense ratio
over 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To see if there's a way to use this information to select funds,
I conducted a simple exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Since Fidelity is by far the dominant mutual-fund company in the
401(k) world, I figured that for many 401(k) investors picking an
investment boils down to choosing among managed Fidelity funds such
as Magellan, Growth &AMP; Income, Contrafund, and Equity-Income, or
buying an index fund.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at each of five ten-year periods between 1986 and 1999,
I used the WAT$ software to learn which of those funds provided the
largest ten-year accumulation with the greatest consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Not Equity-Income. It finished last for the ten-year periods
ending in 1999, 1998, 1997, 1996, and 1995. It wasn't Magellan,
either. For all the fuss over its performance this year, it never
came in better than third.
</P>
<P>
   The index fund? Nope. It came in third or fourth most of the
time _ but it beat Magellan in three of the five most recent
periods. The respected Growth &AMP; Income fund was fairly consistent
second.
</P>
<P>
   The winner for all five ten-year periods was Contrafund, giving
401(k) investors one more piece of good news.
</P>
<P>
   Contrafund has been closed to new retail investors since April
1998 but remains open to new money from 401(k)-plan participants. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
