<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONUS-401(K)-900&AMP;SIDEBAR-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT PAYS TO PLOD: A HARE-AND-TORTOISE RACE TO RETIREMENT WEALTH  
  
 (NOTE: OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS AT END OF STORY)  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Personal-Finance Editors)   (This consumer-friendly 900-word ``separate-buy'' financial story _
WITH SIDEBAR _ is from the March issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To
publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: THIS 900-WORD STORY OFFERS A 1,625-WORD SIDEBAR,
COMPARING THE EVEN-BETTER-THAN-ADVERTISED RETURNS OF 24 TOP 401(K)
MUTUAL FUNDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By SCOTT BURNS  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retirement savers have enjoyed a pretty good run lately _
probably even better than they think. Or so I concluded after
studying the performance of 24 leading mutual funds used in 401(k)
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Most investors collected a nice ``installment bonus'' on their
401(k)-plan investments. Not because they invested brilliantly but
because they invested methodically, making regular tax-deductible
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of an installment bonus comes from San Antonio
investment adviser Jaye C. Jarrett and WAT$, his software for
studying stock-market returns. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: TO LEARN MORE ABOUT THE BONUS THAT COMES FROM
INVESTING ON THE INSTALLMENT PLAN, SEE SCOTT BURNS'S ARTICLE, ``THE
MOLEHILL-TO-MOUNTAIN MYTH OF RETIREMENT SAVINGS,'' FROM THE
FEBRUARY ``WORTH'' MAGAZINE, VIA THE NEW YORK TIMES SPECIAL
FEATURES. STORY IS SLUGGED
BC-BADNEWS-BOOMER-MATH-750&AMP;add-WORTH-NYTSF.) &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While trying to develop spending rules for the portfolios of
retirees and charitable institutions, Jarrett discovered that if
you are making regular withdrawals from a portfolio, your actual
return will trail the advertised rate of return about 60 percent of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are making regular additions, your return will exceed
the advertised rate about 60 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The reason this happens is simple. While most investment returns
are calculated on the basis of a single, onetime investment, most
people build their 401(k) portfolios by making a lot of small
investments over a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Over a ten-year stretch, they don't invest once; they invest 120
times _ once a month _ in the same assets.
</P>
<P>
   Since investment performance varies from month to month, they
are, in effect, dollar-cost averaging: buying more shares when
prices are down and fewer when prices are down and fewer when
prices are up.
</P>
<P>
   In retirement, the whole process runs in reverse: They sell more
shares when prices are down and fewer when they are up. The net
effect is that retirement savers tend to earn a
higher-than-expected return when building up their accounts and
lower-than-expected return when drawing them down.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you had committed to investing $100 a month in Vanguard
Index 500 starting Dec. 1, 1989. Over the next ten years you would
have invested $12,000 and accumulated $31,848, assuming you earned
the annual total return of 17.37 percent that Vanguard reported for
the ten years ended Nov. 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Your account statement, however, would show a different number:
$35,901. That's a bonus of $4,053 _ an amount equal to 40 months of
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Similar installment bonuses were produced by 19 of 24 funds
popular among 401(k) investors. Each fund's installment bonus (or
penalty) was calculated using Jaye Jarrett's WAT$ software.
</P>
<P>
   The results point up some dramatic performance gaps. At $39.895,
second-ranked American Century Ultra is about $4,000 _ 40 monthly
contributions _ ahead of Vanguard Index 500 and more than $10,000
ahead of Fidelity Equity-Income.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard Primecap, the top-performing fund on the list of
$43,476, topped American Century Select by 124 monthly installments
_ quite a feat, considering that the period being measured was only
120 months long.
</P>
<P>
   There was little correlation between a fund's advertised return
and its installment bonus. And in the case of Fidelity Contrafund,
an installment penalty seemed to be the price of a constantly
escalating net asset value.
</P>
<P>
   There are other surprises hidden in the numbers. Look at where
Vanguard Index 500, which mirrors the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Stock
Index, ranks on the list _ 9th out of 22 equity funds (Fidelity
Puritan and Dodge &AMP; Cox Balanced are balanced funds.)
</P>
<P>
   This means that 36 percent of the leading 401(k) funds beat the
market.
</P>
<P>
   During the same ten-year period _ one that marked the rise of
index investing _ only 16.4 percent of all domestic equity funds
could make that claim.
</P>
<P>
   In this connection, it's worth pointing out that the average
domestic equity fund now has an expense ratio of 1.43 percent a
year, but not one of the funds on this list has an expense ratio
over 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To see if there's a way to use this information to select funds,
I conducted a simple exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Since Fidelity is by far the dominant mutual-fund company in the
401(k) world, I figured that for many 401(k) investors picking an
investment boils down to choosing among managed Fidelity funds such
as Magellan, Growth &AMP; Income, Contrafund, and Equity-Income, or
buying an index fund.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at each of five ten-year periods between 1986 and 1999,
I used the WAT$ software to learn which of those funds provided the
largest ten-year accumulation with the greatest consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Not Equity-Income. It finished last for the ten-year periods
ending in 1999, 1998, 1997, 1996, and 1995. It wasn't Magellan,
either. For all the fuss over its performance this year, it never
came in better than third.
</P>
<P>
   The index fund? Nope. It came in third or fourth most of the
time _ but it beat Magellan in three of the five most recent
periods. The respected Growth &AMP; Income fund was fairly consistent
second.
</P>
<P>
   The winner for all five ten-year periods was Contrafund, giving
401(k) investors one more piece of good news.
</P>
<P>
   Contrafund has been closed to new retail investors since April
1998 but remains open to new money from 401(k)-plan participants. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Scott Burns is the
