<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6836 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-THOM-MAYNE-ARCH-2TAKE     03-14 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOM-MAYNE-ARCH-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERY ONCE IN A WHILE, BEAUTY WORKS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like other architects of his generation, Thom Mayne has resisted
beauty. He has evidently considered it a seductive idea that, like
Circe, threatens to take away a big guy's strength. So I am happy
to report that the strength of the new Diamond Ranch High School,
designed by Mayne and his firm, Morphosis, for the Pomona Unified
School District in California, lies precisely in the beauty it
brings to an already spectacular hilltop site in Diamond Bar, 40
miles east of Los Angeles. No loss of power here.
</P>
<P>
   At 56, Mayne has reached a point in his career when commissions
for large public buildings are coming his way. In a recent
monograph, he declares that, unlike most architects, he regards all
his designs, built or unbuilt, as projects. I share that view, up
to a point.
</P>
<P>
   But architecture is a medium that enables architects and others
to negotiate with uncommon depth between their inner and outer
worlds. Buildings exist simultaneously on the material and
metaphoric plane. They let us witness metaphors as rooflines
against sky. That dual identity helps account for the beauty they
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond Ranch High School must be seen, first of all, as a work
of landscape architecture, a field governed, like medicine, by the
rule ``First, do no harm.'' That doesn't mean you're not allowed to
touch the land. Reyner Banham, the first great interpreter of Los
Angeles building, once said, ``Architecture is that which changes
land use.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayne and his project architect, John Enright, and Thomas
Blurock Architects, co-architects for the school district, have
lifted blunt definition to a metaphysical plane.
</P>
<P>
   The steep-sloped 72-acre property was considered unbuildable
before the Pomona Unified School District, the school's enlightened
client, decided to grade it. When Mayne was hired, in 1996, he
determined that the design should integrate the building and the
existing topography. Don't build on the top of a hill, Frank Lloyd
Wright insisted. Build just beneath it, on the brow. Mayne has
heeded that advice.
</P>
<P>
   Almost invisible from the nearby highway, the school is
approached by a winding road, punctuated halfway up by a concrete
sign that previews Mayne's angular, industrial vocabulary. On clear
days (there aren't many), you can see the snow-capped peaks of the
San Bernardino mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Pomona itself stretches out in the valley below, a fine example
of the Southern California sprawl some people consider outrageous
but others find sublime. The school is removed from the sprawl at a
vertical and horizontal distance that gives Pomona a certain Alpine
charm. That's on a very, very clear day.
</P>
<P>
   The hill has been graded in four levels. The highest and lowest
of these are playing fields, planted directly on the land. Rooftop
terraces (above) and parking lots (below) integrate the land with
built structure. So does the plan of the building, which expresses
the school's academic structure.
</P>
<P>
   Physically and academically, it is designed as semi-independent
units that function as schools within the school, which serves
1,200 students, in grades 9 to 12. Instead of science classes in
one area, languages in another, classrooms and faculty offices for
all fields of study are clustered in each unit.
</P>
<P>
   The units are housed in two-story structures arranged along a
central open-air spine, or pedestrian street. Lower-school units
are aligned along the northern side of the spine, upper-school
clusters on the south. The units are also separated by outdoor
terraces and lawns, set at a cross-axis with the spine.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-axial spaces are composite architecture, made of
building, landscaping and views of playing fields, mountains and
sky. Besides providing circulation and a sense of identity for each
unit, these areas are great observation platforms. They root the
school to the site and establish its relationship to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Along the pedestrian street, there is more architecture, less
nature, but the architecture is nature transformed. The angular
forms of the units echo the contours of the mountains. They also
convey the crystalline structure of rock. The shapes recall the
first time you went hiking in the mountains and noticed that rock
is crystal: for a moment, it looks more precious than a gemstone,
because your eyes made the discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Mayne's outdoor pedestrian street produces a similarly magic
effect. One minute you're looking at cheap industrial materials _
concrete, corrugated metal, glass _ and then you notice that you're
walking through a place that's as exceptional and democratic as the
academic village Thomas Jefferson designed for the University of
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   In previous projects, like the Cedars-Sinai Comprehensive Cancer
Center Hospital, Mayne has created sculptures, often suspended in
space, that present the design's vocabulary in microcosmic form.
The device, which resembles a three-dimensional version of the
Russian constructivist Lissitzky's Prouns, has always seemed like a
mannerism.
</P>
<P>
   Mayne has abandoned it at Diamond Ranch. Instead, he clusters
fragments of forms and materials in the corners of the units. This
helps to unify the pedestrian street, and also turns the entire
building into a stylized microcosm of the landscape and the city
that spills across it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The counterpoint between fluid space and angular form is key to
the design's rhythmic grip. This is processional architecture, but
the sequence of spaces is flexible, mutable, not rigidly
controlled. Surprises abound, like the grand flight of concrete
stairs that doubles as an outdoor amphitheater. Proscenium stages
turn the cafeteria and the gym into performance spaces. The gym
itself is a vast, column-free cavern buttressed by earth.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, Diamond Ranch is going to be compared to a more
recent village, the Getty Center. Both are built on hilltop sites.
Both let in lots of nature. Both use a consistent vocabulary of
materials and forms to unify separate pieces.
</P>
<P>
   But when you visit the Getty, you take in the site, the
landscaping, the acres of travertine, the perfectly enameled metal
panels, and you think: money made this. Big bucks. Lots of dough.
At Diamond Ranch High School, you take in the site, the
landscaping, the cheap metal cladding, the concrete terraces, and
think: poverty made this. Need, resourcefulness and talent. No
expense has been unspared. Where money was lacking, love had to
pitch in. This is not a bad lesson for high school students and the
rest of us who may need refresher courses later on.
</P>
<P>
   It's in the nature of Southern California to hazard such an
odious comparison between a luxurious museum and a public high
school. In this sprawling urban condition, buildings call to one
another across vast distances. The tall buildings of downtown Los
Angeles and Wilshire Boulevard are the Getty's vertical cousins,
the freeway and the ocean its horizontal pals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Connected Isolation'' is Mayne's title for a 1993 monograph of
his work. That idea drives the articulation of the units at Diamond
Ranch, and it also abstracts the region's social ecology.
</P>
<P>
   This building evokes another kind of connectedness, the links
between buildings that represent contemporary urban intelligence.
Imagine being stuck in some suburban community planned by the New
Urbanism. Talk about isolation: the buildings are close together
but disconnected from anything larger than market research.
</P>
<P>
   But go to Mayne's Diamond Ranch High School, Peter Eisenman's
Wexner Center for Art in Columbus, Ohio, or Tod Williams and Billie
Tsien's Neurosciences Institute in La Jolla, and you step through
the window to a wider world. The horizon expands. We hear a lot
about sense of place, and this school certainly provides it. But it
also addresses an adolescent impulse as prevalent in the suburbs as
the desire for roots. It goes, ``Get Me Outta Here!''
</P>
<P>
   I don't think Thom Mayne has ever been accused of sweetness.
Abrasive is more like it. Sore-thumbed. Hard-edged, sometimes to
the point of coldness. At Kate Mantilini, the Beverly Hills
restaurant he designed in 1986, you often feel at risk of
hypothermia, and not because of the air-conditioning. Diamond Ranch
has bite but no chill. This is partly due to the presence of
schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   But the warmth is also due to smooth contours of the landscape,
which is intensified by the building's angular forms. And the light
pulled down by the metal cladding has an almost physical softness.
There are spots where you look out from a height over the playing
fields toward Pomona and the mountains beyond. You can't quite hear
the athletes' voices. The atmosphere is pure potential. You've been
here before: you recognize the altitude from dreams.
</P>
<P>
   I sympathize with those who prefer old school buildings to
modern ones. But age isn't what makes them appealing. It's their
weirdness, their misfit quality, the comic images they summon up of
theater owners unplugging the soundtrack at showings of ``Rock
Around the Clock.'' Collegiate Gothic style, come to think of it,
is pure Addams Family values.
</P>
<P>
   There's one supremely Gothic moment at Diamond Ranch: an outdoor
courtyard that adjoins the faculty lounge. The courtyard's concrete
walls are three stories tall, and virtually windowless. One can
envision teachers walking there silently in a circle during breaks.
The height of the space is exaggerated by a parapet designed to
prevent students from peering down from above, but this protective
device is also a flagrant invitation to toss water balloons and
other ritual offerings over the side. The Mayans never built ball
courts more awesome than this.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
