<SLUG> BC-TV-HUNGER-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIF. UNIVISION WORKERS IN 4TH WEEK OF HUNGER STRIKE OVER WAGES
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.)  (fb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRESNO, Calif. _ Refusing to eat solid foods for the last three
weeks, broadcast journalists have joined television cameramen and
technicians at a television station here in a hunger strike to
demand better wages and other terms in the station's first union
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The strike at KFTV, Channel 21, a Spanish-language station of
the Univision network, began nearly four weeks ago. Three of the
eight strikers who began fasting on Feb. 17, including a union
negotiator, were still having no solid food on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 21 station employees who joined the Communication Workers
of America in May 1999, seven went on the fast, saying that
although they worked at the highest-rated television station in the
area, their salaries were below those paid by English-language
stations in the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to take a drastic measure to let people become aware
that discrimination, labor abuses and exploitation of workers
happens even at the highest levels,'' said Fermin Chavez, the
anchor at Channel 21, who subsisted on juice while continuing to
give his newscasts. ``It doesn't just occur out in the fields or in
small businesses, but even at companies like Univision.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, 15 pounds lighter and complaining of weakness and
cramps, broke his fast with a bowl of chicken soup on Wednesday
night, saying he was following doctors' orders. That left three on
the fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about trying to be Gandhi,'' Chavez said. ``We were
not being taken seriously and had to make a point.''
</P>
<P>
   The general manager of the station, Maria L. Gutierrez, called
the hunger strike a melodramatic gesture. ``This is a
garden-variety labor dispute in connection with a first contract,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Channel 21, with 54 employees, is one of 19 stations owned by
Univision, the largest Spanish-language network in the country,
with about 30 broadcast affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Reina Cardenas, a reporter, is paid $25,300 a year and has been
offered a $1,200 raise, she said. Chavez, 37, who anchors the
station's noon and 11 p.m. newscasts, makes $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Anchors at local ABC and NBC affiliates in Fresno make $80,000
to $100,000 a year, says Carrie Biggs-Adams, the contract
negotiator who is on hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for Univision stated that its wages could not be
compared with those of networks with more means.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
