<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-REPUBS-GASOLINE-NYT     03-14 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-GASOLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS DROP CALL FOR ROLLBACK OF GASOLINE TAX  
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas, Miss., Pa., Okla.) (fb) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans backed away on Tuesday from their
call to repeal a 4.3-cent-a-gallon gasoline tax to lower the
skyrocketing prices at the pump and cool consumers' anger.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans have criticized the Clinton
administration as failing to address the soaring fuel costs. Sen.
Trent Lott, R-Miss., the Senate majority leader, has labeled the
levy the ``Gore tax'' because Vice President Al Gore cast a
tie-breaking vote in 1993 that raised the federal excise tax on
gasoline to 18.4 cents a gallon from 14.1.
</P>
<P>
   But an outcry from leading Republicans, road builders and
truckers has forced supporters of the repeal into a retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not get bogged down on only one dimension of the
problem, that is in itself a short-term dimension that offers scant
relief,'' Dick Armey, R-Texas, the House majority leader, told
reporters Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to all House members, the chairman of the House
Transportation and Infrastructure Committee, Bud Shuster, R-Pa.,
and three other top panel members warned that rescinding the tax
increase was ``the wrong way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuster, whose influence stems from his committee's power to
dole out lucrative road and bridge projects to colleagues'
districts, said the Transportation Department estimated that a
4.3-cent repeal would slash highway funding by $20.5 billion
through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``An average of 420,000 high-paying jobs would be lost in each
of the years 2002 and 2003,'' Shuster said.
</P>
<P>
   If that were not chilling enough to Republicans eager to
maintain their tenuous control of the House this fall, other party
leaders voiced skepticism over the repeal's impact on consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it has any effect on fuel costs,'' said Rep.
J.C. Watts, R-Okla., a member of the House Republican leadership.
``Supply and demand is driving price right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders said they would shift the focus of their
attack to the administration's efforts to persuade domestic
refineries and oil-producing countries to increase production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's look at the larger longterm problem of U.S. dependency
on foreign supplies, failed diplomatic relationships with critical
producing nations, and our own inability to fully develop our own
domestic resource,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a House Appropriations subcommittee would become
the latest congressional panel to grill Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson over the administration's multipronged efforts to bring
down fuel prices rising toward $2 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the majority whip, and Watts, were
planning a news conference at a Capitol Hill filling station to
castigate the administration's policies.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson pleaded his case on three network morning shows
Tuesday. ``We're moving ahead with getting refiners and gasoline
people and oil companies to get more gasoline out into the
market,'' the secretary said on ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
``We know people are hurting, but we're moving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CASUALTIES-ART     03-14 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CASUALTIES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
PSKOV, Russia: by comparison.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever one may think of the conduct of the Chechen war, it was
hard to fault Tuesday's proceedings. By any definition, these men
were military heroes, Sokolov first among them.
</P>
<P>
   It was a small 2,500-foot-high ridge near the southern Chechnya
village of Urus-Kert that Company Six of Pskov's Regiment 104 took
Feb. 29, on orders to stop some 2,000 Chechen guerrillas from
escaping into neighboring Dagestan. By that afternoon they were
trapped in a fierce battle, with the nearest reinforcements more
than 5 miles away. Command of the force fell to Capt. Sokolov, who
had wanted to go to Chechnya last fall, during the bombings.
Instead, he shipped out from Pskov barely a month ago, just before
his 28th birthday on Feb. 16.
</P>
<P>
   At Urus-Kert, Sokolov organized the final defense of the
hilltop, aided by a few soldiers from a platoon that had broken
through rebel lines. At 11:30 p.m. that day, hundreds of guerrillas
began a nightlong attack against the defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Sokolov, by then wounded in the hand, rounded up six of his
company's newest members as the guerrillas drew close. He told them
to attempt a retreat, then radioed Russian forces and ordered
strikes on his own position in a last attempt to repel the
attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen Russians died that night, including Sokolov. The rest
were killed as the battle raged on. The six men Sokolov ordered to
flee were the only survivors.
</P>
<P>
   In a private ceremony on Monday, two able-bodied survivors came
to the yellow stucco gymnasium of the 104th Regiment, where the
caskets lay in state. There they kneeled before Sokolov's bier and
thanked him for his sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the funeral, a truck bearing his body arrived at a
small church in a run-down section of town, trailed by a bus
carrying family and friends. An honor guard unloaded the coffin. To
the beat of a snare drum and a trumpet, the soldiers carried
Sokolov past a broken iron gate and down a path of rutted frozen
mud strewn with spruce boughs.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four soldiers followed the coffin, and perhaps 75
mourners. Sokolov's mother buried her face in her husband's
shoulder, sobbing as she walked. Mrs. Sokolova, her head shrouded
in black lace, was silent.
</P>
<P>
   As they reached the newly dug grave, the soldiers lifted the
rust-colored cover from the coffin, revealing the Russian tricolor
and a small window above Sokolov's face. His father, Vladimir
Timofeyevich, fell upon it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgive me for remaining alive,'' he cried, before being
lifted from the coffin and into a relative's arms.
</P>
<P>
   A camouflage-clad officer spoke over the coffin. ``They did
everything for Russia to survive,'' he said. ``We will do
everything so that the cause you struggled for will continue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
