<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA LINEUP FINALLY AT FULL STRENGTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The UCLA men's basketball team will unleash its
most talented lineup when it opens NCAA Tournament play Thursday
against Ball State in the Minneapolis Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   It features a rapidly improving junior point guard, Earl Watson;
two big men with NBA talent, Jerome Moiso and Dan Gadzuric; and two
McDonald's All-Americans on the wing, Jason Kapono and JaRon Rush.
</P>
<P>
   For size, talent and experience, it's probably UCLA's best
quintet since 1997, when Cameron Dollar, Toby Bailey, Charles
O'Bannon, J.R. Henderson and Jelani McCoy fueled a late-season
charge into the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Rush's 24-game suspension, the Bruins have had few
opportunities to pair him with Kapono. Rush might not start against
Ball State - he hasn't started all season - but he'll be on the
court early and often.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good chance you'll see quality minutes for Jason and
JaRon at the wings,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono, a 6-foot-7 freshman, is a dead-eye shooter (47.7 percent
from 3-point range) who can ease Watson's ballhandling load. Rush,
a 6-6 sophomore, scores from inside and outside and is a superb
rebounder (5.3 per game) for his size. Kapono can play guard on
offense (for ballhandling) and Rush can play guard on defense (for
quickness).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great combination,'' Watson said. ``I think it'll cause
matchup problems. Most (shooting) guards are my size (6-foot).''
</P>
<P>
   Getting his wind back: Rush didn't expect to be in top shape
after missing 24 games and a slew of practices because of his NCAA
suspension. But he didn't lose as much conditioning as he expected.
</P>
<P>
   He has averaged 20.6 minutes in three games and fatigued only
once - against Washington State - after several grueling practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll be ready for the tournament,'' Rush said. ``I
just need to get a little more running in practice and get my reps
with the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Dome doings: The Bruins closed the regular season with their
finest 3-point shooting in years, hitting 44.2 percent during the
six-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Can they keep it up? Perimeter shooting is critical to offense;
it expands defenses and gives Moiso and Gadzuric room inside.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy, not with tournament pressure, better
competition and the awkward shooting background in domes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while to get used to it,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   In their lone dome experience of the season, Syracuse's Carrier
Dome, the Bruins shot 18.2 percent from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   The itinerary: The Bruins practiced for two hours Monday, then
attended their postseason banquet. (Watson, Moiso and Kapono were
named tri-MVPs.) Tuesday, they practiced for 90 minutes before
boarding a 5 p.m. flight for Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   They'll have a light workout today in the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week isn't physically going to have a dramatic change,
but the mental preparation is most important,'' Lavin said.
``What's most important is to be fresh mentally and physically and
be feeling good about ourselves. It's less-is-more at this time of
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
