<HEADLINE>
WRECK KILLS 1 ON RICE DEBATE TEAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn. Ill.) 
 
By S.K. BARDWELL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A member of Rice University's forensics team was
killed and five other students and two coaches injured when a
minivan carrying squad members back from a competition in Omaha,
Neb., was rear-ended late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The crash is the third this year involving Texas college
students traveling to competitive events.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Shepard, vice president of public affairs for Rice, said
Monday's accident could have been more tragic had Rice officials
not reviewed and tightened student travel policies in the wake of
the earlier crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred at 10:35 p.m. CST on Interstate 45 in
north Houston, said Harris County sheriff's deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Two vans carrying 11 Rice students and three coaches were
southbound when construction that reduced the southbound freeway to
one lane caused both vehicles to slow to a stop, deputies said.
</P>
<P>
   A Ford F-250 pickup pulling a trailer loaded with heavy
equipment was unable to stop, and it slammed into the back of one
van, driving it into the back of the van in front, said officials.
</P>
<P>
   Dead at the scene was 18-year-old Daniel Henning of Vernon
Hills, Ill. Henning was a passenger in the rear van, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Austin, Texas, Henning was a freshman attending the
university's Baker College, Shepard said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when the Rice debate team won the national Pi Delta
Kappa forensics competition in St. Louis, Shepard said one of nine
individual championships the team received went to Henning, in the
``Student Congress'' competition.
</P>
<P>
   The team was returning from a national competition in Omaha over
the weekend, Shepard said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other students, both passengers in the same van as Henning,
were taken to Memorial Hermann Hospital by Life Flight helicopter,
One had a broken leg, the other was being checked for possible
internal injuries. Both were listed in fair condition.
</P>
<P>
   Two coaches and three other students were taken to Memorial
Hospital Northwest and treated for less serious injuries. All had
been released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old driver of the pickup was not seriously injured.
Authorities said the driver could be charged.
</P>
<P>
   In January, three music students from the University of North
Texas were killed when a van traveling the wrong way on I-20 near
Gordon slammed into their car as they drove to a weekend
performance with the Abilene Philharmonic Orchestra. The driver of
the van also died in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, four members of the Prairie View A&AMP;M track team died
and several were injured on their way to a track meet in Pine
Bluff, Ark., when their van veered off a northeast Texas road and
rolled, ejecting several of its 15 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The Feb. 10 Prairie View wreck caused Rice officials to review
travel policies, Shepard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was reflected in the fact that we had older
drivers, and everyone was wearing seat belts,'' Shepard said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rice minivans were being driven by a coach and a senior
student when the accident occurred, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alas, there are some accidents that cannot be prevented by
being careful,'' Shepard said. ``This was one of those.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
