<HEADER>
A6878 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AMERICAN-PIE-MUSIC-$A     03-14 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-PIE-MUSIC-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW SPIN THAT MAKES A NEW SONG  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't forgive her for this,'' a fellow Madonna fan declared
to me recently as her reworking of ``American Pie,'' from the
soundtrack to ``The Next Best Thing,'' wafted through the
microbrewery where we sat.
</P>
<P>
   My friend was not alone in being offended that the queen of pop
would even consider touching Don McLean's relentlessly popular
ballad about ``the day the music died.'' With her version earning
violently mixed reactions, it is evident that this dare was as
risky for Madonna as her many earlier, flashier ones had been.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pie'' is one of the great monuments of musical
cheese, a song everyone scorns but few can resist. Since its
overwhelming success in 1972, its eight minutes of tangled
allusions to the icons of the turbulent 1960s, offered by McLean in
a collegiate folkie's warble, have come to represent the nadir of
songwriterly self-seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   Its defenders love ``American Pie'' precisely because of those
references, which are actually about as cryptic as a good Sunday
puzzle. On the Internet, which has made such things documentable,
interpretations have been actively debated since at least 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Most read the song as an elegy for Buddy Holly and his innocent
rock 'n' roll. Others explore it as an account of the Kennedy
assassination or a Bible-tinged foretelling of the apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   Parodies of the song hit a new level when the renowned lyric
juggler Weird Al Yankovic rewrote it last summer to coincide with
the release of ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phanton Menace.''
Besides Anakin Skywalker, others who have stood in for McLean's
Buddy Holly include Bill Gates, television science fiction heroes
from ``Star Trek'' and ``Babylon Five,'' and Charles Schulz.
</P>
<P>
   Self-described techno-nerds have written versions praising the
Linux operating system and defaming America Online. One industrious
fan even translated McLean's verses into Latin. This endless
dismemberment further alienates already contemptuous critics,
because it caricatures our own interpretive efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pie'' has not attracted many top-notch artistic
interpreters either, although the proudly shameless Garth Brooks
and the truly bold Tori Amos have given it a whack. Respectable
rockers have generally stayed away from the song, leaving it to a
list of performers that includes the Dueling Banjos, the King's
Singers, the John Williams Orchestra and the Brady Bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes Madonna, who usually works so hard to be
trend-setting, and, lately, tasteful. What does she sense in this
song? Her version trims every ounce of fat, eliminating three and a
half verses and almost all the references that have fascinated so
many listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics and fans have denounced her for this. But Madonna
knows she is better served by myth than history, and so she and her
favorite sound designer, the producer William Orbit, have created
an anthem out of time, uninterested in the moment McLean depicted,
and surprisingly appropriate today.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna's ``American Pie'' captures the notion of the bystander,
which was the core of McLean's version, too. The seeming complexity
of the lyrics, and his somber delivery, obscured the fact that this
song was not about making history but about helplessly witnessing
it.
</P>
<P>
   Setting plaintively ethereal vocals against an anesthetic bed of
light beats and effects, Madonna tells the first-person part of
McLean's story, the saga of a shy, average fan whose soul was saved
just enough by rock 'n' roll to give him a small place in a
bewildering America.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Next Best Thing,'' the song creates exactly such a
place for an outcast group that Madonna has long championed. The
film's ``American Pie'' singalong is, in fact, an act of gay
liberation.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna's character, Abbie, and her gay pal and eventual
co-parent, Robert, played by Rupert Everett, stand with a dear
friend at the burial of his lover. Across the grave are the lover's
disapproving parents, who insisted on this church funeral instead
of what the deceased wanted: to have his ashes scattered in the
desert while his friends sang ``American Pie.'' Quietly, Robert
begins to sing, and eventually the pals join in, asserting their
rights through this blockbuster song.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who is openly gay, insisted that the scene use
``American Pie'' instead of Madonna's choice, the punkier Patti
Smith song ``Easter,'' or a disco or show tune from the gay
liberation songbook. He must have realized the stronger impact of
attaching the notion of gay rights to this utterly mainstream song.
The moment encapsulates the film's message, which is that no one
should be excluded from ``normal'' life.
</P>
<P>
   Separate from the film, Madonna's version works differently.
Instead of acting as a key that admits exiles into the center of
society, her frostily cosmic ``American Pie'' reflects upon our
shared sense of being on the margin. The verses, about a fan who
hopelessly wishes to be a star, a lover who watches someone steal
his sweetheart at a dance and a tripartite deity who boards that
old mystery train and departs, depict possibility straying beyond
one's grasp.
</P>
<P>
   People can relate to that feeling now, as the information age
progresses at a speed that most brains or modems cannot comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone believes Madonna's recent turn toward the
spiritual, which also informs her recording of an anthem many
consider vaguely religious. Whatever she really gets from her
well-publicized yoga practice, the singer has again homed in on an
emerging social mood.
</P>
<P>
   Don McLean's ``American Pie'' was a cry for things to slow down
during the spasmodic death of the counterculture. As intense as
public life was then, things are moving even faster today.
Madonna's ``American Pie'' taps into people's hunger to be more
than witnesses. Beneath its cool veneer is a longing for the
opposite: music that comes close enough to touch, a call to life
instead of a lament for what we let die.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
