<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LOTTO BETTING ON HIGHER ODDS TO JACK UP POT, TAKE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a risky move calculated to increase ticket
sales, the Texas Lottery Commission on Tuesday tentatively agreed
to add four balls to the 50-ball lotto drawings, a change designed
to fatten jackpots by making them harder to win.
</P>
<P>
   Despite predictions that the major rule change will upset some
loyal lotto players, it could jack up sales by $166 million a year,
officials estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in June, players would have to match their six chosen
numbers with the six numbered balls drawn from a batch of 54 balls,
under rules unanimously approved by the three-member commission.
</P>
<P>
   The change would make the odds of winning about one in 25.8
million. As the game is now, with 50 balls drawn, the odds of
winning are one in 15.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The same proposal was put forward last year as a way to bolster
sagging ticket sales, but it was withdrawn due to player
opposition. The players argued against any significant change in
the game rules or odds of winning.
</P>
<P>
   Unsure how to proceed and under legislative scrutiny, the
commission conducted a series of public hearings around the state
late last year to gather ideas. Officials warned that the odds
change, though unpopular among some players, would be necessary if
sales didn't improve.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, for example, average weekly sales in the first half
of fiscal year 1999 were $2.1 million, but in fiscal 2000, the
Houston average has sunk to $1.4 million a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's vote begins the formal process to make necessary
changes to the Lotto Texas game to renew player interest,'' said
Chairman Harriet Miers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We indicated last fall changes should be considered if sales
did not improve. While instant ticket sales have improved, Lotto
sales remain sluggish. We hope to engender renewed excitement about
Lotto Texas,'' Miers said.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the commission agreed to publish in the Texas
Register proposed rules that would implement the change. After a
30-day public comment period, the commission may consider adopting
the rules as proposed, but the changes wouldn't take effect until
June, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action today should not come as a surprise to anyone,''
said Lottery Director Linda Cloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Texas has one of the largest beginning jackpot prizes
in the country ($4 million), many of our players don't get excited
enough to get into the game until the jackpot climbs into the
double-digit range,'' Cloud said.
</P>
<P>
   She projected that the $166 million in additional sales would
yield an extra $26 million a year for the Foundation School Fund,
which supports Texas public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud added that within a year, the change should increase
average jackpots from $9 million to about $19 million. To achieve
that, the payout would increase from the current 50 percent of
sales to 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lower tier prizes also would increase, Cloud said.
</P>
<P>
   The public can comment on the proposal by writing the Texas
Lottery Commission, attention Kimberly L. Kiplin, general counsel;
P.O. Box 16630, Austin, Texas, 78761-6630.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
