<HEADER>
A6883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DATE-RAPE-DEATH-NYT     03-14 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATE-RAPE-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 GUILTY OF MANSLAUGHTER IN DATE-RAPE DRUG CASE 
</HEADLINE>
 (hm) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Three young men have been found guilty of involuntary
manslaughter in one of the first criminal cases in the nation
involving GHB, a colorless, odorless recreational drug that has
been linked to date rapes.
</P>
<P>
   In two separate trials that concluded Monday and Tuesday, the
men were convicted of putting the drug into a soft drink consumed a
year ago by Samantha Reid, a 15-year-old high school freshman who
lived in the southern suburbs of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   After telling her mother that she was going to a movie, Samantha
went instead to a small party with two friends. All three girls
were apparently served GHB-laced drinks at the party without their
knowledge. Samantha died within hours, while one of her friends,
Melanie Sindone, went into a coma for half a day. She has since
recovered. The third girl did not touch her drink.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha's death brought nationwide attention to the spread of
GHB, or gamma hydroxybutyrate, which can be made in a kitchen using
recipes from the Internet that include ingredients like paint
remover, furniture polish remover or drain clearing agents. Two
Michigan Republicans, Rep. Fred Upton and Sen. Spencer Abraham,
pushed legislation through Congress this winter putting GHB on the
federal list of the most-controlled substances. It joins heroin and
LSD as a so-called Schedule 1 drug.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton signed the legislation last month, and it took
effect Monday. The new law, which does not apply to Samantha's
case, prescribes prison sentences of up to 20 years for GHB
trafficking, and life sentences when a death occurs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to involuntary manslaughter, Joshua Cole, 19, and
Daniel Brayman and Nicholas Holtschlag, both 18, were convicted of
two counts each of mixing harmful substances in drinks. They were
acquitted of a more serious poisoning charge, mixing lethal
substances in drinks.
</P>
<P>
   The three men face up to 15 years in prison for the manslaughter
charge and up to five years for each of the lesser poisoning
charges; they could have been sentenced to life in prison if they
had been convicted of the more serious poisoning charge. A fourth
man, Erick Limmer, 26, was convicted of being an accessory to
manslaughter, mixing a harmful substance in a drink, delivery of
marijuana and possession of GHB. He faces up to five years in
prison on the most serious of these charges, being an accessory to
manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing for all four men was set for March 30. Douglas M.
Baker, Wayne County's deputy chief prosecutor for drug cases, said
he would insist on jail time for the men, but he had not decided
what sentences to recommend.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors said Cole told the police that he put the GHB in
the girls' drinks to make the party more ``lively.'' The other
three defendants unsuccessfully contended that Cole, who was tried
separately, should be held solely responsible for the crime.
Holtschlag's lawyer, Brian T. Dailey, declined to comment Tuesday
on the verdict. Lawyers for the other three men did not return
telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Drug Enforcement Administration, 65 GHB-related
deaths and more than 5,700 documented cases of GHB abuse have
occurred since 1990, when the Food and Drug Administration banned
sales of the substance. There have also been 15 sexual assault
cases involving 30 victims drugged with GHB.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny quantities of the drug produce lassitude and a temporary
euphoria, and sometimes hallucinations. Its use is frequently
followed by temporary memory loss. But the slightest variation in
the quantity or purity of the drug can produce unconsciousness and
even respiratory failure and death.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians recommend that a person rendered unconscious by GHB
receive immediate care from an ambulance crew or emergency room
doctors who have been told to suspect the drug's presence.
Toxicologists have said that Samantha died because the young men
argued among themselves instead of seeking immediate medical
attention for her when she passed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
