<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6884 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ELTON-JOHN-AIDA-ART-3     03-14 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELTON-JOHN-AIDA-ART-3TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN `AIDA' BORN OF ECSTASIES AND EXPLOSIONS 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one was selling peanuts, and instead of metal bars there were
velvet ropes, but Elton John, the evening's prize peacock, was
being scrutinized as surely as if he were in a zoo.
</P>
<P>
   It was Dec. 9, 1999, the opening-night performance of Disney's
``Aida'' in Chicago, a little more than three months before the
Broadway opening on Thursday at the Palace Theater.
</P>
<P>
   At the party afterward, hundreds of people trooped into the
Hotel Allegro, where John was escorted into an elegant holding pen.
A few friends followed, including a stout Billie Jean King and a
willowy Lynn Wyatt, the Texas socialite, who had flown in just to
see the show (what fun!). The fact that the hotel had arranged a
VIP platter for them that combined sushi and pastries fazed John
not at all; he dove for the chocolate while the show's press agent
valiantly blocked the television cameras. After all, the man has
given up drinking, drugging and (most of) his other bad behavior.
Can't a superstar eat an eclair in peace?
</P>
<P>
   The gawkers lined up, chewing their own food, and watched John
from the world outside the rope. That is a byproduct of celebrity,
of course. It's just that some of those gawkers also happened to be
in the cast or on the staff of ``Aida'' and they wanted a look,
too. Because, besides his one visit to a New York rehearsal last
September, they hadn't seen him either.
</P>
<P>
   This night was the first time the composer had watched his own
show in its revised version, following a disastrous attempt in
Atlanta in 1998. No midnight conferences on the road for him. You
want something, you can fax him. Jule Styne must be scoffing in his
grave.
</P>
<P>
   But as one of those ubiquitous Disney songs has it, Broadway has
indeed become ``a whole new world,'' one in which industry types
are just grateful that an internationally known songwriter like
Elton John would deign to sit down and write a score at all,
because really, why should he? The theater is not only hard work
but collaboration, and this man has done just fine by himself,
thank you, selling more than 60 million albums during his 30-year
career.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else, though, he wants more. I met with him
earlier that day in Chicago, in his suite at the Four Seasons
Hotel, where he talked about being 52 and finding that life as a
legend isn't quite enough. He would still like to grow, try
something new. So when Disney executives presented him with the
children's-book version of ``Aida'' by Leontyne Price, herself a
famous Aida, he and the lyricist Tim Rice, his collaborator on
three songs for ``The Lion King,'' went for it. They were mostly
excited, John said, that it was not a remake of an animated
musical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also the fact that it had already been done by Verdi was
playing with fire,'' John said that afternoon, curled up on a fat
red couch. ``It appealed to my sense of masochism.'' He was
barefoot and wearing a black velour bathrobe with ``Aida''
emblazoned on the back. The ever-present plate of cookies sat on
the table before him and his robe fell open just enough to show his
bare chest. I halfway expected him to pick up the remote and turn
on ``One Life to Live.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to plot, though, daytime drama has nothing on this
``Aida,'' which varies from the opera. A Nubian princess, the title
character, is captured by an Egyptian warrior, Radames, who falls
in love with her instead of his betrothed, Amneris, an Egyptian
princess; when the forbidden romance is revealed, Amneris shows
mercy by letting them die together, buried alive in the same tomb
(mercy being a somewhat relative notion).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragic but hopeful love triangle,'' John says, ``with
people giving up everything for love, everything they owned, their
customs, religious teachings. They are willing to die together
because they love each other.''
</P>
<P>
   John wrote the songs the same way he always does, lyrics first,
faxed by Rice. ``The big advantage was that it started with a story
and we wrote it to running order,'' John said. ``Disney said not
for me to say this but I wrote it in 21 days, including the
instrumental music. It came out very quickly. What `The Lion King'
did for me was to open so many doors. I'm a comfortable artist,
concerts always sold out, which is nice, but that can be boring. It
takes courage to diversify and have other challenges. I want to
succeed desperately, but I'm a novice. I have a great CV, but I'm
putting my foot in the water with this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney is, too. ``Aida'' is the first stage musical it is
producing under the umbrella of its new Hyperion Theatricals unit;
the different name is meant to emphasize that the show is not
geared toward children. It is also the first Disney show that has
not been adapted from an animated movie, like ``The Lion King,''
``Beauty and the Beast'' or ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame,'' which
opened to lukewarm notices in Berlin last June, where it is still
playing.
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that Disney could use a public relations coup
with ``Aida,'' instead of the black eye it got with the Atlanta
version; the company's financial travails in the last year have
cast its chief, Michael Eisner, in a less than glowing light.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To this end, Disney has hired some of the theater's best talent
for the ``Aida'' team. After the Atlanta run, in which an enormous
pyramid chronically malfunctioned, Disney hired the director Robert
Falls, who last season won a Tony Award for his revival of ``Death
of a Salesman.'' He and David Henry Hwang, who won a Tony for ``M.
Butterfly,'' have rewritten the book that was begun in Atlanta by
Linda Woolverton.
</P>
<P>
   Also new is the set and costume designer Bob Crowley, who won
his Tony for ``Carousel,'' and Wayne Cilento, the choreographer,
who won his for ``Tommy.'' The three stars are: Heather Headley in
the title role (she was Nala, the young lioness in ``The Lion
King''); Sherie Rene Scott as Amneris (Randy Newman's ``Faust''),
and Adam Pascal as Radames (``Rent'').
</P>
<P>
   While the show is said to cost $15 million _ the same cost
estimate as ``The Lion King'' _ Peter Schneider, chairman of Disney
Studios, refused to verify the amount. ( Schneider and Thomas
Schumacher, president of feature animation at Disney, are the
producers of ``Aida.'') ``We never talk about money,'' Schneider
declared. ``At the end of the day, it is immaterial what it
costs.'' (Is it any wonder that the rest of the theater industry
resents them?)
</P>
<P>
   None of the intrigue, offstage or on, however, seems to concern
John. ``Because I'm a busy bee and I've got a career of my own,
I've really left it to them,'' he said. ``I'm not going to swan
onto the stage and say I'm Elton John. I'm going to tell Bob Falls
what to do? I don't think so. He just won a Tony for `Death of a
Salesman.' You have to let people edit and you have to be able to
take that, otherwise it's not worth it. Some things with `The Lion
King' I got my way and some I didn't. That's the whole point of
being out of town and having the opportunity to see if it works.''
</P>
<P>
   John was stung by the reception for last summer's release of the
all-star ``Aida'' concept recording that included artists as varied
as the Spice Girls and Boyz II Men. People magazine included it in
its ``Worst of Song'' list for the year, saying, ``Roll over
Beethoven and tell Verdi the news: this popmeister version of his
1871 opera is a tragic bore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Universal didn't believe `Aida' was going to happen,'' John
said. ``They did the record to appease me and didn't promote it. In
hindsight, doing an eclectic album before the stage version comes
out, well, live and learn. It didn't do as well as it should have
done.''
</P>
<P>
   And though British tabloids screamed that he might be
financially strapped, after problems with his former manager, John
said he was doing fine. ``Everyone assumes I'm in debt,'' he said.
``I sacked my manager two years ago because my finances were in a
mess. Unfortunately, I trusted someone and shouldn't have. But I
don't stick pins into voodoo dolls. I can always go out and make
money. I've had to pay attention to it now the same way I had to
pay attention to my drug habit. It's no good saying I don't want to
know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has something of a nest egg certainly, from his astonishing
string of hits starting in 1971 with ``Your Song'' to his remake of
his own ``Candle in the Wind,'' which he performed at the funeral
of his friend Diana, Princess of Wales, in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That loss came on the heels of the murder of another friend,
Gianni Versace, who, John says, had loved his score of ``Aida.''
Since Versace's murder in July 1997, John said, ``I take
precautions now in America. I have a bodyguard. But not in London.
You can't be a prisoner because of fear. In England, where I live
most of the time, the rules are different. The press can be so
vicious. America reveres personalities and stars so much, but in
England they love you for five minutes then shoot you down. I'd
rather have that, actually, than be shut off in that Michael
Jackson or Barbra Streisand control syndrome where you end up
having no clue what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   In the States, John keeps an apartment in Atlanta because of its
airport; he can play mostly anywhere and fly home at night. ``I've
been 30 years on the road as Elton John and I prefer to come
home,'' he said. ``Atlanta is a place where I can breathe and not
be involved in the Elton John industry 24 hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   On this wintery day, at least, he seemed quite mellow, sitting
around all cozy in his robe. ``I threw a huge party when I turned
50 because at one point I thought I'd never make 50, the way I've
lived my life,'' he said. ``I always had a problem with my weight
and that gets harder as you get older. But I've never been happier.
I'm calmer. There is always a Vesuvius in me, in any creative
person. I see my picture in the newspaper and look the size of
Orson Welles, but from an inner point of view I think it's great.
I'm fit. I play tennis. No coke, no drinking, no smoking. After the
amount of excess in my life, this is a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says in one of my prior lives I was Louis XIV,'' he
continued, ``but in my next life I'd like to be a woman, see things
from their perspective. As a gay man who was married for six years,
I'm interested in what women feel, what they need.'' He giggled.
``Plus the clothes, the accessories are so much better. I'd need a
whole house just for the handbags.''
</P>
<P>
   For almost seven years, John's partner has been David Furnish, a
filmmaker, and between that relationship and his work, he says he
is content. ```Lion King' and `Aida' got me out of doing the
album-to-video syndrome,'' he said. ``I loathe and detest videos.
With a couple of exceptions they're all dreadful. An artist can
only learn by going out and playing live, which keeps him or her
learning the craft, building an audience and a fan base. Videos are
an incredible waste of money, and young talent today is all about
how many records and videos they've sold. It's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When we finished talking, he changed into his long Versace
sparkled coat and pants and went to the opening, where he seemed
genuinely proud. Unlike Eisner, who was seated in front of him,
scribbling busily, John took no notes.
</P>
<P>
   En route to the party, he stopped backstage to see the cast.
``Look who's here!'' enthused Falls. ``How much do we love Elton?''
The group applauded dutifully as the composer made the rounds,
hugging the two female leads, then . Pascal.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner pulled John aside, praising the show, as a photographer
snapped their picture. ``We have a little ways to go, I think,''
John said, beaming. ``That's why we're here,'' Eisner beamed back.
</P>
<P>
   The following morning, Richard Christiansen gave ``Aida'' a
mixed review in The Chicago Tribune, calling it a combination of
``the good, the bad and the what were they thinking?''
</P>
<P>
   Work began again. John and Rice wrote a new song for Pascal;
Falls and Hwang rewrote much of the book; Cilento trimmed the
dances. By the time previews began in New York on Feb. 25, the
company was optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   At the Sunday matinee on Feb. 27, the house was packed and John
sat with Schumacher to watch the changes. It had been a week in
which John was much in the news; after receiving a lifetime
achievement award on the Grammy broadcast, he was reportedly rude
backstage, alienating Grammy officials and even Billy Joel, who had
flown out to Los Angeles especially to present the award. That
Sunday, though, he seemed to be in good spirits, making jokes at
which Schumacher laughed too loudly, causing everyone around them
to turn and stare.
</P>
<P>
   But about 15 minutes into the first act, John got up and left in
a diva-sized huff. He did not like some incidental music that had
been written by the dance arrangers _ a practice common in
musicals. Instead of staying to give notes, he got on a plane and
flew back to Atlanta, leaving the rest of the company dispirited,
to put it mildly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were shocked, surprised and embarrassed by his behavior,''
Falls said a few days later. ``It was plain and simply rude. He
called the next day and apologized, actually. He said he couldn't
help himself, that he's a perfectionist.'' Falls sighed. ``The sad
thing about Elton self-destructing the way he did is that he really
cares about the show and has a genuine desire to push himself into
new areas. In the year and a half I've worked with him he has been
a gentleman, down to earth, unpretentious, trusting and open to
collaboration, something not every top superstar is.''
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't help but remember the party in Chicago, where one of
the people inside the holding pen was Bob Halley, John's personal
assistant of 25 years. Didn't he find it odd that his boss was at
the party, but not at the party? He looked over at John, who was
listening, rapt, to Billie Jean King beside him on the couch, while
the line for the bar snaked past them, people pointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' he said cheerfully. ``It's show biz.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
