<HEADLINE>
ORACLE REPORTS 80 PERCENT INCREASE IN THIRD-QUARTER EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (hm) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Buoyed by strong sales of Internet software,
Oracle Corp. reported on Tuesday an 80 percent gain in
third-quarter earnings, exceeding analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle said progress on its stated goal of cutting expenses by
$1 billion had increased its profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bulk of its revenue still came from its core
database business, Oracle has moved aggressively in the past year
to position itself as the software engine of the Internet.
Companies embracing electronic commerce and moving other business
practices to the World Wide Web increasingly use Oracle's database
and application software. Oracle has also used the Internet
internally to cut costs, centralizing tasks like human resources
that used to spread across many continents.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle shares closed at $77, down $1.75, amid the broad decline
of the Nasdaq on Tuesday. In after-hours trading, Oracle shares
traded as high as $81.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they had expected a strong quarter, but had
received no guidance from Oracle suggesting that their estimates
would be too low. They noted that while software sales were up,
particularly compared to a somewhat weak quarter a year ago,
overall revenue growth was held back by a decline in consulting
business.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, which ended Feb. 29, Oracle reported earnings
of $763 million, or 25 cents a diluted share. That compared with
$293 million, or 10 cents a share, in the comparable period a year
earlier. Sales rose 14 percent to $2.4 billion from $2.1 billion in
the third quarter of fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Third-quarter 2000 earnings include $432 million of pretax
investment gains from the sale of 11 percent of Oracle's holdings
in Liberate Technologies, a spinoff originally known as Network
Computer Inc. Without those gains, Oracle earnings increased 80
percent to $498 million, or 17 cents per diluted share, which was
better than the 13 cents expected by analysts surveyed by First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any software company is in a position to lead us into the
new economy, it is Oracle,'' said Bob Austrian, an analyst with
Banc of America Securities. ``One of the interesting takeaways here
is that Oracle's own financial benefit from using its technology is
an example for other companies. The real goal of this technology is
to wring the costs out of whole sectors of the economy, and Oracle
is using it to enhance revenues and dramatically increase profit
margins,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become the software standard for the Internet,''
Lawrence J. Ellison, Oracle's chairman, said in a telephone
conference call with securities analysts. ``This is much more
important than mainframe computing or PC computing. This is a whole
new way of doing business. We're in this extraordinary position
where we're the only company that can offer a complete suite of
software to get major organizations and smaller organizations on
the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Database software sales increased 32 percent, to $778 million.
Total applications software sales increased 35 percent, to $199
million. Within that total, sales of customer-relationship
management applications grew 179 percent, to $49 million, and
Internet purchasing software grew 231 percent, to $26 million.
Consulting, education and support revenues grew 10 percent, to $1.4
billion. Of that total, consulting was down 10 percent, education
up 10 percent and support up 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   During the quarter, Oracle announced a series of so-called
Exchanges, Internet-based purchasing systems for major industries
including automobiles, with Ford, DaimlerChrysler and General
Motors, and retail, with Sears and Carrefour of France. Last week,
the company announced a program for government purchasing, and
announced Monday the creation of a new exchange for the lumber and
paper industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
