<SLUG> BC-PACIFIC-PACIFIC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Pacific Exchange Maps All-Electronic Future  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Ending an era in West Coast finance, the Pacific Exchange yesterday
unveiled an alliance to create an all-electronic exchange and
shutter its stock trading floors in San Francisco and Los Angeles.
<P>
   The San Francisco bourse said it plans to join forces with
Archipelago, one of a new breed of computerized stock trading
networks, to set up the new electronic exchange. The alliance is
the first between a traditional exchange and an electronic network.
</P>
<P>
   Details remain to be worked out and financial terms were not
disclosed. But if Pacific and Archipelago nail down a formal
agreement and the Securities and Exchange Commission gives its
blessing, the exchange would phase in its stock trading activity to
the new venture, beginning as soon as this year.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific's Los Angeles stock operation would probably close its
doors this year, while trading in its massive granite building on
Pine Street in San Francisco's Financial District would halt next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific's options trading floor in the Mills Building wouldn't
be affected by the move, though many observers expect that
operation eventually will be replaced by an electronic system too &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Pacific has previously said it intended to close its stock
trading floors. But the Archipelago alliance marks the first time
the exchange has put in place a specific program and timetable for
doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Securities industry experts said closing stock trading floors,
where frantic brokers buy and sell stocks in a central location, is
inevitable given the relentless march of computerization in the
securities business. Even the redoubtable New York Stock Exchange
is reportedly exploring options for switching to electronic
trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Floor trading is the equivalent of the slide rule or the buggy
whip,'' said Junius Peake, a finance professor at the University of
Northern Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Pacific Exchange is bound by tradition, and some see
sadness in the demise of its old floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cold, it's damp, but if you look up on the wall you see
photos of traders taken in 1935,'' said Mark Laurent, who has &LR;  been
 &LR; a floor trader in the Pine Street building for four years. ``A lot
of things have gone down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific and Archipelago said their venture will create the first
all-electronic national stock exchange able  &LR; to trade shares from
the three major U.S. markets: the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq
and the American Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Investors could get access to a large pool of potential buyers
and sellers, which could make it easier to execute orders at the
prices they want. ``It could potentially give more eyeballs that
will see your order,'' said Chase H&AMP;Q analyst Greg Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific officials said an alliance with an electronic player
represents their best hope for reviving a money-hemorrhaging stock
market operation that has been losing business for years to
stronger rivals such as New York's Big Board. The exchange recently
changed its stock market operation from a membership association to
a for-profit corporation to make it more nimble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need enhanced technology and a lower cost of doing
business'' to be competitive, said Philip DeFeo, Pacific's chairman
and CEO.chief executive. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Archipelago is one of several so-called electronic
communications networks, or ECNs, that have emerged in the last few
years and now handle more than one of every three trades on the
Nasdaq stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ECNs take orders from retail brokerages and match them directly
with orders from other customers. That eliminates the middleman
firms, called market makers or specialists, through which
traditional stock exchange trades are routed.
</P>
<P>
   Archipelago, the fifth-largest ECN, gets its orders from online
broker E-Trade, among other sources. Linking with the ECN gives
Pacific access to a large group of new customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, I thought regional exchanges such as the Pacific
were dead,'' said Credit Suisse First Boston analyst James Marks.
``But these changes in trading are giving them new life.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange rules put strict limits on the ability
of ECNs to trade its stocks. Allying with Pacific, which is free to
trade New York stocks, provides Archipelago a way around those
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predict more alliances between traditional exchanges
and ECNs that could dwarf the Pacific Archipelago venture. All the
same, said DeFeo, ``We are acting while they are talking.''
</P>
<P>
   The new arrangement will take business away from Pacific's
specialist firms, which who  &LR; employ fewer than 100 traders. The
firms are middlemen who promise to buy or sell shares, profiting
from small price differences. Still, the specialists will be needed
to handle orders when no matches are available and they could
benefit if the new exchange's business grows.
</P>
<P>
   ``ECNs have changed the dynamics,'' said Jonathan Werts,
president of the San Francisco Specialists Association. ``Traders
hate change, but we're also realists.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Sam Zuckerman at szuckerman &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
