<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Big 3Q Gain in Income for Oracle 
 &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Software titan Oracle further distanced itself from a difficult
first quarter yesterday, posting an 80 percent jump in income for
the third quarter on strong demand for its database licenses.
<P>
   Redwood Shores' Oracle, which makes software programs for
high-powered corporate networks, said income from operations for
the three months ended February 29 totaled $498 million (17 cents a
share), compared with $277 million (9 cents) for the third quarter
of last year.
</P>
<P>
   That handily beat the 13-cent average estimate of analysts
polled by First Call Corp. and matched so-called ``whisper''
estimates of 17 cents published in investment Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Net income rose by a whopping 160 percent to $763 million (25
cents a share), from $293 million (10 cents) a year ago. That
figure includes a $432 million investment gain from the sale of an
11 percent of its  &LR; stake in Liberate Technologies Inc., a San
Carlos firm that makes software for ``smart phones'' and other
Internet-cruising devices.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the three months ended February 29 grew to $2.4
billion, up from $2.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrific performance,'' said William Epifanio, an
analyst at J.P. Morgan Securities in New York, who rates the stock
a ``buy.'' ``It's great to see their fundamentals are catching up
with their stock price.''
</P>
<P>
   Oracle's stock price fell $1.75 to $77 in regular trading. After
its earnings were announced following the market close, shares were
trading above the $83 mark on electronic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle's stock price slumped last fall when the company missed
sales forecasts for the first quarter. But since the beginning of
the second quarter, when it surpassed analysts' expectations,
Oracle shares have roughly doubled. Many investors have been
encouraged by the company's push into the online exchange arena and
strong post-Y2K sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out of Y2K, the lockdowns are coming off and companies
are picking up their buying,'' said Gary Abbott, an analyst at
Punk, Ziegel &AMP; Co. who also maintains a ``buy'' rating on Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   However, most agree that the key factor behind the quarter was
Oracle's efforts to make good on Chief Executive Larry Ellison's
pledge last year to reduce of reducing  &LR; operating costs by $1
billion by June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management has taken its goal of improved margins very
seriously and they're delivering on that promise,'' Epifanio said.
</P>
<P>
   Also boosting its bottom line was surging demand for software
that caters to the e-commerce boom. Oracle said customer
relationship management applications, which automate responses to
customer queries and help companies target potential customers by
gathering data on buying histories and preferences, rose 179
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The only dim spot on the company's earnings statement was its
consulting services revenue, which increased by a meager 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really been de-emphasizing consulting,'' Oracle Chief
Financial Officer Jeff Henley told Bloomberg News. ``But we think
that may be hitting the bottom, and I think it may turn around and
grow this calendar year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
