 _ SF CHRON  
 
 Stanford Endowment Gets New CEO 
 &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Robertson Stephens Chairman Mike McCaffery is leaving investment
banking after 22 years to return to Stanford, not as a student but
as president and CEO of the Stanford Management Co.
<P>
   He will be in charge of the university's $7.9 billion endowment
fund, which includes stocks, bonds, venture capital investments and
hundreds of acres of prime real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity to do something different,'' said
McCaffery, who stepped down as CEO of Robertson Stephens two months
ago. ``This will permit me to use my experience and network and
move into the investment side from investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffery will assume his new post in September, replacing
Laurie Hoagland, who has held the job since 1991 and announced last
October that he will leave to oversee investments of the Hewlett
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The value of Stanford's stock, bond and venture capital
investments was reported to be $6.2 billion last August 31. But
sources close to Stanford say that excludes many unrealized gains
and about $1.7 billion in real estate holdings.
</P>
<P>
   As large as it is, Stanford's endowment trails those of Harvard,
Princeton, Yale and the University of Texas, a public university
whose wealth has been bolstered by land grants and oil.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's targeted, long-term ``real rate of return,'' adjusted
for inflation, is 6.25 percent. Over the past decade it has
surpassed that goal in all but one year (1998), and last year its
endowment grew by 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Each year the endowment fund pays out about 5 percent of its
endowment, enough to cover about 12 percent of the university's
operating budget. That compares to about 30 percent coverage of the
operating expenses at Princeton and 23 percent at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most top executives who jump to a new job, McCaffery will
not be making more money. Sources close to the university say his
salary will be close to $500,000 plus incentives. That's just a
small fraction of his total compensation at San Francisco's
Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not approach this job thinking about compensation at
all,'' said McCaffery. ``It's a great opportunity to become a
member of the Stanford community where I earned my MBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Life at Stanford should be more peaceful than at Robertson
Stephens, which has endured three ownership changes in the past
three years. It was bought by Bank of America in 1997, sold to
BankBoston in 1998 and sold again to Fleet Financial Group last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the investment bank is thriving. New CEO Bob Emery
said revenues &LR;  rose from $360 million in 1998 to $1 billion last
year and will exceed $650 million in the first quarter of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Peter Sinton at psinton &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
