<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush, Gore clench party nominations in Southern primaries
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The math now matches what the nation has known
since last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With solid support in his home state, and a big boost from his
brother's, Texas Gov. George W. Bush on Tuesday clinched the
Republican nomination for president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's six southern primaries also gave Vice President Al
Gore more than enough delegates to win the Democratic nomination to
face Bush in November.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who celebrated with supporters at the Dell Jewish
Community Campus in Austin, said he is ready for the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I filed for president, I pledged I'd come home to Texas
with the nomination of my party,'' Bush told cheering supporters.
``Tonight we can say: Mission accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee, where he voted for himself, Gore said Tuesday the
fall race will offer ``a real choice'' on how to approach the
nation's problems. After the polls closed, Gore said the November
race offers ``a choice between keeping prosperity going or going
back to the Bush-Quayle days of gigantic budget deficits and
paralyzed democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential battles ended last week when Gore and Bush took
Super Tuesday wins that knocked Democrat Bill Bradley and
Republican John McCain from the race. Former Ambassador Alan Keyes,
who has earned only a handful of delegates, remains in the GOP
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore won Tuesday contests in Texas, Louisiana,
Tennessee, Mississippi, Oklahoma and Florida, where Bush's younger
brother Jeb is governor and is being counted on to help deliver the
state for the GOP in November.
</P>
<P>
   An Associated Press analysis showed that Bush's delegate count
would reach 1,090 and Gore's would reach at least 2,540 by the end
of the night _ far more than either man needed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush family political machine also produced two votes for
the Texas governor Tuesday. Former President George Bush and his
wife, Barbara, voted for their son in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets down to family and how lucky we are,'' the former
president said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tuesday sweep gave Bush more than the 1,034 delegates needed
to clinch the nomination that will formally be given to him at the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia in August.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also has topped the 2,170 delegates needed for the
nomination to be awarded at the Democratic National Convention in
Los Angeles, also in August.
</P>
<P>
   In a Tuesday night e-mail, Gore congratulated Bush and invited
him to debate within two weeks. Gore also wants both candidates to
do without TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's agree to forgo all campaign advertising and instead
agree to a regular series of debates on the major issues facing the
country,'' Gore told Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he is not interested in forgoing television ads.
</P>
<P>
   Bush voted for himself last Wednesday in Austin, the morning
after he effectively won the nomination. Gore voted for himself
Tuesday in Tennessee. He told reporters he plans to make full
employment and universal health insurance key issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is a real choice between two different ways of
approaching those problems and I want to be president to make sure
we solve these problems the right way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Bush drew loud response from supporters when he
turned his attention to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are halfway _ but only halfway _ to ending the Clinton-Gore
era in Washington, D.C. To get there, we must face one more
Clinton-Gore campaign. The last week has been a preview. The Gore
campaign will say anything and try to win at any cost,'' said Bush,
reprising what has become an everyday jab.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will confront their tactics one more time, and this time we
will prevail and they will fail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said Gore cannot distance himself from President Bill
Clinton because the vice president has served as
``cheerleader-in-chief.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore can't solve campaign finance problems when he
symbolizes them,'' said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Tuesday he will go to work on earning support from
moderate Republicans and independents that Bush needed to win in
November. A CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll released Tuesday showed that
Bush, so far, is doing a better job of attracting McCain voters
looking for a new candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Bush held a 49 percent to 43 percent edge among the
likely voters surveyed. Eighty percent of the respondents who
identified themselves as McCain Republicans said they are now Bush
backers. Only 14 percent are siding with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Among ``McCain independents,'' Bush got 46 percent and Gore took
37 percent. ``McCain Democrats'' backed Gore by a 76 percent to 13
percent margin.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls conducted Tuesday by Voter News Service showed
McCain, though out of the race, picking up support from more than
20 percent of independents and Democrats who voted in GOP
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Today in Chicago, Bush will be endorsed by Illinois state Rep.
Jim Durkin, former chair of the McCain campaign in that state.
</P>
<P>
   In numbers that look good for Bush, the exit polls indicated
that Bush ran stronger among Democratic voters than Gore did among
GOP voters. Just 6 percent of voters in Republican primaries said
they would vote for Gore in November; twice as many Democrats said
they would defect to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Though Tuesday's outcomes were no surprise, Bush didn't miss a
chance to work on the image he wants to craft for November: Mr.
Inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Because all major hotel ballrooms in Austin were booked by South
by Southwest events, the Bush party wound up at the new Jewish
center.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 letter to the Anti-Defamation League, Bush expressed
regrets for his 1993 statement that his Christian faith tells him
that heaven is open only to people who accept Jesus Christ as
personal savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``In discussing my own personal faith as a Christian, I in no
way meant to imply any disrespect or to denigrate any other
religion,'' Bush said in his letter to the ADL.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign booked the gymnasium at the Jewish center,
which opened in January, for $8,000. The campaign also had to make
some last-minute menu changes. Pork barbecue ordered before the
site was selected was deleted from the dinner provided to the
traveling press corps.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also used the event, with national television cameras on
hand, to highlight his support among minority officials. At last
Tuesday's victory party, Bush was introduced by Houston educator
Phyllis Hunter, an African-American, and U.S. Rep. Henry Bonilla of
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, El Paso Mayor Carlos Ramirez, a Democrat and
longtime backer of Bush, did the honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president, this is a man who won't just do things right,
he'll do the right thing,'' said Ramirez. ``And for Democrats,
Republicans and independents, this is the candidate who offers the
most hope on the most important issue _ the education of our
children.''
</P>
<P>
   The emcee for the event was Texas Railroad Commissioner Tony
Garza, a Hispanic who many Republicans would like to see move on to
higher office.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is eager to be seen as a new breed of Republican, more
inclusive and always eager to bring minorities into the fold. He
appeared on television ads for Railroad Commissioner Michael
Williams, an African-American, and Texas Supreme Court Justice Al
Gonzales. Both were appointed by Bush and faced opponents in
Tuesday's GOP primaries. Both were opposed in the primary and were
enjoying early leads in their respective races.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's November effort depends heavily on carrying California, a
state where Hispanics have increasing ballot-box clout and have
clung to Democratic candidates in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's primaries ended a process that began a year ago with
fund-raising, continued through the Iowa GOP straw poll last August
and began in earnest with Bush's win in the Iowa caucuses on Jan.
24.
</P>
<P>
   After crushing losses in New Hampshire and Michigan, Bush
finally knocked McCain from the race by winning most of the Super
Tuesday contests, including New York, California and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's Super Tuesday sweep knocked Bradley from the contest.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
