<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 A BUSINESS _ SF CHRON   10 Steps to Prevent Internet Sabotage 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
What should a small business do to protect itself against Internet
sabotage and possible hacker attacks on its computers?
<P>
   &LR;   &QL; 
 &LR; A: The California Society of Certified Public Accountants suggests
several ways to protect against e-terrorism, random hackers and
computer viruses. California CPAs who are systems and business
consultants came up with these 10 steps:
</P>
<P>
   1. Do not put sensitive information on a PC running Windows that
is always directly connected to the Internet through a fiber-optic
cable or DSL line.
</P>
<P>
   2. Put a properly configured firewall between your office
machines and the Internet. A firewall will keep outsiders from
seeing or poking into your office machines, especially when you're
not around.
</P>
<P>
   3. Keep your own Web site completely separate from your
sensitive business information. Have an Internet service provider
maintain your Web server and assume that this machine will be
hacked into sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
   4. Never download and run a program from the Web or received as
an e-mail attachment unless it comes from a reputable source and
you have good reason to run it.
</P>
<P>
   A. Assume that every floppy or program you get from the
``outside'' is ridden with viruses unless you have reason to be
certain otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   B. Separate business from pleasure. If you want to run screen
savers, games or other downloaded software, do it on your ``fun''
machine (perhaps at home). Make sure your staff does the same.
</P>
<P>
   5. Don't use Internet file transfer protocols ``telnet'' or
``ftp''(``anonymous ftp'' is OK). These Internet procedures send
passwords used to log onto remote servers in clear text over the
Internet. If you have to log onto other computers on the Net, use
encryption products such as SSH Secure Shell, which can be easily
downloaded from the Web.
</P>
<P>
   6. Regularly use available virus scanners such as Norton
Antivirus to catch bugs that make it into your system.
</P>
<P>
   7. Configure your PC not to boot from a floppy disk or CD, which
all too often harbor viruses. Always start up directly from the
hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   8. Get a systems pro to verify your setup is secure.
</P>
<P>
   9. If suppliers are attacked and cut off, be sure you have
fall-back arrangements with other suppliers to ensure your business
isn't interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   10. Review your business interruption insurance policy and be
sure it doesn't explicitly exclude cyber- or e-terrorism as causes
of loss.
</P>
<P>
   Redondo Beach CPA Kenneth Hamaguchi notes there are
industry-specific hosting sites that take care of much, if not all,
of the security issues _ for a price. For example, the nursery
industry has a new hosting site called Growzone (www.growzone.com)
where members can have their Web page created and maintained for
about $2,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea is to set up a standalone system with all the
software you need. Take a CD recorder and copy the entire disk to a
CD. If someone hacks into your system, you should reformat the hard
disk and download the CD. Since it's a stand-alone, your main
accounting system can't be hit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another Web site has lined up experts to selectively answer
small-business questions such as ``How do I bring my business
online?,'' ``Where do I begin to find investors?'' and ``What will
my staffing needs be?''
</P>
<P>
   Inc.com (www.inc.com), announced yesterday that it is
establishing a mentor program featuring more than 20 experts in a
variety of fields from marketing and finance to law and taxation.
Local contributors include Garage.com founder Guy Kawasaki and
``Guerrilla Marketing'' author Jay Levinson. (Inc.com will answer a
question a day and build up a library of queries and responses.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hamilton of Daly City e-mailed to say I seemed to
sympathize with brick-and-mortar merchants in my discussion of
Internet taxation two weeks ago. Instead of taxing Internet
merchants to create a level playing (or paying) field, he suggests
removing the sales tax burden on all businesses. He also recommends
looking at Web sites of the Internet Tax Fairness Coalition
(www.nettaxfairness.org) and Americans for Tax Reform
(www.atr.org).
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Andy Ross, president of Cody's Books in
Berkeley, e-mailed to say pressure is building to force the state
Board of Equalization to force out-of-state companies with a
presence in California and e-commerce subsidiaries, like some of
the giant book retailers, pay their fair share of sales taxes.
Assemblywoman Carol Migden co-authored a bill to ``clarify''
existing law and get businesses such as BarnesandNoble.com and
Borders.com to pay sales taxes. The text of the bill, AB 2412, can
be found at www.leginfo.ca.gov/bilinfo.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
