<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6900 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HEADHUNT-HEADHUNT_SFC     03-14 1786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADHUNT-HEADHUNT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Baiting the Hook for Tech Execs  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
One commodity that is scarcer and going up in price even faster
than Bay Area homes and gasoline is high-tech management talent.
<P>
   And no one knows this better than Bay Area executive recruiters
who are paid big bucks themselves to locate and lure savvy CEOs and
other top executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is so starved for top-rated talent that there's
been a significant escalation in what people are willing to pay to
get it in the past six months,'' said Mel Connet, who runs a CEO
recruiting firm of the same name in Atherton and conducts a dozen
or more searches a year.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this recent offer to a 38-year-old fast-tracker to move
to San Francisco from a top 500 U.S. company. According to Connet,
the offer included a $600,000-a-year base salary, $500,000 annual
bonus, $250,000 sign-on bonus, options on 7 percent of the
company's stock, reimbursement for up to $625,000 in lost stock
option gains at his current employer, $1 million home loan and
flights home every other weekend until he relocates his family.
</P>
<P>
   He turned down the job.
</P>
<P>
   John Holman, a San Francisco headhunter who has recruited about
150 CEOs during the past 22 years, said two or three years ago it
was common to hire a CEO for a 2 to 3 percent ownership stake after
initial public offering. Now the figure is often double that.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have salaries gone up but so have most other benefits.
``The bottom line is it's a wonderful time to be a candidate for a
senior executive position at a first class high-tech company,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Executive recruiter Valerie Fredrickson in Menlo Park said some
hot prospects might get 50 or more calls a week from headhunters.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Hewitt, CEO of Versata Inc. in Oakland, knows both the joys
of joining an Internet startup and the agony of attracting and
signing top talent.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Versata held its initial public offering and saw
its shares shoot up to $92.75 from $24 before settling back to
$64.75. Hewitt, who joined the company five years ago as chief
financial officer and beat out external candidates to become CEO in
1997, holds 1.5 million shares and a paper profit approaching $100
million. His salary of $180,000 and bonus of $110,000 a year is
almost incidental.
</P>
<P>
   Attracting top executives these days ``is harder than nails,''
said Hewitt, 56, a veteran executive and former undersecretary of
the U.S. Department of Energy. ``You can find a lot of `B' players,
but `A' players are really tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Versata, which makes software that automates
business-to-business e-commerce applications, recently had to hire
three top managers. It took five months to find a new CFO. ``I must
have interviewed 30 to 40 candidates and only ended up with two
real candidates,'' Hewitt recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Last November 30, the company landed Kevin Ferrell, former
investment banker and CFO of EQE International and McKesson Corp.
The cash portion of Ferrell's compensation was ``pretty small,''
but he negotiated options on 450,000 shares of Versata's stock and
the right to buy an additional 100,000 shares at $5.56 each. Those
options are worth more than $30 million based upon Versata's
current price.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley executive recruiter David Powell figures that
recruiters currently are searching for about 200 CEOs for local
companies and thousands of other candidates for such key positions
as CFO, vice president of sales and VP business development.
</P>
<P>
   Landing the right team of executives quickly is especially
important for dot-com companies if they are going to get to market
ahead of the competition. ``If Silicon Valley has an Achilles'
heel, it's management talent.'' Powell said. ``This is the most
critical issue today.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand for executive talent has exploded over the past three
years as venture capital firms have funneled billions of dollars
into startups. As these companies hit the jackpot by going public
or getting acquired, the investors have ever more cash to reinvest
with hot entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent survey by Korn/Ferry International, global
demand for executives jumped 16 percent last year, with tech talent
topping the list for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter of last year, hiring by dot-com,
telecommunications and other information technology companies
accounted for 27 percent of the total, according to Korn/Ferry, the
largest executive recruiting firm. That compared with to  &LR; 13
percent for financial services and 12 percent for health care and
pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for CEOs increased from 13 percent of the total in 1998
to 16 percent in the fourth quarter of last year, the survey noted.
</P>
<P>
   One executive who took the bait and jumped to an Internet
startup is Alan Naumann, 40, chief executive of Calico Commerce in
San Jose. After 15 years in various management positions at Cadence
Design Systems and Hewlett-Packard, Naumann decided to bail out in
1997 even though his salary and bonus of $212,148 at Calico
Commerce is about half what he was getting at Cadence.
</P>
<P>
   But the stock-option package more than made up the difference.
Naumann received a $240,000 loan from Calico to buy 1.2 million of
its shares for 20 cents each. Today, he holds about 1.5 million
shares in the company, which went public last September, and his
4.5 percent stake is worth about $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, a huge compensation package is not necessarily the main
motivator. Naumann said he had been previously approached by
executive headhunters but only became interested in switching from
chip design to the Internet world three years ago. ``I wanted to be
in the middle of the tornado,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But not just any dot-com opportunity. Naumann was interested in
a company with an opportunity to become 10 times as large as
Cadence's $1 billion size, as measured by revenues. He wanted a
company with a unique product that is already accepted in the
market, not just a concept. (Calico, which provides e-commerce
application software to help companies sell over the Web, had
already received a ``supplier of the year'' award from one of its
key customers, Cisco Systems.).
</P>
<P>
   Naumann also wanted to join a ``quality'' company with
first-class investors and a supportive board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final factor was, was it the right place for me?, &LR; '' said
Naumann. ``Would I be allowed to set strategy? Would I have
significant stock ownership to reward me for taking risks?''
</P>
<P>
   At Calico, close to 35 percent of the stock was reserved for
employees. Naumann said this has been essential to hiring key
executives. For example, last year the company recruited Tayloecq &LR; 
Stansbury as vice president of its major sales unit from Xerox and
Art Knapp from BMC Software as chief financial officer by offering
each executive about 400,000 shares of Calico stock.
</P>
<P>
   More than 160,000 high-tech recruits in the United States
reportedly became millionaires last year by cashing in their
options. But not all startups have a happy IPO ending.
</P>
<P>
   Mohr, Davidow Ventures general partner George Zachary estimates
that only about 2 percent of companies nurtured by angel and
venture capital investors make it to the IPO launchpad.
</P>
<P>
   Of the remainder, he figures close to 40 percent of the startups
go nowhere, forcing the executives and employees to start all over
again. And the majority, close to 60 percent, get acquired, but in
many cases for just the value of their assets.
</P>
<P>
   But even as many companies fizzle, Silicon Valley is like an
industry on fertility drugs; it keeps spawning more and more
startups .
</P>
<P>
   Finding managers to head all these companies would be hard
enough. But executive recruiter Connet observes that ``experienced
startup CEOS are often less inclined to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories of serial entrepreneurs abound, but many top executives
who have already made a mint, would rather serve on boards and
become angel investors where they can nurture other entrepreneurs
without sacrificing every waking hour.
</P>
<P>
   Mohr, Davidow's Zachary concurs that some high-tech veterans
don't want to lead the charge again and give up any chance of
leading a balanced life. ``They want to be like Obi-Wan Kenobi and
offer advice and connections, not swing the light saber,'' he said.
His Menlo Park venture capital firm has an investment portfolio of
about 40 companies and has 10 recruiting firms searching for about
100 executives at any time.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of the times, Sequoia Capital in Menlo Park has hired
former Heidrick &AMP; Struggles headhunter April King as ``director of
people'' to provide hiring tips to the venture capital firm's
portfolio companies.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech giants like Hewlett-Packard, Lucent, Nortel and Oracle
continue to be training grounds for executive and technical talent,
but they are offering more incentives to their own workers to stay.
That means executive recruiters have to dig deeper. They are
drafting directors instead of vice presidents and managers who may
lack broad operating experience.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, executives from traditional industry have been
waking up to the allure of the new economy. Top managers of many
elite 500 U.S. companies have watched folks half their age become
multimillionaires and increasingly are following suit. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _Covad Communications of Santa Clara lured U.S. West
Communications Executive Vice President Bob Knowling to become CEO
in 1998 with $650,000 cash compensation, a $1.5 million signing
bonus and 1.4 million shares of stock priced at $1.50 each.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which went public January 22, has catapulted from
 &LR; to $97.12 from $18 per share, giving Knowling a paper profit
topping $140 million. As icing on the cake, Knowling received a
$500,000 loan to help purchase a house in the Bay Area, with 25
percent of the loan forgiven for each year he stays with the
company.
</P>
<P>
   _Webvan recruited Andersen Consulting CEO George Shaheen to lead
it last September just before the Foster City company went public.
Among the lures to join Webvan, which delivers groceries and other
products ordered online, Shaheen was offered 15 million shares of
stock, about 5 percent of the total, for $8 a share. (Webvan shares
peaked at $34 but have since tumbled to $10.25.)
</P>
<P>
   _EBay, the San Jose online auctioneer, recruited Margaret
``Meg'' Whitman from toymaker Hasbro in 1998, offering her a 6.4
percent stake in the company nine months before its stock offering.
Even after selling off some shares, her current 6.5-million-share
stake is worth about $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Peter Sinton at psinton &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
