<P>
   (NYT17) ROCKVILLE, Md. -- March 14, 2000 -- SCI-GENOME-ACCESS-2
-- Dr. William Haseltine in his lab at Human Genome Sciences, Inc.
Calling the effort to decode the human genome ``one of the most
significant scientific projects of all time, President Clinton and
Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain issued a joint statement
Tuesday saying the genome data ``should be made freely available to
scientists everywhere.'' Haseltine said he agreed with Tuesday's
statement because raw genomic data ``has no practical use,'' an
observation which he termed ``the biggest untold secret of the
human genome project.'' (Ann Grillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) ROCKVILLE, Md. -- March 14, 2000 -- SCI-GENOME-ACCESS --
J. Craig Venter, president of Celera Genomics, leans on a gene
sequencer being installed to be used in decoding the human genome.
Calling the effort to decode the human genome ``one of the most
significant scientific projects of all time,'' President Clinton
and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain issued a joint statement
Tuesday saying the genome data ``should be made freely available to
scientists everywhere.'' The statement is a bureaucratic outgrowth
of the longstanding rivalry between a public consortium of American
and British academic centers and the Celera Corporation of
Rockville, Md, to complete the sequence of the human genome. (Marty
Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LAWYERSVILLE, N.Y. -- March 14, 2000 -- ESKIMO-REMAINS-2
-- Minik Wallace circa 1900, from the book ``Give Me My Father's
