restaurants with more than 35 seats has been banned since the
Smoke-Free Air Act of 1995. But while fewer diners may be consuming
first or second-hand smoke, a newly hardened resistance is digging
in. Social and serial smokers are puffing away at an underground
network of restaurants that would rather risk an inspection than
alienate valued customers. (Normon Y. Lono/The New York Times)
