<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIESEL-POLLUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING HEALTH RISK, EPA CUTS SULFUR IN DIESEL FUEL
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Environmental Protection Agency has decided to
sharply reduce the level of sulfur allowed in diesel fuel, calling
diesel emissions an important health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a new rule, which will probably be announced in
a few months, has opened a vigorous debate between the oil industry
and state officials, not about whether to cut sulfur levels, but
how much.
</P>
<P>
   State air pollution officials plan to release a report on
Wednesday contending that soot from diesel engines increases the
cancer risk so that after a lifetime of exposure there would be
125,000 extra cases around the country. Sulfur in fuel clogs
emission controls on trucks and buses, so they are prodigious
producers of soot and of nitrogen oxides, which cause smog.
</P>
<P>
   The state officials want a 97 percent cut. S. William Becker,
executive director of the State and Territorial Air Pollution
Program Administrators, the group releasing the report, noted that
the EPA assessment of the cancer risk from diesel exhaust is
``between `likely' and `highly likely.' This stuff is bad for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are dozens of chemicals as part of diesel particulates
that are bad for you, that are causing cancer, aggravating asthma,
and other ailments,'' Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   But the refiners said Tuesday that the technology to produce
such clean fuel did not exist, and that even if it did, the cost
would drive some refineries out of business and that would create
shortages for all oil products. The industry acknowledges
``concern'' over the health effects of diesel emissions, said
Edward H. Murphy, a spokesman for the American Petroleum Institute,
the trade group, which has volunteered to reduce the sulfur limit
to 90 percent of the current peak. But that reduction will cost 5
or 6 cents a gallon, he said, and going down to 97 percent could
cost an additional 10 to 12 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The federal environmental agency plans to release a proposal in
the next few months ordering cuts in the amount of sulfur, capped
since 1993 at 500 parts per million. Murphy's group has volunteered
that in addition to an absolute limit of 50 parts per million, the
national average would be 30; Becker wants a cap of 15.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts that a cut is coming. ``Diesel sulfur levels need
to be significantly reduced,'' said Urvan R. Sternfels, president
of the National Petroleum Refiners Association, another industry
group.
</P>
<P>
   David Cohen, a spokesman for the EPA, said his agency had ``put
out no hard numbers'' about what it would propose, but he added,
``it has long been our position that particulate emissions,
including diesel, represent a major threat to public health and the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   But considerable doubt exists on just how big a threat the
exhaust is. The state air pollution officials developed their
estimate of cancer cases by drawing from a draft report prepared by
a California agency, the South Coast Air Quality Management
District, an influential agency that is often first to set
standards that spread nationwide. The California agency said that
90 percent of the cancer risk in the Los Angeles area came from
buses, trucks and cars, and that 70 percent of the risk was
attributable to diesel particulates.
</P>
<P>
   The extrapolation by the state group assumes that urban and
suburban areas around the United States have half as much soot as
Los Angeles, and that rural areas have one-tenth as much.
</P>
<P>
   But the California agency is one of the few to try to express a
numerical relationship between diesel soot in the air and cancer
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel S. Greenbaum, president of the Health Effects Institute,
an independent scientific organization in Cambridge, Mass.,
financed jointly by the EPA and various heavy industries, said that
most studies were more cautious. ``If you look across all the
public agencies that have reviewed the scientific data you see some
consistency in them saying the diesel is either a probable human
carcinogen or likely to be a human carcinogen,'' Greenbaum said,
``but that's one step below saying it's a known human carcinogen.''
</P>
<P>
   The EPA said in 1996 that diesel exhaust was ``highly likely''
to be carcinogenic when inhaled.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's rule making is running up against two other factors.
One is the recent spike in the price of diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
   But ``everything today is caught up in the rhetoric of gas
prices going up, and how we can't afford to do anything,'' Becker
said.
</P>
<P>
   The other is that the refineries already have a lot of other
government-mandated work to do. Sternfels, of the refiners'
association, pointed out that a separate EPA rule, announced in
December, cuts the allowable sulfur content of gasoline by 90
percent. Refiners cannot implement both rules at once, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6915 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TRIBUNE-WILLES-2TAKES     03-14 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBUNE-WILLES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL WHOSE TIME RAN OUT: TIMES MIRROR'S WILLES SOUGHT TO STRETCH
LIMITS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.; Texas; Colo.; Ga.)   (See also TRIBUNE-CHICAGO) 
(fb) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joshua, the Biblical general, is best remembered for commanding
the sun to stand still. Canute, who ruled England early in the 11th
century, is best remembered for commanding the tide to recede.
Years hence, when the purchase by the Tribune Co. of the Times
Mirror Co. is old news, Mark H. Willes, Times Mirror's last chief
executive, may best be remembered for declaring that his flagship
newspaper's circulation could increase by 500,000 _ a figure
greater than the total circulation of all but 10 American
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that Joshua got his way and Canute did not. Willes
had achieved one-tenth of his goal before Times Mirror's Chandler
family sold the business out from under him. Whatever the legends
eventually say, circulation figures for The Los Angeles Times' so
far indicate his command will prove as futile as Canute's.
</P>
<P>
   Such numbers, however, cannot measure the impact of Willes'
effort to stretch the limits of the possible.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, executives came and went through the
revolving doors of the imposing Times Mirror building with alarming
regularity. Strategies, too, came and went. Newspapers were closed,
businesses sold, hundreds of employees laid off and costs cut,
leaving a trail of bitter bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the detritus and the rampant skepticism about his goals and
tactics, Willes pushed a drifting institution _ and the hidebound
industry to which it belonged _ to question its basic assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Smith, president of the Atlanta-based Cox newspapers, said
on Tuesday that ``Mark suffered from not coming out of a newspaper
experience, in terms of finding the occasional wrong way to say
something, the wrong words to use. But if you listened carefully
and stripped that away,'' he said, Willes was raising the most
important issues facing the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tremendously impressed by the passion this man brought
to the business,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Willes, 58, first articulated his passion for reinventing the
newspaper business shortly after he was named chief executive at
Times Mirror in the spring of 1995. But it was articulated in
executive terms: He completed the previously planned closing of The
Baltimore Evening Sun; closed the 10-year-old New York Newsday and
sold or closed some cable and media operations.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,200 people lost their jobs so that, as Willes said
in October 1995, ``We were sinking like a rock in a number of
places in the company,'' explaining the sweeping overhauls he had
undertaken. In 1995, only the $1.6 billion gained in the sale of
its cable business kept the company in the black.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, however, gave his strategy high marks, as the price
of Times Mirror shares rose 80 percent by the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Cutbacks and the sale of businesses continued to be Willes'
leitmotif throughout his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   This trend, which began before Willes arrived _ Times Mirror had
already shed newspapers in Dallas and Denver and sold its cable
business _ has left the company with seven newspapers, an
navigational and aeronautical publisher, and a stable of magazines
including Golf Digest and Field and Stream.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate discipline was the passion Willes brought to Times
Mirror. The board rewarded the subsequent financial success with
repeated grants of stock and options, which according to the
company's March 1999 proxy, were worth at least $43 million, not
counting the value of options.
</P>
<P>
   But he developed a new passion after he named himself publisher
of The Los Angeles Times in October 1997. Within weeks, he declared
his new circulation goals in an interview with The Wall Street
Journal. In subsequent interviews with outside reporters, he would
throw out his idea of the moment for pumping up circulation _
attracting women by publishing articles that were ```more
emotional, more personal, less analytical,'' or starting a separate
section for Latino news.
</P>
<P>
   The ideas, many later abandoned, demonstrated Willes'
willingness to flout conventional wisdom. They also flouted
journalists' sensitivities.
</P>
<P>
   When he suggested tying editors' compensation to the number of
women and minorities quoted in the articles they handled, a St.
Petersburg Times editorial cautioned: ``Purposely manipulating news
sources in order to satisfy diversity goals is a good way to
undermine the credibility of a newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were four basic ideas that he never abandoned. One
was pairing editors with marketers and advertising sales
representatives in every department, to make The Times more
entrepreneurial and profitable. A second was planning some coverage
with direct goals in mind _ most notably in the ``Reading By Nine''
program to improve literacy among elementary schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Willes' desire to reach out to minority communities and
raise circulation in minority neighborhoods, led to the creation of
a special Latino desk, with 13 reporters, and to partnership
arrangements with four small newspapers _ Korea Times, the
Spanish-language newspaper La Opinion, the Chinese Daily News and
the Rafu Shimpo, a publication aimed at the Japanese community.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he redeployed the reporting and editing resources. He
added space and 11 new reporters to the business section, added a
foreign bureau in Vietnam. The newsroom work force remains about
1,000 _ with one major change. About 200 of the reporters work for
15 small regional papers, called Our Times, which offer local news
about schools and traffic in the disparate regions of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Over his 19 months as publisher, the newspaper's financial
performance faltered, and his idea of editorial-business
cooperation foundered. Executives left in droves. Profits dipped
below expectations. Members of the Times Mirror board openly
questioned the wisdom of Willes filling the roles of chief
executive and Times publisher. In June last year, he turned over
the publisher's reins to Kathryn M. Downing.
</P>
<P>
   The financial picture began to brighten.
</P>
<P>
   High-margin classified advertising, which had apparently been
leaching away to the Internet, returned. The performance of The
Times began to catch up to the company's East Coast newspapers.
Advertising volume at The Times grew 13.4 percent in 1999 over the
previous year, better than the 4.9 percent increase at the East
Coast newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Monday, Willes said: ``My heartache is that
all the things we've been doing on the East Coast have been paying
off for four years. Out here at The Times they are just now paying
off. It's frankly an enormous personal disappointment that I didn't
have a couple of more years to let everybody see how profound the
changes have been and how strong the base is on which we're
growing.''
</P>
<P>
   But while he was attending to corporate issues and focusing on
the company's Internet initiatives, Downing, an enthusiastic
disciple, made the deal to share revenue from one magazine issue
with a downtown arena, the Staples Center _ the subject of the
magazine's coverage.
</P>
<P>
   With the newspaper's credibility under siege and its journalists
in revolt, Willes' vision of revolutionizing the business seemed
irrevocably tarnished.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Richard A. Oppel, the editor of The Austin American-Statesman,
said Tuesday: ``The Willes leadership has had effects on the
culture of journalism. Some are good. The newspaper is more
innovative and entrepreneurial.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``A lot of us were heartened to hear a publisher say
we're going to increase circulation by 500,000. That spirit should
live and I'd like to see the underlying strategies that make it
work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The great challenge of the newspaper CEO,'' Oppel added, ``is
understanding that balance between innovation and preservation of
enduring values. The person who casts out the latter has no chance
of sustaining the credibility of a modernized, updated newspaper.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6918 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-GENOME-IMPACT-1STLD-W     03-14 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-IMPACT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-BLAIR STATEMENT ON GENOME CAUSES SELLOFF IN BIOTECH
STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert Haseltine's first name in 2nd graf of 2nd take.)  
(Eds: This story updates SCI-GENOME-ACCESS, which moved earlier in
`a' category. This is now an A1 story.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT16 and 17 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX BERENSON and NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton and Prime Minister Tony Blair of the United
Kingdom said Tuesday that the sequence of the human genome should
be made freely available to all researchers, leading to a sharp
selloff in the stocks of biotechnology companies that hope to
profit by creating drugs based on genetic data.
</P>
<P>
   The White House quickly said that it did not intend to hurt the
fledgling biotechnology industry, but investors who have made
biotechnology stocks the darlings of the market were unconvinced.
In frantic selling, they wiped away tens of billions of dollars in
market value from the industry. Genomics companies, which are
racing to produce a database of human DNA, were hit hardest, with
some off more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The drop was not confined to the biotechnology sector. After
briefly passing 5000 in morning trading, the Nasdaq composite
index, which is heavily weighted in technology stocks, fell
steadily. The index closed at 4706.63, down 200.61 points, its
second-largest point loss ever.
</P>
<P>
   For investors, the drop is noteworthy, because biotechnology and
Internet companies have led the stock market so far this year,
while most other stocks have languished. Despite falling almost 13
percent Tuesday, the Nasdaq biotech index remains up almost 30
percent this year, thanks to investors' belief that a new wave of
drug discovery and gene therapy is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the rapid runup, the stocks are pricey by all
traditional valuations. The joint statement from Clinton and Blair,
which said that the genome data ``should be made freely available
to scientists everywhere,'' served as a spark for excitable
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Whitfield, chief executive of Incyte Pharmaceuticals, which
shed 28 percent of its market value during the day, said that
investors failed to distinguish between genome sequences and gene
sequences. The genome, referring to the total human DNA, has no
commercial value in itself and cannot be patented. The genes, which
occupy only 3 percent of the genome, can be. Researchers can work
on the sequences of patented genes in academic work and have to pay
license fees only if they wish to sell some invention based on the
sequence.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders' statement, which was eight months in the
making, is a bureaucratic outgrowth of the longstanding rivalry
between a public consortium of American and British academic
centers and Celera Corp. of Rockville, Md., to complete the
sequence of the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium, largely funded by the federal National
Institutes of Health and the Wellcome Trust of London, is posting
its findings daily on a Web site open to all. Celera promises to
make its version of the human genome freely available when it is
finished, probably this summer. Celera plans to patent some genes,
but its principal business plan is to operate a database of the
human and other genomes, charging fees for use of the programs that
search and analyze the genetic data.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was intended simply to codify the government
position in the rivalry _ that the human genome sequence should be
made publicly available to all researchers _ but appears to have
been interpreted as a challenge both to Celera's intellectual
property rights and to those of other genome and biotech companies.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official said neither challenge was intended,
noting that the statement explicitly endorsed intellectual property
protection for patents based on genes.
</P>
<P>
   The statement cuts across a complicated two-way rivalry between
the public consortium and Celera, and between Celera and its two
chief rivals, Incyte Pharmaceuticals and Human Genomes Sciences.
Both the consortium and Celera aim to sequence the human genome,
which means determining the order of the 3 billion chemical units
in the DNA, the genetic information possessed by each human cell.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of Incyte and Human Genome Sciences is to focus on
the genes themselves, patenting as many as possible. The genes, the
programming instructions that operate the cell, are hidden in the
DNA, with no obvious signposts, and are hard to find even when the
genome sequence is known.
</P>
<P>
   The government statement adds to the tension between the public
consortium and Celera, which last week announced they had
effectively broken off merger negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Celera and its president, J. Craig Venter, have long been at
odds with the leading scientists of the public consortium, chiefly
Dr. John Sulston of the Sanger Center in Britain and Dr. Robert
Waterston of Washington University in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Before merger talks broke off, the public consortium proposed
that both sides abandon what it called ``the current antagonism and
excessive competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiative for the statement issued Tuesday is believed to
have come from the Wellcome Trust. Michael Dexter, Wellcome's
director, said the trust's concern was over the general ownership
of the genome, which in his view ``is mankind's and should not be
owned by any one company, individual or country.''
</P>
<P>
   Denying that the statement was aimed at any person or company,
he said the raw sequence _ the string of chemical units making up
the genome _ was not patentable and that the trust ``would fight
any patents based on sequence if they obstruct academic work and
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Venter, however, indicated that he thought Celera was a target
of the statement, but unfairly so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are puzzled by the statement and we think it represents the
lack of insight and the confusion that has been generated out
there. Our business is not in patenting the genome or tying it
up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Venter reiterated his previous position that Celera would make
available the sequence of the human genome when it was finished,
and said the onus was on rivals Incyte and Human Genome Sciences to
make their data public. ``I agree with the president and Tony Blair
that Incyte and HGS should publish their data,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Dexter and Rachel E. Levinson, a senior official at the
White House Office of Science and Technology Policy, said the joint
statement acknowledged intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
   Levinson said nothing in the statement changed existing patent
law. She said she was ``very concerned and upset'' about the
reactions on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neal Lane, the White House science adviser, said the
statement would not affect Celera because of Celera's known intent
to publish the human genome sequence, Levinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Haseltine, the chief executive of Human Genome
Sciences, said his company's data was being published through the
patent system. When a patent is issued, the underlying invention is
fully described.
</P>
<P>
   Haseltine said he agreed with Tuesday's statement because raw
genomic data ``has no practical use,'' an observation that he
termed ``the biggest untold secret of the human genome project.''
When researchers with the public consortium published the first DNA
sequence of a human chromosome in December last year, he said, ``No
new medical discoveries were made and no new genes were found.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason, he added, is that the computer programs for finding
genes are still far less efficient than the method pursued by his
company, one based on short DNA sequences called ``expressed
sequence tags,'' or ESTs.
</P>
<P>
   The EST approach exploits the fact that humans may not be able
to spot the genes in the genome but human cells surely can. They
regularly make transcripts of the genes whose information is needed
to synthesize the cell's various proteins. Researchers can capture
and analyze these transcripts, known as messenger RNAs, and from
just a small portion of their sequence can identify the
corresponding part of the gene from which they come. These little
snippets of genes, the ESTs, are the basis of gene-searching
approaches used by Human Genome Sciences and Incyte.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Patent and Trademark Office has issued some patents
based on ESTs alone, any such patents seem likely to be weaker than
patents based on the full-length genes.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures released by Human Genome Sciences, Incyte
leads in the human gene patent race with 353 U.S. patents issued,
followed by Human Genome Sciences (114 patents), SmithKline Beecham
(60), the US government (49), the University of California (46) and
Massachusetts General Hospital (45).
</P>
<P>
   There is still wide disagreement on the number of genes
contained in the human genome sequence. Both Dr. Randy Scott,
president of Incyte, and Haseltine estimate that there are 140,000
genes, double the number that Venter has favored.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the biotechnology companies have yet to prove their
ability to translate their research into revenues, much less
profits. Yet these stocks have helped drive the Nasdaq composite to
an 86 percent gain last year, the best performance by a major index
ever in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   By traditional valuation standards, the Nasdaq is
extraordinarily expensive, leaving some analysts worried that it is
overdue for a sharp drop. The average Nasdaq stock trades at well
over 100 times expected 2000 earnings, and some large Internet and
computer stocks trade at unheard-of price-earnings multiples of 500
or more.
</P>
<P>
   A drop in the biotech and computer high-fliers could shake the
broader stock market, which has already been rattled by the Federal
Reserve's recent increases in short-term interest rates, analysts
said. For the year, the Dow Jones industrial average is down more
than 14 percent, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index is off 7.5
percent, while the Nasdaq is up 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Cliggott, U.S. equities analyst at J.P. Morgan, called
the market ``very fragile'' because the stocks that are driving it
higher are already so expensive. ``We see the kinds of
price-earnings multiples that the Nasdaq's trading at as being
absolutely, positively unsustainable,'' said Cliggott, who turned
cautious in January.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, broader indexes followed the Nasdaq down. After
spending most of the day up, the S&AMP;P slipped 24.47 points to
1359.15, a 1.8 percent drop. The Dow industrials fell 135.89
points, or 1.4 percent, to 9811.24.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, analysts who have dared to be bearish have been
wrong for the last five years. Byron Wien, chief U.S. investment
strategist for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, noted that the Nasdaq is
very volatile and that investors might shrug off this decline as
simply a buying opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had bad days in the Nasdaq before, and they've snapped
right back,'' Wien said. ``What we have to see is whether the `buy
the dips' mentality is broken.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
