<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HILLARY'S IRISH STEW _ STEP-DANCING AS FAST AS SHE CAN
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I have never understood why gays fight so hard to
get into the St. Patrick's Day Parade on Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of wanting to go to an Irish parade, rather than having
to go, is mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   The mere tap-tap sound that signals the approach of
``Riverdance'' or a pack of wolfhounds in green doggy sweaters
fills me with dread.
</P>
<P>
   I am still haunted by the memory of waking up in St. Louis,
where the Ancient Order of Hibernians was holding a convention,
hearing the strains of ``When the Saints Go Marching In,'' and
running to the hotel window in time to watch, blushing in childish
embarrassment, as my parents led an Irish parade down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Now I find myself identifying with Christopher, the mafia
soldier in ``The Sopranos,'' who got shot and had a near-death
experience in which he learns that hell is an Irish bar called The
Emerald Piper where it's St. Patrick's Day every day.
</P>
<P>
   Coming cold into New York's trellis of unbelievably prickly
ethnics and minorities, Hillary Clinton stumbled into the dreary,
unending troubles over St. Patrick's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, she was asked if she would march in the Fifth
Avenue parade. Sure, she said gamely, apparently not realizing that
many Democrats boycott the parade because it excludes gay groups.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to mollify angry lesbian and gay groups, she then agreed
to march in an alternative parade in Queens County the Sunday
before last, in which participants could and did wear buttons that
said ``Kiss me, I'm queer'' and ``Fascist Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   I went to Queens to see how the candidate would fare. The parade
was a glum sight. Hillary marched down the street waving to a
sparse crowd, without the benefit of a band or even a boom box with
``McNamara's Band'' to liven things up. In front of her, a solemn
group representing Census 2000 trudged along.
</P>
<P>
   One guy on the sidelines was booing her, and another, an
Iranian, held up a sign with her picture that said: ``Not here. Not
now. Not ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Later she again defended her decision to march on Fifth Avenue,
after she got heckled speaking to the Gay and Lesbian Independent
Democrats in Greenwich Village. ``I have worked very hard over the
last six years or so in every way I could to further the peace
process in Northern Ireland,'' she said. Marching in the Hibernian
parade was ``one way of demonstrating that.''
</P>
<P>
   Her step-dancing among different groups is complicated by her
role as first lady. Just when we thought we were out, the Clintons
pull us back into their wacky marital deal.
</P>
<P>
   First it looked as if Bill was trying to help Hillary out on the
Puerto Rican terrorist clemency deal. Then Hillary tried to
capitalize on Bill's peace efforts in Northern Ireland, and
rationalize with them. Now Hillary has waded into yet another
ethnic kerfuffle with the Pakistanis, leaving the impression that
she might be influencing Bill's policy decisions for a pot of gold.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani-Americans and Indian-Americans were watching his
decision whether to stop in Pakistan on his upcoming visit to the
Indian subcontinent. The Pakistani community encouraged the stop;
Indians staunchly opposed it. According to The New York Times'
Raymond Bonner, a group of Pakistani-American donors moved up the
date of a fund-raiser for Hillary so they could press her to
support the stop in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   They were told she would not appear unless they raised at least
$50,000. They prepared spicy goat curry, but she did not stay long
enough to eat. She told the donors she hoped her husband would go
to Pakistan. Last week he announced he would.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed about the story on Tuesday, Clinton said, ``If anybody
thinks they can influence the president by making a contribution to
me, they are dead wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Come again? If big spenders did not think they could influence
the president by currying favor with the first lady, then why did
Johnny Chung spend hours in the East Wing, gazing at pictures of
Hillary and waiting for brief audiences with her?
</P>
<P>
   Chung, who gave Clinton's aide, Maggie Williams, a check for
$50,000, compared the White House to a subway: ``You have to put in
the coins to open the gates.'' No blarney there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
