<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6927 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MAJIDI-FILMS-2TAKES-$     03-14 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAJIDI-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING THE WORLD'S EYES TO THE STRUGGLES OF IRAN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Nancy Ramsey's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about the
Russian director Aleksei Guerman.  
 
 By NANCY RAMSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a sunny Friday afternoon last fall, the director
Majid Majidi, in town for the New York Film Festival from his
native Tehran, was in demand. Negotiations for the American
distribution of his latest film, ``The Color of Paradise,'' which
opens March 31, were under way.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week reporters had been talking with him about
Iranian films, about why they are so often about children (many of
the directors worked with the state-sponsored Institute for the
Intellectual Development of Children and Young Adults) and what it
is like making films under censorship (it has eased up in the last
two years).
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, Majidi was in Cliffside, N.J., at the home of a
friend, Jamsheed Akrami, a professor of film and television at
William Paterson University in Wayne, who was interviewing him for
a documentary. Looking out over a sparkling Hudson River at
Manhattan, Majidi fielded calls on a portable phone as Akrami
instructed a student to videotape him from first one angle, then
another.
</P>
<P>
   The festival circuit is nothing new to this soft-spoken,
sad-eyed 40-year-old director. His last film, ``Children of
Heaven,'' was the first Iranian film ever nominated for an Academy
Award. (``Life is Beautiful'' won.) But it is hard not to notice
the striking difference between the glossy festival world and the
worlds Majidi portrays in his films of rural and urban Iran, of
impoverished families, of parent-child struggles that erupt beneath
the surface of strict Islamic codes of behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children of Heaven'' had a simple narrative. A poor young boy
is sent to the market to retrieve his sister's pink shoes from a
cobbler. He sets the shoes down, and they are picked up by a blind
peddler. Returning home, the boy admonishes his sister not to tell
their father, and the two concoct a scheme for sharing the boy's
one pair of sneakers, each day racing through Tehran's alleys to
make the trade-off.When the pink shoes are found, they are on the
feet of the peddler's daughter, and the siblings understand that
that family is even worse off than their own.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Color of Paradise'' (it was called ``The Color of
Heaven'' at the New York festival), the main character, a young boy
named Mohammad (played by Mohsen Ramezani), is blind. To research
the film, Majidi visited schools for the blind and watched the
children interact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very little in the script was born of my imagination,'' he
said. To cast the film, Majidi took four blind boys on a trip to
rural northern Iran. Two had grown up in the desert (including
Ramezani) and had ``no concept of the sea, of birds, of the
jungle,'' said Majidi. ``Whenever we went to a new location, they'd
say, `We want to see it.' That meant touching, and they'd use the
word `beautiful' to describe what they had touched. At a riverbank,
the boy who plays Mohammad started reading the pebbles, making rock
formations in Braille.''
</P>
<P>
   The film opens in Tehran, where Mohammad attends a school for
the blind, and moves to the countryside, where he is to spend the
summer with his widowed father (Hossein Mahjub), his grandmother
(Salmeh Feizi) and his sisters. Wildflowers and lush green hills
and forests fill the screen; sounds of woodpeckers, insects and
rushing streams provide a backdrop to the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Nature often plays a major role in Iranian cinema. ``It's
cheaper to film in rural settings, requires fewer permissions and
there's less censorship,'' said Hamid Dabashi, a professor of
Iranian studies at Columbia University. ``But there's a deeper
reason,'' he added. ``In recent history Iran has lived through a
revolution and a war. There's a subconscious desire to reclaim the
land. Filmmakers are doing it visually. You take the camera and
go.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Paradise,'' the natural world that both gives life and
takes it away is reflected in the narrative. Over the grandmother's
objections, the father tries to pawn Mohammad off to a blind
carpenter. Their struggle takes on religious overtones, with the
blindness shifting metaphorically to the father, who cannot see the
beauty around him and for whose soul the grandmother fears. ``In
Iran, we refer to the blind as `light' or `bright-hearted,' meaning
that they have a wisdom in their hearts,'' said Akrami. ``There is
this idealized vision that somebody who's blind can see more than
other people do.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, life for the blind in Iran is difficult; they are
often marginalized by society, much like many of Majidi's other
characters. ``He cares deeply about social issues,'' Akrami said.
``The life in `Children of Heaven' could have been his own life as
a child.'' ``Paradise'' is Majidi's fourth feature, but only the
second released in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His first, ``Baduk'' (1992), is about fatherless children who
are sold into slavery. His second, ``The Father'' (1995), centers
on the struggle between an adolescent boy and his stepfather.
Although set in Iran, the film has a Hollywood style with chase
scenes, quick cuts and traditional plot.
</P>
<P>
   It is Majidi's two most recent films that have more of the
languorous qualities associated with Iranian cinema, a sign,
perhaps, of the director's maturing or of the success of Iranian
films on the festival circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood cinema was a big influence in Iran, even over the
past 20 years when it had to go underground,'' Akrami said. ``First
time around, you're dominated by those formulas.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the themes of his films, it's not surprising to learn that
Majidi was only 16 when his father died. Ramezani's father is also
dead; to elicit moving performances from him, Majidi would often
tap into his sense of loss.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the film's strongest scenes, Mohammad delivers a
heartbreaking monologue about having been born blind. It was based
on an afternoon in the production office when Ramezani's brother
was late picking him up. ``He said that people get tired of him
after a few days, that they're only with him out of pity,''
recalled Majidi. ```If I see God one day,' the boy said, `I'm going
to ask him, `Why did you create me in this form?' I asked him to
recreate that monologue for the camera and for two days before
shooting talked with him about his father.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking late last month from Tehran, where he was finishing
production on a film about a relationship between a young Iranian
Turk and an Afghani migrant worker, Majidi recounted how Ramezani
had been interviewed for magazines, radio and television.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more famous than I am,'' Majidi said, laughing. In a
perfect world, a bright future would await Ramezani. As Mohammad,
he was sensitive and charming; wearing sunglasses, he exuded the
charisma of a young rock star. But the director worries about his
life after the attention has subsided; acting roles for the blind,
of course, are few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   So, how did the star like the film?
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time he saw it was at Fajr, the Tehran film
festival,'' Majidi said. ``Before the movie screened, he went up to
the microphone and said, `You have no idea how happy I am to be
watching my movie today.' I was sitting next to him, and the people
around us were dividing their attention between him and the film.
During scenes with no dialogue, he'd ask me what we were watching.
And when there were scenes when he wasn't in them, I'd whisper to
him what was happening. In one, the father was having a fight with
the grandmother. He listened carefully, and at the end of the scene
turned to me and said, `You know, she really is a fine actress.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
