u i BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-1STLD-WRI     03-14 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACEKEEPERS ARE OVERWHELMED IN KOSOVO, PENTAGON ENVOY SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS to correct time element in 7th graf)  
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(fb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a sobering assessment of the deteriorating
situation in Kosovo, a senior Pentagon official said Tuesday that
the NATO-led peacekeeping operation, which includes American
troops, had reached a ``decisive moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The official, who just returned from a visit to the American
sector in Kosovo, did not say that more American troops would be
sent to Kosovo. But the situation is so precarious that ``we're at
ground zero,'' even though NATO-led troops have been in Kosovo
since June, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   By this, the official meant that the United Nations effort to
restart civilian life was so weak in Kosovo that the American
troops were still involved in chores that should be done by the
police and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, an insurgency outside Kosovo's border in
southern Serbia had sprung up, causing new problems. The official
described a situation in which troops could not keep the peace
between Serbs and Albanians within Kosovo and at the same time seal
Kosovo's borders, as the commander of the NATO-led troops there,
Gen. Klaus Reinhardt, has suggested.
</P>
<P>
   In order to seal just the rugged 125-mile border of Kosovo that
the American troops are in charge of, ``two to three times'' more
troops would be required, the official said. About 6,000 American
troops are now stationed in Kosovo, all based in the eastern part
of the territory.
</P>
<P>
   To get a better handle on what was happening in the Presevo
Valley, just over Kosovo's border in southern Serbia, the official
said the Pentagon was planning to send unmanned aerial vehicles,
known as drones, for surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   The official, who briefed reporters on Tuesday, said he believed
that about 500 Albanian insurgents organized into ``8 to 10
elements'' were in the ``no-man's land'' between eastern Kosovo and
Serbia and in the Presevo Valley.
</P>
<P>
   NATO military officials are concerned that the Albanians are
making targets of Serbian policemen there, which could provoke a
crackdown against the Albanians from the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic. This, they fear, could cause a possible repeat
of circumstances that caused NATO's war last year over Kosovo:
Serbian repression of ethnic Albanian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Pentagon official said Tuesday that it had not been
decided how NATO would react if that happened. ``At what point you
make a move, that's a political decision,'' he said. ``As of today,
we cannot cross over'' into Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the Clinton administration was attempting to
deliver a serious message to the ethnic Albanian leadership in
Kosovo, particularly through the State Department spokesman, James
Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting on Tuesday in Gnjilane, the main town in the
eastern zone, Rubin told local leaders from the Presevo Valley that
NATO would not intervene if a conflict blew up beyond the Kosovo
borders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
