<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      03-14 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home-Equity Lender Profits With Wall Street's Help
</P>
<P>
   First Alliance, a national home-equity lender, has been sued by
more than a dozen consumers who contend the company has used a
deceptive sales pitch to lure homeowners into loans that expose
them to the threat of foreclosure and financial ruin. The company
has also been sued by regulators in four states. But First
Alliance, which steadfastly denies wrongdoing, still has some very
important supporters: the investment banks on Wall Street that help
it raise the money lent to people. An investigation by The New York
Times and the ABC News program ``20/20'' shows they have pumped
hundreds of millions of dollars into First Alliance in recent
years, even as lawsuits and state inquiries have raised questions
about its practices.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle Posts an 80 Percent Gain in Profit
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by strong sales of Internet software, Oracle reported an
80 percent gain in third-quarter earnings, exceeding analysts'
estimates. Oracle said progress on its goal of cutting expenses by
$1 billion had increased its profit margins. Before the results
were posted, shares of Oracle fell $1.75, to $77. In after hours
trading, Oracle traded as high as $81.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Remarks Cause Stock Sell-Off
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain said
the sequence of the human genome should be made freely available to
all researchers, leading to a sharp sell-off in the stocks of
biotechnology companies. The Nasdaq composite index fell 200.61
points, or 4.1 percent, 4,706.63. The broader indexes followed the
Nasdaq down. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 135.89 points,
or 1.4 percent, to 9,811.24. After spending most of the day up, the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index slipped 24.47 points, or 1.8
percent, to 1,359.15.
</P>
<P>
   European Regulators Reject 2 Deals
</P>
<P>
   European antitrust regulators took some of their most strenuous
action against big corporate mergers, blocking a planned $7 billion
purchase by Volvo of the rival Swedish truck maker Scania and
forcing three large aluminum companies to withdraw their proposed
$17 billion combination.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Player Licensed to Rival
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, asserting that its effort to produce software that
enables Internet users to listen to audio and watch video is moving
ahead rapidly, said that it had licensed its Windows Media Player
technology, without charge, to its main competitor, Real Networks.
</P>
<P>
   Egalite, Fraternite, Burgers
</P>
<P>
   Forget those protests that attacked McDonald's restaurants in
France as an erosion of French culinary tradition and a threat to
French agriculture. Denis Hennequin, the president of McDonald's
France, says McDonald's has been a success there. Why? ``Try taking
your kids to a French cafe,'' he said. ``There's cigarette smoke,
and alcohol. And there's nothing kids hate more than sitting for
hours over a meal. Adults always tell me: `I go to McDonald's but
only with the grandchildren.' But it's not true. Secretly, they
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Sale of U.S. Trust Is Opposed
</P>
<P>
   A community group is protesting the proposed $2.7 billion
acquisition of U.S. Trust by Charles Schwab, contending that U.S.
Trust has a weak record of lending in poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Final Touches Put on Privacy Accord
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Europe completed the wording on a data
privacy agreement that will put strict new controls on how American
companies collect personal information about European consumers.
</P>
</TEXT>
