<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORISM-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. IS SAID TO SEEK DEATH PENALTY IN EMBASSY BOMBINGS IN AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors in Manhattan are pursuing the
death penalty against at least one defendant in the bombings of two
U.S. embassies in East Africa in 1998, according to defense lawyers
involved in the broad terrorism case.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Mohamed Rashed Daoud al-'Owhali, is one of three
suspects in the embassy bombings who could face the death penalty,
and the lawyers said it now appeared very likely that prosecutors
would also seek the death penalty against the other two.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in Manhattan,
which has not been made public, is subject to approval by Attorney
General Janet Reno. But death penalty experts said they expected
Reno to concur, noting that she has given approval in all four
previous cases in which White's office has sought capital
punishment. Each of those cases resulted in plea bargains that led
to long prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   The decision in the al-'Owhali case has been watched
particularly closely by death penalty experts because prosecutors
say he was a suicide bomber who had actually wanted to die as a
martyr in the explosion at the embassy in Nairobi, Kenya. That
bombing and a nearly simultaneous explosion at the embassy in Dar
es Salaam, Tanzania, killed more than 200 people and wounded
thousands on Aug. 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty decision is also the first in the series of
major terrorism prosecutions of about two dozen Islamic militants
in New York since the 1993 World Trade Center bombing, including
another plot to blow up major landmarks in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In some of those cases, the convicted terrorists did not face
the death penalty because their crimes occurred before a 1994 law
that broadly expanded the use of capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Two lawyers for al-'Owhali, Leonard F. Joy and David I. Bruck,
would not comment Tuesday on White's decision to pursue a capital
case. The lawyers had met with prosecutors recently to make a
direct appeal against a death penalty prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   White's office also refused to discuss her decision Tuesday or
say whether she planned to seek the death penalty against two other
defendants in the embassy bombings. But a lawyer for another
defendant, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said he learned
of White's decision Tuesday. ``This sort of takes the mystery out
of what's going to happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A total of six defendants are in custody in the case in New
York, but the other three are not charged with capital crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali is the only defendant whom prosecutors directly
accused of being a would-be suicide bomber. Al-'Owhali, who was the
first suspect brought back to New York from Africa in the weeks
after the bombing, was said to have acknowledged that he rode as a
passenger in the truck that carried the massive bomb to the U.S.
Embassy in Nairobi, according to federal charges.
</P>
<P>
   The government has charged that al-'Owhali admitted to
investigators that he tossed a dummy grenade at a security guard
seconds before the bomb was detonated, that he was prepared to die
and that the bombing was intended as a ``martyrdom operation in
which he did not expect to survive.'' The indictment also contends
that the driver of the truck, identified only as Azzam, was killed
in the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   A number of defense lawyers and others have questioned whether
the government would seek the death penalty for such a defendant,
since it would then seem to offer him the reward he was seeking: a
highly publicized execution and a trip to paradise at the hands of
his enemy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was not clear Tuesday how White and a committee of
prosecutors who examined the case viewed such issues. Nor was it
known whether White's office considered how a death penalty
prosecution in the bombing case would play out in Islamic
countries, including Afghanistan. The man suspected of
masterminding the embassy bombings, Osama bin Laden, has been
living there under the protection of the fundamentalist Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   One effect of a capital prosecution will most likely be to force
two separate trials before Judge Leonard B. Sand in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan. One trial would involve el-'Owhali and any of
his co-defendants who face the death penalty, and the other would
involve the defendants accused of participating in what the
government says is bin Laden's global terrorism conspiracy against
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   A single trial for all the defendants is now scheduled for
September.
</P>
<P>
   The other two defendants who could face the death penalty are
Mohammed Saddiq Odehand Khalfan Khamis Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the practice in other federal death penalty cases,
the defense lawyers, Joy, Bruck and Robert Tucker, are expected to
travel to Washington and ask Reno's office to overrule White.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers who have watched the four other federal death
penalty cases in Manhattan said that Reno had been generally
unreceptive to such appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they said, in two other recent cases in Manhattan, Reno
is believed to have overruled a decision by White not to seek the
death penalty and ordered a capital prosecution. In one case, the
defendant has pleaded guilty. The other case is pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
