<SLUG> BC-SENATE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE GENE KELLY TAKES A STEP FORWARD IN EARLY RETURNS IN
TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gene Kelly, a perennial candidate with a famous
name, was leading a field of five candidates in early returns
Tuesday for the Democratic nomination for a longshot challenge of
U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Gandy, an Austin economic development consultant and
former state representative, was battling Don Clark, a Mesquite
businessman, for a runoff spot against Kelly on April 11.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, a military retiree from Universal City, a San Antonio
suburb, has unsuccessfully run for office four times in the past
eight years and shares the name of a now-deceased dancer and movie
star.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly vowed to fight for the ``interest of the working people of
Texas and their families.'' His goals included protecting Social
Security, strengthening Medicare and making health care available
to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Gandy, the only Democrat in the race who has previously been
elected to public office, has advocated campaign-finance reform,
expanded access to health care and environmental improvements.
</P>
<P>
   He was an early favorite of some Democratic activists and
received some key endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, a computer programmer, systems engineer and analyst, has
called for continuing AIDS research, ``reasonable'' gun-control
measures, preserving the environment, rebuilding the military and
opening foreign markets to U.S. products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see enormous opportunities ahead as technology continues to
enrich our lives, but I remain disappointed in the inequities that
wrinkle our social fabric,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Democratic runoff will face an uphill fight in
November against Hutchison, the Republican incumbent who was
unopposed in her party's primary and already has raised $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The once-dominant Texas Democratic party, suffering through hard
times after losing all statewide races in the last two general
elections, failed to recruit a well-known candidate to challenge
Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   But five mostly unknown hopefuls stepped forward.
</P>
<P>
   They also included Bobby Wightman-Cervantes, a Dallas lawyer who
spent election day in jail, and H. Gerald Bintliff of Leonard in
Fannin County, a former airline employee.
</P>
<P>
   Wightman-Cervantes, a New York native who ran unsuccessfully for
a Dallas judgeship as a Republican in 1998, was arrested at his
home Thursday and is serving a 90-day contempt of court sentence
stemming from a 1997 incident in which he accused a judge of
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Wightman-Cervantes had appealed the jail sentence, but a federal
magistrate recently denied his latest appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Wightman-Cervantes, who includes his mother's Hispanic maiden
name as part of his surname, also lost a court fight against the
Texas Democratic Party, which listed him on ballots as Bobby
Wightman.
</P>
<P>
   Bintliff, who has no government experience, made campaign
finance reform and tax relief two of his top priorities. He also
proposed legalizing various drugs, abolishing the death penalty and
discouraging tobacco smoking.
</P>
<P>
   A Libertarian Party candidate, Mary J. Ruwart, also is seeking
the Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
