<SLUG> BC-IMF-UKRAINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF SAYS UKRAINE OVERSTATED AMOUNT OF THE NATIONAL RESERVES
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The International Monetary Fund said on Tuesday
that Ukraine, a leading recipient of aid from the United States and
international financial institutions, misled the fund's experts
about the size of foreign currency reserves and persuaded the fund
to give it more money than it otherwise would have received.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement issued Monday night, the Washington-based fund
said that the Ukrainian central bank, in three separate
transactions from 1996 to 1998, created the impression that it
controlled more foreign currency than was actually the case. The
amount of money involved was nearly $1 billion, the monetary fund
said.
</P>
<P>
   The monetary fund and the U.S. Treasury Department announced
that they would consider whether to put new controls on future
loans to Ukraine as a consequence of the findings. The fund said
any future disbursements of aid to the country would be
administered by the fund itself and would not be deposited directly
in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   The fund examines how much foreign currency an aid recipient has
as one key measure of the overall health of its economy. It serves
as an indicator of how much foreign investment is flowing into the
country, the strength of a country's currency and the stability of
its banking system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that a number of transactions in 1996-98 gave the
impression that Ukraine's reserves were larger than was actually
the case,'' the fund said in a statement. ``The view of the IMF
staff is that Ukraine appears to have received disbursements from
the IMF on three occasions in late 1997 and early 1998 that it
would not have done if the true state of Ukraine's reserves had
been known at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The manipulation of currency reserves suggests that Ukraine
engaged in tactics similar to those used in neighboring Russia in
recent years. U.S. lawmakers have sharply criticized the fund's
management of Russia's multibillion-dollar foreign aid program,
accusing the fund of turning a blind eye to corruption and of
fueling official graft there.
</P>
<P>
   The fresh revelations also come at a time when critics of the
monetary fund have been pressing for a radical overhaul of its
operations. A congressional commission just last week issued a
scathing critique of the fund and recommended that it cease all its
long-term lending programs, including those in Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6949 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-REAL-NYT &LR;      03-14 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT LICENSES MEDIA PLAYER FREE TO MAIN COMPETITOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (hm) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Microsoft Corp. said Tuesday that it had
licensed its Windows Media Player technology, without charge, to
its main competitor, RealNetworks.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft used the occasion to assert that its digital media
effort _ producing software for Internet users to listen to audio
and watch video _ is moving ahead rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's news is significant for the future of digital media,''
said Will Poole, general manager of Microsoft's Digital Media
Division. He said the announcement would lead to new momentum for
audio and video producers to settle on a single media format _ one
controlled by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts and Microsoft competitors offered a mixed view on
whether there had been any real shift in an industry alignment
where Microsoft has been a clear No. 3 until now.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Glaser, a former Microsoft executive who is founder and
chairman of RealNetworks, played down Microsoft's announcement.
``Microsoft is working as our PR department,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His company's software, RealPlayer, which is available for a
variety of operating systems, has a significant lead over the
Microsoft Windows Media Player by most market research
measurements.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you cut through the malarkey, this is a release about
Microsoft being one of nine codecs,'' or competing formats, that
RealPlayer will be equipped to play, he said. The Windows player
also plays files in several formats, but not in RealNetwork's.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's executives said that Tuesday's licensing deal and a
report by the Internet measurement company Media Metrix were
indications that the industry would soon move to a single media
format: Microsoft's. The Media Metrix report found that Windows
Media Player was used more than any other multimedia player in
American households in December.
</P>
<P>
   But Glaser and several industry analysts said that for technical
and other reasons, Microsoft was unlikely to achieve the dominance
with its Media Player that its Internet Explorer program gained
over Netscape's rival Navigator browser.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that Windows Media Player is the fastest-growing
format, but it's from an installed base of zero,'' said Richard
Doherty, president of Envisioneering Inc., a computer industry
consulting firm, in Seaford, N.Y. ``Also, their position hasn't
been earned so much as blazed with a trail of greenbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   He said RealNetworks still had a technical advantage over
Microsoft, and a large lead in installed base, having distributed
more than 100 million copies of its software.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the Media Metrix numbers cited Tuesday by
Microsoft, Nielsen/NetRatings reported that in the month of
November, various versions of RealPlayer were used by 8.9 million
people on the Internet, representing 12.1 percent of active
Internet users. Microsoft's Windows Media Player was not only far
behind; with 2.4 million users and a market share of 3.2 percent,
it was not even in second place. No. 2 in November was Apple
Computer's Quick Time media player, with 5.4 million users and a
7.4 percent market share.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts Tuesday did see risk for RealNetworks in
Microsoft's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downside is that Microsoft's technology may become the
default standard,'' said Rob Enderle, vice president and research
leader at Giga Information Group, a market research firm in Santa
Clara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   That apparently will not happen any time soon. Both RealNetworks
and Microsoft executives acknowledged that the clear dominant media
standard is still the free MP3 technology, an audio format
controlled by none of the big players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call MP3 the 800-pound gorilla,'' Doherty said.
``It's more like a pack of hundreds of mischievous chimps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
