<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: MUSEUMS GIRD FOR NEW SALVOS IN THE CULTURE WARS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last fall it was ``Sensation,'' the show of
contemporary British art in Brooklyn that offended religious groups
and animal-rights activists. Now it is ``Sanitation,'' the
soon-to-be-unveiled installation at the Whitney Museum of American
Art that some people say trivializes the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``What next?'' asks Abraham H. Foxman, national director of the
Anti-Defamation League, which objects to the Whitney's decision to
show ``Sanitation.''
</P>
<P>
   People in the art world are asking the same question, but not
about the art.
</P>
<P>
   After a breather in the mid-1990s, the culture wars that began
in the late 1980s seem to be resuming, and museum officials worry
that their institutions, not the halls of Congress, are
increasingly becoming the battlefields. As they see it, the
contemporary art they show _ as provocative as it often is _ is
only one ingredient of the trend. More troubling is what they say
is the growing tendency of Americans, in this no-holds-barred
talk-show culture, to try to suppress ideas they do not like.
</P>
<P>
   Joan E. Bertin, executive director of the National Coalition
Against Censorship, which monitors the arts and literature as well
as other spheres, says she sees something even more disturbing in
this climate of of intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's not the numbers that tell the story,'' she said.
Rather, she went on, the impulse to suppress difficult art and
ideas is now coming from the left _ from feminists, civil rights
advocates, gay activists _ as well as from the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different when it comes from the left, which is
traditionally anti-authoritarian,'' Bertin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people who say they believe in free thinking draw lines
and say, `Not here,' it's more troubling,'' she explained. ``And
when it comes from both sides of the political spectrum, there's a
legitimacy provided.''
</P>
<P>
   Attacks from the right and the left broaden what is likely to be
protested. The right usually objects to artworks that include
nudity, have sexual or religious themes, or denigrate symbols of
patriotism like the American flag. In recent years, from the left,
feminists have opposed the display of nudes, Bertin said, while
blacks have protested the art of Kara Walker, saying her
often-brutal depictions of black life reinforce racial stereotypes.
Some years ago blacks and other groups objected to a mocking
portrait of Harold Washington, Chicago's first black mayor, in an
exhibition there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are using the `Words wound' theory,'' Bertin said. ``The
idea that racist speech, for example, is tantamount to a racist
act. It's a blurring of the distinction between the act and the
idea. And it's increasingly shared across the political spectrum.''
As a result life for many museums could get more difficult.
Although art has been provocative in one way or another for
centuries, since at least the 1960s a great deal of contemporary
work has focused on politics and social problems. ``There is no way
to be a museum that shows contemporary art and not engage in social
and political issues, because that's what artists are doing,'' said
Carol Becker, dean of the School of the Art Institute of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The fights in Washington over funds for the National Endowment
for the Arts encouraged that trend among artists, serving as a
challenge, not a warning, to them. In ``Sanitation,'' for example,
Hans Haacke, the German-born artist, tries to make a point about
the First Amendment's protection of artistic freedom. By lining up
a row of garbage cans that blare the sound of marching troops and
creating a wall of condemnatory quotations from Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and others in Fraktur script, a traditional German
typeface once also favored by the Third Reich, he seeks to connect
the Nazi campaign to ban ``degenerate'' art with the present-day
statements.
</P>
<P>
   One quotation, from Pat Robertson, the conservative broadcaster,
reads, ``Do you want to face the voters in your district with the
charge that you are wasting their hard-earned money to promote
sodomy, child pornography and attacks on Jesus Christ?''
</P>
<P>
   Even curators acknowledge that some artists make provocative
works as a career move, knowing it will bring them media attention.
But showing the art of the day, vetted by curators and scholars, is
a core mission of museums like the Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney founded this museum,'' said
Maxwell L. Anderson, its director, ``our responsibility has been to
show contemporary art, challenging and not.''
</P>
<P>
   But many museumgoers do not agree with that policy. ``The
biggest problem for art and artists and contemporary art museums is
the gap between what artists are interested in doing and what the
public expects to see in an art museum,'' Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   So far museum officials, fearing self-censorship more than
protests, say they must simply go ahead with exhibitions of the art
that is out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show the best of world art, and some of that may be
difficult for some people to appreciate,'' said James Welu,
director of the Worcester Art Museum in Massachusetts and president
of the Association of Art Museum Directors. ``But some of the great
art on this earth was controversial in its time.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said: ``If we mount what we show depending on who might
take offense, even the Met would have to clad a lot of nude figures
and cover a lot of other masterpieces. Once you begin that, you
don't know where to draw the line. If no political art could be
shown, David, Gericault and Delacroix could not be shown. It's an
impossible battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, curators and directors say, it is hard to predict what
will offend. Becker said she and her colleagues used to joke about
hiring an outsider, preferably a conservative one with values
distant from the contemporary art world, to preview exhibitions and
point out what might be vexing. ``There was truth to it because we
just didn't see what was offensive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The point, however, was never to remove an offending work but to
try to explain it. Beyond such labels, museums are responding to
recent challenges by posting notices at the entrance to exhibitions
warning visitors that shows contain challenging or difficult work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position has to be, `Don't come to the museum if you're
afraid of being offended, but we'll let you know in advance if
there are works that are likely to be offensive,''' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Any other stance would go against the grain of what the United
States stands for, museum directors seem to be saying. But that
means museums will find themselves increasingly on the defensive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
