<SLUG> BC-MERGERS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: 3 BIG AGENCIES FORM WORLDWIDE PARTNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The three partners in the world's newest giant agency company
gathered Tuesday for an unusual event that was part pep rally, part
christening, part mixer and part Wall Street warm-up.
</P>
<P>
   The partners, still getting to know one another, are Leo Group
in Chicago, which owns agencies like Leo Burnett and Starcom
Worldwide; the MacManus Group in New York, which owns agencies like
D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles and Mediavest; and Dentsu Inc. in
Tokyo, which owns agencies independently around the world as well
as in partnership in Asian-Pacific markets with Young &AMP; Rubicam
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering, at the Leo headquarters in downtown Chicago, was
to formalize the creation of the agency company born Jan. 31 when
Leo and MacManus merged and then sold a stake of approximately 20
percent to Dentsu for an estimated $400 million. The merged entity
plans an initial public offering in the next 12 to 18 months, and
Dentsu plans one in the fall of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The merged company had temporarily been called BDM _ for
Burnett, Dentsu and MacManus _ until Tuesday, when the official
name was announced: the B Com3 Group. That moniker, likely the
first on Madison Avenue to use a superscript numeral, is an amalgam
of names suggested by several employees, playing on the word
``beacon'' and the number of partners.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the genesis of B Com3 , it underlines a fundamental
reason for the deal, which created a behemoth with revenue last
year of $1.93 billion and billings of $15.7 billion: be big or be
gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today in this business, size does matter, size does matter;
there's no question about it,'' Roy Bostock, chief executive of
MacManus, who becomes chairman of B Com3, said at the event, which
was made available to reporters nationwide by teleconference. ``You
need size and scale to compete aggressively on a global basis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This provides us access to the Japanese market, which is very,
very important,'' he added, because that market is second in
advertising spending only to the United States, ``and provides
Dentsu with much greater capabilities for its clients outside Japan
and Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Dentsu will have two seats on the seven-member board of B Com3 ,
which will be based in Chicago; the Dentsu executives to take the
seats have not been named. Two other seats go to executives
formerly at MacManus: Bostock, 59, and Craig Brown, 48, who becomes
president and chief operating officer at B Com3 after serving as
vice chairman, chief operating officer and chief financial officer
at MacManus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next 12 to 18 months, B Com3 will be very active,''
said Roger Haupt, the chief executive, ``building our organization
in areas like direct marketing, database marketing and
e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed the financial, practical and people resources
available by aligning B Com3 with Dentsu,'' he added, ``which has
helped to create a global advertising powerhouse with 16,000
employees and 500 operating units in 90 countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed initial offering of B Com3 shares would ``give us a
currency,'' Haupt said, ``and with that currency, you can be sure
we will aggressively grow this organization.''
</P>
<P>
   As to whether B Com3 would acquire a stake in Dentsu when that
agency goes public just as Dentsu has acquired a stake in B Com3,
Haupt said: ``There are no plans to do so at this stage, but we
frankly have not discussed that. I wouldn't rule it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Haupt, 52, who had been president and chief executive at Leo, is
one of three former Leo executives on the B Com3 board, along with
Richard B. Fizdale, 60, vice chairman, who was chairman at Leo, and
Christian Kimball, 44, chief administrative officer, who held that
same post at Leo.
</P>
<P>
   Leo had long been in discussions with Dentsu, which holds almost
25 percent of the Japanese ad market, about some form of
cooperation; the two share large clients like Coca-Cola, Philip
Morris and Procter &AMP; Gamble, as did Leo and MacManus (not so
coincidentally).
</P>
<P>
   When Leo initiated the merger talks with MacManus last fall,
after the two had abandoned plans to combine Starcom and Mediavest,
Haupt notified Yutaka Narita, president at Dentsu.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new alliance comes at a significant time,'' Narita said
in remarks to the gathering, which he delivered in English.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will give B Com3 true access to Dentsu's vast resources in
Japan,'' he added, like its powerful media services operations,
``while building a strong network'' for Dentsu abroad ``to exceed
the expectations of our global clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a reporter whether Dentsu was interested in expanding
further in the United States by acquiring agencies like Rubin
Postaer &AMP; Associates, Narita replied: ``We are not planning to buy
anything. We have two good partners here.''
</P>
<P>
   The other executives were quite deferential to Narita. For
instance, Fizdale described him as ``a most revered guest'' and
said to him, ``Narita-san, you distinguish us with your presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the event was informal, sometimes even jocular. When
a reporter asked how the partners would tackle disagreements among
themselves, Bostock replied: ``If there are differences, the chief
executive will make the call. So if there are any problems, Roger's
got to solve them.''
</P>
<P>
   Haupt at one point gave Bostock and Narita what he described as
``the keys to the door'' of the Leo headquarters, which becomes the
B Com3 headquarters. And he later said that he pursued the merger
so aggressively with Bostock that ``Roy was referring to me as a
stalker.''
</P>
<P>
   Narita, for his part, humorously described as ``destiny'' the
fact that on March 29 and 30, when Major League Baseball opens its
season for the first time in Japan, the Leo, Dentsu and MacManus
headquarters cities will all be involved because ``the Chicago Cubs
will play the New York Mets, in Tokyo.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
