<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: A HOTEL DIVIDES ITSELF UP LIKE AN AIRPLANE 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code) 
 (bl)  
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The following is a typical conversation that Frank
Banks says he used to have back in the early 1990s when trying to
persuade a top corporate executive to stay at the Rihga Royal, the
luxury hotel he runs in midtown Manhattan:
</P>
<P>
   ``I always stay at the Marriott,'' the executive being wooed
might say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? What's the rate you're paying over there?'' Banks might
ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``About $195 a night for a room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the same rate we're charging here for a luxury
suite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but the Marriott looks better on paper to my board of
directors.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking the quiet hallways of the Rihga Royal, nearly all of
whose 500 rooms were occupied one day last week, Banks recalled
those days with a shudder. The hotel was new. It was expensive, and
in a then-questionable part of town for business travelers, just
north of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't Park Avenue, after all,'' he said. ``All I could
think was, how am I going to fill 500 suites and make a profit?''
</P>
<P>
   In the world of high-end corporate travel, decisions were being
made by executives and boards still sensitive to the public outcry
that had accompanied the horror stories of the corporate excesses
of the late 1980s. It was a tough time to be going on line with a
hotel meant largely to appeal to top-shelf tastes in both the
corporate and the leisure trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I divided the hotel up like an airplane, with levels that
corresponded to first class, business class and coach,'' Banks
said. At first, only a single floor of the hotel's suites were in
the top class.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, as the economy began booming and attitudes toward
high-end corporate travel began to loosen across the board, more of
the lower-priced suites were combined and redesigned for the higher
level. Now, Banks said, the hotel has 100 Pinnacle Suites, which
cost $625 for a one bedroom and $1,100 for two bedrooms. Other
suites range up to $3,300 a night for the top-of-the-line Grand
Royal Suites.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the top price for a luxury hotel room in New York
City, where some suites at better-known hotels can cost $9,000 a
night. Instead, the Rihga Royal, which is owned by Royal Hotel
Ltd., a Japanese company, is carefully positioned to appeal to the
sort of corporate executives ``who don't have to get two or three
supervisors to approve their expenses,'' said Banks, who himself
lives in the hotel on West 54th St.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to corporate travel managers that I don't want big
corporate volume. I want the two or three people in a company who
are going to be able to avail themselves of our level of service.
In effect, it's like selling more first-class and business-class
seats,'' at a time when even airlines are reconfiguring planes to
set aside more premium seats and take advantage of more relaxed
business spending in a booming economy _ for the select few who
qualify for top-dog travel.
</P>
<P>
   Expense accounts from luxury hotels, of course, form only a tiny
portion of the $175 billion that American companies spend a year on
travel and entertainment. Most corporate travel departments _ and
travelers _ are really struggling to deal with increases in costs,
especially for airline travel. Tuesday, the Air Transport
Association reported that with oil prices soaring, airline fuel
prices are expected to rise 40 percent this year, suggesting that
for air travel, ``ticket prices could jump dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   And mostly because of rising air fares, business travel expenses
have already gone up 40 percent in recent years, even without
inflation, said Kevin Mitchell, the chairman of the Business Travel
Coalition, which lobbies for greater competition in the airline
business and better cost controls for business travel across the
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see the kinds of problems in the hotel industry that
we have in the airlines industry,'' Mitchell said. ``Hotels are a
more classic model of a perfect market, where buyers and sellers
both have really good information and there's unrestricted supply
and access to the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   From the 54th floor of the Rihga Royal, looking out across a
section of the city that now throbs with economic prosperity, Banks
said things were looking good for businesses like his that served
the well-heeled traveler willing to pay for space, convenience,
service and in-room amenities like home-style comfort, plus private
fax lines, personalized cell phones and video-phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, we kept redesigning our suites upward to
change the mix,'' said Banks, who ran his own hotel in
Massachusetts and was a general manager of the St. Regis Hotel in
New York before he took over at the Rihga in 1991, the year after
it opened. ``The demand for a higher lever of service keeps going
up, just like on the airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks the high end of the market will hold its own for the
foreseeable future. But there are no guarantees, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if the economy goes south,'' he said, ``we go south
along with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
