<HEADLINE>
TEXAS REPUBLICAN VOTERS BACK STUDENT-INITIATED PRAYERS AT SPORTING
EVENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The issue is in the hands of the U.S. Supreme Court, but Texas
Republican voters let it be known in a non-binding referendum
Tuesday that they support student-initiated prayers at school
sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   Early returns in the Republican Primary showed voters across the
state approving The Texas Religious Freedom Referendum in large
numbers, with 94 percent saying they think such prayers should be
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The measure may have been at the bottom of the ballot when
voters stepped into the polling booths _ and it carries no weight
with respect to the law _ but it is an emotional issue for many
Texans, as much part of the ritual of some high school football
games as the contests themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of Texas voters have said with a loud and clear
voice that voluntary, student-initiated prayer at school sporting
events should remain an honored Texas tradition,'' said Susan
Weddington, chairman of the Republican Party of Texas. ``When
activist federal judges decided to ban a Texas tradition and
curtail the rights of Texas students, the Republican Party lead by
providing one of the few forums in which voters could have a voice
in this debate, and the response was overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether students should be allowed to pray
before sporting events found its way into the court system in 1995
after some parents in the Santa Fe Independent School District sued
to stop the practice, which they contended violates the
constitutional separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans upheld the
parents argument and ruled that ``nonsectarian, nonproselytizing''
prayers at public high school graduations could not be expanded to
allow prayer before football games, and, in November, the U.S.
Supreme Court agreed to take the case.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney's for the school district are expected to argue that
the prayers are simply the legitimate free expression of students
seeking God's assistance in being good sports during the game, not
official, school-sponsored activities.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney's for the parents, who are being represented by the
American Civil Liberties Union, have said they intend to argue that
while they ``wholeheartedly support'' the students' right to pray,
they cannot support ``government-sponsored prayer'' and that the
essential issue is whether ``student-lead, student-initiated
prayers at football games violate the Establishment Clause of the
First and 14th Amendments.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Griffin, an ACLU attorney from Galveston who is set to
argue the case before the high court later this month, said it was
``disappointing'' that voters apparently still don't appreciate why
it is important to have a constitutionally protected separation
between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the vote) is probably consistent with the general public
perception that there is nothing wrong with prayer in school,''
Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   While the lawyers wrestle with the legal ramifications, the
issue took on political significance when the state Republican
Party decided to place it on the primary ballot, a decision that
was apparently not made without dissent from within the party
ranks, and which drew harsh criticism from the state's Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party officials said part of the reason the measure
was included on the ballot, a decision made behind closed doors,
was that certain members felt it could draw Republicans to the
polls in a Republican presidential primary election that was never
a contest in the state. Other Republicans expressed concern that
there could have been serious negative consequences for the party
if the referendum failed.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Democrats charged that including the measure
on the primary ballot was nothing more than ``a cheap advertising
ploy to rally right-wing supporters.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
