<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENTIAL-PRIMARIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, GORE WRAP UP PRESIDENTIAL NOMINATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Setting the stage for what could be a close and
unpleasant national campaign, Democrat Al Gore and Republican
George W. Bush clinched their party's presidential nomination
Tuesday in six Sun Belt primaries.
</P>
<P>
   They dueled immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Gore called for quick debates and a cease-fire on
party-sponsored ads paid for with unregulated ``soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, deriding Vice President Gore as President Clinton's
``cheerleader in chief,'' seemed to rule out debates until the fall
and said Clinton and Gore ``don't have any credibility'' on
campaign-finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also edged closer than previously to putting Colin Powell,
former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, near the top of his
list of vice-presidential prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's a little early to talk about vice presidents,''
Bush said on CNN's ``Larry King Live,'' ``but there's no question
that a man of Colin Powell's stature would send a strong signal to
Americans that I know how to attract the best minds in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore ran up wide victory margins in voting in Texas,
where Bush is governor, and in Tennessee, the home state of Gore,
as well as in Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Associated Press count, Gore and Bush ended the
night with far more delegates than needed to ensure their
nomination at the parties' national conventions this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Their triumph came just a week after Gore and Bush became
prohibitive favorites to win their party's presidential nomination.
Tuesday's voting was the first major tests for both parties since
former Sen. Bill Bradley dropped out of the Democratic contest and
endorsed Gore and since Sen. John McCain suspended his Republican
challenge but refused to endorse Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I filed for president, I pledged I'd come home to Texas
with the nomination of my party,'' Bush said in remarks prepared
for delivery to supporters in Austin, Texas. ``Tonight we can say:
Mission accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in Florida, challenged Bush to debate within two weeks on
the economy, tax cuts, Social Security and Medicare. In an e-mail
to the Texas governor, Gore also said he would urge the Democratic
National Committee not to run commercials financed by ``soft
money'' contributions _ unrestricted funds that are supposed to be
used for party building _ unless Republicans air ads financed that
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to you and your party whether you want to start the
ad-war arms race,'' Gore wrote Bush. ``You have the power to join
me in banning soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   As for a quick debate, Bush said: ``There's going to be plenty
of time to debate when Americans are paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Gore was cranking up the ``old tradition'' in U.S.
politics of having ``a debate on debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush treated Gore's point on ``soft money'' as virtually a joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I believed him, I might be willing to accept it,'' Bush
said, pointing out that Gore and Clinton continue to raise ``soft
money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a man who went to a Buddhist temple to raise money,
and a friend of his was convicted because of that fund-raising
event, and I'm not going to let Americans forget that,'' Bush said
on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds of delegates up for grabs Tuesday, Bush began the
day with 752 of the 1,034 delegates needed to win the nomination at
the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia this summer.
McCain had just 239 delegates, according to The Associated Press
count.
</P>
<P>
   Gore began the day with 2,014 of the 2,170 delegates needed to
win the Democratic nomination at the party's national convention at
Los Angeles in August. Bradley had 313.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore, who have been whacking at each other for weeks,
signaled anew that the general campaign had begun eight months
before the national election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush indicated he would continue to try to hang President
Clinton around Gore's neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't distance himself from the president when, for eight
years, he's served as the cheerleader-in-chief,'' Bush said in
remarks prepared for delivery to supporters in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, however, indicated he was happy to be judged on the last
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a choice between keeping prosperity going or going back
to the Bush-Quayle days of gigantic budget deficits and paralyzed
democracy,'' Gore told The Associated Press, referring to the Texas
governor's father. Earlier in the day, Gore declared the election
``a real choice between two different ways'' of governing.
</P>
<P>
   Gore awaited returns in Tallahassee, Florida's capital, and
planned to speak to supporters at Leon High School.
</P>
<P>
   Former Reagan administration official Alan Keyes remained on the
Republican ballot but is not a factor as the primary season plays
itself out.
</P>
<P>
   The primaries came as new national polls showed Bush and Gore in
a tight race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush led Gore 49-43 percent lead among likely voters in a USA
Today-CNN-Gallup survey published Tuesday. The poll had a 5
percentage point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's even, I like my chances,'' Bush said on ``Larry King
Live.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll, taken Friday through Sunday, had good news for Bush:
He is pulling 80 percent of McCain's Republican supporters and 46
percent of the senator's independents, while Gore gets 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, without referring to that finding, promised to fight for
votes outside his party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever energy I might feel like putting into celebrating, I
am putting into the general election instead,'' Gore said earlier
Tuesday. ``I'm going to reach out to Republicans and
independents.''
</P>
<P>
   An Associated Press analysis of exit polls in Tuesday's voting
showed, however, that Bush ran stronger in the Southern and Border
states among Democratic voters than Gore did among GOP voters. Just
6 percent of voters in Republican primaries said they would vote
for Gore in November, while twice as many Democrats said they would
defect to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In another national poll of likely voters at the end of last
week by Zogby International, Bush led Gore 45 to 41 percent, well
within the sample's margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   The Zogby survey showed Gore winning solid support among black
voters but splitting Hispanic support evenly (47-47 percent) with
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said that the vice president chose
to spend election night in Florida because he believed the state
``would be in play'' in the general campaign, despite the fact that
Bush's brother Jeb, also a Republican, is governor of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a state where Al Gore's policies translate into great
politics,'' Lehane said, referring to the vice president's more
generous proposals regarding Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father carried Florida narrowly in 1992 as he lost the
presidency to Bill Clinton, and Clinton won the state in 1996
against Republican Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his wife, Laura, voted last week in Austin. His
parents, former President Bush and first lady Barbara Bush, voted
for their son in Houston. The former president said: ``It gets down
to family and how lucky we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his wife, Tipper, voted early Tuesday afternoon at
Forks River Elementary School in Elmswood, an unincorporated hamlet
near their family farm outside Carthage, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporters Bennett Roth and R.G. Ratcliffe contributed to
this article.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
