<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-USTRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION ARISES TO SCHWAB ACQUISITION OF U.S. TRUST 
</HEADLINE>
  (hm) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A community advocate group is protesting the proposed $2.7
billion acquisition of U.S. Trust by Charles Schwab, saying that
U.S. Trust has a weak record of lending in poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab, the discount brokerage based in San Francisco, is
seeking federal approval to take over U.S. Trust, a New York-based
bank that caters to very wealthy people.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition would be the first of its kind since Congress
passed legislation last fall that tore down decades-old barriers
that largely kept banks, securities firms and insurance companies
out of each others' businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal ran into its first hurdle this week when a
Bronx-based group that frequently opposes bank mergers weighed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confrontation that comes up is if you are going to own
banks, you have some duty to poor people, and how are you going to
meet it?'' said Matthew Lee, director of group, Inner City
Press/Community on the Move. Lee's group was the first to comment
on Schwab's application last week to the Federal Reserve Board
seeking its blessing for the aquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Community Reinvestment Act requires banks to provide
services, including loans, to even the poorest neighborhoods in
areas in which they operate.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he would like to see Schwab lay out a plan to provide
credit to poor people in the New York area and in other parts of
the country, where U.S. Trust owns five other banks. ``Schwab's
operations are extremely banklike'' already because the firm lends
money to its customers against the value of their stocks and mutual
funds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After buying U.S. Trust, Lee asserted, Schwab would essentially
be a bank holding company with a national network of branches that
should have to provide services to low- and moderate-income people.
</P>
<P>
   If that argument prevailed, it could create new burdens for a
variety of financial services companies, such as Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co., that want to branch out into new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trust did not respond to several calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   A Schwab spokesman said U.S. Trust had ``a strong record of CRA
performance.'' He said Schwab did not expect the protest to delay
the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab should not be able to rely on U.S. Trust's claim that it
serves only wealthy customers and should be treated differently
than regular commercial banks like Bank of America, the group said.
U.S. Trust's record of lending to minorities and immigrants is
``abysmal,'' states Inner City Press' protest letter.
</P>
</TEXT>
