<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-RELATIONS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL TRAINING CONFERENCE IN KANSAS CITY INVOLVES POLICE, RACE
RELATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY SPIVAK  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The recent allegations of police misconduct
around the country may ultimately benefit race relations, a
criminal-law attorney and author told U.S. Justice Department
officials in Kansas City on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   John Burris, who represented police beating victim Rodney King
in a civil case, said O.J. Simpson's murder trial highlighted how
differently black people and white people viewed the criminal
justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a police corruption scandal in Los Angeles and racial
profiling becoming issues in presidential politics, Burris said
whites could better understand how African-Americans felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whites now see there was some truth to what blacks were
responding to in the O.J. case,'' Burris said. ``It's important
that whites see these things can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Burris is author of Blue vs. Black, a recent book about police
misconduct cases. He spoke at the Westin Crown Center hotel at a
national training conference for the Justice Department's Community
Relations Service, which typically gets involved in controversial
police cases.
</P>
<P>
   Burris cited racial profiling as one police misconduct issue
gaining more attention.
</P>
<P>
   He said Democrats Al Gore and Bill Bradley were the first
presidential candidates he could remember who not only acknowledged
that racial profiling existed, but also demanded that it be
abolished.
</P>
<P>
   Burris suggested one important way to remedy police-community
conflicts was for people to become involved in police complaint
review boards.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said such boards had been ineffective because they
lacked subpoena or investigative powers, ``it's better in the long
run to have citizen oversight in policing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
