A7083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CONGRESS15-COX     03-14 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In race No. 6, challenger may head to runoff for Senate seat in
Texas
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gene Kelly, a retiree and six-time candidate who
has yet to win a general election, appeared headed for a runoff
Tuesday in the Democratic primary for U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   With 35 percent of the statewide vote counted, Kelly led the
field of five candidates with 35 percent of the vote. Former state
Rep. Charles Gandy of Austin and bank executive Don Clark of
Mesquite were vying for second place with 23 percent and 22
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   If necessary, a runoff election for the Senate race would take
place April 11. The winner then would face Republican U.S. Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison in November.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison faced no opposition in her primary.
</P>
<P>
   In another Central Texas congressional race, three Republicans _
activist Ronnie ``Reeferseed'' Gjemre, physician Charles Moritz,
and Pflugerville financial consultant Jerry Mikus Jr. _ waited to
find out who will challenge U.S. Rep. Lloyd Doggett (D-Austin) in
the November general election for District 10, which includes most
of Austin and Travis County. Moritz led the early voting with 61
percent, followed by Mikus, who had 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, a retired military lawyer, did little campaigning.
Instead he depended on the name recognition that he said he's built
up over six previous runs for statewide office. He won the
Democratic nomination for the Texas Supreme Court in 1990, a
victory many attributed to the fact that he shares a name with the
famous dancing film star, but lost the general election to John
Cornyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good start, it's just a matter of counting,'' Kelly
said Tuesday night from his home in Universal City, near San
Antonio. ``We'll find out at the end of the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Although few believe Hutchison can be toppled, Kelly said he
thinks Texans ``are tired of the Republicans, and she's one of
them, and I think they'll drop her.''
</P>
<P>
   Gandy said it was too early to speculate on the results, but
``I'm confident that if I get in a runoff ... I'm in pretty good
shape to win.''
</P>
<P>
   After none of the state's marquee Democrats entered the Senate
race to challenge Hutchison _ who has a $6 million campaign war
chest _ Kelly, Gandy, Clark, and two other other relatively unknown
candidates jumped into the primary.
</P>
<P>
   While Kelly waited at home, one of his opponents, Bobby
Wightman-Cervantes, watched the results from jail Tuesday.
Wightman-Cervantes, a Dallas lawyer, began serving a 90-day
sentence for contempt of court last week, a result of a 1997 letter
he wrote to a Dallas judge accusing the judge of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   In other Texas congressional races, state Rep. John Culberson
and businessman Peter Wareing raced out in the lead in early
returns in the heavily Republican 7th Congressional District,
centered in Houston. Republican National Committee member Cathy
McConn was in third. Eight Republicans entered the primary to run
for the open seat that retiring House Ways and Means Committee
Chairman Bill Archer has held since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   With no candidate expected to top 50 percent, the two top
finishers are likely to advance to an April 11 runoff. The eventual
GOP winner is considered a shoo-in against Democrat Jeff Sell in
November.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for District 11, which includes Waco, Killeen, and
Temple, three Republicans _ former Waco TV sportscaster Rob
Curnock, retired Temple oilman Ramsey Farley and Belton contractor
Rodney Geer _ vied for the nomination to challenge Rep. Chet
Edwards (D-Waco) in the fall. GOP leaders have cited Edwards as
among their top Texas challenges.
</P>
<P>
   In East Texas, actor Noble Willingham of ``Walker, Texas
Ranger'' fame sought the GOP nomination to take on Rep. Max Sandlin
(D-Marshall), who defeated a primary challenge from Paris plumber
B.D. Blount.
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
