r a BC-CARD-THEFT-KAN &LR;      03-14 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARD-THEFT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE THINK 3 ARRESTED MEN LINKED TO NATIONAL CREDIT CARD THEFT
RING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It wasn't the massive purchases of perfume
and jewelry that attracted police to three men at Oak Park Mall in
Overland Park, Kan. It was the two-way radio one of them carried.
</P>
<P>
   Police now think they've cracked a national ring of thieves who
steal credit card numbers and create bogus cards, which they use to
buy merchandise for resale on the black market.
</P>
<P>
   The three California men, who allegedly used counterfeit credit
cards to buy about $13,000 worth of perfume and jewelry, are jailed
in Johnson County, Kan. Prosecutors dropped state charges Tuesday
afternoon when the U.S. marshal's office filed a federal detainer
on the men; federal charges are expected today.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Richard Medley, arriving at the J.C. Penney store to
pick up a shoplifter in an unrelated case, saw the man with the
radio. Medley thought the man might have been a security guard
until Medley mentioned the man to a store employee.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers with radios are unusual, so Medley went outside and
watched the man get into a green van and drive to another part of
the parking lot, near Nordstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Medley went back inside, where employees said the man had just
bought a $3,800 ring and about $5,000 worth of perfume with a
credit card. Police asked them to check the transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The store employees called the credit card company, which called
the legitimate cardholders and learned they knew nothing about the
purchases. Police would not say where the card numbers were stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Medley called for help, and Sgt. John Jackson blocked in the
van. Inside Nordstrom, Jackson saw three men ready to carry off
about $4,000 worth of perfume they had purchased with a credit
card.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men tried to run, said Jackson, who grabbed him and
arrested all three. Police searched the van and a Merriam, Kan.,
hotel where the men were staying and found tens of thousands of
dollars worth of jewelry, perfume and electronics, along with about
50 counterfeit credit cards. Names on the cards matched those on
fake identification cards and passports that police found.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the merchandise was packaged for shipment elsewhere in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities think the three men flew into Kansas City on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators wouldn't say how the men got the credit card
numbers, but they think they disrupted a national crime ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amounts here are staggering,'' Jackson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
