<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MCI-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYST PREDICTS SPRINT-MCI WORLDCOM MERGER WILL BE BLOCKED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sprint Corp.'s proposed merger with MCI WorldCom attracted
another skeptic Tuesday, one predicting that antitrust regulators
will move to block the deal in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Cleland, a telecommunications analyst and managing
director with the Legg Mason Precursor Group in Washington, made
his prediction in a conference call with institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   He said his conclusions weren't based on any inside information
but on an attempt to analyze the merger by the same standards that
Justice Department officials will use in their review.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that in the next several months, the antitrust
division of the Justice Department is going to seek and win a
temporary injunction to halt this merger, and that will effectively
scuttle this merger,'' Cleland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people in the market will probably be surprised when this
occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint and MCI WorldCom issued identical responses to Cleland's
comments: ``We remain convinced that the merger will go through in
the second half of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint is slated to mail out its proxy statement detailing its
merger arguments shortly. A special shareholders meeting to vote on
the deal is scheduled for April 28.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland's opinions are by no means universal in the analyst
community. Tony Ferrugia, an analyst with A.G. Edwards in St. Louis
and a former Sprint employee, issued a note to clients that said,
``We disagree with the opinion that Justice will deny the
WorldCom//Sprint merger.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrugia did agree with Cleland, however, that if the merger is
blocked, there is no shortage of willing partners for Sprint,
including Deutsche Telekom and BellSouth, both of which have come
knocking before.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland offered little new information in his analysis but said
he was pulling together threads of evidence that have appeared in
various forums in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   That evidence includes what he called ``ominous process
precursors'' that key government officials have a ``clearly
negative predisposition against this merger.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited statements by Federal Communications Commission and
Justice Department officials, a leaked memo from a prominent FCC
staffer and Justice's hiring of a renowned antitrust lawyer,
Stephen Axinn, to assist in its evaluation of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Steve Axinn is there for a purpose, and that purpose
is to prepare for and win in court,'' Cleland told his audience.
``Our research indicates that that's exactly what they're doing,
from the questions they're asking people around the country.
They're preparing for a court fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his analysis of the regulatory smoke signals, Cleland
looked at the potential concentration in the Internet and
long-distance markets that would result from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is in the second, detailed phase of its
merger review after receiving initial filings from the companies.
Cleland said regulators would be examining three important issues:
</P>
<P>
   - Whether the merger would result in undue market concentration
that gives the combined company the ability to control pricing in
any of its businesses.
</P>
<P>
   - Whether there would be adequate competition or changing market
conditions that would allow the market to correct an
overconcentration.
</P>
<P>
   - Whether the deal could be allowed if the new company is
required to sell certain businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland concluded that when the merger is subjected to the
traditional indexes that regulators use to judge market
concentration, the numbers ``are way beyond highly concentrated.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the combined company would control 50 percent of
Internet traffic and 35 percent to 40 percent of the long-distance
market.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom and Sprint long have argued that the long-distance
market is irreversibly competitive, with more than 600 competitors,
soon to be joined by the powerful regional Bell companies.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also argue that the industry pricing model is
quickly changing to ``all-distance pricing,'' where consumers pay
one price for all their calling.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland said the day of all-distance pricing might be coming but
was still years away. He also argued that only Sprint, MCI WorldCom
and AT&AMP;T Corp. have the brands, network and marketing clout to set
long-distance prices; that Sprint played an important industry role
as a pricing maverick; and that the entry of the regional Bells was
unlikely to change the competitive landscape for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland also suggested that Justice would not be disposed to try
to cure the potential market concentration in the Internet by
requiring the new company to sell off Sprint's Internet business,
as has been widely predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Justice required MCI to sell off its Internet backbone when it
merged with WorldCom two years ago, a transaction that ended up in
court when the buyer said MCI failed to transfer the necessary
employees, contracts and network support to run the business going
forward.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom recently settled that case for $200 million, but
Cleland says that the company now lacks credibility with regulators
and that the department won't want to spend the energy and manpower
to make sure this deal goes as promised.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators ``aren't dumb,'' Cleland said. ``They'll realize
it was a mistake the first time around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
