<HEADLINE>
CROWD CELEBRATES AS BUSH DELIVERS PRESIDENTIAL NOMINATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ To the tune of Stevie Wonder's ``Signed, Sealed,
Delivered, I'm Yours,'' about 400 Texas Republican loyalists
Tuesday night celebrated the Republican presidential nomination
that Gov. George W. Bush earned after more than a year of planning
and campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   A large-screen television at the packed Dell Jewish Community
Center gymnasium entertained the crowd with a short movie of
outtakes from Bush's year on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   It showed his appearances on the ``Tonight Show'' and ``The Late
Show With David Letterman,'' as well as Bush holding up lobsters in
New Hampshire and looking at bass in an aquarium in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a picture of his likely presidential opponent, Vice
President Al Gore, appeared on screen, the audience booed, and they
cheered wildly as Bush declared the nomination was his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Bush all over,'' said Patricia Adam, 59, of Navasota,
Texas, who has worked in the archives and library of Bush's father,
former President George Bush. ``I wouldn't have missed tonight for
all the tea in China, just to say I love him and all his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush told a home-state crowd he had clinched the GOP nomination
with primary victories Tuesday in states that included Texas and
Florida, where his brother Jeb is governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I filed for president, I pledged I'd come home to Texas
with the nomination of my party. ``Tonight we can say: Mission
accomplished,'' said Bush, with large Texas and U.S. flags draped
behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are halfway, but only halfway, to ending the Clinton/Gore
era in Washington,'' Bush said, referring to President Clinton and
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was surrounded on stage by almost all of the statewide
elected Republican officials.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison declared, ``Tonight begins a new
era in American leadership,'' while Lt. Gov. Rick Perry said Bush's
overwhelming victory in Tuesday's Texas presidential primary was an
endorsement ``by those who know him best.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush was introduced to his election night crowd by El Paso Mayor
Carlos Ramirez, a Democrat who had supported Bush in his 1998
re-election bid as governor. Ramirez campaigned for Bush earlier
this year in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president, this is a man who won't just do things right,
he'll do the right thing,'' Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   Railroad Commission Chairman Michael Williams, a Bush appointee
who is seeking election to the office, told the crowd Bush was his
campaign manager 16 years ago when he ran for county attorney in
Midland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got soundly defeated in the Republican primary,'' said
Williams, who won the GOP nomination for his own office Tuesday.
``Governor, we're turning it around tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was off the campaign trail Tuesday, was awakened at
6:30 a.m. CST at the Governor's Mansion by his cats, Ernie and
Willie, said spokesman Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the first thing the Republican nominee did was feed his
cats,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush then made coffee for himself and his wife, Laura, Hughes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent part of the morning meeting with lawyers from his
general counsel's office to discuss the impending execution of
Ponchai Wilkerson, 28. Wilkerson, who was on death row for the
murder of a 43-year-old jeweler in Houston in 1990, was pronounced
dead at 6:24 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   During Bush's appearance Tuesday night, a small group of
anti-death penalty protesters briefly interrupted Bush's victory
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Bush closed his speech by praising the late Lt. Gov. Bob
Bullock, a Democrat who supported Bush in his 1998 re-election bid
and endorsed him for president before his death last year.
Bullock's wife, Jan, was on stage with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless Bob Bullock, and God bless Texas,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
