<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7097 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CT-SKAKEL-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      03-14 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-SKAKEL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO VICTIM'S MOTHER, SKAKEL SAYS HE IS `THE WRONG GUY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Spelling `Dorthy' is CQ.) 
 (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ Amid a huge news media stakeout reminiscent of
the O.J. Simpson trial, Michael Skakel appeared in court for the
first time Tuesday to face the charge that he murdered Martha
Moxley, his friend and next-door neighbor, in Greenwich nearly 25
years ago, when they were both 15.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel, a nephew of Ethel Kennedy, is charged as a juvenile, and
his arraignment Tuesday was nothing more than a seven-minute
procedural hearing at which he did not even enter a plea. The only
drama came afterward, when Skakel walked to the railing by the
first row of spectators and stood face to face with Moxley's
mother, Dorthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel your pain,'' he said, looking Moxley in the eyes. ``But
you've got the wrong guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Moxley, thunderstruck, said nothing, and Skakel turned and
walked away. Later, surrounded by reporters, she said she remained
convinced of Skakel's guilt and that his comment ``was a very
rehearsed statement.'' The last time the two of them saw each other
was the morning after the killing in 1975, when Moxley, looking for
her daughter, who had not come home, knocked on the door of the
Skakel home and Michael Skakel opened it. He said he had not seen
Martha.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, outside the state Superior Court complex in Stamford,
where dozens of camera tripods stretched for more than half a block
and 14 television satellite trucks lined the street, Skakel's
lawyer, Michael Sherman, said the remark to Moxley had been
spontaneous and ``came from the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not know he was going to make that remark,'' Sherman
told the media crowd, adding: ``He did not say it in an arrogant
fashion. He didn't say it to annoy anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But moments later, Sherman said he would allow Skakel to make
public comments ``only after his acquittal.''
</P>
<P>
   By law, juvenile judicial proceedings are closed, but in a
landmark ruling Friday, Judge Maureen Dennis granted a motion by
five newspapers to open the Skakel case to the press and to the
public. In her decision, Dennis noted that Skakel had supported the
motion and that at age 39 he no longer needed the protection of
confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, all 46 seats in the courtroom were filled Tuesday,
mostly by reporters. But for all the anticipation _ many arrived
hours in advance of the 2 p.m. arraignment _ there was little to
see. Dennis announced the murder charge, read Skakel his rights,
and recognized Sherman as Skakel's lawyer and guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Then, she scheduled a so-called reasonable cause hearing for
June 20, and the proceeding was over. Because Skakel is charged as
a juvenile, he did not have to enter a plea. At the next hearing,
prosecutors are charged with demonstrating that there is sufficient
evidence against Skakel, and they will ask Dennis to have him tried
as an adult in Superior Court in Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   The reasonable cause hearing, which is expected to last several
days, will provide the first opportunity for the presentation of
evidence in the case. If the case remains in Juvenile Court, it is
unclear what if any penalty Skakel will face if he is found guilty.
</P>
<P>
   But if Skakel is tried as an adult, a conviction would carry a
mandatory sentence of 25 years to life in prison. The state's
attorney in Bridgeport, Jonathan Benedict, who is the lead
prosecutor in the Skakel case, said only that he was intent on
getting the case moved to Superior Court and that he would
demonstrate reasonable cause ``through witnesses and through
evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman would not identify the witnesses he planned to call or
the evidence he would present in defense. ``Michael's defense and
his only defense is he did not commit this crime,'' Sherman said.
``The evidence is totally insufficient to support a conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the evidence will almost certainly be the golf club that
was used to bludgeon Moxley to death on the night of Oct. 30, 1975.
The club, a 6-iron, was traced by police to a set owned by Ann
Reynolds Skakel, Skakel's mother. Mrs. Skakel, who had died two
years earlier, was the sister-in-law of Ethel Kennedy, the widow of
Robert F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Moxley, a popular blond 15-year-old, lived with her family next
door to the Skakels in a wealthy enclave in Greenwich. Her brother,
John Moxley, who was 17 at the time of the killing, said he would
like to see Skakel serve a maximum sentence. ``They have put us
through 25 years of hell,'' he said. ``Why not the same thing for
him?''
</P>
<P>
   And if all the television trucks outside the court house were
not enough to bring the O.J. Simpson case to mind, among the more
than 115 reporters, photographers, cameramen, pundits and other
gawkers was Mark Fuhrman, the former Los Angeles detective, who
wrote a book about the Moxley case called ``Murder in Greenwich''
naming Michael Skakel as the killer.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman has been hired by ABC as a television commentator on the
case, but outside the courthouse Tuesday he was anxiously sought
out by other television crews, including ABC competitors.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Moxley came out of the courthouse, she faced a crowd
of reporters and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost a miracle that we are where we are today,'' she
said, describing the quarter-century in which justice seemed
elusive. ``I still cry,'' she added. ``But I can handle it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
