<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spring debut for Rocker easy as 1-2-3
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Through the publicity nightmare, the strain on
his family and friends, and the walk back into a potentially
hostile Braves clubhouse, John Rocker has maintained that none of
his off-the-field turmoil would affect his pitching.
</P>
<P>
   He got his first chance to prove it on Tuesday night, taking his
first sprint from the bullpen to the mound for the ninth inning of
the Braves spring training game against the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   In front of 10,078 fans, the biggest crowd to see a game since
the Braves moved to Disney's Wide World of Sports two years ago,
Rocker was wild but effective in a scoreless ninth inning, retiring
Gregg Jefferies on a popup, Javier Cardona on a groundout and
striking out Robert Fick looking at a slider.
</P>
<P>
   And he did it predominantly to cheers, something he begrudgingly
acknowledged to the media afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I'm talking is because Bobby (Cox) asked me
to,'' said Rocker, who was then asked how it felt to receive a
standing ovation. ``How do you think it felt? The best thing I got
out of that was maybe it finally showed you people in the media
that not everyone is against me. ... I've been well received
everywhere I go.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first trip to the mound since Game 3 of the World Series
and the first time since he incurred the wrath of countless
millions for his comments in Sports Illustrated, Rocker threw 12
pitches, six of which were out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked how he always looks, jacked up,'' pitching coach Leo
Mazzone said. ``He looked fine. He was up a little bit with some
high heat, but he threw good breaking stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was Rocker's chance to gauge the progress he's made
after arriving two weeks late into spring training while he waited
on arbitrator Shyam Das's ruling. He'll pitch again Saturday in
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel comfortable,'' Rocker said. ``I had no release
point at all. I was racking my brain to make adjustments out there
but it was the first inning I've pitched in 4 1/2 months and there
was some adrenaline going. I didn't like missing as badly as I did
with my fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted afterward, while he went in contemplating throwing
at 75 percent to 80 percent effort, he was pretty much at
full-bore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in pumping, giving it everything he's got,'' Cox said.
``That's the way he pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
