<HEADER>
A7101 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     03-14 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING'S FOR CERTAIN IN NCAA TOURNAMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By my own humbled estimation, I have lost enough money on NCAA
Tournament office pools to feed several Third-World countries.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least to buy them a Big Mac.
</P>
<P>
   I have never won. I have never even come close to winning. By
the night of the NCAA basketball championship game, my photocopied
bracket perennially lies crumpled in disgust at the bottom of some
trash can.
</P>
<P>
   The people who win office NCAA pools are the same ones who
wouldn't know a Cinderella from an evil stepsister. Their
``system'' is usually an amalgam of birthdates and phone numbers of
close relatives.
</P>
<P>
   True story: Few would argue that the 1985 final, won by
Villanova over mighty Georgetown, was one of the great upsets in
tournament history. Yet, a reporter at our newspaper won the office
pool by picking Villanova, with its 10 regular-season losses, to go
all the way.
</P>
<P>
   She explained later: ``I thought the name sounded pretty.
Villa-nova. It's Spanish, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Be forewarned. If you work anywhere around alleged adults, this
is a good week to stay away from the Xerox machine.
</P>
<P>
   While the American economy is forwarded to voice mail, a large
chunk of the country's labor force is pausing to perform one of two
March rituals _ prepare for its fantasy baseball draft or fill out
its NCAA Tournament bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance is futile. This is the time of the year when suddenly
everybody is an expert on either Matt Mieske or Central Connecticut
State. Guys who can't remember their anniversaries can tell you
Jamie Moyer's runners-per-nine average or the names of the point
guards for all the No. 6 seeds.
</P>
<P>
   They can tell you who's hot (Arkansas) and who's not (Kansas).
They can tell you that Chris Porter (Auburn) is out, but Demtrius
Porter (Fresno State) is in. When in doubt, they'll tell you, bet
Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Duke is everyone's Get Out of Jail Free card at this time of
year. Kentucky is close behind.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid at all costs anything named Winthrop or any school whose
mascot outfit looks like a rental. If the pointspread is less than
10 points, bet the coach with the most hair. And teams wearing
green can beat teams that wear blue, but not teams that wear red.
</P>
<P>
   I told you I've never won.
</P>
<P>
   A story the other day said that an estimated $500 million will
be bet on the NCAA Tournament these next few weeks. A group in
Washington, made up of 48 members of Congress and 75 coaches, is
pushing for a bill that would ban wagering on college sports in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Don't these people pay attention around the water cooler? The
real cash is going down this week, $5 and $10 at a time. The newest
scourge is buying into a tournament bracket over the Internet,
where one Web site is offering $10 million to anyone who picks all
63 games of the tournament correctly.
</P>
<P>
   You probably have a better chance of marrying Mark Cuban.
</P>
<P>
   There are no gimmes at NCAA Tournament time, history tells us.
Look at Cincinnati. It ran out of mulligans before the tournament
even started, relegated to a No. 2 seed despite unquestionably
earning a No. 1 with a 26-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   The word from the NCAA selection tower was that it didn't think
Cincinnati would be that good without injured star Kenyon Martin.
See? Even the NCAA committee thinks it can predict the bracket.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do they know how good we'll be without Kenyon?'' Bearcats
coach Bob Huggins asked.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that at tournament time, everybody has $10 that
says they're an expert.
</P>
<P>
   Temple's John Chaney? Can't win; never has.
</P>
<P>
   Duke? Too many freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas? Left its Cinderella slippers at the Southeastern
Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Louisville? So why is Denny Crum still walking around with his
1966 hair?
</P>
<P>
   I'd give you my picks, but it really doesn't matter. I liked
Stanford, but that loss to Arizona cooled me. I was impressed with
Iowa State, but the Cyclones will have a nasty gantlet to run.
</P>
<P>
   It really doesn't matter. When in doubt, bet the better mascot.
</P>
<P>
   Or the team that sounds Spanish. I've seen it work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
