<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-VANGUNDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIMEOUT MICROPHONE FOR VAN GUNDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a week of bitter words and expensive fines
between the National Basketball Association and its coaches
regarding the wearing of microphones, the league struck a temporary
compromise Tuesday night that, at least for one game, avoided a
messy confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Van Gundy was scheduled to wear the microphone for the
first time when his New York Knicks faced the Houston Rockets at
Madison Square Garden, but he had resisted and during the day he
received permission from his boss, James Dolan, the president and
chief executive officer of Cablevision Systems Corp., to refuse to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   When Toronto's Butch Carter and Seattle's Paul Westphal opted
not to wear microphones Sunday, their organizations were each fined
$100,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But after the NBA reached a compromise with the National
Basketball Coaches Association during discussions Tuesday, Van
Gundy and Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich were given the option of
wearing the microphone or allowing a boom microphone to listen in
on their huddles during timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy chose the boom microphone and Tomjanovich, who had
voluntarily worn the microphone during two other games, chose the
microphone. ``For me, it's totally different,'' Van Gundy said
before the game. ``Now I don't have to monitor my dialogue with my
coaches or the one-on-one player dialogue throughout the game. It's
much less intrusive. It's not all the time. It's not as I'm talking
to my coaches throughout the game. It's not my reaction to a
referee's call. This is strictly in timeouts and so it's much less
intrusive. They can't use strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Without allowing his strategy to be broadcast in the
tape-delayed comments that the networks would use, Van Gundy was
asked what would be left in the huddles that could be used on
television. ``Got me,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   The microphones are only used on the national telecasts, so in
the New York area, where MSG preempted TNT, there was no miking.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Goldberg, executive director of the National Basketball
Coaches Association, worked with the league to strike the
compromise and said: ``We are seeking a way to reach a comfort
level for coaches who don't feel comfortable wearing a microphone.
This is a step in that direction, with respect to this game. This
is still on the table. But we may be on our way out of this
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   The league will continue discussions Wednesday on whether to
make the option permanent or to revert to the original edict.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the microphone attached to a coach, he would have the
option of turning it off whenever he wanted. But Van Gundy felt
that the microphone was an intrusion he did not want to deal with
during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be thinking about that,'' Van Gundy said. ``I
know there's some people that don't understand why coaches would be
adamantly opposed. Some are, some aren't. But I think everybody's
concerns are legitimate. I don't think coaches should have to do
something like that they believe is intrusive to their job. Coaches
like Rudy don't believe it's a problem and that's great. I think
everybody should have that chance to do what they feel is okay.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said: ``I'm not going to say I'm completely
comfortable with it and I do believe that coaches should not be
forced to do it if they feel it in any way hurts their chances to
do their job. I think they have that right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league came to me and they thought that it could help our
league and I'm all for that. They asked that we trust them, that it
would not be any strategy or any embarrassing type situations. And
in my experiences with them, there hasn't been anything, just human
interest, a little banter between the coach and the referee.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I do think that it's a very big responsibility on the TV
people to keep that promise, and once somebody is hurt, if that
ever happens, they should just say that we didn't stick to our plan
and scrap it.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has argued his stand over more than just the use of
game microphones, attempting to keep the media out of practices.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy said he and the Knick organization agreed over their
distaste for the microphones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were all united on the belief that not only wasn't
it the right decision, but the implementation, the timing of it,
there was no discussion, those were all factors that led to it.,''
he said. ``I just thought it was not handled the right way. I
appreciate their understanding of how I think.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we don't want to be fighting the NBA, because everybody
involved _ players, coaches, management _ have profited from the
NBA. It's not about fighting the NBA, but there has to be a person
at the league office, someone that will be a caretaker for the
game, who will not allow the game to be compromised for better
business. I think that's critical.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
