<HEADLINE>
STARS' FERNANDEZ CHILLS THE NEGATIVITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marc Fernandez delivered a stern lecture to his son,
Manny, on Saturday before returning to Montreal after a four-day
visit to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wasn't too happy with the way I was thinking and
talking after the first two games,'' Manny Fernandez said, ``and he
flat out said that to me. I think that maybe got me thinking `I'm
not going to go down this easy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' rookie goaltender hasn't either.
</P>
<P>
   After a less-than-impressive beginning to his fill-in role for
usual starter Ed Belfour, where he had an 0-1-1 mark against NHL
also-rans Vancouver and the New York Islanders, he rebounded with
back-to-back victories against the NHL-leading St. Louis Blues and
the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez will make his fifth consecutive _ and likely last _
start in place of Belfour when the Stars play the Eastern
Conference-leading New Jersey Devils at 6 p.m. Wednesday in East
Rutherford, N.J..
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has got to give Manny a little bit of a break,''
Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner said. ``It's a tough situation
stepping in and carrying the load when it's kind of unexpected like
that. And I think he's done a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour hasn't played since being charged with misdemeanor
assault and resisting arrest Wednesday. The police report stated
Belfour was intoxicated, which led to a mandatory evaluation of
Belfour by a substance abuse program sponsored by the NHL and
players' association. The evaluation was completed Sunday, but
Belfour didn't join the team until Tuesday night in New Jersey and
isn't expected to play until Saturday in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves one more big start for Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be a confident individual right now,'' Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock said. ``He's got wins in big games and had to come up
with big saves.''
</P>
<P>
   He should be confident, but Fernandez isn't always what he
should be. Nobody was harder on Fernandez for his performance
against the Canucks and Islanders than Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hadn't played well. He said he felt a bit nervous. He
said he felt pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Dad, along with his teammates, told him to chill. He finally
listened when Stars captain Derian Hatcher approached him after
Monday's first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me I was doing fine. That helped,'' Fernandez said.
``I still felt a little bit nervous, but to a certain degree I'd
like to feel a little nervous when I play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the change in Fernandez's mind-set has been
noticeable on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Even Fernanadez noticed, finding himself surprisingly satisfied
with Monday's 4-3 victory against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it finished 4-3 and three goals for me is not
really a happy zone, I thought I made some good saves,'' Fernandez
said. ``I thought I played like a No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   So when the Stars' No. 1 goalie returns on Saturday and
Fernandez returns to being a backup, it's fair to say he's going to
have some mixed emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm going to miss it,'' Fernandez said. ``In a way,
I'm also really glad to see him come back. This team has really
missed him over the last week.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
