<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHER-SHORTAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. HIRING RULE ON TEACHERS IS RELAXED
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a move to address a looming teacher shortage in
New York City and across the state, education officials have
decided to allow credentialed teachers from most other states to
begin teaching here immediately rather than waiting until they pass
New York's certification exams.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Board of Regents quietly approved an emergency
amendment to state education regulations on March 7, giving the
Education Department the ability to grant a two-year provisional
certification to licensed teachers who move to New York from one of
39 other states or to those who have a national teaching
certificate.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was introduced to the Regents by Richard P. Mills,
the education commissioner, at the request of Harold O. Levy, New
York City's interim schools chancellor, who resigned from the Board
of Regents earlier this year when he took charge of the city's
school system.
</P>
<P>
   New York City is facing a potentially crippling teacher
shortage. A recent survey of its members by the United Federation
of Teachers found that an estimated 14,000 of New York City's
78,000 public school teachers planned to retire over the next 18
months, a far faster pace than previously predicted.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 teachers from other states apply for certification
in New York each year, a figure that Mills predicted could easily
double under the new standard.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers hired under the new provision will have two years to
complete the appropriate New York certification exams, which are
administered quarterly. Until now, teachers from other states might
have been discouraged from applying here, finding more lenient
policies elsewhere, education officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Although New York City has hired significant numbers of
uncertified teachers in recent years, the new policy is expected to
expand the number of applicants from other states because the
city's Board of Education will give preference to candidates with
certification, even from other states, over uncertified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, about 10,000 New York City teachers, more than 10
percent of the total, are unlicensed. But state law will forbid the
hiring of unlicensed teachers beginning in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   New York City hires about 8,000 new teachers each year, but the
Board of Education anticipates needing 19,000 new teachers for the
school year that begins in September 2001. Over the next five
years, the United Federation of Teachers has said, 54,000 new
teachers will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   The new measure to broaden hiring from out of state is
restricted to teachers who are licensed by states and territories
that have signed an interstate agreement that defines some of the
qualifications that are necessary to obtain a teaching license.
Forty states plus the District of Columbia, Guam and Puerto Rico
are parties to the agreement. The 10 states that are not are
Alaska, Iowa, Kansas, Minnesota, Missouri, Nebraska, North Dakota,
South Dakota, Wisconsin and Wyoming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-00 2354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000314.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7107 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-WHITEWATER-NYT     03-14 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WHITEWATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CLOSING THE BOOKS ON WHITEWATER
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, March 15:
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ray, who succeeded Kenneth Starr as independent counsel,
owes the American people a final report tying up the many loose
ends of Whitewater and other aspects of a mammoth investigation
that began six years ago. The $50 million investigation covers a
range of questionable activities involving Bill and Hillary Clinton
that disappeared from public view the moment Monica Lewinsky came
along. As a matter of both law and common sense, the public
deserves a summing up _ delivered in one piece and delivered
promptly.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ray has reportedly chosen to release this information
bit by bit in a series of reports over the coming months. This
drawn-out procedure is sure to become a source of continual
disruption throughout this year's election campaigns, and it
violates accepted notions of fair play. Ray is also said to have
reopened the possibility of indicting the president after he leaves
office on the same charges involved in the impeachment drama _
whether he lied under oath to a grand jury, and whether he asked
Lewinsky to lie about their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   This page has consistently backed a thorough investigation of
the multiple accusations against the Clintons and a full airing of
its findings. But at this very late date in the proceedings the
issue of proportionality and timeliness loom large. The independent
counsel's office has had virtually unlimited resources and years of
time to conduct its inquiry. Surely Ray has the staff and
sufficient information to complete a final report in short order if
he sets his mind to it.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there any reason for the prosecutor to pursue Clinton
when he leaves office. The charges against him were fully
adjudicated in the impeachment trial before the Senate, the forum
designated by the Constitution for dealing with presidential
misdeeds. The Senate trial was exhaustive and obviates the need for
further legal action. A report in Monday's Times by Neil Lewis
suggests that Starr himself may have reached the same conclusion,
namely that the proper forum for all these charges was the
impeachment battle and that there was no need for any separate or
subsequent criminal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Times story, Ray plans three reports between
now and the fall. The first will involve the White House's improper
acquisition of about 900 FBI files, including dossiers of prominent
Republicans. This report is likely to conclude that the so-called
``Filegate'' scandal involved no criminal wrongdoing and resulted
from unwitting mistakes by low-level White House aides.
</P>
<P>
   The second and third reports could be more problematical for
Hillary Rodham Clinton. One will deal with the firing of several
longtime employees of the White House travel office shortly after
the Clintons came to power. Mrs. Clinton has said she had little to
do with the episode, while others have told investigators that the
first lady played a central role.
</P>
<P>
   The third and final report will cover a range of activities
falling under the heading ``Whitewater'' _ the Arkansas real estate
deals that originally attracted the attention of the press,
Congress and the Justice Department and led to the appointment of
an independent counsel six years ago. This report would cover
important unanswered questions involving Mrs. Clinton's billing
records from her days as a lawyer in Little Rock as well as her
sworn testimony about her role in Whitewater and other
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel's office owes its judicial overseers _
and through them the nation at large _ a complete report of its
findings. But that report should be delivered to the judges now, so
that it can be processed and released early in the election
campaign. That will give the political process time to assess the
implications for the candidacies of Mrs. Clinton and Vice President
Al Gore and respond to the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Such a report, expeditiously delivered, would be consistent with
the statutory responsibilities of the independent counsel. A series
of reports extending well into the election season would raise
serious questions about Ray's motives and could well undermine the
credibility of his work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
