<HEADER>
A7109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-TRIBUNE-L.A.-TIM     03-14 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TRIBUNE-L.A.-TIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SELLING OF THE LOS ANGELES TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, March 15:
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward consolidation of newspaper ownership is by no
means new, but Tribune Co. of Chicago's agreement to purchase Times
Mirror Co. offers several lessons about the economic and
journalistic issues involved in today's mergers.
</P>
<P>
   One is that the concept of ``newspaper chains'' is rapidly
becoming outdated by investor and marketing pressures to form
multimedia companies that stretch across newspapers, broadcasting
and the Internet. Tribune Co., which will now own 11 daily
newspapers, 22 television stations and a major share of America
Online, has been one of the most aggressive of traditional media
companies in exploring ways to expand its reach. This $6.45 billion
acquisition positions it powerfully for the new game of finding
multiple uses for content from one medium _ newspapers, for example
_ in other media, say its broadcast and Internet outlets. This
convergence of content from different media has huge implications
for publishing, programming, advertising and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The new media environment has also touched off a churning debate
among journalists about professional standards and the task of
insulating news coverage from commercial pressures. Some members of
The Los Angeles Times, including its highly regarded former
publisher, Otis Chandler, saw the takeover by The Chicago Tribune's
parent company as a positive sign. For the past five years the
Times Mirror chairman, Mark Willes, a former cereal company
executive, had tried to dismantle the traditional wall between the
editorial and business sides of The Los Angeles Times. While Willes
drove up Times Mirror stock, he lost the confidence of the paper's
journalists and drew Chandler's public condemnation. Now the
combined company's newspaper operations will fall under the
direction of Jack Fuller, president of Tribune Co.'s publishing
unit and a former editor who has written extensively about
preserving journalistic standards in the new media environment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is shock in Los Angeles that the Chandler family,
which owned the paper for 119 years and helped shape the city and
state, was no longer in control, just as there was shock in Boston
when The New York Times Co. purchased The Globe from its longtime
owners, the Taylor family, in 1993. The Chandler family's share of
the new company is worth over $1 billion at current stock values,
but the newspaper industry _ and family-controlled newspapers like
this one _ will read a managerial as well as a financial lesson
into Times Mirror's decision to sell. Discord among the family
shareholders led to the Willes regime in Los Angeles and ultimately
to a change in ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Many smaller papers, such as The Louisville Courier-Journal,
have fallen victim to such disunity, but no one had expected the
largest and most important newspaper in the West to change hands so
abruptly. Then again, no one expected the newspaper that was made
into a national force by Chandler to experience the journalistic
turmoil brought about by Willes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
