<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-COLVIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM COLVIG, 82, MUSICAL INSTRUMENT BUILDER  
(HM)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Colvig, an instrument builder who collaborated with
composer Lou Harrison on gamelans and other percussion instruments
and who was Harrison's companion for 33 years, died March 2 in
Capitola, Calif. He was 82 and lived in Aptos, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Colvig was born in Medford, Ore., in 1917. Although he sometimes
described himself as an amateur musician, he studied the piano,
trombone, baritone horn and tuba while he was growing up in Weed,
Calif., and he won a scholarship to study music at the University
of the Pacific in 1934. But he soon decided to study electrical
engineering instead, and in 1937, he transferred to the University
of California at Berkeley. He continued his studies at Berkeley for
two years before joining an expedition of naturalists traveling in
the Yukon.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, he served in the Army on radar
installations in Alaska. He returned to California after the war
and worked as an electrician in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   He became involved at that time with the Sierra Club. He later
became a guide and a leader of backpacking expeditions for the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Leta E. Miller, the co-author, with Fredric Lieberman, of ``Lou
Harrison: Composing a World,'' wrote that Colvig and Harrison met
after a concert of Harrison's works in 1967 and that they quickly
discovered they had common interests in music, acoustics and
politics. They had both been early supporters of KPFA Radio, a
nonprofit pacifist radio station in Berkeley, and they were both
members of the Society for Individual Rights, a San Francisco group
that promoted gay rights. A few weeks after they met, Colvig moved
into Harrison's woodland cabin in Aptos.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison had by then become interested in the sound of the
Indonesian gamelan orchestra _ an ensemble of pitched percussion
instruments _ but had found that importing an authentic gamelan was
prohibitively expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Colvig and Harrison began building a gamelan, based
partly on traditional Indonesian designs and partly on using found
objects. Aluminum slabs, tin cans, electrical conduits and empty
oxygen tanks, cut to various sizes and struck with sawed-off
baseball bats, replaced the gongs of the Asian gamelan.
</P>
<P>
   Colvig and Harrison called their instrument the American
gamelan. It was first used in Harrison's work, ``La Koro Sutro,''
in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Colvig and Harrison built several other gamelans, as well as
harps, bowed stringed instruments and percussion instruments.
Besides being used in performances of Harrison's music, the
instruments have been shown in several exhibitions. Two of their
gamelans were bought by San Jose State University and Mills
College.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Harrison, Colvig is survived by two sisters,
Donna Straight of Auburn, Calif., and Claire Oberon of Paso Robles,
Calif.; and three brothers, David of San Francisco, Richard of
Oakland, Calif., and Ray of Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
