<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENCY IS DENIED POLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JUDI VILLA  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(FLORENCE) _ Patrick Poland leaned forward and in a shaking voice
spoke to the families of the men he killed nearly 23 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say I'm sorry. I've lived with this every day, and I
wish I could just go back in time,'' Poland, 50, said. ``I hope
everyone can accept my apology, understand me and forgive me.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite Poland's remorse and passionate pleas to save his
life, the Arizona Board of Executive Clemency voted 4-1 on Tuesday,
March 14, to go ahead with Poland's execution.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to die by lethal injection at 3 p.m. today,
March 15, at the state prison in Florence for killing armored-van
guards Cecil Newkirk and Russel Dempsey in May 1977. Poland would
be the 21st inmate executed in Arizona since the state resumed
capital punishment in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for Patrick Poland and I hope he can truly repent for
what he did,'' Newkirk's grandson, Cecil III, said after the
hearing. ``I'm sure if he could go back, things would be different
but, unfortunately, it can't be like that. He has to serve (his
sentence) for what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Poland's attorney, Tom Gorman, filed a last-minute appeal with
the U.S. Supreme Court on Tuesday, March 14, night. A decision is
expected today, March 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it. That's the highest court there is,'' Gorman said.
``We're hoping they will grant us a stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's, March 14, eight-hour hearing was marked by tearful
pleas for mercy and heartbreaking stories of abuse that Poland
suffered as a child at the hands of his father. Three of his
siblings, including his twin brother Jeff, and his two children
spoke on his behalf. So did two prosecutors and the FBI agent who
once rallied to put Poland on death row.
</P>
<P>
   All wanted Poland's death sentence reduced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look in my father's eyes and I've got so much love for him,
and I feel like I'm 4 years old again,'' said Guy Poland, Patrick's
son. ``I love my father so much I can't even imagine being here
without him.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times during breaks Tuesday, March 14, Guy and his
sister, Stacey, looked toward the enclosed chamber where their
father sat, and mouthed, ``I love you, Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were realistic and we knew it probably wouldn't happen,''
Stacey said after the board's decision. ``Everything that could
have been done has been done.''
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Guy and Stacey said their final goodbyes
through the glass of a visitation booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love him. He knows that,'' Stacey said. ``And I told him to
give me a kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   Poland has asked that his family not witness his execution.
</P>
<P>
   Poland and his brother, Michael, posed as highway patrolmen to
pull over a Purolator Inc. armored van, steal $288,000 and kill
both guards. They then drove 250 miles to Lake Mead, wrapped
Newkirk and Dempsey in custom-made canvas bags weighted with rocks
and dropped them from a rented boat to a watery grave.
</P>
<P>
   Newkirk's widow said in a letter to the board that ``the Poland
brothers cheated my husband from many years of happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does this man deserve to die?'' Lola Newkirk wrote. ``Yes, he
does! He must pay with his life! This will not bring back my dear
husband, but justice must be served.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
