u s BC-GLF-WEBB-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      03-14 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WEBB-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBB IS THE PLAYER TO BEAT IN LPGA 
</HEADLINE>
  (hm) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Karrie Webb has won every tournament she has entered this year,
something that even Tiger Woods has not done.
</P>
<P>
   While Woods' exploits have dominated headlines in the golf
world, Webb has also been brilliant, winning all three of her tour
starts this year. If Webb wins this week's Standard Register Ping
in Phoenix, she will become the first woman since JoAnne Carner in
1982 to win four consecutive tour starts.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lopez holds the career Ladies Professional Golf
Association record with five consecutive winning starts in 1978,
and considering the way Webb has played, Lopez's streak does not
seem out of reach. Webb has actually won four consecutive starts,
but her victory in last month's Australian Ladies Open was not an
official LPGA event.
</P>
<P>
   At age 25, Webb already has 19 career victories on the tour, and
she is clearly a cut above her peers. But with Woods riding a
six-start winning streak earlier this year, Webb's exploits have
been somewhat overshadowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has left me some privacy, but the only thing that annoys me
is that the LPGA hasn't gotten as much publicity from it as they
probably should have,'' Webb said during a national conference call
on Tuesday. ``We have great players, and we have just as good a
show as the PGA Tour does.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're never going to hit it as far as the men, but with a
five-iron in our hand, we can hit it just as close as the average
guy can. The average golfer can relate to us much more than they
can to Tiger Woods hitting it 350 yards. The average male golfer
can watch us play, see us hit from positions that he would be in,
and watch us hit clubs he would hit. People just need to come watch
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Webb play these days means watching a great player at
her best. One of the tour's longest hitters, Webb switched to a
cross-handed putting style at the beginning of last year and raised
her game to a new level. She won six times last year en route to
the player of the year award, and she set a career record for the
single-season scoring average, 69.99.
</P>
<P>
   Webb has lowered that scoring average to 69.22 this year, and
her improved putting has made her even more aggressive and more
confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say 70 to 80 percent of the reason why I've played so well
is because of my putting,'' said Webb, a native of Australia who
lives in Florida. ``I've seen so many more putts go in. Now, I can
miss a green and still get it up and down. Before, I didn't feel
like I was making as many putts as I should, so if I missed a
green, I'd be afraid of making bogey. And my short game has gotten
better. I'm not scared to hit it by the hole if I have a tough
chip, because I know I can make the putt coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb took last week off, when Annika Sorenstam qualified for the
LPGA Hall of Fame by winning the Welch's/Circle K Championship.
Sorenstam will not officially become a member of the Hall of Fame
until she fulfills the requirement of playing 10 years on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry between Webb and Sorenstam, however, could be a
boost to the tour if both players have big years. They already went
head-to-head at the Takefuji Classic earlier this month, when Webb
defeated Sorenstam on the first hole of a playoff. Both Webb and
Sorenstam will play this week and at next week's Nabisco
Championship, the first LPGA major of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My relationship with Annika is that we're friends at the golf
course,'' Webb said. ``I don't know Annika away from the course,
but I have a lot of respect for her game. Her making the Hall of
Fame was a given.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb appears destined for that honor as well, and she would love
to continue her current streak. Like Woods, Webb enjoys an
advantage these days when her name appears on the leader board.
This week and every week, everyone in the field knows she is the
player to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when players see my name on the leader board, they
know there's a good chance I'll stay on the leader board,'' Webb
said. ``It's the same for me when I see Annika or Juli Inkster's
name. I know they won't go away. Instead of making pars, other
players have to think about making birdies.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
